<HEADLINE>Husband to sue over asbestos allegations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MacDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE family of a woman who apparently contracted cancer from her husband's
asbestos-covered overalls yesterday announced legal action against Scottish
Nuclear.
Mrs Janice Hughes became ill 30 years after her first husband spent 18 months
supervising construction work at the Hunterston power station in Ayrshire.
At the time, she regularly shook out his work overalls and is thought to have
inhaled dust from white asbestos fibres, leading to mesothelioma cancer.
Mrs Hughes' first husband, Mr David Cozens, an electrical engineer, died from a
brain tumour in 1966. He came into contact with the asbestos dust while mixing
powder to form pipe lagging.
The fight for compensation is being led by her second husband, Mr John Hughes,
of Clywd in North Wales, after a coroner recorded a verdict of death from an
industrial disease.
At an inquest on Thursday, East Clwyd coroner David Jones said: ``There was a
30-year time lag before the onset of the illness but I am told by doctors this
is not unusual. I consider that it is more likely than not that the
mesothelioma was caused by exposure to asbestos.''
Mr Hughes said his wife, who was 56 when she died last November, had been
forced to leave her job as a nurse in Liverpool after contracting the illness.
His solicitors said yesterday they would be serving a writ for compensation on
Scottish Nuclear, which took over Hunterston from its former owner, the South
of Scotland Electricity Board.
Ms Lavinia Houghton, of Bullock Worthington and Jackson in Manchester, said the
coroner's verdict strengthened their case.
A Scottish Nuclear spokesman said officials were awaiting details of the
inquest and any legal claim, which would be given full consideration.
He said the company placed the highest possible emphasis on the safety of both
its staff and the public.
</TEXT>
