<HEADLINE>Ballet dancer alleges assault</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323138</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE law has stepped in to investigate an alleged behind-the-scenes clash
between two of Scotland's leading ballet dancers.
According to insiders, Scottish Ballet ballerina Catarina Lappin claims she was
assaulted by male principal dancer Robert Hampton in a backstage flare-up
during a performance of A Midsummer Night's Dream in Edinburgh's Festival
Theatre last month.
The pair, both long-servers with the company, were playing the roles of the
fairy king and queen, Oberon and Titania.
Police confirmed yesterday that they were investigating a 25-year-old woman's
complaint that she was assaulted in the theatre on October 6.
A spokeswoman for Scottish Ballet said the company had not been made aware
officially of police involvement but confirmed that it had held its own
internal investigation into a complaint by Catarina Lappin about an alleged
incident involving Robert Hampton.
Refusing to disclose the outcome, she said: ``Catarina Lappin has lodged an
appeal, so it is still under investigation by the company. It is an internal
matter''
One insider said: ``From what I have heard, there was a disciplinary meeting
and both were told off and Catarina was unhappy and felt she had been dealt
with unfairly.''
</TEXT>
