<HEADLINE>Labour attacks `rationing' of health care</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323140</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE row over the future of the NHS was reignited yesterday when a leading
professor said a health authority had referred 15 patients to an NHS hospital
for fertility treatment - and then refused to pay the #10,000 bill.
The cost of in-vitro fertilisation was eventually met by a charitable trust of
which Professor Robert Winston is a trustee.
The professor of reproductive medicine at Hammersmith Hospital, west London,
said: ``That's a typical example of what is happening in some health
authorities in this country.'' It was a ``form of rationing'', he said.
At the same time, Labour claimed health care was becoming a lottery depending
on where people lived.
Professor Winston intervened during a news conference where Shadow Health
Minister Alan Milburn said one in three health authorities had started
restricting or scrapping certain treatments.
The professor said Portsmouth and South East Hampshire Health Authority
referred the fertility treatment patients to him last year.
``Once they were on the waiting list and accepted for treatment, the health
authority refused to pay the bill, and left me to pay the bill,'' he said.
Mr John Henly, director of health care purchasing for Portsmouth and South East
Hampshire Health Commission, said later he would need to examine the case.
``Our normal practice is to commit ourselves to patients admitted on a waiting
list for treatment.
``If there is a change in our policy, then any patient previously on a waiting
list for that treatment would normally be funded.
He added: ``Obviously, after that policy had been agreed, it would be expected
that no further patients would be accepted on a waiting list.''
Labour published a national map of where treatments were being ``rationed'',
and claimed 40 of the 129 health authorities in England, Wales, and Scotland
had stated that they were either not buying certain categories of care, or
limiting it.
Shadow Health Secretary Harriet Harman said that as well as treatments being
excluded from the NHS, preventive services, such as routine ultrasound tests in
pregnancy and screening for certain forms of cancer, were being excluded.
``This is the thin edge of the wedge,'' she said. ``Yesterday, it was fertility
treatment and sterilisation. Today it is varicose veins. Tomorrow it will be
hernias and hip replacements.''
The Health Department keeps no record of the treatments offered by different
authorities.
The survey published by Labour was compiled privately by Blackwell Masters, a
consultancy based in Leyburn, North Yorkshire, by pulling together the annual
purchasing plans of each authority.
Ms Harman said: ``Forty health authorities are now admitting in their
purchasing plans to restricting or excluding certain treatments.
``Ten have targeted varicose veins, 23 have targeted ear grommets, eight have
targeted screening for osteoporosis, eight have targeted fertility treatment.''
Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell said the evidence did ``not remotely justify''
the charges Ms Harman was making.
``What the evidence from the health authorities which Ms Harman quotes shows
quite clearly is that health authorities are consulting clinical opinion about
which treatments reflect good value and latest clinical practice,'' he said.
``The question to Ms Harman is why she criticises health authorities for using
clinical evidence to ensure NHS resources are targeted on real need.
``Let me make the Government's commitment to the NHS clear. Health care is
available to those who need it without asking whether they can pay for it.''
He said the NHS would not undermine doctors' freedom to do what they thought
was in their patients' best interests.
Meanwhile, health service professionals in Fife yesterday expressed concern and
surprise that the region had been ``wrongly singled out'' in the Labour Party
study.
Fife Health Board, which is responsible for a population of 350,000, was the
only one of 15 Scottish health authorities listed among 40 in Britain which
Labour said had begun the explicit rationing of NHS treatments.
Fife was claimed to be limiting the number of ear operations it carries out.
Fife Health Board denied that it was limiting services. Ms Pat Frost, the
board's general manager, said yesterday: ``This report is simply not correct.
Grommets (ear operations) have not been, and never will be, excluded in Fife.''
Dr Eric Baijal, Fife's acting director of public health, said: ``Fifers can be
assured that no treatment is excluded from the range of services purchased on
their behalf.''
</TEXT>
