<HEADLINE>Horse's ear was thrown at woman, court told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323141</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN told a court yesterday that a friend of her former lover had thrown a
horse's severed ear at her.
Mrs Anne McConnell, 33, said the ear came from her thoroughbred mare called
Fallon.
She told Glasgow Sheriff Court she had driven with her three-year-old son to a
small-holding owned by Mr Frank Carberry, 33, after she had received a
telephone call telling her the horse was dead.
She believed she was to collect a vet's death certificate but as she arrived at
Carberry's driveway, Mr Carberry had walked towards her carrying a polythene
bag.
``He said `Here's your f******g documentation', put his hand in the bag, took
something out and threw it at me,'' Mrs McConnell told the court.
Mrs McConnell claimed Mr Carberry then told her: ``You'll get the rest of the
horse through the post.''
She said she picked up the ear and had wanted to throw it back at Mr Carberry.
But as she raised it above her head her friend, Ms Carol Tracy, had grabbed her
arm and prevented her.
Mrs McConnell told the court that she took the ear to the police and was so
upset it was two hours before she could compose herself enough to give them a
statement.
She claimed that in the police station she received a call on her mobile from
Mr Carberry who told her to check all her other horses' ears.
Mr Carberry, of The Holdings, Wester Boghead Road, Lenzie, denies maliciously
damaging a horse last June by removing its ear, assaulting Mrs McConnell by
throwing an ear at her, and committing a breach of the peace.
Mrs McConnell said that Mr Carberry was a friend of her ex-boyfriend Mr Charles
Swan who had a farm outside Kilsyth.
She worked for her friend Ms Carol Tracy who ran a horse trekking business from
Mr Swan's farm.
They quit the business because the rent had increased and there was a legal
dispute over a debt.
Nine of the 10 horses were moved out of the farm despite a court order and Mrs
McConnell admitted she was brought before a sheriff for contempt of court but
admonished.
Fallon, however, remained at the farm and the next time she saw her she was
lying dead in a field near Cumbernauld with her ears removed.
Defence lawyer David Hunter suggested to Mrs McConnell that the incident never
happened, a claim she denied. She also denied that she owed Mr Carberry money
for horse feed.
Ms Tracy told the court : ``Fallon was my father's horse and I was very
attached to her, but Anne was more attached because she looked after her.''
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
