<HEADLINE>Judge allows hospital to withdraw treatment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323142</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERMISSION for a hospital to withdraw life-sustaining treatment from a man who
has been in a persistent vegetative state since suffering brain damage during a
dental operation was given by a High Court judge yesterday.
The 27-year-old man, known for legal reasons only as C, has been in the same
state since his heart stopped while his wisdom teeth were being removed under
general anaesthetic in February 1991.
Mr Justice Johnson said he was sure that C had no glimmer of awareness and that
his interests required the court to make the order withdrawing the
administration of nutrients and hydration by artificial means.
He also ordered medical staff to ensure that the man suffered the least
distress and maintained the greatest dignity until such time as his life might
come to an end.
The application was brought by the local NHS Trust at the initiative of the
man's parents.
The judge made an order preventing the publication of anything which would
identify the man, his family or the hospital caring for him.
A consultant at the hospital, who also cannot be named, said the man's
condition was very severe indeed and there was no prospect of any improvement.
If the present ``exemplary'' standard of medical care was maintained, he might
live for a further 30 years.
The judge said that, every day, C was turned, lifted, and strapped into a
wheelchair. He showed no recognition of those around him and there was nothing
to indicate he could see. His body would jerk in response to loud sound. He was
mute, although he could cough, choke, and sometimes sneeze quite violently. On
occasions, he would vomit.
The man made no voluntary movement of his limbs, which were stiff, and his
facial expression had at times exhibited distress or anguish.
The judge said the decision was supported by the hospital, the doctors, and by
the Official Solicitor, who has been appointed by the court to represent C's
interests.
The judge said C's parents had explained that he had always been a private and
gentle person whose biggest fear was losing control.
They felt he would not have been able to bear being in his present state and
that he would want to die if he was able to make the decision.
They explained that they had put him first in reaching their conclusion in
February 1994. The judge said that C's family and the staff caring for him
would need professional counselling and it would be made available to them.
q SCOTLAND'S first ``right to die'' case is due to be heard later this month at
the Court of Session. Mrs Janet Johnston has been in a persistent vegetative
state at Law Hospital, Carluke, for more than three years and is being kept
alive by artificial feeding.
The hospital trust, with the support of Mrs Johnston's husband and daughter, is
petitioning the court to be allowed to withdraw feeding. The hearing has been
set down for November 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
