<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory MP faces complaint</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323143</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR's deputy leader, Mr John Prescott, last night lodged a formal complaint
with Parliament's new sleaze-finder general, Sir Gordon Downey, over the
conduct of Tory MP Patrick Nicholls.
Mr Nicholls, MP for Teignbridge, in Devon, who is a former Minister, is alleged
to have offered to use his influence in Whitehall to act for a private company
in return for shares.
The allegations were made last weekend. Mr Nicholls has consistently claimed he
had acted absolutely in accordance with the rules governing Members' interests.
Mr Prescott said at the time that any ``shares for influence'' deal was just as
bad as the ``cash for questions'' row which led to the Nolan inquiry into
standards in public life.
Last night, Mr Prescott said: ``I have today formally submitted a complaint to
Sir Gordon Downey, Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards, about the conduct
of Patrick Nicholls and forwarded all the evidence we have received.
``I believe Mr Nicholls has breached the rules of the House and I remain
concerned about this matter.''
Mr Nicholls was reported to have agreed to take a 5% shareholding in a water
equipment firm in return for trying to persuade the Government to buy its
products.
</TEXT>
