<HEADLINE>Couple fail in bank battle Judge's ruling could spell ruin for pair who claim Barclays wrecked their business</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323144</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE latest high-profile legal battle between consumers and the banks ended in
disaster yesterday for a couple who claimed their businesses were wrecked when
Barclays Bank called in their overdraft.
Nigel Green and Yvonne Challis could face ruin after their compensation bid
failed, leaving them to pick up a bill of #350,000 for taking on one of
Britain's biggest High Street banks.
The pair started the legal fight when a replacement manager at their branch saw
they had a huge business overdraft and immediately called in the debt.
However, a judge at the High Court in Cardiff yesterday rejected their
compensation claim and ordered them to pay a total of #311,000 in overdraft,
loans, and interest. They were also told to pay the costs of the hearing,
estimated at #30,000.
Banking pressure groups last night said the defeat would not derail their
campaign for laws to regulate the banking industry more tightly.
Mr Green, 42, and 41-year-old Miss Challis, of Clymelyn Farm, Llanllwni, Dyfed,
had sought #1m in compensation, claiming that their riding school and haulage
businesses were wrecked by the bank's decision to demand repayment.
However, Judge Michael Gibbon ruled that the bank was entitled to call in its
overdrafts.
``They took the view that further funding of the business would be throwing
good money after bad,'' he said, ruling that Mr Green should pay #207,000 and
Miss Challis #104,000, with both sums including interest.
The couple, who moved to the tiny village in West Wales from Kent, said: ``Our
dreams are wrecked.''
Mr Green added: ``We are completely gutted. We had complete and utter trust in
the bank manager, we feel badly let down.
``We knew we were tackling a giant when we took on the bank but we felt
confident in the justice of our case.''
However, they said they had issued writs against Barclays claiming they were
given bad advice by the bank manager.
A Barclays spokesman said: ``We are pleased with the judgment but regret we had
to bring the case at all.
``Legal action followed a number of attempts over the past three years by the
bank to resolve the dispute and recover the outstanding sums.''
The High Court ruling came as Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley intervened
on behalf of two constituents whose Legal Aid was withdrawn just two working
days before their court battle to save their home from repossession by Lloyds
Bank.
Mrs Bottomley wrote to the Legal Aid Board after it withdrew the certificate on
Wednesday because Mrs Yvonne Wright, who is fighting the case with her husband
Bill, had turned 60 and was entitled to a pension.
Mrs Wright, of Dockenfield, near Farnham, Surrey, is still waiting to hear if
she will have Legal Aid when she appears in court on Monday after Mrs Bottomley
wrote to Legal Aid Board chief executive Stephen Orchard asking him to
``carefully re-examine the case''.
The Legal Aid Board said it it was unable to comment.
The case involves a joint venture property partnership which the Wrights
entered into with another couple, who are Lloyds Bank customers and who
allegedly gave a legal charge over the property to cover their personal debts.
Both cases follow a string of other bitter fights between the banks and their
customers.
q In September, Ms Julia Verity, 55, and Mr Richard Spindler, 36, were awarded
#77,500 by a court in a landmark legal victory after their Lloyds branch
manager was found to have given them bad advice.
q Last week, there was outrage when NatWest Bank charged businessman Colin
Crosby, of Dewsberry, Oxfordshire, #8000 for a #2000 overdraft. The bank agreed
to repay the #8000 after admitting ``not following procedures''.
q Earlier this month, banking watchdog Audit UK said that, out of 4000 cases it
had investigated in four years, around 82% had been overcharged.
Last night, Ms Pat Griffiths of the independent Banking Action Group, called
for the Government to clear up the law.
``I think there have been big changes in the last three years and I think
people are fighting back hence we are seeing all these court cases.
``There used to be huge trust for the bank managers, who were regarded like
doctors, but it has now been exposed that the banks are not acting in a
professional way towards their customers.
``It seems the Government is allowing this to go on,'' she said.
Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the British Chambers of Commerce,
said banks were providing an ``increasingly good service'' and said managers
should not be prevented from being able to call in loans.
However, commenting on yesterday's case, he added: ``We deplore any lender who
does not exercise discretion and acts with intemperate expedience without
offering alternative solutions.''
</TEXT>
