<HEADLINE>Court moves to capital to clear trials backlog</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF Court is set to move 20 miles to catch up with a backlog of trials.
However, the proposal to cram in almost 300 trials due at Linlithgow Sheriff
Court into nine days at Edinburgh Sheriff Court has been criticised by the
Lothian and Borders branch of the Scottish Police Federation.
The federation fears with so many police witnesses having to move out of West
Lothian in March and April there will be a lack of police cover during that
period.
Spokesman Norman Macleod said yesterday: ``No matter how carefully they try to
reduce the number of police witnesses, they will still have a minimum two
officers per trial and they plan to hold 40 trials a day.
``That's 80 officers off the streets and cover will have to be maintained. The
only way is for the force to bring in other officers on overtime and the bill
for that could be substantial.''
The reason for the backlog of trials at Linlithgow has been blamed on a lack of
accommodation at the court and a series of long trials.
The Scottish Office says trials should be dealt with no later than 12 weeks
from the date they are fixed. However, at Linlithgow it has taken 30 weeks for
some trials to come to court.
Linlithgow's difficulties were highlighted when Rangers goalkeeper Andy Goram
was told he would have to wait until July for trial on a drink-driving charge.
Mr Goram is just one of 1044 people awaiting trial at the court, with more than
two-thirds waiting more than three months.
The Sheriff Courts Administration Service proposes to use five courts in
Edinburgh for six days in March, with a target of clearing eight trials a day -
to dispose of 240 trials. Another 72 trials are expected to be heard over three
days set aside in April.
Linlithgow Sheriff Clerk, Mr Roy Sinclair, said: ``If we succeed, then we
should make a considerable dent in our backlog, which has occurred for a number
of reasons. But the main problem is the lack of space here at Linlithgow. We
just can't keep up with the number of cases coming in here.
``We will continue as normal at Linlithgow while the trials are cleared at
Edinburgh. It is not in the interests of justice for this situation to carry
on.''
Lothian and Borders Sheriff Principal Gordon Nicholson said: ``It is not an
unusual problem for courts to have a build-up of cases. But in other areas
there is the facility to convene extra courts in the same building to catch up.
``We don't have the accommodation in Linlithgow and hence our plan to involve
Edinburgh in the process. But we recognise there will be disadvantages to
police and the public. We are attempting to minimise that inconvenience and a
number of agencies are working closely together to try and ensure this exercise
will be successful.
``There may still be problems for the police in maintaining cover, but we have
their fullest co-operation.''
In the longer term, the Sheriff Courts Administration Service is negotiating
with West Lothian District Council to lease part of its Livingston headquarters
for use as a permanent Court annexe to Linlithgow.
A spokesman for Lothian and Borders Constabulary said yesterday: ``It will
certainly have an effect on us but, overall, the merit to the justice system is
worth the disruption. We will have to look at our resources but it will not
mean that West Lothian won't be policed.''
</TEXT>
