<HEADLINE>New lease of life for Dundrennan firing range</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE top-secret 4500-acre firing range at Dundrennan, near Kirkcudbright, is set
to become an infantry training range, with up to 40 jobs for civilians.
The Ministry of Defence will spend up to #9m building barracks and improving
the ranges for some of the 12 battalions of 500 men each that will use the
facilities during six months in the summer.
In the winter, it is planned to use the range, overlooking the Solway Firth,
for training infantry recruits from Catterick.
An official announcement is expected before Christmas by the Government but at
a top-level meeting at the range yesterday, Mr James Arbuthnot, Minister for
Defence Procurement, and the Army's top Land Command officer said they were
highly optimistic about its future.
They were talking to councillors, management, staff, and union representatives
at the range, which is due to close by the end of 1997 with the loss of all 120
jobs, 30 of whom have already gone.
For 13 years, depleted uranium shells were developed and tested at Dundrennan
before being used for the first time in the Gulf war. Despite repeated
attempts, none of the shells has been recovered from the Solway.
Mr Arbuthnot said it was expected that 40 civilians would be required, once a
final decision had been made, as well as a large number of troops coming into
the area and spending their money there.
Colonel Finlay Maclean, from HQ Land Command, Salisbury, who is in charge of
the Army's ranges, said he was delighted with Dundrennan.
He said that 78% of the 120,000-strong British Army was now based at home,
compared with 49% of a 150,000-strong army before the end of the Cold War, and
they needed more ranges, with Kirkcudbright being ideal.
He added: ``I expect an announcement in the next couple of weeks. The people
are keen on it and there is no opposition here.''
The news of the possible 40 jobs was welcomed by councillors and workers and Mr
John Morris, a Stewartry District councillor from Kirkcudbright, said it looked
as if the future of the range was assured for many years to come.
``The 40 jobs will be welcome and we would have liked more, but in these
economic times it isn't possible,'' he added.
Mr Denis McGarrie, the Transport and General Workers' Union representative,
said the workers would be able to apply for the jobs which would not be
skilled, when the Army took over.
</TEXT>
