<HEADLINE>Music  BBC SSO, Henry Wood Hall, Glasgow The haunting embrace of the East</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE presence on the Scottish music scene of Chinese composer Tan Dun, who made
his official debut on Thursday night as associate composer/ conductor of the
BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, in one of their Cutting Edge series of
concerts, has several implications.
First, Tan's extraordinary mix - an authentic and original blend - of cultures
adds a new dimension to Scotland's music. In its own way, his music is radical.
There's nothing original in a composer creating a collaboration between ethnic
and modern idioms - they've been at it for years.
But Tan Dun's two Orchestral Theatre works - the second receiving its UK
premiere on Thursday - are something else: they are a homogeneous mix of the
ancient and the avant garde, of West and East, in an integrated unit.
The other implication is that we're going to have to find some way of
describing this astonishing music. Orchestral Theatre II is pure performance
art. Two conductors - Tan and Jerzy Maksymiuk - directed the SSO, whose
woodwinds were stationed around and above the audience, and the audience itself
(which joined full-throatedly in the chanting) in an amazing performance of
what was nothing less than ritual art.
Written entirely on one note, with the conductors themselves involved in
shouting, chanting, miming in silence (God knows what the Radio 3 listeners
made of that), with a staggering range of orchestral sounds embracing haunting
woodwind, baying brass and a terrifying crescendo on basses that was like a
fleet of approaching bombers, and bass Stephen Richardson intoning and yelling
like a demented Tibetan monk, the whole thing was awesome in its primal effect.
Jerzy Maksymiuk conducted the rest of the superb programme, including
high-energy performances of Messiaen's Oiseaux Exotiques (with pianist Rolf
Hind) and Stravinsky's Symphony in Three Movements.
</TEXT>
