<HEADLINE>Victory for art gallery plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE inevitable was confirmed last night when the Post Office accepted a bid
from Glasgow Development Agency for its premises in the city's George Square.
It is understood the GDA, acting on behalf of trustees who want the building
for a National Gallery of Scottish Art and Design, paid #3m, which is reputedly
half the figure offered by an Aberdeen-based property developer.
Under the deal, the National Galleries of Scotland now has a 12-month option on
the premises.
Mr Kenneth Graham, chairman of the Scottish Post Office Board, denied that the
goalposts were changed to favour any bidder during the controversial sale
process.
Glasgow District Council leader Pat Lally, who supports the gallery plan, also
dismissed suggestions that the PO was pushed into accepting a lower tender.
``I do not accept that,'' he said, arguing that it was probable too many
conditions had been attached to any other offers.
He said: ``If the Post Office wanted to realise the asset at an early date,
then clearly the best bid was that which offered a speedy return. It is better
to have money in the hand than not at all.''
The PO 11th-hour decision to seek fresh bids last month led commercial
developer Jarlaw to call on the Scottish Office to intervene.
It had offered #4.5m, compared with the GDA's #3m, but the PO not only rejected
the bid, but announced new stipulations. These reduced retail and office floor
space by 20,000sq ft, slashing the commercial value, and included the
successful bidder having to provide a philatelic museum.
Jarlaw said then it would consider legal action against the Post Office,
arguing it treated unfairly.
Mr Graham, announcing the winner in Edinburgh, said the idea of a collaborative
venture was raised by the National Galleries' trustees during the evaluation
process, and went on: ``We decided to be even-handed to enable all interested
parties to develop their propositions.
``The best way forward was to give the opportunity to bidders to re-tender. The
goalposts were changed similarly for everybody.''
He insisted there was no pressure brought to bear by politicians in Glasgow,
adding: ``We would not accept any pressure and there is no way we would
tolerate bullying from anybody.''
Mr Graham declined to say how many bids were received, or give any details
about them.
The key issue had been the attractiveness of the GDA proposal. The Post Office
was not in the business of providing art galleries, and it had offered the
building for sale on commercial criteria.
``We have operated to those commerical criteria,'' said Mr Graham, who said
considerable thought was given to all bids. ``There is no doubt whatsoever in
our minds that the GDA's bid offered the best commercial package.''
Councillor Lally denied the PO had little choice but to accept a lower bid
because of fears that Jarlaw would not receive planning permission from Glasgow
District for its mainly retail and office development.
He said the firm, if it had won, would have been treated fairly by the local
authority, and been subjected only to planning regulations.
Councillor Lally said he was ``absolutely confident'' that the galleries will
be open in time for Glasgow's reign as City of Architecture and Design in 1999.
It is understood only two bids were received, with a second commercial
developer having dropped out after considering a bid of at least #5m.
GDA chief executive Stuart Gulliver said the decision was ``excellent news for
Glasgow and for Scotland''.
The PO, with a long tradition of supporting the arts, had taken an enlightened
and publicly-responsible view in respect of the sale of an important listed
building.
Mr Gulliver added the decision showed the PO recognised the importance for
Scotland of the creation of a national gallery, which would have a major impact
on the economy.
It is expected to attract 850,000 visitors a year, plough #17m into the
economy, and create up to 400 jobs.
Mr Angus Grossart, chairman of the Trustees of the National Galleries of
Scotland, said the decision was ``a significant step towards creating a
National Gallery in Glasgow by the new millenium.''
The GDA, to allow the proposals to proceed, has offered the building to the
trustees on a 12-month option.
Mr Timothy Clifford, director of the National Galleries of Scotland, conceded
that the project was still a long way from completion, but added: ``Securing
the preferred building is a major step forward.''
Directors of Jarlaw were unavailable for comment last night. In their protest
to Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch, it was argued the original sale
process had been ``in a manner not normally associated with the disposal of
surplus Government property''.
The PO said the agreement will allow the transfer of most of its #500m
philatelic collection and museum of postal history from cramped conditions in
London to Glasgow.
</TEXT>
