<DOCNO>GH951118-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hi-tech firm in #160m jobs boost</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN investment of #160m which will create 235 jobs over four years was announced
yesterday by Shin-Etsu Handotai Europe Ltd when it signalled the start of the
third phase of its factory at Livingston, West Lothian.
The company, the world's largest producer of semi-conductor silicon wafers,
arrived at Livingston in 1984 and employs 300 people. The new project will
bring the total workforce to 540. The additional jobs will be mainly for
process operators, technicians, and engineers.
The new project involves the construction of a 14,000sq m plant next to the
present plant.
The European semi-conductor market had grown dramatically, not only because of
the computer business but also due to a great upsurge in telecommunications and
automotive applications.
Mr George Kynoch, Scottish Industry Minister, said Shin-Etsu's announcement
came at the end of what was possibly the best week so far for good news in the
Scottish electronics industry.
After the announcements on Monday at Motorola in East Kilbride and the Chunghwa
announcement in Glasgow on Tuesday, it showed how, not bad news, but good news
came in threes, reversing old folk beliefs.
He said: ``More and more, our businesses are committing themselves to training
and to re-investment and this in turn creates an improved business confidence,
and re-affirms the correctness of choosing Scotland as a business location.'
</TEXT>
