<HEADLINE>Major launches offensive on two fronts as he tackles constitutional problems All-out for progress on Ulster</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister will attempt to relaunch the Ulster peace process this
weekend.
He will present fresh proposals to Irish Prime Minister John Bruton aimed at
breaking the deadlock over IRA arms decommissioning.
Mr Major will speak to Mr Bruton next week and hopes to set a date for a
UK-Irish summit, to replace the one that was abruptly cancelled by Mr Bruton
two months ago.
Britain proposes to revive the ``twin-track'' approach, which would see the
appointment of an international commission to examine the weapons issue, while
allowing preparatory talks with the Ulster parties in advance of all-party
talks.
The same proposals were on the table for the September summit, but the Irish
Government declined to participate after Sinn Fein warned the plan would be
unacceptable. The Republicans reject the British demand that the IRA give up
weapons before all-party talks can begin.
Mr Major said yesterday: ``I will put these proposals to Mr Bruton. We will
then look for an early summit date.'' He reiterated his insistence that Sinn
Fein would have to compromise on weapons.
``Sinn Fein have been taking a very hard line on negotiations for some time.
What Sinn Fein have been saying about seeking peace I very much hope they mean,
but they still have a long way to go,'' he said.
``I hope we will be able to get Sinn Fein into talks with the other parties.
That has been the intention from the beginning. But Sinn Fein have to accept
that they have to make concessions.
``It is not possible to enter into negotiations with a private army at your
back. They must realise that that isn't the way to get into democratic
politics.''
Downing Street emphasised that Sinn Fein should not be allowed to have a veto
over the peace process. Britain's proposals, a Government source said, were
``extremely reasonable''.
However, Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams warned that the process could collapse
through British refusal to allow all-party talks, and that the conflict could
``re-occur'' after 15 months of uninterrupted ceasefire.
``I think it is patently clear that the British succeeded in making the peace
process a high-wire act. That high-wire is now stretched like elastic,'' he
said.
The Government was last night under pressure to quicken the pace of prisoner
releases in Northern Ireland. Loyalist prisoner pressure groups warned that
there would be no political settlement until all the jailed paramilitaries were
out.
Eighty men and three women at the top security Maze and two other jails were
yesterday freed early under a revised 50% remission scheme introduced to try to
develop the peace process.
John Heaney, from Armagh, who served six-and-a-half years for a terrorist
offence, was the first to walk out. He embraced his wife and young daughter but
would not comment.
Outside the gates, banner-waving relatives and friends of opposing factions
stood only yards apart to cheer and hug prisoners as they walked free.
The 200 lifers do not qualify. Around 850 men and women with paramilitary links
are still in prison.
The Irish Government welcomed the releases, but the Democratic Unionist leader,
Dr Ian Paisley, claimed it was a move by the Government to keep the IRA and
loyalist ceasefires in place.
He told a meeting in Enniskillen, County Fermanagh: ``They have embarked upon a
policy of the most cunning evil to deprive the people of Northern Ireland of
their British rights, heritage, and way of life.''
q A man who was beaten and abducted by an armed gang said yesterday that he was
roped to a tree for 24 hours and questioned repeatedly. John Hegarty, 19, from
Strabane, County Tyrone, said he escaped after struggling free from his bonds.
It is believed the Provisionals wanted to know if he had any part in an armed
raid at a church community centre when #17,000 in Christmas savings was stolen
at the end of last month.
