<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baby boomers come of age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CATHERINE sloyan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S difficult to imagine Diana Moran as old. She of the famous green leotard,
flawless complexion and ever-youthful charm becoming stooped, wrinkled and
doddery. Well that's what old ladies are like isn't it?
Happily, Moran is still in her prime, but by current standards at 56 years old
she is positively geriatric to be a model fronting an international campaign
for a beauty product.
Having survived breast cancer and a double mastectomy and endured depression
after her new husband left her for a younger woman, she's come out on top.
Despite her trials, in a way she's lucky. Lucky to have been born when she was,
one of the first baby boomers, a generation now in their 40s and 50s.
Growing up in a time of unprecedented economic growth, those baby boomers
became the first real teenagers, the rebels who invented rock'n'roll and later
thrilled at the outrage their short skirts, long hair and free love caused
their parents.
Those first teenagers are now middle-aged and because of their sheer numbers
and relative affluence, they represent a vital market for consumer products and
services.
``The choice of a woman in her fifties to sell a beauty product is
ground-breaking,'' says Moran. Television viewers see a radiant woman of a
certain age explaining how Ulay's Pro-vital keeps her skin fresh and vibrant -
not young-looking - and yes, there are visible lines ascending from her lips
and a soft-focus camera lens does not try to hide them.
A survey of 50-plus women for the cosmetics industry revealed that mature women
are fed up of seeing images of flawless youth selling consumer products for
mature women. They want models of their own age portraying mature beauty.
``It's a massive international campaign and the reaction of women on the street
everywhere has been tremendous,'' says Moran, brimming with delight at her good
luck.
Moran is up there in the vanguard along with Catherine Deneuve and Lauren
Hutton, creating role models of mature beauty to assure that vast middle-aged
market that you don't have to be young to be desirable.
Mike Hepworth knows nothing of face creams. As a leading expert in the field of
ageing and sociologist at the University of Aberdeen, he knows about the
demographics and economics of the world's ageing population. ``These new
mid-lifers are not going to grow old in the way their parents did. They have a
more vigorous attitude towards ageing, they have more resources and higher
expectations and they won't be content to sit back and grow old gracefully and
disengage from society.
``What's happening now is there are fewer younger people and generally they
have less money to spend and the balance of consumer power is shifting.
Increasingly, people who make consumer products and provide services see the
middle-aged as an important group to target. In fact, it's now argued in the US
that unless firms target that middle-aged market, they won't survive.''
All very well for the Jollies (Jetset Oldies with Lots of Loot) in this brave
new world, but what about the rest, grimly brave at the prospect of growing old
in the youth culture they created. Those in work are warily looking over their
shoulders at ``wunderkind'' ready to jump into their jobs at the next round of
redundancies. Those sixties rebels who bandied the slogan ``Never trust anyone
over 30'' are now haunted by the spectre of ageism.
Always difficult to prove, ageism today is rife. A survey by Gallup for the
Brook Street Bureau found that up to 90% of employers discriminate against the
over-35s. The Carnegie Trust, which researches into aspects of ageing, says
employer prejudice is holding back Britain's economic recovery. Mike Hepworth
cautions: ``If the prime market for consumer goods and services becomes too
insecure to spend, recovery could be a long time coming.
``Because of the way the population is changing, we need older people as a
resource more than ever before, but we haven't got rid of the age prejudice
that comes out of this youth culture.
``Age prejudice is based on a belief that as people get older they lose the
ability to perform tasks; they become less flexible; they can't learn new
things. All this is a myth deeply embedded in society, especially in a time of
rapid technological change. Research shows over and over again that older
people are perfectly capable of adapting and learning throughout the entire
life course.''
Some far-sighted companies, seeing the future shortfall in potential employees
and the advantages in available labour, have adopted policies of employing
older people, and not just to stack shelves. B&amp;Q's chairman, Jim Hodkinson,
himself now 51, has recently extended his company's policy of hiring over-50s
to retail management.
While we wait to see what happens at the sharp end of the generation
battlefield, Moran, now a female icon for that not-so-wrinkly baby-boomer
generation is defiant.
``Ageing is more a problem for the young than the middle-aged. It's youth's
perception of old age that's all wrong. They see only the things that we appear
to be losing. They think that 60 is way over-the-hill and that we are flabby
wrinklies who are losing our memories, our energy and even our interest in sex.
``In three and a half years I'll be 60 and I can assure you that I will not be
written off. For my generation, so long as we keep our health and fitness and
we have some disposable income, the world is still there for us. We have more
time for ourselves to do at last the things we really want to do. And those
youngsters don't know about the surge of energy a woman gets after 50.
``Another hidden bonus that maturity brings is a new-found confidence. The
older you are, the stronger you become. It's a wonderful time of life. We must
change the pathetic image to match the reality.''
Can't you just imagine what she might have been like in the sixties? Afghan
coat and jockey cap waving a placard and railing against social injustice, the
bomb, the war or out-dated values of an old-fashioned, fuddy-duddy regime?
Today Moran is a defiant spokesperson for Age Power, a soon-to-be-launched
national network of clubs for anyone over 49.
``There'll be no upper age limit, and mature people will come together to learn
about health, fitness, finance, the arts, computers, everything we need to keep
in touch and buzzing and bring more quality to our lives after 49,'' Moran
enthuses, no doubt sure there'll be a few whinges about the younger generation.
Hepworth, himself a few years older and no doubt wiser than those first
teenagers adds: ``The baby boomers are once again causing a stir. They're
re-inventing middle-age and demanding a more positive attitude to ageing.
``They've always been a loud and visible group with high expectations and the
power to change what they don't like. They are already changing attitudes
towards later life and helping to improve the quality of it.''
n.See Diana Moran and Mike Hepworth on The Good News About Ageing, a special
edition of Grampian Television's One Life To Live on Sunday, December 3, at
5.55.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lunch first and then we'll take Berlin</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In Berlin lunch is delightful. The city exudes a sense of the risqu, a
Bohemian permissiveness. But the restaurants are elegant, the food surprisingly
adventurous and the wine list so extensive you can effortlessly avoid polluting
your taste buds with the sickly or insipid German variety.
Also German professionals seem more interesting than those at home. I am sure
they care about where Borussia Dortmund is lying in the league or the problems
of their golf handicap but, thankfully, they tend to keep these concerns to
themselves. They would much rather discuss the single currency or their
country's place in Europe. I know this attitude would disqualify them from
appearing on any programme out of Cowcaddens but it makes a refreshing change
from 100 women discussing the menopause.
What is uncomfortable, however, is the growing Anglophobia. In short, we Brits
are not popular.
For those who wondered what the Germans were obsessed with, when not on holiday
skulking around to place their towels next to the swimming pool, I can tell
you. It is Perfidious Albion.
I arrived at a bad time, mind you. The papers were full of Germans, worried
about the future of the Deutschmark, secreting money in Swiss bonds. There has
not been such vigorous cross-border activity since the Nazis plundered Europe's
treasures for posterity or their pension plan, which ever came first.
Then there was the news that billions of marks were making another exodus, this
time to UK shores for investing in industry. Hard on their heels whole
companies were preparing a flit to take advantage of our low labour costs.
Furthermore, John Major has been colluding with Jacques Chirac to undermine the
Fourth Reich, currently operating under the guise of the European Union.
Neither wants a federalist Europe so they have been chummy, and are prepared to
stick the stiletto in Chancellor Kohl at the appropriate time.
All of which makes you rather proud to be British. I haven't felt this way
since Margaret Thatcher bestrode the globe and we were all able to command
large sums of currency from foreign banks in exchange for a few dog-eared pound
notes.
My lunchtime companions were an economist, a lawyer - both women - and a trade
unionist who could not eat his meal because he was so upset. It was ``unfair'',
they chanted, that we were taking das Brot from their mouths when they had the
problems of unification with the East, were Europe's biggest paymasters and
were doing their best to make the EU uberglucklich, which may sound
uncomfortable but actually means blissfully happy.
(I hadn't the heart to tell them we were uberglucklich already after hearing
that Chunghwa, the Taiwanese company, was bringing 3300 jobs to Mossend because
of lower labour costs, skilled workers and an excellent infrastructure).
It seemed the wrong thing to say that we must be doing something right if we
are able to put one over on the strongest economy in Europe but I said it
anyway. The reaction was similar to Arthur Scargill turning up to a cheese and
wine party at the Blairs.
``Nein, nein,'' was the anguished cry. This was the equivalent, they said, if I
may loosely translate, of robbing Helmut to pay Fritz.
We were all in a sinking tub together and the only way to patch it up was a
stability pact, something dreamt up by Theo Waigel, the German finance
minister, and Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank President. It is a real wheeze.
The plan is to punish with fines those countries which do not run their
economies properly and pile up budget deficits after they have joined the
single currency.
It would mean we would lose all sovereignty over taxation, fiscal policy,
spending and borrowing. They smugly announced this will be presented at the
Euro Summit in Madrid next month. (As my trade union friend played with his
bratwurst my thoughts wandered to Alex Salmond and his contention that we would
all be better off with independence in Europe.)
Of course, this passion for closer union has little to do with providing more
jobs in Drumchapel, more to do with the Deutschmark. They are paranoid about
it. Maybe they have reason after the inflationary excess of the thirties which
made the 27% rate achieved by the last Labour government - almost as distant a
memory - seem prudent.
Opinion polls show overwhelmingly that the majority of Germans are reluctant to
exchange the Deutschmark for a single currency. Now the opposition Social
Democrats are exploiting the formerly taboo subject of the European Monetary
System for political ends.
But this will do nothing for the unemployment which bedevils their continent
with one in 10 out of work - one in five if you are under 25, although to be
fair they don't have a Gordon Brown to propose starving youngsters into a job.
Nevertheless in America unemployment is lower than 6% and just more than 3% in
Japan.
When will they ever learn the problem is that labour is taxed too heavily in
Europe? In America and Japan taxes and social security contributions add up to
about 30% of GDP. In the EU it is more than 40% ranging from Britain - with the
lowest at 33% - to Denmark with 52%. Add to that the regulations which bind
business and it is obvious that Europe's problems are structural, not cyclical.
Meddling economics are the bane of every nation's life. If we had an
independent bank like the Bundesbank, Eddie George would have raised interest
rates months ago. It would have spelled disaster and everyone now recognises
these should be cut. Economists yesterday expressed surprise at the healthier
state of the UK's public sector borrowing requirement. What baloney. Don't they
know that corporation tax is usually paid in October and that the sum would be
significant because of high growth last year? And because borrowing is down the
Chancellor is now able to leave more of our pay in our pockets. Now there's a
further surprise.
Cut taxes. Cut interest rates. Cut public borrowing. Pass me a glass of
Riesling.
</TEXT>
