<HEADLINE>Bold boys in black</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323156</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE REFEREE
THE ROOM was dimly lit, feet shuffled embarrassingly, an awkward silence
gradually pervaded the air. Eventually, one man stood up, head bowed, and
blurted out ``I admit it: I am a referee'', and sat down to warm applause.
Fantasy, of course, but Referees Anonymous might not be such a bad notion for a
group of men whose fondness for the traumas of football arbitration sets them
as a race apart, a kind of masochistic order whose inner workings will forever
remain impenetrable.
They are a motley collection of architects, lawyers, builders, plumbers and
social workers who discard their rational personnae on a Saturday afternoon to
perform the modern version of the Christians having a day out at the Colosseum.
Unlike the Christians, however, they volunteer. They do get paid, a princely
#130 for League matches, more for Cup games, but the verbal assault they endure
would persuade very few sane adults to work for that money.
Who would be a referee? The answer seems to be failed players or, at least,
young men who had the honesty to recognise they were never going to be good
enough to earn a living playing the game. No matter how many you talk to, you
will discover a common denominator - the desire to be involved in football,
somehow.
``It is really just love of football,'' was how Kenny Hope, former top ref and
now one of the referee supervisors employed by the SFA, put it. ``And no matter
how many people mock that ideal, it is the truth. Football is in their blood
and they want to take part, to give something to it.
``You may have to be a born referee, to have the grit and guts to face up to
the life. They have to put up with a lot but they would tell you it is worth
it.'' That ``lot'' can vary from experience to experience but most of the
referees who make it to Grade 1 status have had some hairy moments in their
early days.
One current premier ref, who prefers to remain anonymous in the current glare
of publicity following last weekend's controversy at Ibrox, recalls his early
times with a shudder, particularly trying to cope with amateur football.
``It can be quite terrifying sometimes,'' he said, ``and funny in hindsight.
``For example, I was not alone in having to dodge a car trying to run me over
in the carpark after a game but one of the funniest incidents, although not at
the time, happened after one amateur game when there had been problems on the
park.
``After the game the secretary came to pay me. When I opened the door, standing
in my spruce blazer and flannels, a bucket of water went over me. I wasn't
laughing at the time, I can tell you.''
He also remembered one match in Glasgow during which he genuinely did not
believe he was going to get out alive and sent out a message for police help
before the game was ended.
Is the love of the game worth all of this? His own view would suggest that the
camaraderie among the refs themselves is one good reason for sticking with it.
``The fun comes in the togetherness we feel as a society, a fraternity. We are
a close-knit bunch, you know. Anyway, the truth is that people don't like us,
but only for 90 minutes. When we bump into fans off the field we find that they
just want to talk about the game. The hatred is gone.'' There may have been a
touch of self-comfort in those remarks, even self-delusion, but in his position
you might seek some solace beyond #130.
Kenny Hope has been luckier than most of his peers, not having experienced some
of the excesses that even Grade 1 men suffer.
Davie Syme, for example, was locked in his dressing room at Tynecastle after
one game during which he did not seem to endear himself to the home
aficionados. Much play was made of rumours that a director had been the turnkey
but the mystery, if it was such, never was officially unravelled.
Another leading light had to stand by while his door was kicked in at half time
by a prominent manager demanding answers to questions. The man's team was
winning 3-0 at the time, too.
Stories of severe intimidation by the most renowned managers are part of the
game's folklore and, if some are apocryphal, others are unquestionably true.
Another well-known ref can recall once when one manager awaited him at the edge
of the tunnel after a major game in which there had been a few controversial
happenings.
``I knew what he was waiting for, all right, but I stood still and waited for
him to move. When he moved I moved until we got to my dressing room. Before he
could say anything I said: ``If you want to speak to me *!*! off! and shut the
door. He cooled down and actually thanked me later on.''
Tales of threatened muggings are pretty normal in their bizarre world but one
man in the middle has a rather unusual recollection of such an instance. ``It
was in the Emirates, I ordered a player off but he refused to go, saying `My
father is a sheikh'. I told him I didn't care if his father was the Archbishop
of Canterbury, he was going off.
``When we were leaving the field he was waiting for me, dressed in all his
glory. But I spotted the open-toed sandals and unfortunately slipped and stood
on his foot in my boots. I never saw him again.''
Supervisor Kenny Hope is at pains to point out that his job now is not to
``crucify'' referees from his perch in the stand. ``We are there to help him. I
tell you this, I feel a great deal of sympathy for the lads nowadays, with the
scrutiny they come under, bearing in mind there are TV cameras at every corner
of the ground, taking in every incident, on and off the ball. The referee still
has to make his mind up immediately, whereas people like yourself can study
tapes as many times as you like before offering an opinion. I don't believe the
public would want a game held up to see TV replays, like American football. It
would lose its momentum.
``The referee gives his decision honestly, right or wrong. Personally, I would
like to stay with that.''
Yet one of his own roles is to fill in a form after each match, pointing out
any errors made by the officials. He would argue that this is so that the
referee can learn from mistakes. The supervisor would also include incidents,
such as violence, that the referee had missed in his report. ``That is not done
to persecute a player but as a normal section of the report. I have never been
asked by the SFA to put in a special report on any incident.''
If the major battle any referee always fights is against criticism, he also has
to be staunchly principled, particularly abroad. It is not unknown for
chicanery to be afoot when the man in the middle plays such an influential part
in any game. Currently, a Dutch referee is suspended pending investigation of
alleged betting irregularities which supposedly involved his having bets on
games he refereed.
Others have taken substantial bribes, sometimes in kind rather than cash, and
if you imagine corruption has been entirely erased listen to the recent tale of
one Scot who, understandably, also wishes to be anonymous.
``Only once in my time have I had to face up to that kind of persuasion and
that was abroad. The chairman of the club concerned made it quite clear that
there would be substantial reward if the result went the way he wanted. In
effect, he asked me to cheat.
``When the result turned out to be different from what he requested, neither he
nor his fellow officials turned up at the after-match dinner they had arranged
for us. I think he took the huff.''
Jim McCluskey, who has been one of the leading lights in Scotland, is one of
the few referees who played the game at senior level. McCluskey was an Airdrie
signing but had to give up the game when he was 26 because of injury. ``I
suppose the next best thing was refereeing, but it is a long way behind
playing,'' he says.
Players past and present have had an ambivalent relationship with the man in
the middle, but Tony Higgins, secretary of the Scottish Professional Players'
Association, believes that, in the end, they will all ask only that referees be
honest.
``There is immense presure on them now, more than ever before because of the
sophisticated cameras that cover games and all they can do is to act honestly.''
Higgins, who was one of the original gentle giants as a player, recalls one of
the six times he was booked in his 17-year career and still has a chuckle.
``I was getting a wee bit thicker round the waist by then. The referee gave a
foul against me during a game with Stranraer against Albion Rovers but it was
so obvious the decision should have been the other way that I started slapping
my thighs with laughter.
``You can't be serious,'' I said, but he threatened to send me off if I didn't
stop. I replied: ``If you do you'll have to tell the SFA you ordered me off for
laughing. I think he saw what I meant.''
Finally, if there is anyone left out there who wishes to enter the profession,
here is the official supporters guide to the perfect credentials:
n Birth details: parents unknown.
n Religion: Bluenose/fenian.
n IQ: Chimpanzee status.
n Identifying features: Poor vision, autocratic bearing, orange streak down one
arm, green down the other.
n Favourite author: Marquis de Sade.
n Role model: Willie Miller.
n Clothes: Hair-shirt.
n Food: Lemon or orange sorbet.
Laugh we may, but without them there is no ball game.
Ian Paul
</TEXT>
