<HEADLINE>Missing bones may remain a mystery, judge tells jury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323157</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JURORS trying Rosemary West on 10 counts of murder were told yesterday that the
mystery of the missing bones might never be resolved.
``It is one of these holes in the case that will never be filled,'' Mr Justice
Mantell declared, continuing his summing up.
Winchester Crown Court has been told that the bodies of young girls and women
were mutilated and, when their remains were unearthed at 25 Cromwell Street,
Gloucester, many bones were missing.
The judge said yesterday the jury might think they were removed routinely -
``for what reason, who knows?'' Frequently, one or both kneecaps were not
there. In some cases, the great majority of wrist, ankle, finger, and toe bones
were missing.
The judge has told the jury that they might just have been able to understand
the horrific proposition that the feet and hands had been removed in their
entirety.
However, that could not be the case, as not all bones from the feet and hands
were missing. This could only have been the result of deliberate mutilation,
said Mr Justice Mantell.
``To what end was it done?'' he asked. ``Was it before or after death. Who
knows? Perhaps, like me, you would prefer to believe it was after death.''
There was no evidence as to why the bones were missing. The only fact was that
they were.
In that case, the jury would have to consider the length of time involved and
what preparation had to be made in advance and what steps had to be taken
afterwards.
The Crown alleges that the killings and mutilations at 25 Cromwell Street could
not have happened without the knowledge of Mrs West.
Mrs West pleads not guilty to 10 counts of murder, including that of her
daughter, Heather, who disappeared, aged 16, and her stepdaughter, Charmaine,
who was aged eight when she went missing.
Continuing his summing up in chronological order, Mr Justice Mantell said
Frederick West attended Gloucester Royal Hospital for treatment to a hand
laceration on January 3, 1974. The judge pointed out that one of the victims,
Ms Lucy Partington, disappeared on December 27, 1973.
The prosecution suggests, he said, it was not coincidental that West required
hospital treatment a few days after her disappearance. A knife was found along
with her remains. Mr Justice Mantell told the jury he was afraid that the
assumption involved the grisly conclusion, one that the jury would have to
consider, that Ms Partington had been kept alive for a period of time before
being killed.
Alternatively, her body had been kept for some days before it was mutilated.
Either way, the Crown contended it would be quite impossible for Mrs West not
to have known of her presence.
Alternatively, the defence point out that her stepdaughter, Mrs Anne Marie
Davis, had lived at 25 Cromwell Street for most of the time and she had known
nothing.
The judge said the taped police interview by West would seem to contain a
number of lies. The Crown had stated that his story that he had known Ms
Partington for some months before killing her was clearly untrue.
The jury would have to consider that, if West was solely responsible for
killing Partington, as he claimed, why was it necessary to rewrite the script.
``Unless, say the prosecution, he was trying to wipe out the part played by
Rosemary West,'' the judge said. Even if West had lied, it did not take the
jury the full distance. He said the prosecution had to make them sure Mrs West
did participate in the killings.
The judge told the jury that, while Mrs West had latterly chosen not to respond
to police questions, they should draw no adverse conclusions from that. ``She
is perfectly entitled to do that,'' he said.
Dealing with the murder of Heather, found decapitated and dismembered, he
referred the jury to Mrs West's reaction when told her husband had confessed.
Defence counsel had described the response as that of a woman greatly
distressed, while the prosecution said it was an ``Oscar-winning performance'',
as were the tears the jury had seen cried by Mrs West from time to time at the
mention of Heather.
The seven-week trial was adjourned until Monday morning, when the judge will
complete his summing up and send out the jury to consider its verdicts.
The jury have been told to bring overnight suitcases.
</TEXT>
