<HEADLINE>Bringing on a nervous breakdown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323158</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHECK-IN
n.NOT that we'd blame those doom-laden RAC adverts, where the super chic female
doctor gets stranded on an evil stretch of dockland obviously left over from
the set of Blade Runner, helplessly waiting to be rescued by the dashing
mechanic on the motorbike, but we are at a stage where six out of seven women
say they would fear for their safety if their cars did break down.
This is according to research by Autoglass, which has teamed up with the Suzy
Lamplugh Trust to offer a safety checklist for female motorists. They also
pledge to treat lone women callers as a priority; they will be along within 90
minutes to fit a new windscreen. Suzy Lamplugh Trust, the charity for personal
safety, is on 0181 392 1839.
n.A HEARTFELT plea from Maggie Fulton, old girl of Notre Dame High School in
Dowanhill, Glasgow, alma mater of such as Maria Fyfe MP and opera singer
Josephine McQueen, now the only local authority all-girls school in
Strathclyde, and fast approaching its centenary in 1997.
If details of the celebrations have been hush-hush up to now it may be because
such loyal graft as Fulton's, who is putting together a centenary book, often
goes unnoticed, in life as in newspapers. However, events include a Centenary
Mass, celebrated by Cardinal Winning; City Chambers civic reception; concert;
open day; time capsule; and a slap-up dinner at the Moat House. Maggie Fulton
would like to hear from past pupils with stories for the book. Contact her on
0141 632 8810.
n.SHAME on publishers Routledge, whose impenetrable press release advertising
its sparky new publication, Working with Men: Feminism and Social Work,
contains some horrendous spelling errors - it's writeen (sic) by feminists,
understaking (sic) to overturn the view that men are responsible for their own
recontruction (sic) and yet manages to keep a straight face while stating:
``The contributors conclude that direct work with men is a legitimate feminist
activity.'' Well, that's a relief. I thought I'd never be able to set foot in
the office again.
n.FOR those of you who thought hosting a party meant nipping down to Marks &amp;
Sparks and stocking up on the salmon roulade bites, or down to the offie for a
12-pack of Tennents, comes good news in the shape of ``top party designer and
caterer'' Johnny Roxburgh. He arrives highly recommended in the form of a press
release from posh people's magazine Tatler, and just happens to be popping in
to Frasers in Glasgow next Wednesday, 1.30pm to 4pm.
A cheery soul, Johnny ``will charm even the most party shy into holding the
event of the year'' with such advice as: ``DON'T have paper napkins''; ``DO
have great soap and lots of loo paper and towels''; ``DO have serious ice'' (as
opposed to the frivolous sort, always cracking up, I suppose) and, amazingly,
``Invite good friends''.
n.SPOTLIGHT on la femme francaise in the French Film Festival showing at the
Edinburgh Filmhouse and the GFT from next Friday. Women directors give us,
respectively, a love triangle with a difference (bored housewife runs off with
another woman in Josiane Balasko's much-talked about Gazon Maudit); Thelma and
Louise on HRT (Personne Ne M'aime from Marion Vernoux) and what sounds like the
Famous Five save Maman from adultery when passions rise during a small-town
amateur dramatics production (Dieu, L'amant De Ma Mere Et Le Fils Du
Charcutier). And there's lots more to offer in films concentrating on the
momentous things life has to offer - love, childbirth, infidelity, fast food,
and Daniel Auteil. Details on 0141 332 8128 and 0131 228 2688.
</TEXT>
