<HEADLINE>Washington, Friday Budget impasse may be easing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323159</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HIGH stakes test of strength between President Clinton and Congress showed
signs of easing tonight, even as the President prepared to veto the latest
Republican plan to end a budget crisis and instead came up with a plan of his
own.
Repeating his vow to veto a second temporary funding Bill drawn up by the
Republicans, Clinton sent Congress his own stopgap measure aimed at ending a
four-day government shutdown.
``I urge the Congress to act on this legislation promptly and to return it to
me for signing,'' he said in a message to Congress.
The first breath of compromise came earlier from Senate Democratic leader Tom
Daschle, who said the President might be willing to back off demands for a
funding law free of any of the strings demanded by Republican leaders.
He predicted that ``a middle ground'' would be found, with Clinton backing off
his demand for a ``clean'' Bill and the Republicans moving away from their
``hardcore, hardline'' demand that the US budget be balanced within seven years.
However the White House today stuck to the decision to veto the funding law
passed on Thursday. ``We expect the Bill will arrive sometime today, we don't
know when. When it does the President, having announced yesterday he will veto
the legislation, will veto the legislation,'' said White House spokesman Mike
McCurry.-Reuter
</TEXT>
