<HEADLINE>Armed killers captured on camera repaired by victim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323160</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE armed robbers were jailed for life yesterday for the murder of a repair
man shot in the back while he lay on the ground during a jewellery shop raid.
Mr Leyland Hoppie, 46, had been repairing a security camera minutes before the
shooting. A video tape recovered from the camera helped capture his killers.
``It is a fortunate irony in the murder of Mr Hoppie that it was his work in
the shop that day which helped to bring these three defendants to justice,''
prosecutor Nigel Sweeney told the Old Bailey in London.
After the shooting in September last year, Shiraz Bhayat, 21, Neville Andrews,
27, and Junior Willis, 27, ran off with jewels worth more than #15,000 and a
security camera - but not the one Mr Hoppie had just repaired.
It recorded the trio bursting into RSA Jewellers in Green Lanes, Ilford.
Mr Hoppie, from Wisbech, Cambridge, was forced to the ground at gunpoint.
``He was shot in the back at close range as he lay on the ground defenceless,''
Mr Sweeney said. The pellets entered his back to a depth of almost 14cms -
severing his spine. He died soon after despite the efforts of a doctor and
paramedics flown to the scene by helicopter to save him.
During the trial, the jury was shown a double-barrelled sawn-off shotgun, said
to be the murder weapon carried by Willis, and also a .38 Smith and Wesson
revolver, carried by Bhayat.
Bhayat, of Bouverie Road, and Andrews, of Glenmar Road, both Stoke Newington,
north London, and Willis, of Mulberry Court, Leyton, east London, had denied
murder, robbery, and firearms offences. They showed no emotion as the jury,
reduced to 11 by illness, returned its verdicts after two-days of deliberations.
As they were led to the cells, people in the gallery of the court shouted abuse
and cried ``racist.'' All three defendants are coloured and their victim was
black.
The Common Serjeant of London, Judge Neil Denison, apologised to the jurors for
the outburst and advised them to leave the Old Bailey by the rear entrance in
case there was any trouble.
After their verdicts, the jury heard that all three men had convictions for
robberies and in Bhayat's case his record included two knifepoint robberies on
jewellers.
Bhayat claimed in the witness box that he had not been on the robbery and had
spent the day at home. The other two did not give evidence.
After the verdicts, the victim's brother, Mr Stephen Hoppie, said: ``I would
like to remember him as he was, somebody caring, somebody who was kind and who
thought about other people.''
</TEXT>
