<HEADLINE>Home growers of cannabis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WOULD like to thank all those friends and associates who have given us their
unreserved support over the past year and who are baffled at what purpose can
be served by the the sentence of 18 months' imprisonment imposed on my wife
Rosalind for growing cannabis for her own use.
The courts maintain that the provisions of the Misuse of Drugs Act, 1971,
compel them to treat this offence seriously and to show no mercy to cannabis
growers.
Clearly one result of the sentence is that it has stopped Rosalind growing and
using the drug but this could have been achieved at minimal public expense by a
police warning as would have happened had the offence been committed in many
parts of England.
It is unlikely to have any effect on the general level of cannabis usage when
considered along with the approach adopted by the Scottish police who told the
Scottish Affairs Committee last year that they targeted dealers but simple
possession cases came to light as a result of the investigation of other
offences such as burglary (sic) or breach of the peace, when the offender in
question happened also to be in possession of cannabis.
Given the provisions of the Act the sentence was specifically directed at
deterring home growers of cannabis. No doubt it will make cannabis users who
are contemplating growing it think twice. Users who already grow their own may
well cease doing so and return to the black market for their supply.
In effect the courts have found themselves compelled to protect the illicit
cannabis market, a consequence which must have been far from the minds of those
who drafted the legislation.
There are similar statutory provisions against the home production of whisky.
This analogy was drawn on by Bill Walker, MP, in a futile attempt to justify
the sentence.
The licensed manufacture of whisky is a legitimate business providing
considerable revenue to the state which it is entitled to protect. The cannabis
market, estimated to gross some #2.2billion in the United Kingdom annually,
only lines the pockets of organised crime.
Worldwide other countries are reappraising policy on cannabis. In Europe states
which have adopted a more pragmatic approach to the problem such as Italy,
Spain, Switzerland, the Netherlands, and parts of Germany have recognised the
absurdity of relaxing the law against cannabis users while protecting the
dealers' market by prohibiting home growing and have made provision for
grower/users to be treated in the same way as users.
The court's hands are tied by the provisions of the Act. Clearly it is contrary
to any conceivable drugs policy to provide statutory protection for the illicit
market. This unforeseen anomaly demands the urgent attention of Parliament.
Keith Henderson,
Advocate,
Advocates Library,
Parliament House,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
