<HEADLINE>World-weary cynic just perfect for a desert island</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LET us for a moment play Desert Island discs with the Bible. You are about to
be shipwrecked in the Pacific Ocean (for the purposes of this wheeze it is
warmer and there are more islands to provide shelter). You are carrying a set
of scrolls and a book of the Bible is written upon each, just as it was with
the originals which were written and assembled at different times and
situations.
However, the snag is that you can take only three scrolls with you since the
weight of more would sink the flimsy raft upon which you are hoping to reach
the shore. Which three scrolls would you take? I have no doubts about my choice.
My three would consist of an Old Testament book, an epistle, and a gospel, not
necessarily for liturgical reasons but it would be a nice balance. These would
be the book of Ecclesiastes, the First Epistle to the Corinthians, and the
gospel of Mark. I am now trying to discern why I made these choices.
The choice of Mark is easy to explain. It is generally thought to be the
earliest gospel and therefore closest to the events it describes, unadorned by
retrospective theologising.
It presents a very human Jesus and tells the gospel story dramatically but
concisely (as the actor Alec McOwen demonstrated when he rendered it as a
one-man play). First Corinthians is also easy to explain. It packs into its 16
chapters reflections on death, love, and practical advice about how to deal
with the quarrels which seem to be integral to church life then and now.
The passages on death and love are among the finest Paul ever penned and
especially so when read in the English translation made by William Tyndale in
the early 1500s and poached by the compilers of the King James Bible nearly a
century later. ``O Death where is thy sting?...... Charity suffereth long and
is kind......''
My third choice is probably a less popular one, but if ever there was a book
for our age, Ecclesiastes is it. Some people consider it is ``not Christian''
but that seems to me a bit silly since it belongs to the Jewish canon and a bit
impudent to imagine it ever would be.
When I get especially exasperated with fundamentalists or revisionist zealots
who want a gay gospel or to rewrite the Ten Commandments as a charter of animal
rights, I turn to Ecclesiastes. His world-weary cynicism is a perfect antidote
to these fanatics and their silly obsessions. ``Vanity, vanity - all is
vanity,'' he observes.
The preacher/teacher who is the author of Ecclesiastes is a sane voice amid
fanaticism, a balanced view and a pragmatist who prefers wisdom to folly, but
is wise enough to know the limits of his wisdom. He lives for the present and
does not expect too much from either God or his fellow creatures.
He is far from politically correct (for example ``the heart of the wise
inclines to the right, but the heart of the fool to the left'' 10v2). His
ability with sound bites and one-liners is much sharper than the book of
Proverbs which it follows in the biblical canon. ``If the axe is dull and its
edge unsharpened, more strength is needed. But skill will bring success.''
Some modern translations render ``vanity'' as meaninglessness which, in my
view, makes the preacher into a nihilist. Perhaps vanity is not the best word,
but it conveys the sense of pretension and pomposity which I am certain is
intended. If ever there was a book to speak to our times it is this. To those
who think their religion or their atheism has all the answers: ``No man knows
whether love or hate awaits him...... as it is with those who take oaths, so it
is with those who are afraid to take them.''
To those who could not care less about the consequences of their actions is
there a better motto for conservationists than: ``as dead flies give perfume a
bad smell so a little folly outweighs wisdom.''
He has sensible advice for those who care too much about their cause or
campaign, what Richard Holloway in his excellent lecture this week on the
follies of fundamentalism identified as ``the provisionality of all systems,
symbols, and instruments''. He pointed out that this leads to a kind of
idolatry in which things which are relative are treated as if they are
absolutes.
There is much of Ecclesiastes about Bishop Holloway, the Episcopal Church's top
ecclesiastic. His thinking about the Bible - that it is a creature of its times
and its truths provisional - is in direct opposition to fundamentalism.
Does that mean that we must consign the Bible to the status of a ``historic
statement'' with increasingly less relevance to our fast-changing world? I
think not, and it is Ecclesiastes who helps me to think thus. He encourages me
to be sceptical about new gurus, cynical about those who claim to be able to
eliminate the ills of the world, gently content with the wisdom which has
proved itself through the years, and that it is right and proper to eat, drink,
and enjoy oneself ``under the sun''.
Come to think of it, there cannot be many better mottos for living on a desert
island - which was the point of taking my copy of Ecclesiastes in the first
place. And it even gives me practical advice on how to get off the island which
does not require me to rely upon a miracle. ``Cast your bread upon the waters
and it will return to you after many days'', he tells me in chapter 11, verse
one. Presumably that applies to putting a message in a bottle and waiting to be
rescued.
</TEXT>
