<HEADLINE>Drugged rioters spark scenes from hell in Athens jail chaos Athens, Friday</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRISONERS high on drugs stolen from the jail pharmacy, fires, cries of agony
and stabbings combined today to create scenes from hell in a revolt by more
than 1000 inmates at an Athens prison.
``I was raped. Please get me out of here. I just stole a car,'' cried one
16-year-old boy as police rushed him and other juveniles to the top security
prison's management building in a bid to protect them.
The air was thick with the smell of teargas fired by riot police struggling to
keep prisoners from fleeing the prison grounds. Ambulances with sirens wailing
collected the injured while relatives pleaded for information.
Maria Papoutsaki, the mother of an inmate, grabbed a journalist's arm and said
in a trembling voice: ``I beg you, tell me if my son is alive. He is a drug
addict . . . you can find out.''
At least 36 prisoners have been injured since Tuesday in the rampage through
the overcrowded Korydallos prison on the western outskirts of Athens.
Four convicts are known to have died, three from drug overdoses on pills looted
from the prison hospital.
The fourth, a foreigner, was hanged by other inmates. ``They threw the charred
body into the prison yard,'' said a senior police officer. ``There are many
unsettled feuds among Greek and foreign inmates and now that they control the
prison they try to get even.''
Police said they could see the slumped figures of 10 to 15 more prisoners
around the compound but did not not know whether they were dead or in a
drug-induced stupor.
``We are afraid we will see more victims,'' said Thanasis Georgantas, leader of
the prison staff union. ``The prisoners raided the pharmacy and took 2500
syringes and 27,000 pills. We had just got in new supplies.''
The rioters have burned and wrecked everything in sight.
Frightened Korydallos residents, whose homes are on the prison's perimeter,
spent much of the night outside ready to flee if the prisoners managed to break
out. All schools in the area are closed.
The inmates today roamed freely, armed with knives from the prison kitchen,
iron bars and shards of broken glass. They have poured petrol in the prison's
four main blocks and are threatening to set them on fire if police storm
in.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
