<DOCNO>GH951118-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>That's just plain dumb</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ruth Wishart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are an awful lot of them about. Streets full of them. Offices bursting
with them. Public houses spilling them over and out. The nation's sporting
stadia positively awash with them. It's not as if men are some strange alien
presence newly disembarked from inter-planetary craft and thrust for the first
time into our vision and our ken. We work with them, and play with them and
sleep with them and an extraordinary number of us still choose to enter into
the kind of long-term domestic contract with them now rarely available in any
other sphere of living. So how can it be that women know so little of them? Not
aliens but certainly still strangers.
And here is another paradox; the women who nurtured them, who shaped much of
their early conditioning, who formed their most ubiquitous adult role model in
their formative pre-school years - their mothers - don't understand them either.
Curiouser still, the mothers see no ambivalence in railing against unacceptable
masculine behaviour in husbands, fathers and lovers yet apparently conniving in
the production of a clone in the person of their own son. Women help to make
boys into the kind of men they can't understand, probably don't much like, and
are sometimes afraid of. Frogs and snails and puppy dog's tails probably don't
have much going for them as ingredients for a rounded human being. But neither
do the kind of qualities we still seem set on instilling in them making vices
from obvious virtues like the honest expression of emotion.
There are of course differences in the basic raw material parents have to deal
with concerning their sons and their daughters. Periodic research confirms that
men are usually stronger and faster with a truer aim whether they're hurling
Olympic javelins or pub darts. The women you see whizzing round the 400-metre
track poured into lycra and clocking up record times may have sexy hair,
earrings and fingernails the colour of blood. What they don't have is much in
the boobs and buttocks department. They're not like men, of course, but they're
built along more similar lines than their well-endowed sisters.
You don't need to be conversant with the basic laws of aerodynamics to deduce
that Dolly Parton wasn't constructed with the Fosbury flop in mind. But the
problem that men have now is that strength and speed are not commodities in
quite the same demand in a modern society and more particularly in a modern
economy. Women, who tend to score more highly in the dexterity stakes, are
arguably more natural users of a keyboard despite the fact that the information
superhighway seems positively jammed with male traffic, much of which would
seem to have broken down in some fashion and be in urgent need of professional
help.
And as the heavier industries are increasingly replaced by the electronic and
service varieties, strength is largely an irrelevant component for employers.
There are other areas, it's true, where male skills have traditionally had a
stronger profile. Men are generally supposed to have more analytical minds and
be more adept at the business of problem solving. Or so much of the published
evidence would have us believe. It would explain perhaps why little boys are
apparently more fascinated with construction toys like Lego just as their
grandfathers were with Meccano sets. This trait survives into later life in a
fascination with moving parts which is overwhelmingly masculine.
A woman at an evening class in car maintenance is there because the last bill
from the garage persuaded her that some DIY might stave off bankruptcy next
time the cylinder head gasket shuffled off its mechanical coil. Some men may be
there for similar reasons. Most seem to get a kick out of figuring out how
things work. I have yet to meet a woman whose idea of a fun Saturday afternoon
is stripping down the insides of a motor which was not sick in order to
reassemble it later that same day.
Other qualities often presupposed to be if not peculiarly masculine then
certainly preponderantly so, are traits like assertiveness, toughness,
combativeness and self reliance. Interestingly, women are usually checked off
against a different list. For assertive, read bossy. For toughness, read butch.
For self reliance read vanity.
In return, men who appear to have ``feminine'' qualities such as intuition and
a readiness to express their emotions openly are similarly rewarded with a hard
time. It wasn't women but other men who coined the term ``wimp'', who got into
bed with all that transatlantic psycho-babble about real men not eating quiche
and indeed only satisfied by red raw steak and beer straight from the neck of
the bottle. The problem with which, for men, is that ``real men'' as
constructed by the Marlboro ads, university beer bars, football supporters'
terracings, rugby club stag dinners, boxing matches and blood sports have
remarkably little appeal to women.
There is a mating ritual which has changed little over the years from the dance
hall to the disco, though perhaps excluding the rave. In order to summon the
necessary courage for the rigours ahead the male of the species takes to drink.
This gives him (literally) the bottle to approach strange women at the
preferred place of entertainment and to have the resilience to cope with
possible rejection.
The difficulty with this scenario is that our intrepid Lothario will consider
himself sexy and irresistible in a direct co-relation with the amount of Dutch
courage consumed. Sadly, this is a counter-productive tactic. The drunker they
are, the less desirable they are and the less likely they are to do anything
about any woman they persuade into their bed. It's a bummer chaps, but who said
life was fair?
Women have this strange inability to discern the attraction of being made
offers by drunks. It may be that we lack the necessary imagination. We
certainly lack the imagination to understand the attraction of that other
cherished male ritual the night out with the boys.
Certainly girls have nights out with the girls ..... but these are rather
different in intent, tone and style. As a special favour I am prepared to
reveal some of what goes on when women foregather in the company of their own
sex in exchange for some straight answers to some straight questions which
follow in due course.
There are women's office or factory nights out. These are characterised by
women getting dressed at least to maim, and joining their workmates for a meal
with a generous drinks kitty. The only men present will be the waiting staff
and perhaps some luckless soul who has persuaded himself that a small but
perfectly formed fee in used tenners is worth the ritual humiliation of
moonlighting from his studies/career as a male stripper. An updated variation
on this theme is the mob-handed outing to the Chippendales, though personally
I'm more of a Tap Dogs woman.
A more modest alternative is a group of female friends meeting for a meal or a
few drinks. The attraction of this is simple: women in the company of women are
prone to great frankness, especially where their male partners (shortcomings
thereof) are concerned. The occasions also guarantee the kind of belly laughter
not usually available in mixed company where there is considerable inhibition
on both sides of the gender divide. But outside of having a bit of a giggle
these occasions can also be invaluable as a kind of informal group therapy;
especially if one of the number is dealing with some kind of emotional,
maternal or medical crisis.
In contrast, from what little I have managed to deduce from interviewees, men
friends, and my own partner, men seem singularly reluctant to use their all
boys together events to discuss anything of any moment. Their lives may be
falling apart, redundancy or divorce may be looming, they may be in despair for
all manner of reasons but they don't seem able or willing to share their
burdens with their closest friends.
So what, gentlemen, is all this time honoured male bonding about? What do you
get from it outside of a guaranteed hangover? Honestly, I really, really want
to know. And I want to know because your apparent reticence is bad for your
health.
Men have a very poor record of taking care of their health or of seeking
medical attention until such time as pain or disability finally propels them to
the surgery.
Men die sooner and get sicker than women. There's also more likelihood of men,
especially young men, committing suicide, becoming homeless and down and out. A
terrifying waste. And you have to wonder how much of that is bound up in men's
seeming inability to voice their distress or seek solace from friends and
partners. Why can't a man be more like a woman!
But there is another great divide which is even more contentious. The other
morning I heard a radio colleague, Alex Bell, wonder aloud what it was we did
to 49 per cent of the population to make them do such horrible things. His
comments came on the back of a new Barnardo's report on abuse and violence,
especially against young people coming out from care with all the added
vulnerability that implies.
It is a fair question. All but a relative handful of prison inmates are male,
97 per cent of sexual abuse occurs by males against females. Men are
responsible for most violence both domestically and in society at large. You
could enlarge on that to suggest that most wars are caused by men, though the
tribal prejudices which prompt conflict are often shared by the women even if
they choose to pursue vendettas in different and less final ways.
Geneticists point out that boy babies are in receipt of the male hormone
testosterone from the seventh week after conception. By the age of 20 they have
enough of the stuff pumping around to make them feel pretty immortal if not
downright invincible though perhaps not that wise. But many men, most men,
deploy that raw sexual and physical energy in acceptable ways. Why do others
misuse their power to abuse their womenfolk or mutilate perfect strangers? And
why is it that marauding packs of young men can connive in the kind of
primitive, brutal behaviour that many of them would find appalling and
completely beyond the pale if they were on their own?
It's a conundrum sociologists, psychologists and assorted penal reformers have
long pondered. But common to their deliberations seems to be a belief that
children who are used violently are more likely to employ violent means as an
adult. Children who are given no sense of self worth have no particular esteem
for others or respect for their freedoms. Children who are taught hate and fear
have no template for the benefits of love and compassion.
It's not just small boys in dysfunctional homes who are treated badly of
course. But they do tend to bear the brunt of violent reprisals. It may not
excuse their graduating into hooliganism in their own right, but it perhaps
helps to explain it. It certainly makes it worthwhile expending time and effort
unpicking the motives of regular abusers as well as trying to heal their
victims. Not least because it is in the victims' and potential victims' best
interests.
The pessimist will point to the fact that most psychopaths are male, that
serial killers are almost always men, that ``bad'' women are often in a
manipulative relationship with wicked men. The optimist might prefer to
conclude that there are numerous examples of ``headbangers'' who have been
persuaded to confront the bankruptcy of their behaviour and construct a
meaningful non-violent life for themselves.
I started by suggesting that men were not an alien, but certainly a strange
species. Perhaps that still remains because as well as finding it difficult to
be entirely honest with each other ..... there is a real dearth of honesty with
the other sex. Ask any woman how problematical it is to have a real no holds
barred discussion with their partner. Very few will tell you that they have the
kind of frankness and verbal intimacy they hoped for.
So many topics fall off the agenda because men are too embarrassed to discuss
them. Perhaps too afraid what they'll see if they look at their relationship
too closely.
Perhaps conditioned to feel that talk of love and lack of romance and child
rearing is ``women's talk''. For very many years now we've heard talk of a
creature called ``new man''. From time to time there have even been sightings,
though verification has proved as difficult as with all other forms of UFO. But
I have faith that new man will eventually turn up in significant numbers.
Faith in men already visible with their babies strapped to their heartbeat in
papoose style carriers, in men who see tears as proof of their humanity rather
than an undermining of their masculinity, in men who see parenthood as a
partnership and employment opportunities as a matter for mutual discussion and
compromise within a relationship.
Such men are not scared of feminism. Such men are feminists themselves. They
realise that equality of opportunity doesn't just mean women expanding into
realms from which tradition and childbearing and sheer prejudice have excluded
them. They see the incomparable benefits of being freed from the tedious
business of being cast in all kinds of roles they don't fancy and for which, as
individuals, many may be altogether unsuited. They see an opportunity to have
real meaningful relationships with their children and be given real emotional
support by their partners. Put another way, let's hear it for men's liberation.
</TEXT>
