<HEADLINE>Eve Perrick</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MAMIE BAIRD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Eve Perrick Journalist; born December 21, 1916, died November 15, 1995
EVE Perrick, the famous Fleet Street columnist of the fifties, who died on
Tuesday at the age of 78, was my friend - and she also helped to change the
course of my life.
Countless readers of the Daily Express in its heyday will remember with
affectionate pleasure her witty and often vitriolic pen, and her wickedly
accurate debunking of human foibles and frailties (mainly among the rich and
famous of fashionable London).
But frequently, to howls of dismay and outrage, she would cast her gimlet dark
eye farther afield and poke not-quite-gentle fun at the quaintness of us
ordinary mortals who had the misfortune to live our lives so far from the
civilising challenges of her beloved London. She wisecracked like Hermione
Gingold and secretly loved to be likened to Dorothy Parker.
I think her first visit to Scotland was for the journalistic jamboree which
gathered at Deeside for Princess Margaret's 21st birthday, which was being
celebrated at Balmoral.
As a lesser luminary of the Scottish Daily Express I was assigned to act as
leg-woman to the great Perrick, feeding her with local colour and titbits of
news for her weekly column a column, I may say, which infuriated all Deeside
with its outrageously exaggerated descriptions of tartan-swathed matrons living
in turreted mini-mansions.
It was vintage Perrick and brought in gratifying sackfuls of indignant letters
to warm the heart of the paper's legendary editor, Arthur Christiansen, who
ranked Eve Perrick and her stable-mate Anne Edwards, the fashion editor, as
``the two best women columnists in Fleet Street''.
Eve, for all her cracks about women who did nothing but stay at home all day,
was a devoted wife and mother, and I have always regretted the faux pas I made
on my first visit when I asked Eve, in front of her daughter Penny, on which
day Eve would be leaving to cover a royal visit to Canada; I wasn't to know
that she hadn't got round to breaking the news of her imminent departure to the
child, and there were tearful scenes before I managed to make my escape.
After the first visit to London, Eve privily arranged for me to be summoned
back to be given my ``big chance'' in Fleet Street. It was a fascinating time.
After a few months I was offered a permanent job, a house and a mind-boggling
salary by the great Christiansen.
The talk of the watering-holes was that I had been brought to London to keep
the great Perrick up to scratch - or as one fellow-hack put it to me: ``You'll
be the girl that's here to put Perrick's nose out of joint.''
It was all too typical of the fevered, back-stabbing atmosphere of Fleet
Street. I declined the offer, the pull of Scotland was far too strong for me.
Eve understood perfectly, even if Christiansen didn't. We remained friends from
then on.
Some of her successors even vied for the title of Leading Bitch of Fleet
Street. But not Eve. She had a magnanimity and goodness of heart which made
her, quite simply, the First Lady.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000033</DOCNO>
