<HEADLINE>Faith of believers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BISHOP Holloway's lecture, largely agreed with by Father Tom Connelly, is not
the view of all Christians as your leader correctly avers (November 15). The
Rev Peter White's succinct comment is one which many believers would uphold and
agree with.
Paul, writing to Timothy, advises him (and us) of the soundness of scripture
and goes on to posit that men will turn from sound doctrine to myths.
And what else can we expect when lame or limp excuses are proffered up to
inform the sinner that there is no sin?
The Bible speaks plainly of sin and of its consequence, and it is not a
departure from the teaching of scripture we need, for we have already gone too
far. Rather we need a return to the teaching of scripture to posit clear moral
values before people.
If Bishop Holloway and his friends pursue the path they are on, then those who
uphold the Doctrines of Grace must depart from them because scripture cannot be
compromised.
Rev Fraser K Turner,
South &amp; Quarter Manse,
Limekilnburn Road,
Quarter,
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
