<HEADLINE>As US Defence Secretary William Perry and Secretary of State Warren Christopher join the Bosnian negotiations at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base for what could be the makings of a peace agreement, Patrick Brogan examines the American bid to repeat the success of Camp David Clinton is counting on Camp David effect in Dayton</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE last time a peace conference was held in the United States was in September
1978, and that was the turning point in the history of the Arab-Israeli
conflict. The President of Egypt, Anwar Sadat, and the Prime Minister of
Israel, Menachem Begin, were closeted in Camp David for 10 days to settle the
outline of the first peace agreement between Israel and one of her neighbours.
President Carter and his secretary of state, Cyrus Vance, were midwives for the
occasion and spent the entire time working on the two obdurate and difficult
statesmen, to persuade them to accept the deal. It was the high point of Jimmy
Carter's presidency.
Camp David was chosen because it was close to Washington and because the press
could be kept out. The President was to preside over the deliberations so he
needed to be within striking distance of the White House.
Camp David is in the hills north of Washington and is a Navy base. Presidents
have used it as a weekend retreat since Roosevelt, and there are comfortable
cabins for his guests and their hangers-on. During the conference, the press
camped out at a small town nearby. One TV network had a balloon floating
overhead to carry an aerial to ensure live transmission back to base, and the
place swarmed with reporters.
None of them got a story. When the press was summoned to hear the results
announced by the President's national security adviser, Zbigniew Brzezinski, in
an office building next to the White House on September 17, no-one had the
faintest idea of what to expect. It was all very dramatic, and then there was
the signing, on live television, in the White House itself.
It was very satisfactory, for the American managers. It was also a great
nuisance for British newspapers which had to remake their front pages at three
in the morning.
This time, the Bosnian negotiators have been banished to an Air Force base in
Ohio. There is less press interest, and more access. We discovered, in 1978,
that Israelis and Egyptians can be exceedingly tight-lipped when they want. So
far, there has been a steady stream of leaks out of the Dayton talks, as
``sources'' slip out of the compound to talk to reporters.
All the same, as conferences go, it is fairly secure. The leaks are not always
reliable and there are still surprises: the Croat-Serbian agreement on Sunday
was not leaked in Dayton.
The three delegations are all housed in a rather low-rent hotel on the base and
have offices next to each other in a military building. Originally, these were
to be ``proximity talks''. The principals were not to negotiate with each
other, but with mediators, chiefly Americans, who would shuttle between them.
This system broke down immediately, and now the mediators are much encouraged,
we are told, to see Croats, Serbs and Muslims in intense discussion with each
other. There are now formal sessions every day, morning and afternoon.
The talks are at Wright-Patterson AFB near Dayton. The town is celebrated for
two historical reasons. Before the interstate highways were built, the main
inland north-south road and the east-west road intersected there. More
interesting, Dayton was where the Wright brothers had their bicycle shop.
There are still plenty of people who remember those two most celebrated of all
American inventors (they flew their first plane on the coast of North Carolina,
to take advantage of favourable winds). The air base is named after them.
Ohio is still part of the industrial heartland of America, the area around the
Great Lakes known rather derisively as the Rust Belt. Cleveland, on Lake Erie
to the north, is where John D Rockefeller had a hardware store and then went
into the oil business. It is still a major industrial town, and now boasts that
it is once again prosperous, after a long and difficult adaptation to modern
times.
Dayton, and the huge air base, are also part and parcel of industrial America,
but without the racial tensions, pollution and, be it said, romance of
Cleveland. There is a symphony orchestra, a museum, and the wheat fields
stretch away from the suburbs and factories.
The base was chosen for the talks to keep the participants away from the
fleshpots and media temptations of eastern cities.
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, who has lived in New York,
protested at the choice. ``Do they think I'm a monk?'' he complained.
Local people, reportedly, were flattered at having an important diplomatic
event on their doorstep and displeased at the assumption by the rest of the
country that Dayton was a rural backwater where nothing ever happened.
The American calculation was that bringing the leaders together was the only
way of making progress. Indeed, the latest agreement, that the Serbs and Croats
have settled the future of Eastern Slavonia, was clearly a deal cut by
Milosevic and Franjo Tudjman, president of Croatia, in Dayton, even though the
announcement was made by lesser officials on the spot.
That is the Camp David principle. Sadat and Begin, when the Americans pushed
them hard enough, could make the decisions and guarantee that their governments
would accept them. The same goes for Milosevic and Tudjman (it is not so clear
that President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia has similar authority).
The difference is that the announcement of a peace agreement, if one is
reached, will be made on CNN instead of in the White House. CNN did not exist
in 1978 and reporters then had to camp out in Camp David - and then rush back
to Washington for the signing.
Now we can sit in our offices and follow it all just as closely as those who
have spent the past three weeks in Ohio.
</TEXT>
