<HEADLINE>Axes out for new forestry chief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Magaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323172</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Margaret Vaughan examines why the new head of the Forestry Commission has
created alarm among champions of the environment
THE roots of dismay among environmentalists at the choice of David Bills to
head the Forestry Commission lie faraway in the tangled forests of a ruggedly
beautiful island off mainland Australia.
Tasmania broke into the public consciousness in 1983 when British botanist
David Bellamy was arrested leading a protest, and thrown into jail. He claimed
its unique wilderness areas and virgin rainforests were under threat from dam
projects and tree felling.
With his almost messianic compulsion to protect the natural world from what he
perceives as the ravages of commercial enterprise it is hardly surprising that
he should be horrified to find an old adversary crossing the world to take over
the helm of the Forestry Commission, from it's Edinburgh headquarters.
David Bills began his career with the Australian company North Forest Products
Ltd in 1979, rising to become general manager in 1986. It was his company which
became the focus for the ire of environmental campaigners.
The firm is Australia's biggest exporter of wood chip to Japan. Much of its raw
products derive from clear felling of ancient forests in Tasmania where the
company owns three of the state's four woodchip mills.
Chief among its critics is Geoff Law, of Tasmania's Wilderness Society. It is,
he says, ``number one among Australia's destroyers of old growth forests''.
Bellamy says he is appalled at the decision to appoint Bills to the sensitive
forestry post: ``The only good thing about it is to get him off the backs of
forests in Australia, but it can't be any good for us.''
Strong words from a man who has been at the forefront of support for the
Forestry Commission's championing of multi-purpose forestry, which he says,
leads the world.
Much of the environmentalists' concern is that the commission's policy, under
which woodlands are managed to yield not just economic but environmental and
social values, will now shift towards commercial objectives.
Martin Mather of the World-Wide Fund for Nature in Scotland said: ``We will be
looking very quickly for Mr Bills to show that the leopard can change its
spots. He won't be in for an easy time.''
Friends of the Earth's habitats campaigner, Tony Juniper, said his
organisation's dismay stemmed from the appointment of someone with a background
in the resource exploitation sector: ``Especially when he is entering an
institution which, we are told, is going into a new phase of enlightenment,
encouraging the social value of forestry. He comes from the old
log-it-and-build-approach to forestry.''
When Bills's appointment was announced, the chairman of the Forestry
Commission, Sir Peter Hutchison, said he came with an impressive reputation as
manager of a large forestry operation supplying timber to Australian and
international markets. He was confident Bills would steer the commission's
future in line with government policies to manage forests in a sustainable way.
Bills began his forestry career as a scientist at the Australian Forest
Research Institute. Educated at the University of Tasmania, where he got a BSc
in forestry, he undertook forestry research in Norway for a time and studied at
the management school in Massachusetts.
In an article in industry magazine, Forestry &amp; British Timber, Bills answered
criticism by acknowledging that issues of old growth and wilderness value had
been debated passionately in Australia. But the debate there was different to
that in the UK, he said.
In Australia, a large component of the industry was still dependent upon native
or natural eucalyptus forests. The debate there was over whether or not to
harvest, rather than in the UK where issues of access, forest design and how to
harvest are more prominent.
He believed he had been a voice of reason in the debate and had a positive
influence in achieving some compromises in difficult circumstances: ``I have
had the opportunity to learn of the importance of the UK's remaining native
woodlands and from a personal and professional viewpoint cannot think of any
circumstances which would cause me to advocate, or even support, a change in
current UK policy towards these forests.''
</TEXT>
