<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323173</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE man appointed director general of the Forestry Commission was a figure of
controversy among environmentalists who campaigned against the destruction of
rain forests in Tasmania.
Mr David Bills, who takes up his post on December 4, was general manager of
North Forest Products Ltd, which became the focus for protests over its plans
to fell virgin forests on the island.
Concern at the threat to the ancient forests sparked international protests.
Campaigners eventually had one of the areas at the centre of the dispute
designated a UN World Heritage Site.
Mr Bills also clashed with environmentalists, notably the World Wide Fund for
Nature, in his role as spokesman for the Australian forestry and timber
industry.
He was a vociferous campaigner, as president of the National Association of
Forest Industries, against a WWF scheme to bring consumer power to bear by
encouraging forestry owners and timber producers to have independent vetting of
management standards.
The environmentalists' concerns centre on Mr Bills's commercial background. It
is feared that the social and environmental aspects of forestry in the UK will
be lost in the race for profits.
The loudest criticism of the appointment has come from broadcaster and
environmental campaigner David Bellamy, who has led environmental protests to
protect the Tasmanian wilderness and its rainforests for more than a decade.
``It is horrendous that the powers-that-be have appointed him. What the devil
did we do to get someone like this in the world's leading forest service?''
Professor Bellamy warned: ``I hope the conservation movement will be able to
work with him to show what the benefits of multi-purpose forestry are on our
overcrowded island, or he will be up against some of the longest picket lines
the world has ever seen.''
When Mr Bills's appointment was announced by the Forestry Commission in
September, he was quoted as foreseeing an exciting economic future for the
forest industry in Britain.
His priority, he stressed, would be to develop focus and processes to ensure
commercial outcomes in line with Government expectations.
A spokesman for the Forestry Commission yesterday said it was unfair to
criticise a man who had not yet arrived to start the job.
Mr Bills, he said, had made his reputation for calm and successful dealings
with high-profile environmental issues in both Australia and Tasmania.
</TEXT>
