<HEADLINE>Hostage `close to death' Srinagar, Friday</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GUERRILLAS holding two Britons and two other Westerners hostage in Kashmir said
today one of the captives could die ``any time'' and urged his relatives to go
to the Himalayan region as soon as possible, the Press Trust of India reported.
The news agency said Al-Faran militants did not name the ailing hostage. The
militants released the statement in Srinagar, the summer capital of India's
Jammu and Kashmir state.
Britons Keith Mangan and Paul Wells have been held hostage in the mountains of
Kashmir for four months by extremists fighting for independence from India.
Al-Faran said the condition of the ailing hostage had deteriorated since
Tuesday, when it released a statement saying he was ``struggling for life''.
The shadowy guerrilla group said the Indian Government had been told about the
hostage's condition but was not interested in his recovery and would be held
responsible if he died.
American Donald Hutchings, German Dirk Hasert, and the two Britons were
kidnapped in early July.
Officials have said Hutchings was believed to be in poor condition, suffering
from chilblains and other ailments.-Reuter
</TEXT>
