<DOCNO>GH951118-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Living on her instincts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are perhaps four things you should know about Sharon Stone before
dismissing her as a Hollywood publicity monster who shows rather too much skin
to be taken seriously.
The first is that in 1980, director Woody Allen cast her as his fantasy woman
in his black and white film Stardust Memories - her movie debut. It makes one
snigger now, but: ``I looked at her and thought I would really like her to kiss
me!'' he is reported as saying.
Stone protested when they put her in a ``bombshell dress'' for the brief clip,
where she kisses him.
``I said: `Wait. Let me explain something - I'm not a bombshell.' They didn't
see it my way. I played Woody's fantasy. And that was the beginning of the
end.''
Ten years later she posed nude for Playboy, proving that at 32 and with a
decade of truly awful potboilers behind her there was not so much a serious
actress waiting to get out as a woman determined to get noticed.
A year later she uncrossed her legs in Basic Instinct; the Sharon Stone package
was revealed, heralding the writhing skin scenes so familiar to those of us who
have yawned our way through the ludicrous plots and moderate box office success
of The Specialist and Sliver.
And in the last two years, it has paid off; more important than taking the
leading role in The Quick and the Dead, last year's female shoot-em-up cowboy
movie, she was the co-producer and chose the director.
This year she finished shooting Casino, playing mobster Robert de Niro's
unfaithful wife. Martin Scorsese, the director's director, chose her for the
role, which is perhaps the only really important thing you need to know about
Sharon Stone at all; as part of Hollywood's elite, she is all future, and the
past doesn't figure at all.
Not that the past necessarily bothers her. She is variously reported as saying
in Basic Ambition, a new biography by journalist Douglas Thompson out this
month:
On the 10-page Playboy spread: ``One, I wanted to be seen. Leading ladies my
age are typed and you need to be sexually appealing for parts in the movies you
might be right for. It's a man's world and when you look like I look, that's
what it is.''
On Basic Instinct: ``Once I realised that was what the guys wanted, I thought:
`Oh, I get it. No matter how he touches her or where he touches her or what
else he does to her, it`s the most, it's the best, it's the sexiest'.''
On Sharon Stone: ``My image is manufactured from very little . . . I realised I
could create an event - this more attractive woman.'' She has maintained she
was ``betrayed'' on the Basic Instinct interrogation scene by director Paul
Verhoeven, who told her to take off her white knickers because they were
reflecting the light, assuring her the shadows were too dark to show anything
very significant. She has subsequently vetted all nude scenes before release.
And Stone and her fans drearily insist that the part of sex killer Catherine
Tramell in Basic Instinct changed Hollywood values for good. This, remember, is
the movie that gave us perhaps the most offensive line in film history: ``I
think she's the f*** of the century.''
``So many female characters are written the way men experience women or would
like to experience women. But that's not the way women really are . . . I think
Basic Instinct showed both men and women in the trenches pitted against one
another,'' says Stone. It is true that Tramell more than matched Michael
Douglas's testosterone-stuffed detective Nick Curran, unlike the sad obsessive
played by Glenn Close in his previous rip-em-off movie Fatal Attraction, but
Stone claims too much here; what is ``the f*** of the century'' but Woody
Allen's dream girl made flesh?
Stone's movies have almost all been written, directed and produced by men, and
until The Quick and the Dead (with the possible exception of Sliver) she has
never carried the film; her role was the main character's love interest.
So forget about the films, which ain't going to change anything; concentrate on
what she does with her stardom.
Vicki Patterson, assistant education officer at the Edinburgh Filmhouse, says:
``She is a phenomenon, and she is interesting; she has created controversy, and
she is determined - I admire her for getting in a position where she
co-financed The Quick and the Dead; it is unusual, especially for women, who
are constantly fighting among themselves for a decreasing number of parts. It
takes guts to put one's reputation on the line.''
Thompson's biography has the precocious Stone telling schoolfriends in rural
Pennsylvania that she would be the new Marilyn Monroe. She escaped home via
modelling, and then to Hollywood, where she appeared in slasher flicks (Deadly
Blessing), creaking adventure pictures (King Solomon's Mines, Allan Quartermain
and the Lost City of Gold), and the execrable Police Academy 4 before losing a
truly career-sapping bad perm and hitting the big time as Arnold
Schwarzenegger's wife in Total Recall in 1990.
The recurring word in interviews is control. On the way she has ditched a
husband and a long-term lover - both film producers - at least two agents, had
a Hello! at home shoot (which caused controversy when it was divulged she had
borrowed someone else's home to do it with), gained a lover 10 years younger
than herself and, most recently, been awarded France's highest mark of esteem
in the arts - the Chevalier of Arts.
Patterson says: ``If Casino goes well that will improve her record at the box
office and guarantee her work in the future.
``Hopefully, she is going to continue to get involved in production. It will
mean more roles for women and better roles and hopefully they can perhaps
champion directors of their choice, maybe directors who are a lot more
sympathetic to female roles.
``I think we should take her seriously, and the French obviously do. Maybe
we're missing something.''
She began as little more than a twinkle in Woody Allen's eye and her image is
manufactured from very little. Even the star herself admits to that. So why,
asks Jane Scott , is Sharon Stone such a highly-marketable phenomenon?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>James Large</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323176</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Harold Large, evangelist; born June 26, 1903, died November 11, 1995
THE evangelist and Bible teacher James Large has died at the age of 92. Though
not a Scot, he had latterly pursued his religious calling in Scotland, and had
lived for 13 or 14 years in Auchlochan House retirement home, Lesmahagow, a
community for evangelicals of every persuasion.
Mr Large started his career as an insurance clerk and became a insurance claims
inspector in Cardiff.
After he experienced a call to be a missionary in his late twenties, he devoted
his subsequent life to this. He belonged to the Open Brethren and worked,
without payment, in the thirties and forties, travelling in a tent or caravan
and conducting services in rural Devon. In this he had the enthusiastic support
of his wife, Hilda. His son recalls that when the last penny went, he would say
that God would provide - and indeed there was always money in the post the next
day.
Later, he served the dozens of Open Brethren chapels in north Devon into the
postwar period. He then performed the same functions in south Devon and Dorset
before moving to north, then east, London. During his London years he did a
great deal of Bible teaching at Open Brethren meetings.
After the war he also assumed a wider role, travelling the country as an
itinerant Bible teacher. He was one of the editors of the magazine Precious
Seed and was also the author of several books on religious subjects. He became
very well known in Scotland in religious circles through conferences. As a
teacher, he had the reputation for dealing with profound matters in very simple
terms.
As far as his Scottish years are concerned, he had a roving commission through
the country, teaching and holding Bible study meetings. Eventually in his later
days he restricted his travels to the Hamilton, Glasgow, and Edinburgh areas.
His old friend Mr Stewart Brown, of Auchlochan, says of Mr Large that ``he
certainly had an aura, a presence. He was a very dignified, unassuming man.''
Mr Large leaves a son, Peter, a former journalist with the Guardian newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Maclagan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NORRIE HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Arthur Thomas John Maclagan, laywer; born on January 6, 1906, died November 15,
1995
BUTE lawyer Arthur Thomas John Maclagan was educated at Edinburgh University
where he studied law, but a break to serve in the Far East with the Malaysia
Defence Force between 1926-36 saw him return to complete his studies at Glasgow
University.
He joined his father's firm of solicitors, MacBeth and Maclagan, in Rothesay in
1937 but had practised for only 18 months before he was called to serve his
country, yet again.
During the Second World War, he reached the rank of major, commanding the 2nd
Bute Battery and served as Military Registrar at Stracathro near Brechin. He
was posted to active duty in India and Malaysia. On being demobbed in 1947 he
rejoined the family practice, which has now served the people of Bute for more
than 140 years.
He was also an Hononary Sheriff of North Strathclyde and served as secretary to
the board of management of the Bute and Cumbraes Hospital.
Mr Maclagan, who will be fondly remembered by those in the legal profession,
retired from his law practice in 1974 at the age of 68. He was followed into
the firm by his son Ian who joined the practice in 1968.
A true Brandane (one born on Bute), Mr Maclagan was an active member of
Rothesay High Kirk where he was an elder and session clerk for many years. He
played an active role in the church and in the Bute community.
Mr Maclagan's wife Margaret died in 1982. He is survived by sons Donald and Ian
and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Relief as Jupp grasps the nettle of welfare reform</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR a man desperately in need of a fillip, it was a triumph. On Wednesday,
Prime Minister Alain Jupp outlined in the National Assembly the first thorough
overhaul of France's welfare system in its 50-year history, and one that even
cautious observers have qualified as a ``revolution''.
The Premier's speech, well modelled and passionately delivered, had all the
conservative politicians in the House - that is to say the immense majority of
them - on their feet and applauding.
Earlier carping by friends of President's Chirac's right-wing election rival,
Edouard Balladur, failed to turn into anything resembling serious criticism,
and Mr Jupp had his day.
A predominant feeling among many politicians was one of relief at seeing the
Government daring at last to grasp the nettle of a debt-ridden system.
The deficit of national welfare accumulated since 1992 is #80 billion, a
staggering sum which has led to all sorts of recent alarmist rumours about the
collapse, among other things, of the pension system.
At the expense of going back yet again on a major Chirac promise not to raise
taxes, Mr Jupp has described the means both to mop up the overdraft and
restrict spending, reducing next year's deficit, for example, from an estimated
#8000m to #2000m.
Mr Jupp's plan is the nineteenth in the past 20 years. But all his supporters
agree that this one will work.
Its great virtue is that of imposing sacrifices on everybody. Tax on income as
a whole will be raised by 0.5% for a period of 13 years, deemed necessary to
absorb the overall deficit.
A special welfare system tax on wages, CSG, introduced by the socialists in
1991 and fiercely criticised by Mr Jupp himself then and later, will be
extended to all incomes, to bring in an extra #3000m a year.
An additional and very similar tax, called the RDS (Reimbursement of the Social
Debt), will be introduced on virtually all incomes, including pensions.
Civil servants will have to contribute for 40 years, like people in the private
sector, instead of 37, to qualify for a full pension.
Family allowances will become taxable in 1997.
Pensioners and people on unemployment benefit will pay higher health
contributions.
Medical fees are to be frozen for a year and the increase in hospital spending
restricted to 2.1% in 1996, the expected rate of inflation. And so on.
Mr Jupp's research, nothing if not thorough, even takes into account the
reduction of maternity leave payment, from 106% of salary to a more sensible
round figure of 100%.
The reform of pensions, first mooted by the Government's very liberal Minister
of Economics, Alain Madelin, sacked two months ago for stepping out of line on
policy, has particularly angered Civil Service unions.
Placed before the fait accompli instead of being consulted as they had hoped,
they have called for a general strike next Friday.
Another stoppage, to protest at the whole of the reforms, is being organised by
other unions, excepting the socialist-leaning CFDT, on November 28.
But what had the unions almost voiceless with rage was Mr Jupp's plan to put
health care under direct control of Parliament.
For with all their #240 billion annual budgets France's health, pension, and
family allowance schemes are run by bodies independent of direct parliamentary
control in which trade unions, and especially Force Ouvriere, play a major role.
The make-up of the administrative boards in charge of various welfare
departments will now be modified, tipping the balance more in favour of
management and government representatives.
For Louis Viannet, general secretary of the communist-sympathising CGT union,
the Jupp scheme is ``a veritable plan of devastation.
``No Government in 30 years has gone so far in its aggression against our
system of social protection and setting up of medical rationing,'' he said.
In the opinion of Force Ouvreire the Government has simply seized control of
the welfare system with a view to privatising it in the long term. The
management union, the CNPF, just like Mr Jupp's political colleagues, approved
the plan unreservidly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323179</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Prince Charles
visits Latvia
RIGA: The Prince of Wales arrived in Latvia yesterday for a brief visit to the
former Soviet republic. During his six-hour stay in the Baltic coast nation, he
met with Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis and business leaders.
He was scheduled to place flowers at the Freedom Monument, a memorial to
Latvian independence, and open a new British Embassy in Riga.
Mitterrand ill
PARIS: Former French President Francois Mitterrand is to miss an award ceremony
in Germany next week because he is too ill. He has prostate cancer. Mitterrand,
79, was to present the 1995 German Media Prize to PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat on
November 23 in Baden-Baden. Mitterrand won the prize last year.
Random sniper
OSLO: A woman was killed and two other people injured yesterday when a gunman
opened fire on vehicles in the Norwegian town of Hurum. Police said the gunman
began randomly shooting at passing buses and cars.
Paris pique
PARIS: France yesterday cancelled a summit with Italy and postponed one with
Belgium in a fit of pique after Rome and Brussels joined most other EU
countries in supporting a UN vote deploring French and Chinese nuclear weapons
tests. Britain voted against the UN resolution.
Security grip
SANTIAGO: Salman Rushdie was yesterday allowed to venture out of an apartment
in Chile after worried police finally loosened their security stranglehold on
him. His publisher said he had been treated ``like a prisoner''.
Aids hospice
NEW DELHI: Nobel Peace Prize winner Mother Teresa plans to set up a hospice for
Aids patients in New Delhi, the Press Trust of India said yesterday. The
85-year-old nun said victims would get ``much needed'' love at her centre
devoted to women and children.
Polish poll
WARSAW: Polish President Lech Walesa and left-wing challenger Aleksander
Kwasniewski have fought the last full day of a presidential election campaign
which will decide whether Poles are ready to entrust power to former communists.
</TEXT>
