<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP welcomed `jobs for the boys' inquiry Liddell tells of `cronyism' complaints</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MP Helen Liddell said yesterday that accusations about Monklands members
running a ``jobs for the boys'' council were a daily complaint from her
constituents.
She said she had no concrete evidence to give day five of the statutory inquiry
in Coatbridge into the allegations.
The Monklands East MP said she was well aware of complaints that council jobs
were being found by councillors for their relatives or friends.
She said: ``That is repeated in various hostelries in Monklands, where it's
said so and so can get you a job on the council because so and so drinks at
such and such a bar. But they are never referred to by name.
``Seldom a day passes that complaints on this issue are not made by my
constituents. They allege not only nepotism but also cronyism.''
She told the inquiry chairman, Mr William Nimmo-Smith, QC, that she was unsure
how much of that was fired by constant rumours and speculation.
She told him that Monklands was not a homogenous community but a marriage of
the two former independent town council areas of Airdrie and Coatbridge.
She said: ``That was not a marriage made in heaven. There have been accusations
on council conduct since the reform of local government in 1975.''
She said she welcomed the inquiry - and so would have the late Labour leader
John Smith she said - because it gave the chance once and for all for those
with evidence of corruption to speak out.
Mrs Liddell hit out at former Scottish Local Government Minister Allan Stewart
for suggesting during campaigning in the 1994 Monklands East by-election that
sectarianism played a part in the running of the council.
She said she had demanded Mr Stewart and the Secretary of State for Scotland
hold an inquiry into allegations against Monklands.
On religious bias in council jobs, she said she could find no evidence. She
said it was ``insensitive and not well advised'' for the council to ask job
applicants to specify their Christian religion in an Equal Opportunities form -
even if that was a voluntary form.
On whether membership of the Labour Party played an influential part in getting
a job, Mrs Liddell said: ``I have nothing to suggest it is true but nothing to
suggest it is not true.''
Meanwhile, a decision by two Monklands councillors to give a pay rise to the
son of Labour group leader Jim Brooks came under fire yesterday from party
chief Jack McConnell.
Mr McConnell, 35, Scots general secretary, told the inquiry that their decision
was just not sensible. He told Mr William Nimmo-Smith this was the only
incident in the past 18 months that had concerned him at Monklands.
He was referring back to the changes in job interview procedures implemented at
the council following an internal Labour party committee in 1992.
That led to the abolition of the staffing rota committee, where between four
and six councillors interviewed all job applicants.
Asked by Mr Nimmo-Smith if there was anything since then that concerned the
Scottish Labour party, Mr McConnell referred to the upgrading of Mr Stephen
Brooks.
The inquiry had heard earlier in the week how councillors Betty Leitch and Hugh
Lucas had upgraded Mr Brooks against the recommendations of officials.
Mr McConnell said: ``It was not sensible for them to do that.''
He said all local authorities should be careful about becoming involved in
staff regrading and that it was better left to officials.
He said it was obvious in any analysis of what happened at Monklands that the
two councillors knew exactly who they were upgrading.
Even if they were technically correct the public perception might be different.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000044</DOCNO>
