<HEADLINE>Lockerbie Cairn coverage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SANDY SMITH of Millhousebridge, Lockerbie, raises the question of BBC2 Scotland
transmission coverage in the South-west (November 14). I will try to clarify
the matter.
BBC2 Scotland was extended to serve the South-west in April 1992, from the
Sandale transmitter in Cumbria. The 15 relay stations in the South-west were
converted to radiate BBC2 at the same time. However, when we came to plan the
service it became clear that there was a significant shortage of clear
television channels which could be used without causing interference.
As a result it was necessary to restrict the power of the new BBC2 service to
20kW (compared with the 500kW of the existing services). In addition, it was
necessary to transmit on Channel 67, which is at the other end of the TV band
from the existing services.
The BBC could not influence either the channel or power allocation and we
implemented the only technical solution available.
We were aware that the higher channel and lower power would cause difficulty
and that viewers who received their signals from the main stations in Cumbria
would require to make alterations to their aerial systems or install additional
aerials to receive the signal either from Sandale or from one of the relays.
Some people, however, have not made adequate alterations. We are more than
willing to provide advice to viewers on the best way to receive a BBC2 Scotland
signal. In addition we will be glad to talk further to people at a public
screening of the Lockerbie programme, America's Memorial to Lockerbie on
November 28 at 7pm in Lockerbie Town Hall. Furthermore, the programme will be
transmitted on BBC1 on the anniversary of the disaster on December 21.
Noble Macpherson,
Information and Liaison Engineer,
Scotland,
BBC Scotland, Broadcasting House,
Queen Margaret Drive, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
