<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Home rule measures Bold new package or tartan mouse?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR the precise details of John Major's latest attempt to appease home rule
sentiment in Scotland, we must await Michael Forsyth's St Andrew's Day lecture.
Given the tinkering with the functions of the Scottish Grand Committee which
was the main fruit of Taking Stock phase one, it is hard to see what further
procedural innovations, within the conventions of Westminster, can ignite
Scottish opinion and quench the majority desire in Scotland for some measure of
home rule. The one significant move left in that gambit is to give the Grand
Committee untrammelled voting powers over purely Scottish legislation. But, as
Ian Lang told The Herald in January, ``the Government has to be able to command
a majority for its legislation, otherwise Parliament cannot operate''. To give
the Scottish Grand Committee the power to vote on the principle of Scottish
Bills at second reading would ensure that the legislation on vouchers for
nursery education, promised in this week's Queen's Speech, would never see the
light of day.
We cannot believe that Mr Forsyth, even in his emollient, listening mode, has
gone soft and persuaded the Prime Minister to go down that revisionist road. So
we must assume that the bold new package being trailed yesterday will look a
lot less impressive when the Scottish Secretary finally gets up to deliver his
Dick Stewart Memorial Lecture. There could be voting, of course. But subject to
the Grand Committee being made less Scottish, and packed with the Tory payroll
vote. Or votes in Edinburgh or wherever could be subject to confirmation by
votes of all MPs back in Westminster. But none of that would take us much
further forward than we were, a year ago, when the Grand Committee met in
Edinburgh to debate the second reading of the Children (Scotland) Bill or when
it met, in chaotic circumstances in Westminster for the first time this
February, for a new-style question time and debate session. We were told, in
his interview in The Independent yesterday, that the Prime Minister now
understands why most Scots feel cut off from centralised Westminster power. Mr
Major was in Scotland when the Constitutional Convention published its detailed
plans for a parliament in Edinburgh. The Prime Minister rejects the whole
premise of these plans but, to his credit, recognises that the document marked
a very important stage in the constitutional debate north of the Border. Yet,
as he puts it himself: ``The London press virtually failed to cover it.'' But,
while the Prime Minister says he understands Scotland's sense of alienation in
an intensely metropolitan United Kingdom, he is powerless to deliver the very
thing which would assuage that feeling: a forum which delivers to Scots the
policies and programmes most of them vote for at the ballot box.
He says a separate Scottish nation is perfectly credible. And as a statement of
fact that is perfectly true. Like Finland, Estonia, or Luxembourg, an
independent Scotland could stand on its own. But, to date, only a minority of
Scots and an even smaller minority of MPs want that to happen. Most Scots, and
the vast majority of Scottish MPs, still subscribe to UK membership but want a
parliament in Edinburgh to decide Scottish priorities on the issues which
affect their daily lives. There is evidence - despite what looks like a badly
botched Scottish Chambers of Commerce survey, which didn't even get round to
asking members their own constitutional preferences - that business opinion is
less hostile to home rule than it was in 1979. Perhaps Mr Forsyth will surprise
us. But if he unwraps another tartan mouse on November 30, there will be
nowhere left to hide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Maintenance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PHOTOGRAPHS of the appalling condition of schools at Lochaber and Portree
clearly show a failure to maintain these buildings properly. It may no doubt be
convenient to say that the buildings have been found out by the flat roofs and
80 inches of rain per year, but the reality is that the buildings display no
signs of regular maintenance.
Statistically, those in charge of public buildings own motor cars, which they
have serviced at regular intervals. Perhaps there should be a similar test for
buildings.
James G Cuthbertson,
4 Newton Place,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pinnacle of achievement</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE JOHNSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
READERS of The Glasgow Herald in November 1833 were summoned to a ``Grand
Bazaar in aid of liquidation of debt and erection of spire of St Mary's Church,
Great Western Road, Glasgow''.
And as the church magazine later reported, despite ``terribly unpropitious''
weather on the opening day, the event was ``a decided success''. There had been
misgivings that few would attend beyond the congregation and their immediate
circle but on the day a large crowd flocked to the Victoria Halls in West
Regent Street to browse at Lady Campbell's silver stall, purchase raffle
tickets for a silver-plated tricycle, and fall victim ``to the grosser
attractions of Mrs Richardson's plump pheasants and excellent mince pies''.
The event raised #2200, which ``happily annihilated'' the debt and presumably
allowed the erection to go ahead as well, as Gilbert Scott's massive spire
still dominates the eastern end of Great Western Road.
Next Friday and Saturday, exactly 112 years later, supporters of St Mary's (now
St Mary's Episcopal Cathedral), hope to recreate the atmosphere of the original
event at a Grand Victorian Bazaar in Glasgow City Chambers. The ravages of time
and the weather have necessitated a major renovation programme for the
cathedral and its Synod Hall, both Grade A listed buildings. Alas, the Countess
of Aberdeen and Mrs Richardson won't be there to peddle their silver and
pheasants. In their place you can expect a range of stalls including crafts,
hampers, gifts, and Victoriana.
Back in 1883 we are told Captain Savage, with an upmarket-sounding backing
group, entertained the crowd while Punch ``apostrophised (sic) his undutiful
Judy'' for the children. Next week their places will be taken by the Cathedral
Singers, a Barber Shop quintet, and Bella McNab's Ceilidh Band.
On Friday you are invited to rifle your attic for suitable garb for a ``Parlour
and Promenade'' Victorian entertainment. There's also an exhibition about
Victorian life in Glasgow.
The target this time is, well, something rather in excess of #2200. So roll up,
roll up.
n.Grand Victorian Bazaar at Glasgow City Chambers. Friday, November 24: Bazaar,
noon to 5pm; Victorian entertainment, 7.30pm. Saturday, November 25: Bazaar,
10am to 3.30pm; Ceilidh, 7.30pm. Contact Pippy McEwan, 0141 649 1537.
ANNE JOHNSTONE
</TEXT>
