<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Three years for sex attack on pregnant woman in park</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323185</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SEX attacker who pounced on a six-months pregnant woman in a late-night
attack was jailed for three years at the High Court in Edinburgh, yesterday.
The victim was saved after her five-year-old niece told a passer-by: ``Someone
is raping my auntie.'' Mr Colin Anderson chased George Brown, 24, and held him
until police arrived.
Brown, of Restalrig Road, Edinburgh, admitted indecently assaulting the
20-year-old woman and threatening her niece with violence on June 29 this year,
at a footpath on Leith Links.
He was originally charged with attempted rape but the Crown accepted his not
guilty plea to that part of the charge.
Lord Clyde was told the woman was taking a shortcut across the park with her
niece about 11.30pm, after visiting a friend. She became aware of footsteps and
realised a man was following her.
Brown grabbed her from behind, put his hands over her mouth, and forced her to
the ground, repeatedly shouting: ``I want to make love to you.''
The screaming woman was repeatedly punched on the face and warned to stop
calling out but she managed to tell her distressed niece to run for help.
Brown got on top of the woman and tried to make her perform a sex act. She kept
telling him that she was six months pregnant but he appeared not to care. He
opened her clothing but when he realised that Mr Anderson was arriving on the
scene, tried to escape.
Mr Derek Ogg, defence counsel, urged Lord Clyde to place Brown, who suffers
from a mental handicap, on probation on condition that he sought treatment.
However, the judge, who had deferred sentence for reports, rejected that option.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Release of prisoners Welcome aid to peace process</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN politics the end often, although not always, justifies the means. The
release yesterday under the 1995 Northern Ireland Remission of Sentences Act
from Northern Ireland jails of 83 Republican and Loyalist prisoners is a case
in point. The means are legal, the release an attempt by the Government to inch
the stalled peace process, which needs all the encouragement it can get, a
little further along the road towards a settlement. It is an end everyone prays
will be achieved, and for that reason, because they should help, we welcome the
releases. As Mr Joe Hendron of the nationalist SDLP said, the important thing
was to show generosity to prisoners from both communities so that the all-party
talks could be started as soon as possible. That generosity was shown, those
released being more or less equally divided between the Republican and Loyalist
factions.
The Government's action is not, as Sinn Fein said, derisory. Nor are there
grounds at the moment for the immediate release of all so-called political
prisoners, as it demanded. It is not ``too little too late,'' as one of the
released prisoners claimed, but a first step towards the eventual release of
more prisoners. Mrs Sandra Peacock, the widow of the prison officer murdered
two years ago by Loyalists, who called the Government's action a disgrace,
deserves every sympathy. Like many before her, and it is no comfort for her, or
others like her, she is the victim of real politik. Her anger, and the anger of
all who have suffered from the actions of terrorists on both sides at seeing
men go free whom they perceive to be guilty in general, and know in some cases
were responsible for the hurt they suffered, is understandable. But that is
life. To reach a peace settlement in Cyprus and Rhodesia, to mention only two
instances, the British Governments of the day had to negotiate with people
branded as terrorists, some with blood on their hands, many of whom went on to
become respected Commonwealth statesmen, men of violence transformed into men
of peace. We must hope that is happening today in Northern Ireland.
The 1995 Act does not apply to those serving life sentences and if the peace
process shows signs of succeeding there will be a case for reviewing their
situation because one should never say never in politics. Yesterday's releases
are only the first in a phased programme and more will follow next year and the
year after that. The hope is they will contribute to recreating normality in
Northern Ireland, although the latest punishment beatings and abductions
carried out by the IRA do not help. All the same, there are once again some
grounds for optimism, although they could disappear at any moment as has
happened so often before. The differences between the Prime Minister and the
Taoiseach, Mr John Bruton, which surfaced while Mr Major was at the
Commonwealth Conference in New Zealand, have thankfully been resolved and the
much delayed Anglo-Irish summit, which should have been held in September, is
back on the ``coming-shortly'' agenda.
The squabble with Dublin erupted after Mr Bruton effectively accused Britain of
foot dragging on the arms issue last weekend. Once back in London Mr Major
wrote to him setting out the British position. The last thing either Government
wanted was for the long-distance slanging match between the two men to gather
momentum hence his clarifications. Dublin indicated it was satisfied that Mr
Major's letter meant the twin-track procedure, under which preliminary talks
take place alongside the commission which will look at disarming the
para-militaries, could be achieved. The Prime Minister sent a second letter to
Mr Bruton on Thursday, will be writing to him again this weekend and, it is
said, discussing their contents with the Taoiseach on the telephone next week.
The peace process may no longer stick in the mud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New York, Friday Media less inclined to publish and be sued</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GAIL APPLESON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323187</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE American tobacco industry, which has used its enormous legal war chest to
win most lawsuits on smoking issues, has begun to use the threat of litigation
to undermine controversial news reports as well, lawyers say.
They warn the chilling effect from this threat has spread to medium-size and
smaller news organisations that are afraid to run sensitive stories because
they risk millions of dollars in legal fees.
``This is driven by the financial bottom line,'' said Bruce Ennis, a prominent
First Amendment lawyer in the Washington office of Jenner and Block.
``Regardless of who is likely to win or lose, the enormous expense of defending
suits is exerting a chilling effect on journalists and the media.''
Last Sunday, Mike Wallace, the veteran correspondent for the CBS news programme
60 Minutes, informed viewers that an interview with a former tobacco executive
criticising the industry was cut because lawyers feared an expensive lawsuit.
The programme has been widely criticised for ``caving in'' to the tobacco
industry even though no suit was threatened. But several newspapers reported
CBS had good reason to fear a suit because agreements it made with the unnamed
source exposed the show to legal liability.
A spokesman for 60 Minutes would not comment.
Experts familiar with press issues say the current climate, while tough for the
titans of communications, is even worse for small news outlets.
``If big news organisations are not prepared to take the risk to defend
themselves . . . why in the world would a much smaller organisation with much
fewer resources take the risk?'' said Jane Kirtley, executive director of
Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press.
The committee counsels journalists on legal issues, and Kirtley said there had
been a sharp rise in the number of calls from reporters fearing their stories
would be killed by their own lawyers because of fear of legal action.
Free-press advocates say these pressures have come even when no legal action
was threatened by the subjects of such stories.
The CBS action follows ABC's decision in August to settle a $10 billion libel
suit brought by Philip Morris over a story about nicotine addiction. Legal
sources said ABC paid some $15m to cover Philip Morris's legal fees.
``I see this as a related series of events and the weakening of the will of the
owners and the executives of news organisations to go to the wall for the right
of journalists to prove the truth,'' said Joan Konner, dean of Columbia
University's Graduate School of Journalism.
Steve Weinberg, former executive director of the group Investigative Reporters
and Editors, said self-censorship was growing as news organisations were
purchased by other entities.
The 60 Minutes decision was announced a week before CBS stockholders approved a
$5400m takeover by Westinghouse Electric Corp. ABC settled its suit shortly
after an announced takeover by Walt Disney Co, but both networks denied any
link.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323188</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AGAINST all odds, and at great personal risk, young - puerile-sounding anyway -
intrepid Ed Marriot, hearing of a lost tribe in a hugely inaccessible part of
Papua New Guinea, decides to go meet the Liawep people who live on the mountain
they worship as their god.
Nobody wants to help him and anthropologists try to dissuade him, gently at
first and then they come clean and suggest that he is nuts and liable to be
eaten. But does he listen? Not Ed. I must come clean myself here because when I
started listening to Our Father the Mountain (R4) I stopped the tape and gave
myself a little talking to. It went like this.
``Critic, put aside your prejudices about that voice. Remember that your
dislike of that kind of voice - no, that character-voice - has been recently
activated by last night's viewing of Four Weddings and a Funeral. Just because
he sounds like Hugh Grant in the jungle (I mean, of course, the Grant persona,
all terribly gosh and upper-class tic) does not mean the result of Ed's awfully
big adventure will be risible, deeply patronising and rather sick. You don't
yet know if it will be Numpty gets Pretty Scared in Bongo Land.'' So I deleted
my bias and rewound.
First of all we had to hear about the drugs and jags he needed to make his
actually illegal journey into primitivism. He is warned about the fatal bite of
some bug or snake (I'm sorry, I was laughing a bit here but it was one or the
other) he might encounter. A female bite of the species would be fatal, so he
asks how he is meant to tell the difference. Things were getting complicated
for Ed and he hadn't even reached the mountain yet.
With his guide Dunstan, Ed reaches the tribe, some of whom immediately scatter
into the nearest bit of denser jungle. Ed notes and ponders this. Things get
worse, and with an analytic grasp of the situation he says it's ``because I'm
basically here, isn't it?''
Yes, I murmured, yes! And as if he had heard me, Ed went on to describe how
suggestions had been made that there might be something colonialist and dubious
about going into a place he had no idea about, with no ideas whatsoever. The
head of the tribe was called Herod and not unsurprisingly, given his name, was
pretty het up about Christianity, de-manding that Ed profess his faith. Well,
he did this pretty reluctantly, he admitted, but you see, he didn't want to
offend, did he?
Herod was getting pretty hostile by this time but I suppose, not having seen
Four Weddings, he probably didn't get the joke. In the middle of this
tragi-comic nightmare, with lots of noise in the background, our reporter
whispers to Dunstan: ``Would it help if I came round to say hello?'' No, I
shouted, but this time he did not seem to hear me because things, astoundingly
in the face of his anthropological sensitivity, got worse.
The mountain got angry, Herod threw a fit, and four children died. Dunstan
rushed into Ed's room suggesting they better get out of there fast. Very fast,
so fast, in fact, that Ed fascinatingly cogitated on the fact that it had taken
them five days to get there, but only three days to get back.
Then once he had got his breath back, and explaining to us that it would have
been inopportune to hang around talking to his little machine in the middle of
the mayhem, Ed finished off his extraordinary contribution to global knowledge
by telling a little garbled nugget which involved 7th Day Adventists and gold
consortiums.
There is certainly a story to be told there, but next time I know exactly who
the producer should send. It came to me while listening to Gentlemen Prefer
Blondes (R4). Lorelei was given a diary; she was confused at first, because it
was a book without words, but once she grasped the diary concept, she warmed to
the idea - although she wondered, given that she thought all the time, how many
books she would need.
I still think that if Radio 4 had given her a cute little recording machine,
like they had given to Ed, she would have produced a better programme, and hit
it off with Herod.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lt Col P S Sandilands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lt-Col Robin Thorburn, regimental secretary, the Royal Highland Fusiliers.</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323189</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lt-Col P S Sandilands, DSO RSF, born November 1911, died August 29, 1995.
LT-COL Pat Sandilands - who was awarded a DSO in 1945 when serving with the 2nd
Battalion, Royal Scots Fusiliers - has died after several months of illness.
The son of of Col Prescott Sandilands, Royal Marines, Pat Sandilands was
educated at Wellington and Sandhurst and was commissioned in August 1931. His
family is descended from Sir James Sandilands, who was granted the lands of
Calder in 1346, and played a notable part in Scottish history.
In the early thirties Pat Sandilands served with the 1st Battalion the Royal
Scots Fusiliers in Palestine and Egypt, subsequently being seconded for three
years to the King's African Rifles on the Kenya/Abyssinia frontier. He rejoined
the 2nd battalion, Royal Scots Fusiliers, in Edinburgh in 1938 and was with the
Royal Guard at Balmoral the following year.
He went to France in 1939, but was recalled to England to attend the Staff
College, Camberley. Subsequently he held various jobs with the Home Forces.
These included planning ``butcher and bolt'' raids on the Continent with HQ 110
Force in Glasgow.
From November 1942 to May 1943 Sandilands was with the 1st Army in North Africa
and from June to August 1943 was a company commander with 8th Battalion, the
Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders, taking part in the Sicilian campaign, where
the Argylls fought with exceptional gallantry and determination.
Pat Sandilands was second-in-command of the 2nd Battalion, Royal Scots
Fusiliers, throughout the battalion's participation in the Italian campaign,
from the landing in Calabria to the fall of Rome, and its subsequent move to
Germany.
His fellow officer David Coutts recalls: ``To serve with Pat Sandilands
throughout the Italian campaign was an object lesson in discipline, patience,
courage, and total dedication.
``His primary role as second-in-command was to preserve himself within reason
for any eventuality. But the frustrations he endured on the many occasions when
the battalion split into `forward' and `back' were understandable. Given the
slightest excuse he would appear at battalion headquarters and company
positions, keeping himself in touch and displaying encouragement and infectious
humour.
``In periods of close fighting and against a determined enemy it was
predictable that this state of readiness was crucial and in January 1944, after
the successful crossing of the River Garigliano, tragedy struck when the
commanding officer was killed and Pat wounded virtually at the same time.
``Although evacuated he refused to stay away and returned to take command in
the line. Only when the situation eased would he agree to enter hospital and
have his wounds attended to.
``Some weeks later he rejoined the battalion in Anzio and again assumed command
when the commanding officer and adjutant were wounded. The leadership he
displayed and respect he engendered carried on when the battalion moved into
north-west Europe in 1945 for the River Elbe crossing and advance to Lubeck. He
was a soldier from the topmost drawer.''
Pat Sandilands's postwar career included stints as commanding officer of 5th
(Scottish) Battalion, the Parachute Regiment, 1947-49, assistant quartermaster
general, HQ Scottish Command, 1952-53, commanding officer of 15th (Scottish)
Battalion, the Parachute Regiment (TA), 1953-56, and assistant quartermaster
general (movements) at HQ Allied Forces Central Europe, Fontainebleau, 1957-59.
He retired in 1959 and became a pig farmer in the Borders before moving to
Lagganmore, Kilninver, to farm sheep. There he became a popular and
well-respected pillar of the community and an elder of the church. He married
Madeleine Turnbull in 1949. They had a son and daughter. His wife died in 1989,
and in 1994 he married his cousin Mary Sandilands.
</TEXT>
