<HEADLINE>Saudi regime given warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE exiled leader of the Saudi Arabian opposition said yesterday in Glasgow
that he feared the door to bloodshed had been opened in his country by Monday's
bomb near Riyadh which killed six people, including four US soldiers.
Professor Muhammad Al Massari, the leader of the Committee for the Defence of
Legitimate Rights, was speaking at the start of a UK tour which aims to expose
the regime as corrupt and hypocritical despots clinging to power.
While they as a peaceful coalition had no part in the violence, they were not
surprised by it and were sure that it would escalate.
``If you open that door to bloodshed, who is going to close it? You have to
have rational politicians and they are not allowed to do anything to solve the
current social and political crisis,'' Professor Massari said.
He was supported by Labour MP George Galloway, who has conducted a virtual
one-man crusade against the Saudi regime in the Commons.
Mr Galloway said: ``A regime which says we took this country by the sword is
inviting its opponents to put them to death by the sword.''
Professor Massari, a leading scientist, fled to Britain last year after being
imprisoned and tortured in Saudi Arabia. From his home in London, he now
bombards his native country with faxes denouncing its royal family.
It was difficult to estimate the size of the opposition in his country, he
said. ``We feel there are tens of thousands who are participating actively
against the regime while there are silent millions who are fed up with it.''
The regime, Mr Galloway said, had literally looted its own country.
``They have lifted thousands of millions out and into the casinos of London and
into investments in real estate in Manhattan. It is grand larceny on a scale
the world has never seen before. It makes Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos look like
poor people.''
He hoped that Britain would not repeat the mistakes it had made with the Shah
of Iran. By backing him when the people were already on the streets, Britain
had contributed to the alienation of the Iraqi people from all things Western.
</TEXT>
