<HEADLINE>US mediators offer final chance for a settlement Washington, Friday</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Dayton conference on Bosnia is on the verge of success, or failure. The
Americans believe that they have all the details of an acceptable peace
agreement ready to be initialled this weekend, probably in the presence of
President Clinton.
The last effort to bring the Serbs, Croats, and Muslims to accept the proposal
as the best they will get will be made this evening by the Secretary of State,
Warren Christopher, who is flying back from Japan.
If all goes well, Nato will start moving headquarters staff and advance teams
into the region immediately.
The Secretary of Defence, William Perry, and the American commander of Nato,
Gen George Joulwan, went to Dayton today to oversee the last details, which
involve the exact lines on the map dividing the parties and the disposition of
the 60,000 Nato troops who will monitor the peace.
Once these matters have been settled and the agreement is initialled, the
President and his administration will try to persuade Congress that it is in
the national interest to send 20,000 American soldiers to Bosnia. It will not
be easy.
The plan is that the 1st Armoured Division, which was the backbone of the
allied forces in the Gulf war, will be sent to Bosnia. Its advanced
headquarters will be in Pecs, Hungary, and advance elements will fly there next
week.
The division will follow overland. Permission will be needed from the Czech
Republic and, perhaps, Austria, for the movement of a major American unit
across what was once the Iron Curtain.
The Serb, Croat, and Muslim leaders are being told that this is their last
chance for a settlement. If the talks fail, Bosnia would face the prospect of
another horrible winter, and possibly an immediate resumption of the war.
The State Department spokesman said this morning that the parties were still
separated on several major issues, but that the US hoped that a comprehensive
peace agreement was within reach.
Serbs and Muslims are still obdurate on the territorial issue.
Neither side will give up any land it now controls and each insists that it
must have more. The Serbs want to take possession of Gorazde, the last Muslim
town in eastern Bosnia, so that they will completely control that region which
is contiguous to Serbia itself.
They clearly hope that in a few years' time they could simply annex it. For
this very reason, the Muslims refuse to give up the town, and furthermore
demand the return of Srebrenica and Zepa, which the Serbs captured this past
summer.
In the west, the Serbs are demanding the return of some of the territory they
lost to the Croatian-Muslim offensive in September and October, while the
Croats demand a strip of territory they lost in 1992 and did not recover last
summer.
The Sarajevo question, also, is unresolved, despite Mr Christopher's best
efforts over a 14-hour session on Tuesday.
The Americans and their allies have hinted that if the two most prominent
leaders of the Bosnian Serbs, Ratko Mladic and Radovan Karadzic, retire to
Belgrade, they will not then be pursued too vigorously.
However, this clemency is not supported by the war crimes tribunal. The chief
prosecutor, Judge Richard Goldstone, was in Washington this week urging the
Americans to insist those accused of war crimes must be handed over to the
tribunal.
So far, the President of Yugoslavia, Slobodan Milosevic, has refused to agree
that Mladic and Karadzic must be removed from office immediately.Similarly, the
President of Croatia, Franjo Tudjman, is refusing to allow Croatians who have
been indicted to be arrested. He promoted one of them to a senior post in the
Croatian army the day after he was indicted, and so far has declined to rescind
the promotion.
Perspective.........................Page 13
</TEXT>
