<HEADLINE>Spillers' Barrhead plant to shed 65 jobs in New Year</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPILLERS pet food company is to shed 65 people from its 352 workforce at
Barrhead in the new year.
A spokesman for the company said the cuts were being made to give the Crossmill
factory ``a competitive edge'' to play a leading role in the company's European
network.
However, a spokesman for the shopworkers' union USDAW said the announcement had
come as a shock, as the Barrhead factory produced pet food at the most
competitive rate of all Spillers' sites.
``I understand that the redundancies will not take place until into the New
Year, but it is bad news for our members going through the festive period with
this hanging over them,'' said Mr Ian Fraser, area organiser for USDAW.
Early this year, Spillers' parent company Dalgety, which makes Arthur's,
Choosy, and Prime pet foods, bought Quaker Oats' European pet food business,
making it the second market leader in Europe behind Mar's Pedigree brand.
Mr Jon Delap, a spokesman for Spillers, said the factory would maintain its
production capacity of about 50m tins of pet food a month but would be changing
certain working practices. Factory manager Graham Martin said: ``We have a
modern factory here in Barrhead and we will maintain our existing production
capability. We are taking these steps to ensure we have the competitive edge
that is essential to our future success. All those employees who are affected
have my personal sympathy and we will provide them with a support programme,
including independent help in finding new employment.''
Spillers' has no planned job cuts for its two other factories in England or a
number of others in Europe.
</TEXT>
