<HEADLINE>Old Testament law</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Episcopal Bishop of Edinburgh in his lecture at Strathclyde University
fails to distinguish between the three categories of Old Testament law - the
ceremonial, the civil, and the moral (November 15).
The ceremonial law involved Israel's worship of God. Christians are no longer
bound by the ceremonial law after Jesus's death and resurrection because Jesus
was the ultimate perfect sacrifice - the Passover Lamb who took away the sins
of the world once and for all for those who believe in Him.
The civil law applied to daily living in Israel. Because our world is so
radically different the civil law cannot be rigidly applied to our society. The
principles behind the civil law can, however, be applied today - fairness,
compassion, mercy, and justice.
Moral law, such as the Ten Commandments, is the direct command of God and
reveals the nature and will of God. It is timeless in its application.
Difficulties arise among genuine and responsible Christians when there is
confusion between the civil and the moral law.
So how do we tell what is God's moral law, and therefore immutable, and what is
civil law and therefore, in its detail, culturally based?
We have to look to Jesus because as the son of God He understands the heart and
nature of God. In Matthew 22, 37:40 Jesus said, ``Love the Lord your God with
all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind. This is the first
and greatest commandment, and the second is like it: Love your neighbour as
yourself. All the law and the prophets hang on these two commandments''.
So any particular moral issue for the Christian must be judged against these
two great commandments. If a particular view or moral stance causes us to
workship something or someone (including ourselves) other than God, that is
wrong.
If it causes us to oppress, hate, ridicule, or hurt other people that is also
wrong.
How are Christians to view homosexuality by biblical standards? The Bible is
quite clear. In Leviticus 18:22 it lays down ``do not lie with a man as one
lies with a woman; that is detestable''.
It is difficult to see this as anything other than moral law rather than civil
law which is culturally based. So why would God proscribe homosexual acts?
It must be because it gets in the way between man and God and, therefore, stops
the homosexual from fully worshipping God with all his heart, soul, and mind.
But the second great commandment teaches us that we must respond to the
homosexual with love, compassion, and understanding. We are all sinners. Jesus
teaches us to hate the sin, but love the sinner.
To practising homosexuals Christ says that you are sinning, but that He loves
you and wants you to stop sinning.
In this life you are not promised that it will be easy, because God disciplines
those He loves; but you will experience real joy and fulfilment and purpose.
You will experience the love of God, which will set you free.
Michael J.R Smith,
6 Ingleside,
Beech Road,
Lenzie.
RELIGION
</TEXT>
