<HEADLINE>Major launches offensive on two fronts as he tackles constitutional problems Raising the stakes with Union card</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government sought to polarise the constitutional debate yesterday, talking
up the threat of independence while attempting to ensnare Labour in more modest
proposals involving the Scottish Grand Committee.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth is seeking Labour approval for an extended
series of meetings of the Grand Committee throughout Scotland and the taking of
evidence from the public on proposed legislation, in a clear attempt to draw
attention from Opposition plans for a Scottish parliament.
Following the Prime Minister's surprising comment to a London newspaper that
``no one should doubt that Scotland could be a separate nation'', Mr Forsyth
asserted yesterday: ``There is only one party that is entitled to argue for all
decision-making to be made in Scotland and that is the SNP.''
Later, in an interview with The Herald, Mr Forsyth refused to comment on
predictions that he will strengthen the Scottish Grand Committee and enhance
the role of Scottish Questions in the Commons, but added: ``They certainly
haven't identified what I'm going to do, and some of what they've identified is
not correct.''
He said: ``I will in the next few days seek agreement from Mr Robertson for a
programme for the whole year ahead of meetings of the Scottish Grand Committee.
I will be expecting very regular meetings.''
Asked if sessions could be held in more remote parts of Scotland, Mr Forsyth
said: ``If the House authorities can find premises to meet the standards
required, and people are willing to host the Grand Committee, why shouldn't it
get round Scotland?''
Mr Forsyth wants people to know in advance where and when the committee will
sit to increase the public awareness of its activities.
While careful to avoid rebuffing this particular move, Labour made it clear
that this was not seen as heavy armour in the fight over the Scottish
Constitutional Convention's plans for a Scottish parliament, to be announced on
the same day, November 30.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson was convinced that the Prime
Minister had scored an own goal in conceding that there was a democratic
deficit. ``He is admitting that what Labour has been saying for the last 16
years, that change is needed, is absolutely correct.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond was delighted by the apparent endorsement of the
viability of his party's case by the Prime Minister, saying: ``Sooner, rather
than later, the Tory Party will have to come to terms with the fact that
Scotland requires real change in the form of an independent parliament, not
more cosmetic tinkering with the Westminster system.''
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said the latest stocktaking
proposals ``did not amount to a row of beans,'
' adding: ``Mr Major's ideas have no real substance and fail to address
Scotland's democratic deficit.''
Mr Forsyth's current sensitivity to the way the constitutional debate is
running was shown in two ways yesterday. He confirmed the appointment of a new
``spin doctor'' as a special adviser.
Ms Jacqui Low, head of media and communications at Scottish Tory Central Office
for the past two years, takes up her post on Monday. Political opponents argue
this appointment has blurred the distinction between Government and party
affairs.
The Scottish Office also put pressure on the Fraser of Allander Institute
yesterday to release data on a survey to be published next Tuesday of the
attitude of members of Chambers of Commerce to constitutional change.
Having received the findings, Mr Forsyth said: ``I am greatly looking forward
to Tuesday, when those who have pontificated about a survey they have not seen
will undoubtedly have egg on their faces.''
The Herald understands that the survey's findings are complex enough for
different sides to make different interpretations, but they are believed to
show a clear shift in opinion in the business community towards being less
hostile to constitutional change.
In his interview with The Herald last night, Mr Forsyth gave an indication of
how far he was prepared to go to prove that the Government listens. He
suggested he would agree to change ``radically'' legislation to licence raves
based on the views of Scotland's young people.
He denied his proposals on St Andrew's Day will amount to no more than creating
a talking shop. ``When I was appointed I made a promise to look at ways of
improving Government in Scotland, of improving accountability, of involving
people more.''
As an example of the sort of initiatives he is prepared to consider following
his consultations, Mr Forsyth cited the plan to transfer to crofters lands
owned by the Scottish Office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
