<HEADLINE>Vatican ban on schools pack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR news report (Dismay at Vatican ban on schools HIV pack, November 13)
showed that, even with a liberal Roman administration, the dogma of Papal
infallibility still shines through.
The Roman Catholic Church cannot and will not at any time sanction artificial
contraception, homosexual activity, abortion, or any other kind of perversity
no matter how many archbishops give their consent.
The fact that the church continues to condemn any departure from its moral
teaching, as in the case of Archbishop Keith O'Brien, at a time when it is
itself infected with liberalism enhances this dogmatic truth.
It is an article of the Catholic faith that Papal infallibility involves the
direct guidance of God, so that in pronouncing universally on matters of faith
and morals the Pope cannot err.
Archbishop O'Brien was fully aware of this when he gave his imprimatur to a sex
education pack, HIV Prevention - A Christian Response, which is opposed to the
moral teaching of the church. By doing so he helped to promote promiscuity (the
cause of HIV) thereby endangering the souls under his care.
The Vatican ordered the removal of the Archbishop's imprimatur from this
scandalous pack, as well as the removal of the pack itself from Catholic
schools. It is a pity that it did not also order the removal of the Archbishop
from his office.
Sadly, however, there are many other Catholic clerics around the world
rebelling in one form or another against the faith. Such is the price of the
ecumenical revolution of Vatican Council II.
Martin Blackshaw,
24 Glen Road,
Deans, Livingston.
</TEXT>
