<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trial venue</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323199</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SURELY Allan Stewart's proposal for progressing the trial of those accused of
the Pan Am/Lockerbie bomb must be considered. It is now several months since he
first stated his support for a trial in a neutral country and, given the lack
of advance since he did so, this may be the only feasible course of action.
There will be those who dismiss the suggestion of a trial outwith Scotland, the
United Kingdom, or the United States. However, I believe a trial in a neutral
country would be infinitely better than no trial at all as it seems destined to
be under the current policy.
Unless they are to be tried in a neutral country, Colonel Gaddafi is not going
to hand over the two suspects no matter how many United Nations resolutions he
is subjected to, no matter how loud the international condemnation is.
The most important concern is not where the trial takes place but that it does
take place. The murderers of the 270 must be brought to justice, a conclusion
which will be unapproachable never mind unachievable if the prime suspects'
participation is denied.
Neil Deerey,
14 Ryat Drive, Newton Mearns.
</TEXT>
