<HEADLINE>High turnout despite death threats Ex-general sweeps to poll victory Algiers, Friday</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALGERIA'S military-backed leader Liamine Zeroual was today officially declared
the outright winner of yesterday's high-security presidential election.
Zeroual, a former general who was appointed to run the wartorn country in
January 1994, won 61.34% of the vote, Interior Minister Mustapha Ben Mensour
said in the capital, Algiers.
He put the turnout at 74.92%, a figure quickly disputed by the outlawed Islamic
Salvation Front, which claimed it was really less than half that amount.
The FIS, barred from taking part in the poll, had called for a boycott and
armed Islamic groups had threatened to kill voters. But in the event the
election was generally peaceful, with an estimated 200,000 members of the
security forces on alert to guard against trouble.
The runner-up to Zeroual at once accused the authorities of rigging the result.
``Votes and ballot boxes were hijacked,'' Islamic leader Mahfoud Nahnah told
his supporters.
According to official results he took 25.38% of the votes, with anti-Islamic
candidate Said Saadi on 9.29% and a fourth candidate trailing with 3.78%.
It was the first election since late 1991 when the FIS convincingly won a first
round in parliamentary polls. The following January the Government cancelled
the second round and more than 50,000 people have since died in political
violence.
Zeroual, 54, today called the elections ``a victory to the sovereignty of the
people and true democracy in our country and a lesson to its enemies inside and
outside Algeria''.
In the streets of Algiers hundreds of his supporters waved Algerian flags and
hooted car horns. Security forces, deployed to guard voters yesterday and still
on high alert, unleashed celebratory barrages of gunfire into the air.
Zeroual, who has cracked down on Muslim rebels while trying to negotiate with
arrested fundamentalist leaders, has pledged to pursue dialogue with the
opposition and create a democracy.
Algeria's former colonial ruler France, which has been hit by a deadly wave of
bombings blamed on Algerian rebels, said it hoped Zeroual's victory would lead
to talks with the opposition and to fresh parliamentary elections.
Early reaction from exiled FIS members did not bode well.
``We still consider that an illegitimate regime is in place in Algeria,'' said
Anouar Haddam, an FIS leader living in the United States.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
