<DOCNO>GH951118-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Disabled dealer avoids jail sentence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEELCHAIR-bound Lawrence Harrison used his disability to disguise his double
life as a drug dealer. Confined to a wheelchair following a stroke, he sold
supplies of controversial temgesic tablets, Paisley Sheriff Court was told.
Fining the 62-year-old, from Greenhill Road, Ferguslie Park, #400, Sheriff
Ronald Smith said he would normally have jailed anyone concerned in supplying
others with drugs.
However, after studying social enquiry reports and a community service
assessment, he said there would be nothing to gain from sending the accused to
prison.
The sheriff had earlier heard how Harrison was found out after police saw him
acting suspiciously at the town's St James's railway station.
He was searched and found to be carrying 300 of the tablets - known to users as
Tems - in his possession.
The court was told how he regularly travelled as far afield as Liverpool and
Derry to get supplies after the painkillers - misused by addicts in the same
way as Temazepam - were outlawed.
Harrison denied being involved in the supply of the drug and claimed instead
that he was forced to find alternative supplies for his own use when doctors
refused to prescribe them.
The sheriff found him guilty after trial and, when Harrison appeared for
sentence yesterday, told him: ``It seems clear to me that you have been using
your disability as camouflage for your wicked practices. It is difficult to
accept that a person with such disabilities would visit these places on a
regular basis except for nefarious practices.''
Drug dealer Lawrence Harrison, who used his wheelchair to disguise double life.
Picture: SPINDRIFT
</TEXT>
