<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Widow wins job claim and #1000</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WIDOW has won an unfair sacking claim on behalf of her late husband.
Mr Gordon Tosh had claimed he was dismissed unfairly when he was made redundant
from his job as business development manager with a Glasgow company.
However, he died five months after he lost his job and before an industrial
tribunal heard his unfair sacking claim against Crouch Hogg Waterman Ltd of The
Octagon, Baird Street.
His widow and executrix, Mrs Maureen Tosh, continued the fight and the tribunal
in Glasgow ruled he had been unfairly dismissed and awarded #1000 compensation.
The tribunal heard Mr Tosh, 57, of Fotheringay Road, Glasgow, was made
redundant on February 1 but died in July.
The company said there was a marked downturn in business due to the recession.
There was no question of Mr Tosh's ability and it was simply a matter of the
business not being there.
They had also failed to win a major contract and decided late last year that
redundancies would have to be made but did not wish to announce these before
Christmas.
Mr Tosh was not given any warning about his redundancy until the date of his
dismissal.
The company claimed he was aware of the general adverse position of the company
but the tribunal said that was not the same thing as giving specific warning
about the possibility of his redundancy.
The tribunal heard that a redundancy letter was prepared in advance and handed
to him. While there was some discussion about his position, there seemed little
doubt that a decision had already been taken to make him redundant.
The tribunal found that there had been little, if anything, in the way of
adequate consultation and warning and ruled his dismissal was unfair because of
inadequate procedures.
However, the tribunal accepted that given the genuine redundancy situation
which existed, it was fairly clear that Mr Tosh would eventually have been
dismissed by reason of redundancy. Further warning or consultaion would have
been unlikely to have produced any different result.
The tribunal therefore awarded compensation for the likely period of
consultation and awarded #1000 compensation.
</TEXT>
