<DOCNO>GH951118-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Access to woods</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are a number of points arising from the article, These woods were made
for walking (November 15), which should be made to put in perspective the
concerns about restrictions on public access to woods sold by the Forestry
Commission.
The fact that in these circumstances apparently only one access agreement has
been struck with a local authority in Scotland does not in itself mean that
access will not be provided by the new owners, usually on an informal basis.
Most of the woods sold are in fact small, purely commercial plantations which
the public have shown no interest in visiting. In such cases there is not in
fact a loss of public access as a result of a sale.
It also has to be realised that these woodlands are often some distance from
the public road and as the commission's title will normally only permit access
for forestry purposes the commission does not always have the legal power to
confer a right of access to the public.
The Scottish Landowners' Federation supported the Government's policy to offer
local authorities the chance to enter into access agreements.
However, there is no doubt in my mind that the lack of interest by local
authorities in entering into access agreements for woodland demonstrates yet
again the regrettable lack of interest in this issue by local authorities
which, with honourable exceptions, do not devote nearly enough resources to an
issue which is of great significance in the countryside and are failing to
provide the benefits which the public expect.
Duncan W Thomson,
Legal Adviser,
Scottish Landowners'
Federation,
25 Maritime Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
