<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J.P. Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING to write this every week can really do your head in. Things get out of
hand when you end up doing things not because you enjoy them, but because it
might spin out into the right number of words. That was my excuse for going to
see the musical Fame in London's Cambridge Theatre on Saturday night.
I had to resort to subterfuge. After a while because of the abuse, I was as
vague as possible. People mocked the musical so much because their only
experience of the Fame concept is the TV series. I remember further back.
On a 1980 Glasgow Sunday night we went to see the film, not knowing a thing
about it. Alan Parker did a great job of catching a moody, backlit, and above
all realistic tale of doomed ambition and I loved every minute of it.
Unfortunately, along came the soft cream cake of a TV series, and the rest was
leotard dressed history. It ruined it all, and the word Fame was synonymous
with a crappy teen soap with a moral at the end of every episode, and a hit
record every six weeks.
Those of you who would expect the show to be nothing but a group of teenagers
singing and dancing for two hours would be wrong. It was more, actually being a
group of teenagers singing suprisingly badly. Given that they were untramelled
by anything as trifling as melody or harmony, you would think that they could
have at least managed to be loud. There are few things I can get worked up
about, the majority involving 11 men in shorts kicking a ball. I can't see the
appeal of the type of shallow tosh that forgoes any degree of character
development in order to allow, among other things, a five-minute song and dance
routine about the physical effects of male teenage lust. (Is this subtle
enough?) (Surprisingly, yes - Ed).
Watching the audience, you'd have thought they were witnessing John Lennon
duetting with Elvis. The girls next to me absolutely loved it, and they were on
their feet at the end of every song.
By the time the finale arrived (``finale''. Italian: meaning interminably
stupid song), I'd just about had enough. It was the artistic equivalent of the
car crash, and I just couldn't help watching. When a cardboard taxi is wheeled
on, even the fat baldy bloke who played the teacher had obeyed the call to
``pardy on''.
I got out quickly. It was our turn to ``pardy on''. Some stupid bugger had
decided to hire Madame Tussaud's for a party. Now I've been to a few good
nights, but I've never been to one like this. It was superb. I'd always been of
the opinion that if you've seen one stupid dummy, you've probably been watching
Late Edition, er ..... I mean, you've seen them all. I was wrong. Maybe it was
just the beer, but I was quite taken by the whole experience. It's nice to see
that Tussaud's has kept up with the times, as Mr T still figures heavily. The
Paul Daniels dummy looked like an annoying wee pratt - so it was probably an
uncanny likeness, but why anyone would want to see a wax effigy of Will
Carling, never mind Will Carling himself is beyond me.
The Chamber of Horrors is the most famous part of Tussaud's, and as the night
neared it's end I had to walk through it on my way out on my own. Some bright
spark had the idea of dressing up as Dracula so he could jump out to
``surprise'' people from the dark alleys         of the Jack the Ripper set. At
two on a Tuesday afternoon that might be amusing. At midnight on Saturday, it
somehow doesn't seem quite so clever.
The last part of the chamber was quite horrific in its ordinariness. It was a
brightly lit prison hall, with a collection of surprisingly short, bland
looking men all around, with a summary of their various crimes pinned to the
walls behind them. With the West trial proceeding, it was interesting to see
that the existence of perverts and psychopaths is not unique to the late
twentieth century. I was alone in the hall, and it was quite unnerving. The
sound of echoing warders' feet mixed with the screams from the next room. With
a shiver, I turned and hurried out.
It was almost midnight, and I had arranged to see Fred MacCaulay at The Comedy
Store late show. Fred was the night's compere, and it was a pleasure to see
him, in better form than ever, looking so at home in the best known comedy club
in Britain.
By the end of the night, I was several beers down the line, sauntering back to
the hotel in good spirits. I was glad I went to the Store, as it helped me
forget the horror of those insane bloodcurdling screams. Yup, that Fame finale
was pretty horrible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000068</DOCNO>
