<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU deadline threat to ski railway plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS for a #17m redevelopment of the Cairngorm ski resort, including
establishment of Britain's first funicular railway, may, even now, be running
out of time for crucial funding from the European Objective One Programme,
which is not due to finish until the end of the century.
This is the fear of the Cairngorm Chairlift Company chief excutive Tim
Whittome, who had hoped to have received planning permission a year ago.
With the first real snow of the year yesterday, the company was preparing for
some serious skiing this weekend but Mr Whittome was looking further ahead, at
the timescale for the EU funding which would be a crucial, but so far
unsecured, element in the whole project.
The plans for a railway to replace the chairlift, which is more than 30 years
old, were first unveiled two and a half years ago but almost immediately ran
into opposition from environmental groups.
Now, visitor management seems to be the last outstanding issue. If the company
can persuade Scottish Natural Heritage on that issue, it might yet get planning
permission.
Mr Whittome is not sure it will be in time: ``Things are getting tight. I think
it is now impossible that there could be a decision at the December meeting of
Highland Regional Council's planning committee. We had hoped to make that.
``The committee's next meeting is in February and then we get into the
change-over at the end of March to the new Highland Council. Also in March, we
have a deadline for submissions for Objective One, for which we need planning
agreement, at least in principle. After that we would have to wait another six
months.
``If everything goes according to plan, we get the approval in February, the
application for Objective One is submitted in March, and we will know sometime
in July or August whether we have got it. So we could then start work on the
railway in May 1997.''
He said the project could be completed by the end of 1999.
He is convinced that if there is any delay in that timetable, if the matter
goes to a public inquiry - which could take two years - the Objective One money
for tourism would have long since been committed.
To have any hope, SNH, which has lodged an official objection to the planning
application, must be convinced that the company's plans for visitor management
are equal to the increased visitor numbers which may be attracted by the new
railway.
Timely agreement may yet be possible, however, SNH's Cairngorm area officer, Mr
Jonathan Stacey, told The Herald yesterday: ``SNH has come in for some
criticism for apparently dragging its feet on this one. That is not the case.
We are not opposed to development in Coire Cas, this is not a Lurchers
Gully-type dispute. We recognise the system that is there is outdated and needs
replaced.
``We recognise the March deadline for European funding, and SNH, along with
Highlands Regional Council and the chairlift company, are working towards that
date.''
A spokesman for Highland Regional Council's planning department said the matter
was progressing and there is to be a meeting with the chairlift company on
Monday. The very earliest it will be considered by the planning committee,
however, will be February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
