<DOCNO>GH951118-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warning that Calton Athletic's former addicts may `convey wrong message' to pupils Schools `ban' for drugs group</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Exclusive
ONE of Scotland's leading drug rehabilitation groups, Glasgow-based Calton
Athletic, claims it has been prevented from giving talks on the dangers of
drugs to pupils in Strathclyde secondary schools.
The controversy has angered those who say the group's tough approach to drugs
and its ex-addict members' first-hand experience of the devastating effects,
are invaluable in the fight against drugs abuse among young people.
Yesterday, the group's project leader, Mr David Bryce, claimed a series of
talks, this month, to pupils at Hillpark Secondary and St Andrew's Secondary
schools in Glasgow, had been cancelled on the advice of a Strathclyde Regional
Council official.
However, the official concerned, the council's regional adviser in health
education, Mr Alistair Ramsay, denied he had ever singled out Calton Athletic.
He said that, on the basis of independent research and advice from the Home
Office, Scottish Office, and the Scottish Affairs Select Committee on drugs, he
advised schools to be aware that ex-addicts could give conflicting messages to
pupils, suggesting that it was possible to be an addict and survive.
He confirmed he had spoken to a teacher at Hillpark Secondary but said his role
was purely advisory and that, ultimately, any decision on bringing in outside
groups to speak to pupils rested with a head teacher.
``In the face of the evidence given by the select committee and the Home
Office, it would be highly irresponsible for us to ignore that advice. If a
head teacher is seeking advice, it is irresponsible not to give it.''
However, in a letter to the region's deputy director of education, Mr David
Alexander, Mr Bryce has demanded clarification of the council's policy towards
drug education in schools. In the letter, he writes: ``I am now staggered to
find that Mr Ramsay is instructing your schools not to allow Calton Athletic's
work to continue as `the Scottish Office does not approve'. It is really quite
appalling that a voluntary group's efforts are being stopped.''
This summer, the group, which receives #200,000 in local authority and health
board funding for its recovery work, received a grant of #80,000 from the
private Robertson Trust for its schools education programme.
Mr Bryce said the group had refined its schools programme over the three years
its members had been giving talks to pupils, and had received praise from
pupils, teachers, and parents. Since March, the group had given talks in 15
schools in Strathclyde and the Borders.
He said he had also demanded an explanation from Scottish Office Education
Minister Raymond Robertson. Last month, the Minister announced three different
drugs programmes aimed at primary and secondary schools.
Labour MP for Kilmarnock and Loudoun, Mr William McKelvey, who chaired the
select committee, said that while drugs programmes in schools had to be looked
at carefully, he had heard only favourable reports of the work done by Calton
Athletic.
``I think the people who work for Calton Athletic do a great job. I see no
reason why Calton Athletic, provided the head teacher agrees, cannot go into
school to talk about drugs.''
Hillpark secondary's guidance teacher, Mr John Philbin, confirmed that Calton
Athletic had been due to give a series of talks which had subsequently been
cancelled.
St Andrew's secondary's deputy head teacher, Mr Frank Lennon, also confirmed
the group had been due to speak to pupils. He said the talks had been cancelled
as they did not fit in with the school's own anti-drugs programme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A decent answer to Constitutional question?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robbie Dinwoodie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE snail's pace progress towards Home Rule has been the subject of much
derision, but while everyone can find something to take issue with in the plans
finally agreed by the Scottish Constitutional Convention, most accept that
there is much in the scheme that is decent and good.
You can exclude diehard Unionists from that analysis, and write off strong
proponents of independence. But among the citizenry well-disposed to the scheme
, who harbour the broad belief that Scotland can be better run from within
rather than without, there is a consensus that the convention plans are a
decent stab at squaring a host of constitutional circles.
The unaligned, non-partisan voter with an insistent but unstrident self-image
of Scottishness has taken to the simple idea of a Scottish Parliament to frame
Scottish laws, while leaving the British strand of their identity intact.
In a sense, this is a question of leaving the tougher options open. Such Scots
can feel proud and to a large extent committed, without taking what some will
instinctively feel is a reckless step into the unknown.
They might be labelled by Nationalists as fainthearts, but their beliefs remain
consistent, according to our polls. What is less certain, is whether the
limited autonomy of Home Rule is seen as a finite end in itself, or whether
people will accept it as a process which may ultimately lead to greater
independence.
The early steps are relatively simple, however. At the next General Election if
the British electorate places its trust in Labour, the party will legislate for
a Scottish Parliament and Welsh Assembly within their first year's legislative
programme.
Doubts have been cast on this in some quarters, even some close to home within
the Labour-Liberal Democrat pact that forms the backbone of the convention.
Chief Whip Archy Kirkwood suggested recently that this legislative programme
would be impossible to deliver, in the face of a concerted attack on the floor
of the House by determined Tories.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson has been bullish in his dismissal of
this, pointing out that the Conservatives have been able to push through
controversial European legislation in the House of Commons.
There is no indication that the SNP would seek to sabotage the passage of such
a Bill.
The reasoning behind this is twofold. One is that the proposed body in
Edinburgh would be better than none at all and could be used as a focus of
dissent, creating the ``slippery slope to independence'' feared by Unionists.
The second is that the Scottish electorate would punish them for a
fundamentalist stance.
As a result, the convention scheme is by far the most likely future scenario
for our future.
Under Mr Blair a Scottish Parliament would take over the existing Scottish
Office control of law, education, health, local government, transport,
planning, industry ,and the environment.
The budget would continue to be a formula agreed with Westminster, but with the
additional power to raise or lower the standard rate of income tax by 3p.
There will be 73 constituencies, based on the existing boundaries but with
Orkney and Shetland receiving one each in recognition of their geographical
need. In addition, in each of our eight current European constituencies, seven
additional members will be returned.
These candidates will be chosen locally by parties under standard selection
procedures, and elected according to a second ``party'' vote. A pact between
parties will also allow this corrective process to be used to get greater
numbers of women into the Parliament.
The 129 Members of the Scottish Parliament will meet during office hours in the
former Royal High School building in Edinburgh. They will will also meet at
committee meetings throughout Scotland.
Beyond then, the great imponderable is whether these MSPs will be happy to
accept the in-built limitations of the devolution scheme denying them powers on
defence, foreign affairs, immigration, social security policy, and
macro-economic policies.
Only this week, a report argued that the Home Rule Parliament must stake a
claim to a say in foreign affairs if it was to have any firm purpose. With
controversies such as nuclear weapons, naval base closures, and the disbandment
of Scottish regiments, it would be easy to see the Parliament in Edinburgh
taking a view.
Where then does the process stop. The line between legitimate interest and the
slide towards independence may then become blurred. What began as a sop to
Scottish opinion could become an instrument of increasing demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former chief of Cosla for Lords</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE only ``Scottish'' working life peer among 11 named yesterday is Professor
John Sewel, who has been instrumental in guiding the preparations for the
Scottish Devolution Bill should Labour win the next election.
He was brought up in Bradford but describes himself as a Scottish politician,
having spent his entire political life and all except two years of his
professional life in Scotland. He moved to Aberdeen in 1969.
Professor Sewel, 59, is a Vice Principal of Aberdeen University and dean of the
faculty of social sciences and law.
He has been a member of the Labour Party for 25 years. For a decade, he was a
member of Aberdeen City Council and for three of those years he was its leader.
From 1982 to 1984, he was president of the Convention of Scottish Local
Authorities.
He said: ``It is obviously a challenging opportunity coming as it does at a
particularly interesting time in Scottish politics. I look forward to being a
full and active member of the House of Lords and doing what I can to secure the
return of a Labour Government.
``I would hope to play an active part to secure that Labour Government's
legislative programme and, in particular, securing a Bill establishing a
parliament for Scotland.''
Sir Gordon Borrie, 64, the man who chaired Labour's inquiry into shaking up the
welfare state, is another new working peer. Downing Street announced five new
Conservative peers, four new Labour ones, and two new Liberal Democrats.
New Tory peers include Lady Wilcox, chairman of the National Consumer Council,
who is also a member of the advisory panel on the Citizen's Charter and
chairman of the charter's complaints task force.
Mrs Helene Hayman, 46, a former MP who represented Welwyn and Hatfield from
1974-79, is a new Labour peer.
Professor Robert Winston, 55, professor of fertility studies at the Royal
Postgraduate Medical School, London University, has been named a Labour peer.
Mr Tom McNally, 52, a former Labour MP who defected to the SDP in 1981, has
been named a Liberal Democrat peer.
The other new Liberal Democrat peer is Dr William Wallace, 54, reader in
international relations at the London School of Economics.
Other new Tory peers are:
Sir Peter Bowness, 52, who was leader of Croydon Council from 1976 until it was
won by Labour last year and who now leads the Tory opposition on the council;
Canon Peter Pilkington, 62, chairman of the Broadcasting Complaints Commission
and honorary canon of Canterbury Cathedral from 1975-90;
Sir Basil Feldman, 69, chairman of the National Union of the Conservative
Party; and
Sir Philip Harris, 53, chairman of Carpetright plc, Harris Ventures, C.W Harris
Properties, and deputy chairman of the Conservative Party treasurers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Move to counter Old Course criticism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323209</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE slice of tee-off times at the Old Course, negotiated by a London company
which is advertising #1390 holiday packages at St Andrews, provoked further
debate yesterday.
The Links Trust responsible for managing the golf course revealed it is to
contact British tourism offices worldwide in a bid to counter criticism of
costs and reduced access which, it is claimed, may damage tourism.
The decision follows revelations in The Herald that US tourists have cancelled
holidays and switched to cheaper venues such as Ireland.
Mr Peter Mason, external relations manager for the trust, insisted yesterday
that corporate packages costing #1390 would be used by only 14% of players who
tee off at the Old Course next year. ``The other 86% of times will be available
at the standard green fee (#60) next summer, a level which we believe is
affordable to most golfers,'' said Mr Mason.
Criticism was sparked by an agreement between the trust, the Keith Prowse
Agency, and a US enterprise, Pensus, which will earn the trust #5m over 10
years in return for the exclusive right to provide corporate packages.
The Scottish Incoming Golf Tour Operators' Association challenges the trust's
figures. Although 86% of players will pay the normal price, the association
points out that only 2500 tee-off times (10,000 players) representing a quarter
of those available all year, are bookable in advance by visitors.
The new deal means that 1040 of these 2500 advance reservations are controlled
by Keith Prowse and Pensus, representing 40% of the advance bookable play. The
restriction on times available to visitors, claims the association, may inhibit
tourism.
Scottish-based tour companies have been offered approximately 150 tee-off
times, the same as last year. The St Andrews Hotels and Guest Houses
Association, whose members will receive 225 times next year, has declined to
accommodate Keith Prowse clients.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh dental hospital gets the go-ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office has finally given the go-ahead to an #11m new dental
hospital and day surgery centre in Edinburgh.
Proposals to relocate the dental hospital at the refurbished Lauriston Building
at the city's Royal Infirmary were approved by Scottish Health Minister Lord
James Douglas-Hamilton.
The deal will also allow the hospital to take on thoracic surgery patients from
City Hospital and extend day surgery cases.
The transfer from City Hospital is part of a strategy to run down services at
the hospital, leading to eventual closure.
Lord James said: ``I am sure that many in the dental profession and the public
at large will welcome the news that the dental hospital is to be replaced by a
modern and much improved clinical facility, providing services for dental
patients into the twenty-first century.''
British Dental Association spokesman Hew Mathewson, chairman of the Scottish
general dental services committee, said: ``The new hospital is long overdue but
the association is delighted with the news.
``Dentistry is moving on rapidly. The existing hospital building is not
suitable for carrying that.''
A spokesman for Edinburgh University, which has campaigned vigorously for a new
hospital, said: ``Naturally, the university will be in discussion with the
Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh Trust about how this will mesh in with the
university's own plans for continuing education for dental practitioners.''
Edinburgh Central MP Alistair Darling said he was ``very pleased'' by the news
but pointed out that a new dental hospital had first been promised in 1985.
``Despite the delay, it is clearly a very welcome development.''
Dr John Baynham, chairman of Lothian Health, and Professor Cairns Aitken,
chairman of the hospital NHS trust, warmly welcomed the decision on the dental
hospital.
Dental hospital consultant and clinical director Robert Brown said he was
``very pleased'' and staff in the existing hospital looked forward to providing
a quality service in the new facility.
Lothian Health initially approved the dental hospital plans in January 1994,
ending a long-running battle, spanning nearly five years, over the future of
the dilapidated Edinburgh Dental Hospital.
In 1989, a working party chaired by Sir Donald McCallum recommended the closure
of the dental school and the building of a new hospital and post-graduate
institute.
The Government's handling of the issue prompted a sometimes acromonious war of
words between Edinburgh University and the then Scottish Secretaries Malcolm
Rifkind and Ian Lang.
Funding for the project has come from joint public and private funding, with
#8m contributed from the public purse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dogs are killed to make gloves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW DRUMMOND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323211</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH dog lovers have made an appeal to Thai Government officials to enforce
laws banning cruelty to animals, after protesting to the embassy in London over
the treatment of dogs that are being slaughtered for golfing gloves and
drumskins . . . and barbecues.
The provincial government of Sakhon Nakhon, in North-east Thailand, said
yesterday it would take action to see that the dogs were treated in a humane
way before being killed. But the slaughter would still go on, as it is not
illegal to kill dogs in Thailand.
The dogs are killed for their meat by families of Vietnamese origin. The skins
are sold for export to Japan, where they are used to make drumskins and golfing
gloves.
Sakhon Nakhon Deputy Governor Chanin Buaprasert said yesterday he was concerned
at the protests made in London by the Canine Defence League, which had been
brought to his attention by the Thai Foreign Ministry.
``We cannot stop the slaughter, because it is not illegal to kill stray dogs.
But we can try and make sure the process is done as humanely as possible,'' he
said.
Dog meat is considered a delicacy by families of Vietnamese extraction and can
easily be bought in the local market at Tha Rae for between 70p and 80p a kilo.
The Canine Defence League, however, claimed the way the dogs were being killed
was horrific.
The dogs are picked up at night by the catchers, who operate in trucks with
torches. They are piled on top of each other in pens and may be kept for three
days without food and water before being clubbed to death in slaughterhouses,
which only operate in the hours of darkness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police in Thailand arrest antique dealer's son in drugs raid after `betrayal' by his best friend Scot faces ecstasy factory charges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW DRUMMOND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323212</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bangkok  A SCOT charged with drugs offences in Bangkok has claimed he was
betrayed by his best friend.
Mr Justin Jackson, the fourth Scot now in a Thai jail on drugs charges, is
accused by police of running a factory producing ecstasy. Mr Jackson, the son
of a Perth antiques dealer, faces five years to life if convicted.
Thai police said Mr Jackson, 25, admitted drugs offences after a friend led
police to his apartment.
Mr Jackson was arrested with another Briton and an American. All were said to
be producing the drugs on the holiday island of Ko Pha-ngan.
British consul staff have visited Mr Jackson, who is now waiting for a trial
date to be fixed.
His father, Mr James Jackson, who has flown to Thailand, said last night: ``The
charges do not relate to heroin but to ecstasy. He told me he had ecstasy
tablets in his flat.'' Mr Jackson, who is to return to his shop in Kintoull
Street, Perth, next week, added: ``Justin said he used them to help him stay
awake at his work. He helped run nightclubs in Thailand.''
Mr Jackson claimed his son had been charged only with possession of the drug.
Sources in Thailand said, however, that the charges involved production of the
drug.
Mr Jackson said his son was suffering from the strain of imprisonment.
``Justin's morale is not particularly good.''
A Foreign Office spokesman said: ``Justin Jackson is currently in jail in
Bangkok on drugs-related charges. No trial date has been set but his father has
appointed a lawyer. There is no timescale of when he might go to trial.''
Mr Carl Parker from Bristol, a friend of Mr Jackson, was arrested first and led
police to Mr Jackson's apartment.
The arrests were made after a police surveillance operation in the Patpong area
of Bangkok.
Mr Parker, 28, had been living in Thailand for three years, most of them
working as a disc jockey. Mr Jackson, a former pupil of Perth Academy, had
taught English for employees of the Petroleum Authority of Thailand. Both,
however, gave up their jobs several months ago, said police.
Lieutenant Colonel Vichai Sangprapai said Mr Jackson was carrying 349 ecstasy
tablets at the time of his arrest. The arrests were made simultaneously in
different apartments in Bangkok.
The charge against Mr Parker, who has been released on bail of #7000, has
apparently been reduced to possession of five tablets of ecstasy. This offence
is punishable by a fine.
A friend of Mr Jackson, who asked not to be named, said last night, said:
``Justin is furious. Parker has turned him in to save his own backside.''
Mr Parker last night admitted leading police to his friend's apartment. ``I had
no choice,'' he said. ``I admitted everything and told the others to admit it
too, to play the game the Thai way. Because I have co-operated, the Thais are
treating me well.''
Mr Jackson is the fourth Scot to be held in Thailand on drugs charges. Earlier
this month, deep sea diver Brent Stirling, 26, was jailed for life on drug
offences.
Scots teacher Sandra Gregory, 30, has spent two years in Klongpen prison
awaiting sentence for drug offences that she has admitted. She has been told
not to expect anything less than 25 years. Her parents live in Pitcaple,
Aberdeenshire.
Another Scot, James Callender, 58, could end his days in a Thai jail after he
was arrested having swallowed a condom containing 178 grammes of pure heroin.
Callender, from Larkfield in Greenock, has admitted the smuggling charges. He
is awaiting trial and is expecting a life sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City firms are slow to back Hogmanay bash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323213</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH'S business community was criticised yesterday for its lack of support
for the city's Hogmanay entertainment programme.
Launching five days of events for New Year, Edinburgh District Council leader
Leslie Hinds appealed to the private sector to support public-sector partners -
the council, Lothian region, and Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise Limited
(Leel) - because of the benefits to business from an influx of visitors.
Mr David Crichton, for Leel, said it was estimated last year's three-day event
had generated an extra #5m for the capital. A visitors' survey conducted by
System.3 found one in five had not been in Edinburgh before and two-thirds of
those had come to the city because of the Hogmanay celebrations. This
achievement has been recognised with an award for the city from the Scottish
Tourist Board for attracting low-season business.
The public sector input to this year's programme has increased by #25,000, with
Leel contributing #75,000, Edinburgh #55,000, and Lothian #50,000. The
remainder of the #600,000 budget is met from box office and sponsorship, which
this year includes the Bank of Scotland's support of the Hogmanay candelit
concert in St.Giles' Cathedral with the BT Scottish Ensemble, and Scandic Crown
Hotel's sponsorship of the torchlit procession on the same night.
Mr Norman Ireland, corporate projects manager for Lothian region, said there
was still not significant support of the programme by the business community.
``They are making money on the back of Edinburgh's Hogmanay but they have not
stepped forward to make a contribution to events. The benefits do not accrue to
the district, the region, or Leel but to shops, restaurants, and bars,'' said
Mr Ireland.
Mr Peter Irvine, of Unique Events, which plans the Hogmanay programme, said the
company had faced difficulty finding accommodation for artists performing
during the period because hotels and guest houses in the city were already
full, with many hotels obliging customers to stay for a period of three days.
It is estimated that the public attendance at the free street party on Princes
Street at Hogmanay, put at 160,000 last year, could reach 250,000. Tickets for
the Hogmanay Ball in the City Chambers are priced at #95, with proceeds going
to Oxfam.
This year's programme begins on December 30, when the emphasis is on
entertainment for children. Gary Glitter will also be performing in Princes
Street Gardens.
There will be a food festival in the Assembly Rooms and tenfold increase in the
number of restaurants which will be open over the New Year period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
