<DOCNO>GH951118-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to pinpoint source of gas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323214</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DRILLING began yesterday at a playing field in Sheddocksley, Aberdeen, in a bid
to detect the source of a toxic gas which is affecting areas of the city.
Eight council workmen have been affected in two separate incidents - two are
still off work with breathing difficulties after more than a year. Two more,
affected in the latest incident in October, are also still off work.
Yesterday, however, it was stressed that those affected had been working in a
confined area within sewers in the city and there was not thought to be any
risk to the public.
The gas is understood to be carried in the city's drainage system but
Councillor Rhona Kemp, convener of the region's policy and resources committee,
said the possibility it was being caused by the sewers had been ruled out.
The drilling operation is being carried out at a former landfill site for
household waste, which was dumped in a former quarry. The first samples taken
did not suggest anything out of the ordinary.
Drilling will also be carried out at a second site where around 1000 cattle -
which died during a foot and mouth outbreak more than 30 years ago - are buried.
The operation is being carried out because the sites sit between an area of
Northfield - where there has been a chronic problem with an unidentified odour
for more than 15 years - and Mastrick, where, in October, people reported a
smell of gas and a leak was ruled out by British Gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warning after man in car grabs boy, 10</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LAWYER whose 10-year-old son fought off a stranger who tried to drag him into
a car appealed for help yesterday to catch the would-be abductor before he
strikes again.
The worried father said his son had lashed out and wriggled free as the man
tried to drag him into his car as he walked home from school. The frightened
boy ran home and raised the alarm.
His father added: ``What worries me is this happened about 4pm, when it was
still light and in the middle of a housing estate, in our street.''
The boy returned to school yesterday.
Police praised the boy for his bravery in escaping from the man who pounced in
Silverknowes Court, Edinburgh, on Wednesday.
The man, said to be aged between 30 and 40, tried to persuade the boy to climb
into his dark-green saloon car. Frightened, the boy ran into Silverknowes Road
East but was chased and caught by the man before managing to break free.
Police said the man is between 5ft 8in and 6ft tall, of medium build with swept
back collar-length hair, and was wearing a gold-stud earring. He may have been
wearing a bomber jacket and jeans with a torn knee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Green pickets target Shell</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323216</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENVIRONMENTAL campaigners will today picket more than 100 Shell petrol stations
in Britain - including ones in Edinburgh and St Andrews - in protest at the
company's #2500m gas deal with Nigeria.
The son of the executed Nigerian minority rights campaigner Ken Saro-Wiwa
yesterday pulled out of a planned press conference in London to discuss the
protest, a week after his father's execution along with eight other campaigners.
Jockey fined
JOCKEY Walter Swinburn, 34, was fined #480 with #200 costs yesterday at
Newmarket, Suffolk, after admitting failing to provide a breath specimen. His
licence was endorsed with 10 penalty points.
Baseball attack
A MAN who attacked his sister with a baseball bat while she lay in bed was
jailed for seven months yesterday. Inverness Sheriff Court heard that Mark
Stewart, 21, of Carnarc Crescent, Inverness, was under the influence of drugs
when he attacked his sister and a man staying at his house.
Murder charge
AN inmate of Perth prison made a second private appearance at Perth Sheriff
Court yesterday, after a fellow prisoner's death last week. Paul Ness, 23, from
Edinburgh, was committed for trial on a charge of murdering Robert Watson, also
23 and from Edinburgh.
Heart boy's treat
FIVE-YEAR-OLD Robert Brock, of Lincluden, near Dumfries, will visit Euro
Disneyland before having major heart surgery at Glasgow's Yorkhill Children's
Hospital in a few weeks.
Fire kills pigs
A SOW and 15 piglets were killed in a fire yesterday at a piggery in Letham,
Angus. The cause of the fire is not believed to have been suspicious.
Peanuts alert
THOUSANDS of bags of Sainsbury's dry roasted peanuts have been withdrawn from
store shelves and destroyed after metal filings were found in packets.
Safety award
THE Scottish Road Safety Campaign was congratulated yesterday by Scottish Roads
Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, after it received a Prince Michael Road
Safety Award in Edinburgh for its Paving The Way campaign. The initiative
targeted adults and children with learning difficulties.
BBC thinks again
THE chairman of the BBC governors, Mr Marmaduke Hussey, yesterday admitted the
corporation ``might have been wrong'' not to have participated in the
two-minutes' silence on Armistice Day. The BBC will reconsider its decision for
next year's commemorations, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hitman in horrific attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LAUGHING hitman, hired by a secretary to teach an imagined office love rival
a lesson, was behind bars last night after being convicted of a ``catastrophic
and tragic'' attack.
Just because Terese Dorne smiled at the wrong person at the wrong time, she was
subjected to a ``nightmare'' of violence which began with CS gas being sprayed
into her face. As she screamed in pain, either Raymond Johnson or his as yet
unidentified accomplice, then slashed her forehead.
The gaping wound was so large a cascade of blood ``rinsed'' the gas from her
eyes.
Her attackers then cut her throat twice before running off laughing in a
display of ``true callousness''.
Mrs Dorne, 36, an accountant, was later taken to hospital and underwent a
series of operations. More than 60 external stitches were used to treat her
injuries.
Johnson, 25, of Deacon Way, Walworth, south-east London, was found guilty of
conspiring to commit grievous bodily harm.
Judge David Pitman remanded him in custody and said he would deal with him on a
date to be fixed after pre-sentence reports had been prepared.
Diana Lewis, 24, of Matlock Road, Leyton, East London, the secretary who hired
him and admitted the conspiracy charge, will be sentenced on the same occasion.
The Snaresbrook Crown Court trial heard how Mrs Dorne's ordeal began when she
started working for a firm of accountants in north London.
Also working there was Lewis, who was having an affair with businessman Ian
French, who worked in the building but not for the same firm. Lewis became
convinced that Mrs Dorne had designs on her lover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The key to the door of Home Rule</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robbie Dinwoodie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN MANY ways there are remarkable similarities between the parliamentary plans
proposed by devolution and independence activists in Scotland in terms of size,
composition, and electoral system.
The key difference, however, is that while Home Rule would provide autonomy
within the UK, the Scottish National Party plan envisages Scotland taking its
place among the nations of the world as the 16th member of the European Union
and the 186th member of the United Nations.
Under the SNP plan, Scotland would have 133 single member constituencies, with
MPs elected by the alternative vote system of proportional representation. A
further 67 members would be elected from lists under the additional member
system.
This is not dissimilar to the Convention system (although the latter elects its
constituency MPs by first-past-the-post), and like that plan it would involve a
single-chamber Parliament serving for a fixed four-year term.
The Scottish age of majority and of consent would be set at 16.
Any person whose principle residence was in Scotland, or whose place of birth
was Scotland, would be deemed a Scots citizen unless this was renounced.
An independent Scotland, which under current SNP plans would retain the Queen
as head of state, would adopt a Bill of Rights and a written constitution.
The SNP maintains that victory in Westminster or Edinburgh elections would only
be a mandate for a start toindependence negotiations.
This process would still have to culminate in a referendum before the Act of
Union would be dissolved.
This process is broadly accepted as being relatively straightforward under
international law, but what about the economic aftermath? Labour claims that
the turmoil of separation would cause irreparable damage to Scotland.
The SNP budget published earlier this week cited Norway's growth rate in recent
years of 2.9% in comparison with British growth of 2%. If Scotland, with
comparable wealth in oil and other natural resources, could achieve 2.5% that
modest economic growth could create jobs and better social services, they argue.
On this week's figures, over a four-year term in office an SNP Government would
plan to raise #6.3bn through economic growth. In turn, they would spend #5.5bn
on jobs measures and welfare improvements.
The figures can be argued over but the SNP now has the Prime Minister
confirming that there is nothing to stop Scotland going it alone.
A key SNP argument has been the concept known on the Continent as the ``tyrrany
of the tiny'', whereby smaller countries such as the Benelux nations have been
able to do well.
SNP chief executive Michael Russell points out: ``It could be the making of
England if they reassess their role and become a modern European nation instead
of clinging to a colonial past.''
So Scotland wins, England wins, Europe wins. A perfect politician's solution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Institute' ready to mark 200 years of learning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323219</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S third biggest university has unveiled a programme of ceremonial,
academic, cultural, and social events to mark its bicentenary next year.
Strathclyde University, Glasgow, began its academic existence in 1796 when, as
Anderson's Institute, it offered lectures to about 1000 students, about half of
whom were women.
Today, it has about 14,000 students, 3500 staff, and about 40,000 people who
attend adult classes and professional development courses.
It has also secured a top-10 ranking of universities worldwide for royalty
income from its inventions, while the quality of its teaching and research have
had consistently high ratings.
Writing in the programme of events for the forthcoming year, Strathclyde's
chancellor, Lord Tombs of Brailes, and its principal, Professor John
Arbuthnott, wonder if even a man of such vision as the university's founder,
the academic John Anderson, would have found it difficult to believe the
progress it had made.
When he died in January 1796, he left instructions for a new kind of university
for Glasgow which opened higher education up to people in employment and made
it more useful to them in their work.
Within five months, his executors had secured permission for its establishment.
Classes began in the Trades House of Glasgow but it was not until 1964 that the
institution, by then named the Royal College of Science and Technology,
achieved university status, when it merged with the Scottish College of
Commerce.
Professor Arbuthnott said it was now more important than ever for the
university to develop its close links with Glasgow.
``We are entering a period of increasing financial restrictions on
universities. Strathclyde will need to draw more than ever upon its partnership
with the city and with the citizens who study here to ensure the continued
fulfilment of our community-based mission.
``We have to be able to convince companies in and around Glasgow that, by joint
efforts and by linking into the university, we will create a training,
learning, and research base which will enable them to extend their businesses
successfully,'' he said.
The university's programme of events will include an international gathering of
Robert Burns' scholars, the bicentenary of whose death also falls next year;
conferences which will attract more than 8000 scholars; lectures and addresses
from a variety of speakers including Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, the
President of Ireland Mary Robinson, and explorer Sir Ranulph Fiennes; and the
publication of three books about the institution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Knife case man wants civil jury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN acquitted by a jury's not proven verdict of murdering a taxi driver is
asking for a second jury if a #100,000 damages action by the dead man's widow
and family is allowed to go ahead.
Mr David Anderson, 24, was charged with the murder of Mr Raymond Mullan by
stabbing him through the heart with a hunting knife during an early morning
taxi ride from Gourock to Greenock in February 1990.
In May that year, a jury at the High Court at Paisley found the charge against
Mr Anderson, of Nelson Road, Gourock, not proven.
Mrs Margaret Mullan is now suing him for #40,000 in a civil action in the Court
of Session and her three children, aged 21, 19, and 16, are claiming #20,000
each.
The family alleges that Mr Anderson stabbed Mr Mullan, 38, deliberately or
negligently. Mr Anderson maintains that contact between the taxi driver and the
knife was accidental.
Mr Anderson is asking temporary judge Gordon Coutts to dismiss the action
because the true motive behind it is not to recover damages but to have him
branded as a killer.
Miss Leeona Dorrian QC, senior counsel for Mr Anderson, submitted yesterday
that the Mullan family's purpose in raising the action was to seek to have the
court declare that Mr Anderson had murdered or otherwise unlawfully killed Mr
Mullan.
``If Mr Anderson is correct about that, they should not be entitled to decree
on the merits of the issue because the court should not allow the civil process
to be used for these ends.''
Miss Dorrian added that if the case got to the stage of evidence being heard,
Mr Anderson's position was that he would wish the case to go to a jury.
Miss Dorrian said that normally the issue of motivation did not arise but this
was only the second case of its kind in Scotland and the first that had been
defended, so the circumstances were highly unusual.
Mr Ronald Mackay QC, for the Mullan family, said they were not alleging murder
but rather an assault which brought about death.
He was unaware of any case in which it had been said that the motive of the
pursuer was of any relevancy in deciding whether the action should be allowed
to proceed.
Some pursuers might be motivated by the simple desire to obtain money; others
might wish the defender to be held responsible for the consequences of his
actions.
Mr Mackay is asking the court to hold Mr Anderson liable for the death of Mr
Mullan and to restrict any future hearing to how much should be paid in damages
to the family.
The judge will issue a written decision later.
A jury in a Court of Session action consists of 12 compared with 15 in a
criminal trial. They would also be asked to decide the case on a lesser
standard of proof - a balance of probabilities rather than beyond reasonable
doubt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kynoch warns of `local tartan tax'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Local Government Minister George Kynoch yesterday raised the spectre
of a ``local tartan tax'' on top of the national ``tartan tax'' that Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth has claimed would be levied by a Scottish parliament.
Mr Kynoch was referring to the latest call by the Labour Party in Scotland to
return councils' power to set business rates.
The call came from Cosla president Rosemary McKenna, who said councils should
control more of their own income.
The Minister, speaking after a visit to Livingston, claimed that on past
experience such a policy would be a recipe for higher local taxes.
Business people, he said, had been enthusiastic about the move to a Uniform
Business Rate set by the Government.
Mr Kynoch has emerged recently as the man many new council leaders love to hate
following a series of high profile attacks on them for allegedly employing too
many highly paid staff, and creating top heavy committee structures in order to
spread special payments as widely as possible.
``A move to raise more tax locally would take the pressure off councils - which
is being exerted by Government - to be more cost effective and efficient,'' Mr
Kynoch claimed.
``I intend to ensure as I am responsible for a large amount of taxpayers' funds
that those funds are used wisely and I will continue to highlight areas where I
think there is wastage and where funds are being diverted away from the
provision of good frontline services into top-heavy bureaucracies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lawyer who stole #2.5m was `conned'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LAWYER who stole #2.5m from his clients was the victim of an international
fraud, a court was told yesterday.
Giles Davies believed all the money he gave to a Mr X - a man who cannot be
named for legal reasons, allegedly behind the fraud - would be returned with
interest, the High Court in Glasgow heard.
Davies, 42, embezzled the money for a ``hare-brained scheme after being conned
completely,'' defence counsel Mr Neville Shaffer, QC, said.
Davies took the money from clients of the 100-year-old legal firm, McCormick
and Nicholson, in Newton Stewart, Wigtownshire, driving it into bankruptcy.
His crime was discovered by a bank manager after the firm had run up an
overdraft and Davies, of Barrhill, Ayrshire, had run off. For nine days after
he disappeared, Davies wrote several letters of apology.
He told his partners: ``I have destroyed everything. I don't understand why.
The Law Society should know that you did not know anything about the mess. I
was conned completely.''
Advocate-depute Alan Turnbull said Davies was charged with embezzlement instead
of fraud because the Crown accepted he believed the scheme to be genuine.
Judge Robin McEwan, QC, asked why Davies' legal partners did not know he was
involved in an international fraud from their offices.
Mr Shaffer said: ``This hare-brained scheme might have been brought to an end
sooner if the partners had taken a greater interest in the affairs of the
firm.''
Mr Turnbull said the partners had their practising certificates suspended after
the collapse of the firm and were now all working for other firms.
Mr X - believed to be English - allegedly made more than #500,000 from the
fraud. He faces court proceedings, said Mr Turnbull.
Davies is expected to be sentenced on Monday. He has been in Barlinnie Prison
since his bail was withdrawn on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
