<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Prime Minister has turned the political focus squarely on the future of Scotland and how we are governed ......Herald writers examine the way ahead for a country at the crossroads The state of the nation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOTHING in the history of the Tory response to Scottish demands for
self-governance suggests that the latest outburst of concern from the Prime
Minister and his proconsul will produce what scholars of devolution insist
matters most: the end of Westminister's right to say no.
One has only to read the words from Michael Forsyth's flurry of media
interviews yesterday, in the wake of the Prime Minister's intervention, to
appreciate how unlikely constitutional change of the sort championed by the
opposition parties is.
Would he give Scotland the right to settle its own affairs free of Westminster
interference? ``Having Scottish MPs vote on Scottish issues without an
involvement for Westminster is Alex Sal-mond's policy - that's independence,''
he told the BBC. Translation: we are committed to the sovereignty of the
Westminster Parliament, and that's that.
In December last year, in a BBC New Year's interview, Mr John Major identified
the problem. ``What happens when there is a conflict between the Scottish
Parliament, if it was established, and the Westminster Parliament? Who is
supreme?'' Devolution, he said, ``is one of the most dangerous propositions
that has ever been put before the British nation''.
The difficulty for the Government, after 16!s years of rule, has increasingly
been to justify the logic of a political system that leaves Scotland governed
by the party it has determinedly refused to vote for over four consecutive
General Elections.
Mr Major has made his passion for the Union a personal thing. He preached its
virtues from his soapbox in the 1992 General Election and has returned to the
theme on a regular basis, most recently in yesterday's interview. Although the
subject was bound to come up in any conversation led by the Independent's
resident Scot Andrew Marr, Central Office sources insist it was Mr Major who
raised it to reinforce what Mr Forsyth is preparing to spring on the Scottish
public.
In 1993, a year after promising to ``take stock'' of Scotland's complaints in
the run-up to the 1992 election, the Government published a White Paper
entitled Scotland in the Union: A Partnership for Good.
A central inquiry unit was set up, with an information line for the public; the
Department of Trade and Industry's oil and gas division moved to Aberdeen with
60 staff; five of the UK's 24 seats (20%) on the new European Committee of the
Regions were allocated to Scotland; responsibility for Scotland's training
budget was handed to the Secretary of State.
However, the most visible results were the new procedures agreed by the House
of Commons at the beginning of the last parliamentary year. These extended the
role of the Scottish Grand Committee, made up of all 72 Scottish MPs, to allow
it to debate and vote on Scottish legislation, to question and take statements
from Ministers, and to hold general debates, some suggested by the Opposition.
To make proceedings more immediate, the committee has taken to sitting in
Scotland. At a recent session in Aberdeen, only 17 out of 49 Labour MPs turned
up.
The Children (Scotland) Bill was the first measure to be handled under the new
rules but only after Labour had given assurances to Government whips that it
would not block the legislation. The expectation now is that Mr Forsyth will,
in his St Andrew's Day speech, announce even greater legislative powers for the
Scottish Grand Committee.
However, no-one believes the Government is about to start accepting the verdict
of its Labour majority on contentious legislation, like nursery vouchers.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson declared yesterday: ``The acid test
will be the Education (Scotland) Bill, announced in the Queen's Speech. Since
it's going to be voted down in the committee, will they accept that?''
Look back at the Tories' previous flirtations with devolution and the primacy
of the status quo of parliamentary sovereignty is clear. In 1967, the Thistle
Group, a Scottish Tory think-tank whose members included Michael Ancram, Peter
- now Lord - Fraser, and Malcolm Rifkind, published a pamphlet suggesting
devolution was essential to Scotland. A year later, Tory leader Edward Heath
made the Declaration of Perth, which promised the people of Scotland ``genuine
participation in the making of all decisions that affect them and to do this
within the historic unity of the United Kingdom''. The result was a Tory
proposal for a 125 member Scottish Convention that was promptly dropped once
the Tories were elected.
The Conservative manifesto in the October 1974 election posited the complete
reverse of what Mr Major is concerned about now. ``Devolution is our policy,''
it proclaimed.
Even Margaret Thatcher backed devolution when it suited her. In 1975, in
Edinburgh, she declared the establishment of an assembly to be a ``top
priority''. She was backed by Mr Ian Lang, Mr Rifkind, and the current Scottish
Tory chairman Michael Hirst.
Twenty years later and the Tories continue to whisper sweet nothings into
Scotland's ear. That the Tories have given the Scottish Office and its supreme
head more devolved powers and greater autonomy than previous Scottish
Secretaries would ever have dreamed of has not been enough to persuade the
Scottish electorate that the Tories do care.
Mr Major admitted as much in yesterday's interview, when he accepted the
possibility that Scotland might just be strong enough to stand alone.
The only way left for the Tories to counter this logic is by reducing the
constitutional debate to an all or nothing simplicity. A Scottish parliament,
with its ``tartan tax'', Mr Major and Mr Forsyth warn, will lead to the
break-up of the United Kingdom, by giving the SNP a chance to work for a
mandate for independence. Devolution, they insist, means separatism - unlike
the 1974 manifesto, which described devolution as the very opposite.
Whatever warm words Mr Major may have for Scotland, he is a parliamentary
sovereignist at heart. He may eventually accept the political necessity of
setting up some sort of super Scottish quango, a talking shop where the Scots
can vent their surfeit of spleen. It might even be the Scottish Grand
Committee. However, give up Westminster's reins on Scotland? Never.
</TEXT>
