<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mapping a way round Nolan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ink was barely dry on the Hansard report on the outcome of the Commons
debate on Nolan when MPs were bombarded with information from PR companies
wanting to help them.
One such missive said: ``You will be aware of the motions passed by the House
earlier this week banning advocacy and requiring, in relation to permitted
parliamentary services, a written agreement to be drawn up and made available
for public inspection.
``By reason of the nature of our practice and having followed the proceedings
of the Nolan Committee closely, we believe we are well placed to advise members
on the appropriate form of agreements and are happy to accept instructions for
that purpose. If we can assist you please contact *.*.*.*.*.*.*.*.*''
What was that phrase about an ill wind?
Gas mark
MUCH more intelligence is reaching us about the great Charter Mark saga
involving British Gas. Judges, apparently, will continue to take a tough line
with Charter Mark-winning organisations which fail to live up to the award's
high standards.
Desperately trying to rescue the thing, Public Service Minister Roger Freeman
insists that the Charter Mark is ``a seal of approval, a recognition of
excellent quality service, and if organisations are not serving the public
properly they do not deserve to keep the mark''.
Stoically, Mr Freeman says that he regrets British Gas felt they had no
alternative but to surrender their Charter Mark which, apparently, is ``not won
easily and not retained automatically''.
He would have us believe that that is why it is so prized by the 227 public
services who have won it so far and by ``the many thousands of people -
parents, patients, and many others - whom they serve''. Oh aye.
Please ignore
THE Department of Irrelevant Information: This week's prize goes to the
Department of the Environment, which put out a five-page press release on new
scrutiny of the paperwork imposed by local government finance systems.
It gets worse. Environment Secretary John Gummer said: ``I propose that my
department undertake a scrutiny in the field of local government finance. The
scrutiny will focus on information flows in relation to systems for financing
local authority spending - chiefly the information central government collects
from local authorities but also the information it feeds back to them.
``This scrutiny will investigate the demands generated by financial systems and
recommend means of reducing unduly onerous administrative burdens,
rationalising central government requirements for information, and improving
Government's efficiency in managing and handling that information.''
Lady Luck
WELL, at least we now know the truth about the National Lottery. Heritage
Secretary Virginia Bottomley has strongly defended it and admitted that the
family syndicate has played every week since the first draw. ``One year on, I
still haven't won a penny,'' she admits. ``This, apparently, makes me a
statistical anomaly. I couldn't possibly comment.''
She may, of course, wish to comment on a remark by husband Peter, Tory MP for
Eltham, who said the other day that his marriage was much more likely to end in
murder than divorce.
Transported
CONGRATULATIONS to Nigel Evans, Tory MP for Ribble Valley, for asking the
Secretary of State for Transport this week ``how merry passengers used the West
Coast main line in 1994.'' Some mistake, surely.
On impulse
A FEW MPs were spotted this week at a bash for the New London Orchestra at St
John's, Smith Square, London. One of the programme notes, for a clarinet
concerto by Finzi, talked about the clash between the clarinet and the string
section. At the close, it says, both parties are in ``lively and impulsive
mood.'' Yes, indeed.
</TEXT>
