<HEADLINE>Inquest hears of drowning at Greek holiday island MP tells of bid to revive his wife</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP Tony Marlow yesterday described his desperate attempts to revive his
wife after he found her floating face-down in the sea during a Greek island
holiday.
Mrs Catherine Marlow drowned the morning after a night spent drinking wine with
her husband in her favourite holiday spot ``in the whole of the world'' on the
island of Zante, an inquest was told.
Mr Marlow described the moment he saw his wife's body: ``I realised it was
Catherine, floating face down in the water. She was by some rocks. I turned her
on her back and froth was coming out of her mouth.
``I got her to some rocks. I tried to give her mouth-to-mouth. I knew she was
not alive.''
The court was told that Mr Marlow found the body at noon. The couple had gone
swimming at 10am and had spent 20 minutes together.
The couple, who were staying in Mrs Marlow's sister's villa, drank a bottle of
``some sort of Greek wine concoction'' the night before, he said.
Next morning, Mrs Marlow, 54, ate a breakfast of coffee, bread, tomatoes, green
peppers, and feta cheese in olive oil.
About 10 to 20 minutes later, around 10am, she went swimming with Mr Marlow,
55, but, the court was told, got into difficulty while snorkelling off the
island's craggy coast.
A post-mortem examination carried out by the Greek authorities revealed there
was still enough alcohol in her system to push the level to just under half the
British drink-driving limit.
Coroner Anne Pember recorded a verdict of accidental death after the inquest at
Northampton General Hospital.
Mr Marlow, MP for Northampton North, was speaking publicly for the first time
about the couple's last night together.
Dressed in a grey suit, smiling, and looking relaxed, he told the court: ``We
had a bottle of some sort of Greek wine concoction the night before.
``It was something like wine. It was in a wine bottle but there were other
flavours as well as wine. It had been left by her sister. It was not labelled.''
Mr Marlow described how he and his wife had gone swimming together at a nearby
beach the next morning, October 2, 1994, three days into their holiday.
He said: ``Catherine was a keen and able swimmer. We went off together and
spent some time swimming together.
``We went round a point. I was trying to keep fit. I went off to do some more
aggressive swimming and left Catherine snorkelling.''
Mr Marlow later swam back past the point where he had left his wife. When he
did not see her, he assumed she had got out of the water.
He told the court: ``At first, I wasn't concerned. I got out of the water. I
thought she had gone off to buy some lunch or for a walk.''
He added: ``I did various things. I put out a fishing line. Then I thought,
`This is ridiculous.' I retraced where we had been swimming.''
Home Office pathologist Dr Clive Bouch carried out a second post-mortem
examination in Britain after the body had been flown back to England.
He told the inquest: ``I have been told by the Greek authorities that the cause
of death was drowning. I have no way of disagreeing with that.''
Mr Marlow, a former Army captain, was educated at Wellington College, Sandhurst
and Cambridge. He married in 1962.
The couple lived at a farm at Willoughby, Warwickshire, and had five children:
Edward, 31; Boris, 30; Emily, 27; Oliver, 24; and 23-year-old Alice. For the 10
years before his wife's death, Mr Marlow divided his time between her and his
secretary.
He spent weekends with his wife and in his constituency home and the working
week with Jill Chambers, with whom he has four children.
</TEXT>
