<HEADLINE>Royal hopeful sits out match</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen's grandson 18-year-old Peter Phillips was on the substitutes' bench
when the Scottish Schoolboys side were beaten 18-9 by the Scottish Under-18s in
The Gordonstoun pupil hopes to be selected for the international series next
month against England, Wales, Ireland, and France in Edinburgh.
Blind justice
A MAN who sexually abused a girl of 13 over a three-year period 20 years ago
was admonished at the High Court in Glasgow yesterday because he is losing his
sight. Robert Carden, 57, of Palmer Avenue, Knightswood, has an
inoperable disease which will leave him housebound.
Bogus callers
POLICE have issued a warning to pensioners after a woman claiming to be a nurse
tricked her way into the home of an 88-year-old man in Peffermill Road,
Edinburgh. Nothing was        stolen, though police believe the woman, in her
thirties, was working with a male        accomplice and had searched the house
before leaving.
Suicide killer
A MOTHER suffering from post-natal depression killed her two-year-old daughter
on a jetty then leapt, clutching her body, into a lake          at Frimley
Green, Surrey, police said yesterday. The bodies of Mrs Marcella       Flowers,
43, and her daughter were found 10 hours after they were reported missing by Mr
Michael Flowers on Thursday.
Not guilty verdict
WILLIAM McGeachin, 28, was found not guilty by jury yesterday of attempting to
murder publican Gerard Duffy, 39, who had barred a customer for stealing toilet
rolls at the Brig Tavern in Easterhouse Road, Glasgow, in July. Mr Duffy told
the High Court in Glasgow            he was shot in the back       with a
sawn-off shotgun. McGeachin's address was given as care of Barlinnie Prison.
Clothing seized
FORENSIC experts are examining clothing seized in raids after the arrest of
four people - three men aged 19, 21, and 23, and a 25-year-old woman - by
police investigating the murder of 15-year-old Naomi Smith in Ansley Common,
Warwickshire, on September 14.
Unit hits century
THE Scottish Liver Transplantation Unit - based at Edinburgh Royal Infirmary -
has carried out more than 100 transplants since it opened three years ago. The
unit receives annual funding of #1.6m for 40 transplants.
</TEXT>
