<HEADLINE>Lift-off for a Swiss knife of satellites</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sarah Vincent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarah Vincent
on the latest
development in
an increasingly
sophisticated
space age
CAPTAIN'S Log, star date 17.11.95. A thermos flask so effective that boiling
coffee placed inside it would take more than five years to cool to a drinkable
temperature.
Its mission: to coolly go where no thermos has gone before.
No, it's not another episode of Star Trek. It is the Infrared Space Observer,
launched yesterday by the European Space Agency.
The ISO - said to be the Swiss army knife of satellites - is so sensitive it
can detect the heat from an ice-cube 100km away.
It will spend the next two years delving into the coldest depths of the
universe by observing faint heat from distant stars that could tell us about
their formation, evolution, and death, and perhaps even indicate what happened
at the beginning of time.
The ISO represents the latest development in a space age that makes the
equipment which took Neil Armstrong to the moon in 1969 look like Technical
Lego.
In the last 25 years since the great astronomical revolution began, our
knowledge of the universe has mushroomed.
We have sent probes to land on Mars, to investigate planets in our solar system
and into the tail of Halley's comet.
Dr Jacqueline Mitton, spokesperson for the Royal Astronomical Society, says:
``There has been a real explosion in the amount of astronomical detail and data
of every kind of astronomical object.
``Technological developments have revealed a completely different picture of
the universe which we didn't know was there.''
One change is that photographic plates are barely used these days, and in their
place are electronic devices which are so sensitive they can register a single
photon of light - the smallest measure of light possible.
The advances in astronomy have been almost entirely due to computers which
enable scientists to achieve what was previously thought impossible.
For example, new telescopes are being built with eight meter diameter mirrors
which can see further into space than ever before.
``This is only possible because of the technology for making thin glass mirrors
which can hold their shape,'' says Mitton.
``These new mirrors do not have to be rigid because they have computer supports
behind them.''
The largest telescope currently in use is the Keck, at the W M Keck Observatory
in Mauna Kea. When its twin is built beside it they will be able to distinguish
the separate headlights on a car 25,000km away - the most powerful pair of
binoculars known to man.
``Not only have things been revolutionised, but they are about to be
revoutionised again with the huge new telescopes,'' enthuses Mitton.
Another leap forward has been the possibility of observing the universe from
space, where rays from outer space are unaffected by the Earth's atmosphere.
This is the aim of the famous Hubble telescope, which is orbiting the Earth and
picking up non-visible radiation, such as X-rays, gamma-rays, ultra-violet and
infrared radiation.
Virtually all objects, whether stars, planets, or the dust between stars, give
off radiation of some kind, and by studying it scientists can tell what the
object is made of, how fast it is travelling, and potentially how old it is.
As a result of the new data, astronomers have convincing evidence for the
existence of black holes - incredibly dense regions of space which have such a
strong gravitational pull that they suck everything nearby, including light,
into them.
They have also become aware of new regions of stars, new stellar objects and
know much more about the composition and life of stars.
One of the eternal enigmas facing astronomers is how the universe began. Recent
evidence points more and more towards the Big Bang theory - the idea that 15
billion years ago the universe exploded out of a single point, and is still
expanding today.
And data from the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE), launched by Nasa in 1989,
showed a background microwave radiation which was consistent with a rapidly
expanding universe, suggesting that at some time in the past all matter was at
a single point.
Mitton doesn't think there is much of a scientific future for humans to be sent
into space.
``The space race has perhaps done the opposite. There is so much one can do by
remotely observing from Earth that the incentive for sending astronauts are
much reduced.
``The reason for wanting to send people into space is now human adventure.''
But the biggest question of all must be - is there anybody else out there?
Mitton says: ``With the ISO we would have hopes of being able to see if there
are other planets orbiting other suns in solar systems like our own, because
that would be the first step in locating somewhere that looks plausible for
life.''
So far no-one has conclusive evidence for any other solar systems - a planet
orbiting a sun where the conditions for life would be fulfilled. But there are
indications that such systems do exist.
One thing is clear. The cleverer we become, the more advanced our technology is
and the further we venture into space, the more we will realise our own
insignificance in this vast cosmos.
</TEXT>
