<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cold snap brings first heavy snows</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND suffered the first cold snap of the winter yesterday, with snow
falling across the north and east of the country.
As if to confirm winter had arrived, Grampian Police said the notorious A939
Cockbridge to Tomintoul road was one of three blocked by snow yesterday. The
A974 and the B976 were also affected.
A spokesman said: ``If any roads are going to block, these are the ones.''
Nethybridge on Speyside was one of many locations where ploughs and gritters
were called out to deal with the first serious fall of snow. More than an inch
fell at Aviemore, but the main Scottish ski resorts were left praying for more.
Snow was reported along the east coast as far south as Berwick, and Glasgow
Weather Centre said that over the weekend temperatures should rise slightly,
with further wintry downpours next week.
In England and Wales, North Yorkshire and Northumberland were worst hit, with
villages isolated by snow-blocked roads for the first time this year.
A huge queue of traffic was halted for several hours on the A169 in North
Yorkshire, between Pickering and Whitby, when lorries failed to climb a snowy,
icebound hill. Flights were cancelled at Newcastle Airport and the city's Metro
system ground to a halt because of frozen points.
A race meeting at Sedgefield became the season's first sporting casualty -
abandoned due to snow. Meanwhile, Ladbroke's odds on a white Christmas fell
from 10-1 to 7-1.
Abroad, snow and wind lashed Scandinavia during one of the worst early winter
snowstorms in memory. One man died in a snowdrift, and Gothenburg Airport was
closed and the city left paralysed.
The weather cast a cold shadow over today's wedding of Danish Prince Joachim,
to Hong Kong economist Alexandra Manley, and royal guards parading outside
Amalienborg Palace had to contend with strong flurries of snow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rap for Celtic over tickets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC yesterday were given a sharp rebuke for selling too many tickets for the
club's European tie against Paris St Germain earlier this month.
The disciplinary action, which followed a computer fault at Parkhead, came from
Strathclyde Regional Council's sports grounds safety sub-committee.
Its members decided to give the club a severe warning after complaints from
some of the fans who were forced to watch the match from stadium stairways
because duplicate tickets had been issued for hundreds of seats.
Club officials yesterday met councillors to explain how the mistake occurred in
Celtic's new #120,000 computerised ticket system.
Councillor David Sanderson, who chairs the sub-committee, said: ``This has been
a very serious breach of the club's safety certificate and we are very
concerned.
``The safety of fans is our main priority and we were seeking confirmation from
the club that their new system will prevent the possibility of over-issuing
happening again. The club gave that assurance.''
Celtic have been told that, if the problem recurs, the committee will meet
again and consider ordering a prohibition which would effectively reduce the
capacity at Parkhead.
A club spokesman said later that they regarded the matter as concluded. He said
only a handful of fans had complained to the club, each of whom had received an
apology and a complimentary ticket for another match.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>School tribute after death of sixth former</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH public school broke up a day early for its weekend leave yesterday
in tribute to a sixth former who collapsed while watching a school rugby match
and later died in hospital.
Loretto School, in Musselburgh, East Lothian, arranged the early closure as a
mark of respect for John Kelsey, 17, on the day following the tragedy, which a
spokesman said had left the whole school community ``in a state of shock''.
Yesterday, his housemaster, Mr Hector MacLean, said: ``John gave 100%. He was a
fine young man who always had a smile on his face.''
John, a boarder from Aberdeen, was described as extremely popular and a notable
1st XV rugby player.
He was an NCO in the school cadet corps and served as a house prefect.
He was intending to study engineering design at university from next October.
John's parents, Peter and Stephanie Kelsey, travelled to the school after being
informed of the tragedy and returned home yesterday.
A post-mortem examination has been called for by the fiscal at Haddington as a
matter of routine.
</TEXT>
