<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Churchill's gun makes a killing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323245</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STEN gun which Winston Churchill kept at home during the Second World War was
sold for #10,125 yesterday.
The 9mm sub-machine gun was part of a cache of weapons the wartime leader kept
at Chartwell, in Kent, in case of attack by German paratroopers.
Mr Martin Long, 45, the chairman of Churchill Insurance bought the gun. He
already owns several other pieces of Churchilliana including a wartime map. His
personal assistant, Ms Karen Sharpe, bid for the lot at Christie's in South
Kensington before taking her prize back to head office in Bromley by Tube and
train wrapped in paper and auction house carrier bags.
Sten guns originally cost 7s 6d each - 37.5p in modern money. They were issued
to troops to provide rapid automatic fire and were an alternative to the
American Thompson .45 sub-machine gun.
The Sten gun will be kept at Mr Long's Bromley office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cards that make allowances for children</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANTHEA MASEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY 13-year-old daughter wants a monthly allowance. She says she is fed up with
getting her pocket money weekly in cash because she simply spends it.
Thirteen-year olds can be very persuasive. She argues that if her allowance was
paid into a bank account, it would help her budget and she wouldn't blow the
lot the moment it hit her account.
Well, I will believe that when I see it. However, I am convinced that children
should be encouraged to look after their own money and that today's teenagers
need to learn about banks, cash machines and rates of interest. And a freshly
opened bank account with a shiny new cash card will make a good Christmas
present.
The question is which bank or building society? My daughter arrived home from
school with a pile of bank literature picked up in the local high street. All
seem to be wooing children like her with offers of free cinema tickets or
record tokens. The children find it very seductive. I, wagging my finger,
pointed out that she should be looking at rates of interest.
My daughter's needs are simple. She wants a cash card which she can use to get
at her money in the high street while she waits for the bus on the way back
from school. I suspect she will be making lots of small withdrawals, a fiver
here, an odd #15 there when she is planning a shopping trip with her friends.
At this stage she doesn't need anything more complicated. Cheque books and
credit cards are obviously out of the question.
I am hoping there will often be at least #50 saved in this account, but which
bank or building society pays the highest rate of interest on amounts as small
as this and which will give her instant access to her money?
All the major cash withdrawal networks are available to her, so I can set up a
standing order with any bank or building society account which offers instant
access through a cash card. But high interest won't be of any use if the bank
or building society that we choose charges a fee if she puts her card in a
competitor's cash dispenser.
According to MoneyFacts, children should aim to find an account paying more
than 3.5% gross. Best buy is the Halifax Quest Club which pays 3.9%, followed
by Britannia Ltd which pays 3.8%. Others worth considering are the Nationwide
Smart account and TSB Firstsave which pay 3.5%. The Royal Bank of Scotland
Route 17 and Dunfermline Headstart also pay 3.5% but only give cash cards to
children from age 14.
The Halifax, Britannia, Dunfermline, Nationwide and TSB all use the Link
network of cash dispensers. There are now more than 8500 Link machines.
However, the Halifax charges 60p for each withdrawal made from machines other
than its own. This restricts the number available to 1600.
The Britannia, which has only 43 cash dispensers of its own, allows free
withdrawals from both the Link and Midland Bank networks which total 10,700
machines. The Dunfermline, with 33 branches, has only five cash machines and
makes no charge for withdrawals made from Link machines. Nor does the
Nationwide on children's accounts or the TSB.
The Royal Bank of Scotland allows free withdrawals from Bank of Scotland,
Barclays, Lloyds or Midland cash machines, a total of just under 9000.
All these accounts deduct tax at source from the interest paid. However,
children are allowed to receive up to #100 a year in interest tax free from
money given to them by a parent, #200 a year if both parents give. To get the
interest paid gross, parents need to fill in form R85 which bank and building
societies can provide.
Tax always trips up parents who want to give money to their off-spring.
Children have their own personal tax allowance from the day they are born. Any
money which is given to them by, say, grandparents or godparents can then grow
tax free so long as the interest doesn't exceed their personal allowance (#3525
in the 1995-96 tax year). This doesn't apply to money given by parents, which
the Revenue treats as still belonging to them.
One of the best ways parents can give money to children is to use National
Savings Children's Bonus Bonds which pay 7.5% if they are kept for the full
five years. Each child can have up to #1000 in Issue G, so if they already own
other issues their savings can be topped up. If you want to give Children's
Bonus Bonds for Christmas, the application form must be in by Monday, November
20.
MoneyFacts publishes a monthly guide to savings and mortgage rates. It costs
#48.50 a year, but it is offering a free copy to Herald readers who ring 01692
500765.
</TEXT>
