<HEADLINE>buy-out at Paterson Arran FINE FOODS</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBERT POWELL
WHISKY distiller Robertson &amp; Baxter has sold its loss-making Paterson Arran
fine foods subsidiary to a management buy-out team, but has retained a minority
stake in the company.
The price paid to the distiller of Lang's blended whisky and Glengoyne malt,
has not been disclosed. Neither has the size of Robertson &amp; Baxter's remaining
stake in the company.
The MBO, led by managing director Alan Hardie and finance director Ian
Appleton, was supported by more than #1m of loans from the Bank of Scotland.
Mr Hardie said it marked the final stage of a year-long restructuring process
aimed at restoring Paterson Arran to financial health.
The company manufactures preserves such as whisky-flavoured mustard at a small
plant on the island of Arran and biscuits and shortbread at its main factory in
Livingston.
It lost about #1m last year on turnover of #12m and is expecting a similar loss
in 1995, but Mr Hardie predicts that it will return to profit in 1996.
The staff is being cut back to 170 from 220 to improve efficiency, with 21 jobs
still to go at Livingston before Christmas. Heavy spending on marketing and
packaging has also been reduced.
``We are just about down to fighting weight,'' Mr Hardie said.
A large plank of Paterson Arran's recovery programme is to expand sales of own
label-foods on behalf of other firms. The company already makes and packages
salad dressing for British Airways and biscuits for diabetics for Boots the
Chemist.
Paterson Arran plans to expand by acquisition, but Mr Hardie said that will not
be for a year or so.
</TEXT>
