<HEADLINE>Weir to put `Baby' in his place BOXING</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Weir is determined to keep his dream alive when he defends the World
Boxing Organisation light-flyweight title against South Africa's Baby Jake
Matlala at Glasgow's Kelvin Hall tonight - a dream in which he sees himself as
the only Scot to win world titles at three different weights.
The little man from Irvine is already the only Scot to win two titles, but will
not be satisfied until he has added the flyweight title to the straw and
light-fly championship belts he has already won.
To keep on course, however, he must triumph in what he regards as the toughest
test of his professional career, against the tiny Matlala, the man who came to
Glasgow and wrenched the world flyweight title from Croy's Pat Clinton. After
three successful defences, Matlala lost that crown to Mexico's Alberto Jiminez,
and that put Weir's ambition on hold.
Explained the 28-year-old Scot, who will be having his sixth world title fight
in just 12 contests: ``The plan was that I would challenge Baby Jake for his
flyweight belt, but Jiminez put paid to that. I am now making a voluntary
defence of my title and have decided to give Baby Jake a shot at it. I wouldn't
have given him his chance if I thought he could beat me.
``I have a great admiration for what he has achieved in the ring, but I am
convinced I'll keep the championship in Scotland, and beating someone like Baby
Jake will put me on the road to even bigger things. I'm still determined to be
a world champion at three different weights.''
As you will have gathered, there is no feeling of inferiority in the Scot, but
he does recognise just how dangerous the 33-year-old South African can be.
Matlala puts his views of the fight in simple terms. ``It really is make or
break time for me,'' he said. ``I have to win and I believe I will win.''
Matlala, the smallest professional fighter in the world at 4ft 10in, doesn't
present much of a target and his aggression and powerful combination punches
have worn down more experienced opponents than Weir.
This is a genuine even-money fight, but I go for Weir. The Scot will not stand
still for Matlala to swarm all over him and he should be able to build up a
convincing lead early in the fight.
The undercard for the show hit a snag yesterday when flu ruled out Denver's
Benji Marquez, who was due to have met Glasgow's Gary Jacobs. The Scot, who is
building up to another world welterweight title fight, will now face London's
Lee Wicks.
The main support, however, will see Tranent's Willie ``The Mighty'' Quinn make
his first defence of the WBO Continental middleweight title. The challenger is
Hull's Peter Waudby, who recently won the Central Area title, and he provides
yet another step up in class for Quinn.
The rest of the bill is:
Cruiserweight - Colin Brown (Glasgow) v David Flowers (Canning Town). Welter -
Joe Townsley (Cleland) v Kevin Toomey (Hull). Light-welter - Mark Breslin
(Barrhead) v Paul Scott (Newbiggin). Super-feather - Hugh Collins (Stirling) v
J T Kelly (West Hartlepool). Feather - Peter Buckley (Birmingham) v Lehlohonolo
Ledbawa (South Africa).
</TEXT>
