<HEADLINE>Lambie overcomes resistance on return to Brockville Straight talker is back at his roots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT IS 36 years since a fresh-faced, enthusiastic, naive teenager called John
Lambie walked through the front door at Brockville to sign for Falkirk. Last
summer, he completed the circle by becoming the team manager, by which time the
naivete had been long since erased, the enthusiasm undiminished.
In a sense Lambie, although very much regarded as a Partick Thistle man or,
alternatively, a Hamilton Accies son, went back to his roots when he agreed to
join his old friend, chairman George Fulston, at Brockville.
It was the presence of Fulston - and, no doubt, the pay rise - but, perhaps
most of all, his own sense of destiny that combined to persuade him to leave
Firhill, where he had not only become a director but a fixture.
However, if you probe gently, you might also discover that within a few days he
wondered if he had done the right thing.
``Of course, that happens when you move clubs, especially to a place like
Falkirk, where Jim Jefferies was so highly regarded. I am a different kettle of
fish altogether to Jim, so it was difficult to begin with,'' says Lambie.
He recalls when there were only three days before a Coca-Cola Cup game with
Queen of the South, he had five players out injured, and he wondered what he
had let himself in for.
In that patently honest fashion that endears him to interviewers, Lambie
concedes that there was resistance to him within the club as a consequence of
the loyalty to Jefferies and the disappointment that he had left for Hearts.
``That wee bit of resentment is bound to be there when you take over at a club,
but it is up to you to weigh up your players, change faces, get players round
to your way of thinking. Do your own thing.''
He firmly believes that, if he had started in the pre-season, a lot of the
initial problems could have been avoided, but adds: ``I said after just three
days here we faced a very big job. I think the chairman and directors knew
that. We are starting to make progress.''
Lambie acknowledges that players were set in their ways, set in Jefferies'
ways, as is always the case at a club. In fact, Lambie's first plan was to let
well alone. ``I came into the job and didn't upset anything. I left things the
way they were. They had done well the previous season - why should I come in
and change things? But as the weeks progressed, I had a look and felt it was
time to do it my way.''
He believes he has brought the club round to his way, but adds cryptically:
``As far as that is concerned, I think I have only one thing to do and we will
be off and running.'' The one thing remained his secret, but perhaps we will be
able to guess in due course. ``Players have got to start to have self-pride,
play for the jersey. A football club is bigger than any player or any manager.''
At 54, Lambie is by far the oldest premier-division manager, an example of how
hard work, complete application, and self-belief can win even in the most
volatile of occupations. He would say that one of his unshakable tenets in
dealing with footballers is to be honest.
``You can't kid players. Telling them the truth might hurt, but in the end they
will respect you for it. If you lie to them, you will end up in a no-win
situation.''
He can take some straight talking himself, as he illustrated when he talked
about Falkirk fans, among whom there was also distinct resistance to his
appointment. He went to a supporters' meeting at which one fan, whose bravery
deserves a mention in dispatches, told him: ``I didn't want you here in the
first place. You were defensive-minded with Partick Thistle and we don't want
that.''
The image that he formed a pattern, an attitude at Firhill, which was designed
to halt the opposition rather than inflict punishment of its own, may have been
the biggest obstacle that Lambie has had to overcome at Falkirk, but his reply
to the fan is his reply to any other sceptic: ``I told him if any fan wants to
ask any player here whether I talk defensive football, he is free to do so. I
have never been a champion of defensive football and never will be.
``I know a lot more think that, but the only way I can satisfy them is by
winning games. I was here as a player for 10 years, so I know what the Falkirk
fans want.''
The relationship between him and Fulston is already notorious, the tales of him
being thrown out of his own home by the chairman when they were together at
Hamilton being confirmed by Lambie's recollection that they didn't talk to each
other for nine months.
``He didn't bring me here because we are friends. He brought me here because he
knows that I took Hamilton twice to the premier division, from second-bottom of
the first division, and I took Partick Thistle from second-bottom of the first
division into the premier, and kept them there for three years.''
He retains a soft spot for both Hamilton and Thistle and was depressed to hear
of the sit-in at Firhill by fans last weekend. ``I understand how supporters
feel at times and I think the money they have to spend to watch these days
allows them to have their opinions. But the chairman, Jim Oliver, was superb to
me.''
In that context, Lambie, maybe uniquely, readily admits that all the chairmen
he has worked for have been ``brilliant.'' They include Jan Stepek, when he was
in charge at Douglas Park, and about whom Lambie tells one particular tale
against himself.
``I asked to speak to the chairman, who invited me up to his house. His wife
poured me a coffee, left us, and I sat down. I asked him for 60 grand to buy a
player. He looked at me, asked me to stand up and turn round, booted me up the
backside and told me he didn't have 60 grand. You knew where you stood then.''
He has never had much cash to spend with any of his clubs and, in fact, set a
pesonal record when he paid #200,000 for Derek Ferguson a few weeks ago. He may
retain a liking for his old clubs, but no-one is more committed to his current
club. ``I am interested in only one thing now, and that is Falkirk Football
Club. There is a difference between here and Firhill, but there are diferences
with every club. I came here when they had finished fifth, and fans are looking
for no less than that this time. In the past I went to clubs who were in dire
straights. Falkirk were having a hard time for a while last season, then
brought in fresh faces and got it going.
``It is one of these strange things that newly promoted clubs into this league
seem to be relaxed and do well. Obviously, the first target for us is to make
sure we stay in this league, but ultimately I would like to take this club into
Europe and also win a trophy.
``To do that we will need quality players. There are some here and I brought in
one in Ferguson. I have been trying to sign another one for the past three
weeks.''
He is a fan of Maurice Johnston, who again has begun to get goals, for the
Brockville club. ``I said to him that everybody knows about his work-rate and
skill, but it was time he was getting into the box and scoring again. He is
doing that. ``Maurice is a real professional who looks after his body. He
doesn't get injured often and that is probably because he keeps himself so
fit.''
Lambie has always believed that any new manager, even one called Technical
Director, needs three years to get his game plan fully operational, but his own
self-appraisal would not allow him to overstay his welcome. ``If I didn't think
I was doing the right job for Falkirk, I would walk away. There is no way I
would embarrass George Fulston.''
He is not one of the mega-rich members of the managerial club - ``I like to
enjoy myself'' - and recalls starting in management as a part-time, #60-a-week
man.
He gave up his share of the bookmaking business, a good deal more lucrative
than his football earnings, to go full-time at Hamilton. He had been asked to
take on the job part-time while Bertie (Auld) was still there, but refused -
``I had too many good times with Bertie.''
Eventually, when he was asked to take over the following season, he was
persuaded by his wife Mamie - ``Remember, I have got to live with you,'' she
said - to give it a try. He has been on the circuit ever since.
``I would like to give it a go for another two or three years, because I
believe this is a young man's game. But I would like to stay involved somehow.
I love football and it is my life.''
Apart from home and family, only one other love competes for his attention -
pigeon racing, although golf is making a bid. The doos are John Lambie's
relaxation. If and when he talks to them, you can be sure there will be no
prevarication. He is not a man for ``flannel.''
</TEXT>
