<HEADLINE>POWER GENERATION Hydro-Electric still in battle for pump storage business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Hydro-Electric is through to the final round of bidding for National
Grid's pump storage business in North Wales, company officials said yesterday.
The two hydro-electric dams at Dinorwic and Ffestiniog open their sluices at
peak periods to shove up to 2300 megawatts of extra power into the English and
Welsh electricity pool for up to four hours at a time.
They later draw electricity from the grid during off-peak periods to pump water
back uphill to their main reservoirs.
The pump storage business, which is being privatised separately from the rest
of National Grid, is expected to sell for between #300m and #400m.
Historically it has made an annual profit of around #50m.
Eleven companies submitted preliminary bids when the pump storage business was
put up for sale in September, but only three have qualified for the final round
of bidding, which closes on December 15.
An official announcement of who the three finalists will be is expected on
Monday. Last night Hydro-Electric still did not know the identity of its two
rivals.
Other firms known to be interested in pump storage include Eastern Electricity,
which was recently taken over by the Hanson group and has just bought two
coal-fired power stations from PowerGen for #450m.
A pump storage management buy-out group, the French state power company
Electricite de France and several US utilities were also thought to be
interested.
If Hydro-Electric wins control of the pump storage business, it will be the
company's biggest investment south of the Border.
Its biggest investment outside Scotland to date is a #280m half-share in a
680-megawatt gas-powered power station at Keadby on Humberside, which is due to
come on stream next month. Hydro-Electric's partner in that deal is the English
regional electricity company Norweb.
A key attraction of the Welsh pump storage business is that Hydro-Electric
already has expertise in running this type of operation.
About 20% of its power comes from hydro-electric dams in the north of Scotland
and the company already operates a 300-megawatt pump storage scheme at Foyers
on the shores of Loch Ness.
Hydro-Electric would have to call an extraordinary meeting of shareholders to
endorse the purchase of the Welsh pump storage if its bid proved successful.
But company spokesman Mike Keohane said the acquisition would be financed from
borrowings without recourse to a rights issue.
Hydro-Electric has gearing of 30%, but Mr Keohane said there should be no
problem raising this to 80% if necessary to finance new investments.
This would allow the Perth-based company to go ahead with a project to build a
700-megawatt gas-powered power station at Avonmouth near Bristol as well as
buying the pump storage business, he noted.
Hydro-Electric has held exploratory talks with British Gas on taking a half
share in the Avonmouth project. This would involve it in further investment of
about #150m, but there has been no decision yet to go ahead with the venture.
Hydro-Electric is taking a different path to expansion in England and Wales to
its south of Scotland rival ScottishPower which recently bought Manweb, an
electricity distribution company, for #1130m.
Hydro-Electric prefers to invest directly in generation and supply without
taking on responsibility for more power cables than it already has to maintain
in the north of Scotland.
</TEXT>
