<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music   Emmylou Harris, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THINGS got mighty serious last night. After all, Ms Harris and her current
accomplice, every earnest musician's earnest musician, Daniel Lanois, were
engaged in forging a brand new genre-busting musical form -
ambient-country-gospel-rock might be the most accurate label - as well as
seeking to span the American ethno-musicological divide from New Orleans funky
funeral-march to Apalachian folkabilly four-step.
Good-time whoop-di-do was absent from the menu, perhaps in part due to
Emmylou's voice being afflicted with a jet-lagged huskiness. Nevertheless Ms
Harris sang to her usual intent: with ragged defiance in the face of the void
which awaits us all.
Similarly, despite his being jokily attired in a Motorhead t-shirt, Mr Lanois
coaxed sonic textures from his guitar with grave delicacy. No mindless
headbanging.
Deeper Well, from Emmylou's current album, Wrecking Ball, is a good example of
where she and Mr Lanois might be headed.
It's a song which Bo Diddley and Hank Williams could have co-written. But only
if they'd gotten into New Age crystal therapy, looking to find water inside
some deeper well, and each hoping that their inner child hasn't drowned down
there.
There were many gorgeous moments last night - ah, the heartbroken recrimination
which Emmylou brought to Lucinda Williams' Sweet Old World - but only if you
knew Wrecking Ball, and were prepared to forget most of Emmylou's other albums.
Yet there was a one-paced air to the proceedings, too.
A small price to pay for seriously good artists taking their art seriously?
