<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>COMMUNICATIONS Buoyant Hewlett-Packard</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEWLETT-Packard, the US computer and communications company which owns a large
factory at South Queensferry, yesterday announced a 52% increase in net
earnings to $2400m for the year to October 31.
The company, based at Palo Alto in California, announced it would share 11.46%
of its second-half profits with employees, the highest proportion since the
scheme began in 1962.
Hewlett-Packard's 5000 UK employees will share #6.8m from this bonus. The
company has factories at Ipswich and Bristol as well as South Queensferry.
Net revenue rose 26% to $31.5bn. The US accounted for $14bn of that revenue,
with the remaining $17.5bn coming from foreign subsidiaries.
Earnings per share jumped from $3.07 to $4.63.
Wall Street investors turned the company's year-end news to their advantage by
taking profits on Hewlett-Packard stock, which gave up $4.50 to close at
$88.50.
Hewlett-Packard's UK operations improved in line with the company's overall
performance, increasing turnover to #1700m from #1314m in the previous year.
Exports were also up, rising by 59% to #700m.
The company's South Queensferry site, which employs 1250 people, specialises in
the design and manufacture of test equipment and network management systems for
telecommunications, mobile radio, cable television and general radio frequency
measurements.
The site, which is home to a microwave, telecom and telecommunications
division, saw its combined turnover increase by 37.5% over the previous year.
``Hewlett-Packard's operations in Scotland are extremely good performers,
relative even to the company as a whole, which has done very well,'' marketing
communications director Hugh Walker said.
He added that the prospects were good for future investment and expansion at
the South Queensferry site.
At Hewlett-Packard headquarters, chief executive Lewis E Platt thanked
employees worldwide for their contributions to the company's success. ``We're
pleased with the consistency of our performance throughout the year and with
the balanced contribution of our businesses and geographies to these results,''
he said.
``Again this year, Hewlett-Packard people around the world have shown energy
and ingenuity in delivering what customers are looking for.''
</TEXT>
