<DOCNO>GH951118-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faced with a costly choice Cautious people who opt to rent rather than buy may pay for their decision later</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HELEN PRIDHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH home owners may have escaped the worst problems that have afflicted
the UK housing market in recent years but they have not been completely immune.
Figures from the Halifax Building Society show that house prices on this side
of the Border fell by 2.2% during the third quarter this year. The number of
households suffering negative equity is also increasing. Latest figures reveal
that more than 13,000 in Scotland are now affected.
Mortgage lenders would like the Government to use this month's Budget to
introduce measures to stimulate the housing market. Top of their wish list is
the abolition of stamp duty, but extra help targeted at first-time buyers has
also been suggested. Additional tax relief and grant type incentives for
first-time buyers are among the measures recommended.
Many potential first-time buyers are delaying property purchase and choosing
rented accommodation instead, despite the attractive mortgages being offered by
lenders. In an effort to convince home makers of the advantages of ownership,
Abbey National has just published a survey showing that in every major city
around Britain the cost of renting a property is higher than buying.
The survey compared the overall cost of buying and renting houses over a
25-year period. It calculated the amount of money spent on buying a property
with a 90% repayment mortgage at a fixed rate of 7.99%, including maintenance
costs, and compared it to the cost of renting somewhere similar - assuming 3% a
year inflation on the rent.
According to the Abbey National, the West of Scotland is the fourth most
expensive area in which to rent in the whole of the UK. It states that a
three-bedroomed semi-detached house in Glasgow will cost more than twice as
much to rent as to buy. Over 25 years, the cost of renting such a house would
be #302,400, whereas buying a similar property would cost #135,556. ``That's a
massive saving of #166,844,'' Abbey National points out.
Its calculations show that savings of more than #100,000 can also be made when
buying rather than renting other types of property in the area.
However, Abbey National seems to have missed the point about why people are not
buying. A recent survey by the Council of Mortgage Lenders into why the housing
market is not moving found that cost was not the major deterrent. Less than 10%
felt mortgage rates were unattractive.
By far the most important reasons given by 25 to 34-year olds for their
reluctance to enter the market was that their employment situation was not
conducive to buying (41%) and that they were unable or unwilling to take on
debt (38%). Other main reasons were that they were saving or still had to save
for a deposit (33%) or were worried that they would find it difficult to keep
up their mortgage repayments (27%).
So the major problem seems to be that people lack confidence in their own
financial position and their ability to service their mortgage and are,
therefore, delaying a decision about buying a house. Practical considerations
about mobility also enter into it. There is a fear of not being able to resell
a property when necessary (13%) and a feeling that renting is more flexible
(18%).
Another survey by the Household Mortgage Corporation also found that the major
worry among prospective house buyers was job security followed by a fear that
interest rates would rise again. HMC also asked existing customers what advice
they would give to their children.
According to HMC's Jeff Wagland, writing in MoneyFacts: ``Young people are
being advised to rent until they are absolutely sure that they have found the
place they want to settle down, and the person they want to settle down with.
They are being told to save up as large a deposit as they can before even
thinking about a mortgage, and to treat home ownership as a very long-term
game.''
Both the Council of Mortgage Lenders and HMC found home ownership was still the
aim of most people. Asked by the CML where they would hope to be living in 10
years, 84% said they would like to own a house.
Thus, renting is mainly seen as a short-term option, which makes Abbey
National's 25-year comparisons rather misleading. Indeed, a more limited
exercise carried out by the Woolwich Building Society comparing renting and
buying over a two-year period established that renting was a cheaper option.
Still, in one respect Abbey National is right. Interest rates are low and, for
those who are ready to settle down, home buying is a cheap option. Mortgage
protection policies are now freely available from companies such as General
Accident to cover your mortgage payments if you become unemployed or sick and
unable to work.
Competitive mortgage offers abound. According to MoneyFacts, Bradford &amp;
Bingley, for example, is offering a first-time buyers' loan at just 1.89% fixed
for the first year with a free valuation thrown in. Mortgages of up to 95% are
available.
For borrowers concerned about future rises in interest rates, a fixed-rate
mortgage may give peace of mind. The Royal Bank of Scotland has recently shaved
the rates on its range and borrowers can lock into a 95% mortgage at 8.75% for
the next 10 years. If you want a 100% loan the rate increases to 9.75%.
</TEXT>
