<DOCNO>GH951118-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Interesting time to invest your trust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN CLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE exciting thing to do in the stock market recently has been to dance nimble
footed with the Scotias, Unipalms, Cortecs and other win-or-bust pharmaceutical
or computing specialists working in the ``leading edge'' areas. Rising hopes
have given a dozen or so of them high ratings and provided good Christmas
dinners for the brave investor.
Back in the safer world of investment trusts, inhabited by investors who like
to spread their risks, Philip Middleton of broking firm Merill Lynch has been
getting a little warmer towards his specialist sector than he has been of late.
In the firm's latest quarterly report he and colleague Charles Cade confess:
``We are becoming more bullish.''ddddd
They are not yet rampantly so. It would take a bear market they say to depress
the discounts at which the prices of trust shares trade compared with the value
of their underlying assets to make them that enthusiastic, and they are not
expecting that sort of fall. But they do say: ``Trusts are getting cheaper and
this is allowing some proper value to come through.''
Although the average discount over the sector as a whole has not moved
dramatically in the last three months, they say there are ``individual
situations which offer very good value''.
If you like the UK market, for instance, they have been running their
calculators over the relationships between discounts, UK content, yields and so
on, and come to the conclusion that Edinburgh Investment Trust is the one they
like best for taking the investor into mainstream UK shares.
Repeating that they are ``not suggesting a raging level of optimism'' but see
more reason for buying than they have done for some time, they suggest the
largest trusts which seem the cheapest to buy are the two European
privatisation trusts, Kleinwort and Mercury, together with Kleinwort's Charter,
Edinburgh, American Trust, Mercury World Mining and Scottish Mortgage, which
they comment is a well-managed general trust at the wide end of its trading
range.
The discounts on Fleming Overseas and Anglo and Overseas have now narrowed to
near their trend lines but have been ``very cheap recently'' they add. Perhaps
these two are also worth keeping an eye on, particularly as Anglo and Overseas
does seem to wander into cheap territory from time to time.
In general, the brokers comment that trusts investing in Europe and North
America seem ``very cheap'', while those investing in general overseas shares
are also ``attractive''.
So far as American Trust is concerned, they suggest its rating has been
affected by the surprising problem faced by Fleming American Trust. As this
traces its ancestry back to what was a railway company, a business it quit in
the early years of this century, it has come up against the US Environmental
Protection Agency.
The agency can demand payments for cleaning up pollution caused in previous
years and the old railway company is accused of letting creosote leak into a
lake. The trust's share of the costs might, the brokers suggest, be ``a few
million dollars'' but until the uncertainties over how much, if anything, it
will have to pay are resolved, it will trade on a rating reflecting this.
So far as they are aware, American Trust is not tarred with the same brush but
it has also been derated, presenting investors with ``a clear
opportunity''.fffff
Interest rates appear to have an effect on investment trust discounts.
Certainly the drop in rates seemed to prompt a big switch from cash deposits in
banks and building societies into shares, bringing strong demand for investment
trusts in 1993.dddddddddd
The men from Merill Lynch say they think the UK interest rate cycle has peaked
and are also ``very bullish of US interest rates''. This is an extremely
positive background for investment trusts as, logically, falling rates should
improve demand for their shares, although the potential reductions in rates are
tiny compared with those a couple of years or so ago.
Interest rates get a lot of publicity as politicians, bankers, economists and
industrialists argue over what should be the correct level. Yet a lot of people
do not realise just where they stand.
Unit trust group Save &amp; Prosper researches this from time to time and its
latest findings are that ``interest rate perceptions are still too high''.
A survey carried out last month showed that nearly half the people with instant
access building society accounts thought they were getting more than they
really were. While interest on #1000 net of tax is around 2.8%, 40% thought
they were receiving more than this and almost 40% confessed they did not know
what they were getting.
Amanda Webster, the group's product development director, says: ``With
inflation running at 3.2% many building society investors are losing out in
real terms from their savings and they are not realising it. The position is
even worse for higher rate taxpayers where they are taxed even further on the
interest earned from most building society accounts.''
Her group's Extra Income Fund, a UK unit trust investing in blue-chip shares
and fixed-interest securities to give a mixture of income and growth, currently
yields 5.6% gross, although part or all of its management charge may be debited
to capital. The fund, launched in October last year, has so far given a total
return of 12.4% if net income was reinvested.
</TEXT>
