<DOCNO>GH951118-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Living on her instincts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
She began as little more than a twinkle in Woody Allen's eye and her image is
manufactured from very little. Even the star herself admits to that. So why,
asks Jane Scott , is Sharon Stone such a highly-marketable phenomenon?
THERE are perhaps four things you should know about Sharon Stone before
dismissing her as a Hollywood publicity monster who shows rather too much skin
to be taken seriously.
The first is that in 1980, director Woody Allen cast her as his fantasy woman
in his black and white film Stardust Memories - her movie debut. It makes one
snigger now, but: ``I looked at her and thought I would really like her to kiss
me!'' he is reported as saying.
Stone protested when they put her in a ``bombshell dress'' for the brief clip,
where she kisses him.
``I said: `Wait. Let me explain something - I'm not a bombshell.' They didn't
see it my way. I played Woody's fantasy. And that was the beginning of the
end.''
Ten years later she posed nude for Playboy, proving that at 32 and with a
decade of truly awful potboilers behind her there was not so much a serious
actress waiting to get out as a woman determined to get noticed.
A year later she uncrossed her legs in Basic Instinct; the Sharon Stone package
was revealed, heralding the writhing skin scenes so familiar to those of us who
have yawned our way through the ludicrous plots and moderate box office success
of The Specialist and Sliver.
And in the past two years, it has paid off; more important than taking the
leading role in The Quick and the Dead, last year's female shoot-em-up cowboy
movie, she was the co-producer and chose the director.
This year she finished shooting Casino, playing mobster Robert de Niro's
unfaithful wife. Martin Scorsese, the director's director, chose her for the
role, which is perhaps the only really important thing you need to know about
Sharon Stone at all; as part of Hollywood's elite, she is all future, and the
past doesn't figure at all. Not that the past necessarily bothers her. She is
variously reported as saying in Basic Ambition, a new biography by journalist
Douglas Thompson out this month:
n On the 10-page Playboy spread: ``One, I wanted to be seen. Leading ladies my
age are typed and you need to be sexually appealing for parts in the movies you
might be right for. It's a man's world and when you look like I look, that's
what it is.''
n On Basic Instinct: ``Once I realised that was what the guys wanted, I
thought: `Oh, I get it. No matter how he touches her or where he touches her or
what else he does to her, it`s the most, it's the best, it's the sexiest'.''
n On Sharon Stone: ``My image is manufactured from very little . . . I realised
I could create an event - this more attractive woman.'' She has maintained she
was ``betrayed'' on the Basic Instinct interrogation scene by director Paul
Verhoeven, who told her to take off her white knickers because they were
reflecting the light, assuring her the shadows were too dark to show anything
very significant. She has subsequently vetted all nude scenes before release.
AND Stone and her fans drearily insist that the part of sex killer Catherine
Tramell in Basic Instinct changed Hollywood values for good. This, remember, is
the movie that gave us perhaps the most offensive line in film history: ``I
think she's the f*** of the century.''
``So many female characters are written the way men experience women or would
like to experience women. But that's not the way women really are . . . I think
Basic Instinct showed both men and women in the trenches pitted against one
another,'' says Stone. It is true that Tramell more than matched Michael
Douglas's testosterone-stuffed detective Nick Curran, unlike the sad obsessive
played by Glenn Close in his previous rip-em-off movie Fatal Attraction, but
Stone claims too much here; what is ``the f*** of the century'' but Woody
Allen's dream girl made flesh?
Stone's movies have almost all been written, directed and produced by men, and
until The Quick and the Dead (with the possible exception of Sliver) she has
never carried the film; her role was the main character's love interest.
So forget about the films, which ain't going to change anything; concentrate on
what she does with her stardom.
Vicki Patterson, assistant education officer at the Edinburgh Filmhouse, says:
``She is a phenomenon, and she is interesting; she has created controversy, and
she is determined - I admire her for getting in a position where she
co-financed The Quick and the Dead; it is unusual, especially for women, who
are constantly fighting among themselves for a decreasing number of parts. It
takes guts to put one's reputation on the line.''
Thompson's biography has the precocious Stone telling schoolfriends in rural
Pennsylvania that she would be the new Marilyn Monroe.
She escaped home via modelling, and then to Hollywood, where she appeared in
slasher flicks (Deadly Blessing), creaking adventure pictures (King Solomon's
Mines, Allan Quartermain and the Lost City of Gold), and the execrable Police
Academy 4 before losing a truly career-sapping bad perm and hitting the big
time as Arnold Schwarzenegger's wife in Total Recall in 1990.
The recurring word in interviews is control. On the way she has ditched a
husband and a long-term lover - both film producers - at least two agents, had
a Hello! at home shoot (which caused controversy when it was divulged she had
borrowed someone else's home to do it with), gained a lover 10 years younger
than herself and, most recently, been awarded France's highest mark of esteem
in the arts - the Chevalier of Arts.
Patterson says: ``If Casino goes well that will improve her record at the box
office and guarantee her work in the future.
``Hopefully, she is going to continue to get involved in production. It will
mean more roles for women and better roles and hopefully they can perhaps
champion directors of their choice, maybe directors who are a lot more
sympathetic to female roles.
``I think we should take her seriously, and the French obviously do. Maybe
we're missing something.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ELECTRICITY London pays out #198m bonus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHAREHOLDERS of London Electricity are in for a Christmas bonus as the group
revealed a cash handout which the stock market saw as an attempt to dissuade a
predator from pouncing.
They will receive a special dividend of 100p a share net of standard rate tax
and a 20% increase in this year's normal dividends to 34.8p. This follows a 29%
rise for 1994-95.
The special amount will be paid at the same time as the interim for 1995-96 at
the end of January.
London Electricity chairman Sir Bob Reid said that after the current year they
expected to continue increasing dividends in real terms. He commented: ``These
proposals are in line with our strategy of returning value to our shareholders.
``Last year we completed a successful share buy-back and next month we expect
that shareholders will be invited to approve our proposals for the demerger of
the National Grid. This special dividend delivers value to shareholders while
maintaining the company's ability to invest in and develop the business.''
The share buy-back reduced the number of shares in issue by nearly a tenth and
the special payout will cost #198m. It is subject to approval by shareholders
at a meeting scheduled for mid-January. It is also proposed to consolidate the
existing Ordinary shares into new Ordinary shares.
The payout plan will have to be partly financed through higher borrowings,
raising gearing to around half shareholders' funds and follows similar moves by
other electricity companies as they tried to escape predators.
There are now just four regional electricity companies retaining their
independence following the takeover boom and the rest are expected to be
snapped up eventually.
Analysts did not think the latest move will make London less vulnerable. One
commented: ``It will make it a bit more difficult, a bit more expensive but I
doubt it would stop someone from making a bid.''
The group could afford to take more aggressive steps to retain independence as
it could raise its gearing significantly further. But its shares, up 19p at
933p, valuing the group at #1900m, are partly discounting a successful bid.
</TEXT>
