<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opera  Mathis der Maler, Royal Opera House, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323258</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Hindemith, whose centenary is marked by the first professional British
staging of his medieval allegory Mathis der Maler, was labelled a degenerate by
the Nazis shortly after the piece was premiered. He eventually fled Germany,
and history proves his prescience: ``Where there's blood and violence, art
cannot thrive.''
The Royal Opera rather bravely handed responsibility for the production to
opera's enfant terrible, Peter Sellars, whose American freeway version of the
Magic Flute still causes shudders among more conservative opera goers. On the
first night of this effort there were a few token boos, but Sellars provided
few causes for dismay.
Hindemith set his story in the sixteenth-century German peasants' revolt, but
Sellars has made explicit the composer's attack on the tyranny of his time. The
setting is apocalyptic modern, full of cruel men in suits, machine guns, and
disinfectant engineers. The steeply raked glass set is dominated by a
continuous-loop television picture of a mysterious silent head.
Led by a passionate Esa-Pekka Salonen in the pit, and an exciting set of
soloists, the production made the most of Hindemith's tense, sometimes soaring
score. Of note, Alan Titus as the tortured, visionary painter Mathis gives a
raw edge to a superb voice. Stig Andersen is a moving Cardinal Albrecht. German
soprano Christiane Oelze is a promising find as Regina, daughter of the rebel
Schwalb, sung by the strong Thomas Young.
The revelation, though, is the Danish soprano Inga Nielsen, a pure,
terrifyingly exciting voice as Ursula.
Hindemith's ideas on art and power are best left to the purity of the music and
the voices. Sellars often obscures them with too much visual PC clutter,
forgetting that less is always more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music  Boris Berezovsky, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GENERALLY speaking, I'm a big fan of Boris Berezovsky. He's an unlikely
virtuoso pianist: a big, sleepy-looking lad who looks as though he's just got
up and forgot to comb his hair. Pianistically, he's down to earth, unaffected,
with his interpretations free of posture and pretension.
I suppose that some of those qualities could be perceived in his solo lunchtime
recital at the RSAMD, yesterday, where the programme was devoted to
Mussorgksy's Night on a Bare Mountain and Pictures at an Exhibition (both more
familiar from their orchestrated versions, but with a different sort of
effectiveness in their original keyboard format).
The trouble was that Berezovsky's playing veered slightly left of naturalness
towards something suggestive of casual indifference, or a preoccupation with
something else. That probably sounds insulting, and isn't meant to be. The best
way to describe his performance yesterday is by analogy.
Mussorgsky's Pictures, for those who don't know the work, is a set of musical
portraits separated by a recurring theme entitled Promenade, and intended to
portray the listener/viewer wandering from picture to picture in a gallery.
Imagine a visitor to the gallery who's merely passing through, taking a short
cut, heading somewhere else.
This was Berezovsky yesterday, striding through the Promenade, passing by most
of the portraits at a rate of knots, getting a general impression, but taking
little attention to detail, dynamic, or colour contrast. Brusque and
disappointing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bank of England will recommend interest rate reduction if final demand weakens Pound continues to suffer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STERLING was still on the rack yesterday as it has been all week. Its
trade-weighted index against a basket of currencies finally closed at 82.3,
beating the previous closing low of 82.5 established on Wednesday.
Against the German mark, it slid to 2.1725 at one stage, before recovering
slightly to 2.1751, down 1.85, and still under its previous record low of
2.1755 seen in May this year.
There are various factors adversely impacting on the pound, not least the
softness of the US dollar as the stand-off between President Clinton and White
House leader Newt Gingrich continues over the US budget. But the pound even
finished 0.39 lower on the dollar at $1.5523.
``Sterling is doing what it does best, going down,'' said one dealer.
Speculation about interest rate cuts, worries about possible imprudent tax
reductions in the Budget and general political uncertainty were also
influencing factors in the UK currency's travails.
Howard Davies, deputy governor of the Bank of England, meanwhile, speaking
after the close of London trading, added his contribution to the interest rates
debate, stating that the Bank of England will change its advice and recommend
an interest rate cut if there are clear signs that final demand is weakening.
But he said the Bank's view of inflation was based on an assessment of the
probabilities. ``We are not yet persuaded that inflation is dead nor indeed
that the Government can achieve its inflation target of 2.5% or less - though
yesterday's figure was certainly encouraging.''
In an address to the Oil Industries Club, he said that, ``if there were clear
signs that final demand has weakened substantially, that would be likely to
affect our assessment of inflationary pressures, and our advice would change''.
He stressed that changing one's mind when the facts change is not a sign of
``dizziness'', rather the reverse. But it is important not to react to one good
number or indeed one bad one.
The deputy governor said the Bank hoped steady growth would continue. ``Our
central assessment is that it will and that the underlying condition of the
economy is healthy,'' he added.
Thursday's inflation data for October showed UK retail prices fell 0.5% on the
month, reducing the year-on-year headline rate to 3.2%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AGAINST all odds, and at great personal risk, young - puerile-sounding anyway -
intrepid Ed Marriot, hearing of a lost tribe in a hugely inaccessible part of
Papua New Guinea, decides to go meet the Liawep people who live on the mountain
they worship as their god.
Nobody wants to help him and anthropologists try to dissuade him, gently at
first and then they come clean and suggest that he is nuts and liable to be
eaten. But does he listen? Not Ed. I must come clean myself here because when I
started listening to Our Father the Mountain (R4) I stopped the tape and gave
myself a little talking to. It went like this.
``Critic, put aside your prejudices about that voice. Remember that your
dislike of that kind of voice - no, that character-voice - has been recently
activated by last night's viewing of Four Weddings and a Funeral. Just because
he sounds like Hugh Grant in the jungle (I mean, of course, the Grant persona,
all terribly gosh and upper-class tic) does not mean the result of Ed's awfully
big adventure will be risible, deeply patronising and rather sick. You don't
yet know if it will be Numpty gets Pretty Scared in Bongo Land.'' So I deleted
my bias and rewound.
First of all we had to hear about the drugs and jags he needed to make his
actually illegal journey into primitivism. He is warned about the fatal bite of
some bug or snake (I'm sorry, I was laughing a bit here but it was one or the
other) he might encounter. A female bite of the species would be fatal, so he
asks how he is meant to tell the difference. Things were getting complicated
for Ed and he hadn't even reached the mountain yet.
With his guide Dunstan, Ed reaches the tribe, some of whom immediately scatter
into the nearest bit of denser jungle. Ed notes and ponders this. Things get
worse, and with an analytic grasp of the situation he says it's ``because I'm
basically here, isn't it?''
Yes, I murmured, yes! And as if he had heard me, Ed went on to describe how
suggestions had been made that there might be something colonialist and dubious
about going into a place he had no idea about, with no ideas whatsoever. The
head of the tribe was called Herod and not unsurprisingly, given his name, was
pretty het up about Christianity, de-manding that Ed profess his faith. Well,
he did this pretty reluctantly, he admitted, but you see, he didn't want to
offend, did he?
HEROD was getting pretty hostile by this time but I suppose, not having seen
Four Weddings, he probably didn't get the joke. In the middle of this
tragi-comic nightmare, with lots of noise in the background, our reporter
whispers to Dunstan: ``Would it help if I came round to say hello?'' No, I
shouted, but this time he did not seem to hear me because things, astoundingly
in the face of his anthropological sensitivity, got worse.
The mountain got angry, Herod threw a fit, and four children died. Dunstan
rushed into Ed's room suggesting they better get out of there fast. Very fast,
so fast, in fact, that Ed fascinatingly cogitated on the fact that it had taken
them five days to get there, but only three days to get back.
Then once he had got his breath back, and explaining to us that it would have
been inopportune to hang around talking to his little machine in the middle of
the mayhem, Ed finished off his extraordinary contribution to global knowledge
by telling a little garbled nugget which involved 7th Day Adventists and gold
consortiums.
There is certainly a story to be told there, but next time I know exactly who
the producer should send. It came to me while listening to Gentlemen Prefer
Blondes (R4). Lorelei was given a diary; she was confused at first, because it
was a book without words, but once she grasped the diary concept, she warmed to
the idea - although she wondered, given that she thought all the time, how many
books she would need.
I still think that if Radio 4 had given her a cute little recording machine,
like they had given to Ed, she would have produced a better programme, and hit
it off with Herod.
</TEXT>
