<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>High life no fun but Liz's sacrifice is worthwhile</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER more than three weeks' training at an altitude of 8500 feet, Liz McColgan
and her husband, Peter, climbed into a truck to take them the hour's drive back
down through the polluted, rarified air to catch their flight out of Mexico
City.
With them, went their host, German Silva, with whom McColgan had done several
training sessions. They bade one another farewell at the departure gate, Silva
bound for New York, the McColgans for tomorrow's Tokyo Marathon. ``I knew
German was in shape to win his race, and that I was on course for mine,'' said
Liz.
Half of the prediction has already been fulfilled - Silva retained the New York
Marathon crown last weekend, while tomorrow, McColgan lines up for the most
vital race of her career, and after the toughest sacrifice she has ever made.
It is five weeks since they last saw their daughter, Eilish, but Liz has risen
at 5am every day, phoning Carnoustie to chat to the four-year-old before
grannie, Betty, took her off to school.
It was the worst possible time to be away, for during it Eilish went to school
all day for the first time. ``I have missed her terribly, but it's just as well
she stayed behind,'' confides Liz.
``Mexico was good for training, but primitive. The house itself was fine - four
bedrooms, rented out to runners. It was owned by German, and his brother,
Rudolpho, who drove us to all the various training venues. But there were dogs,
roaming wild in packs. A couple of times I was chased, and they set on one
runner.
``Hygiene-wise, it was safer to stay home and do our own cooking. We used
bottled water for cooking and even brushing teeth. Despite being very careful,
I had a stomach bug - could not last 20 minutes without going to the toilet,
and needed antibiotics.
``Later a storm cut off the phone and electricity for a week. It was so cold,
we had to order wood for a fire. It arrived strapped to the back of a donkey.
``Basic? Yes, but if it works, we'll be back next March, to test it again
before doing it for the Olympics. If things don't go well, we will modify the
timing.
``This is an experiment, to see how I respond to altitude - planned
meticulously, coming down exactly the same number of days before Tokyo as I
will for the Olympics. I know I'm in my best-ever shape for a marathon, and
will be disappointed if I don't break 2hr 27min, assuming conditions are okay.''
The background may be alien as McColgan runs between towering glass
skyscrapers, bristling with the antennae of Japan's high-tech communications
industry, towering over tiny pavement restaurants - six or eight fold-down
seats ingeniously hinged around rickshaws parked on the pavement with all
cooking equipment on board, and serving freshly cooked sea slugs - past the
frantically jangling pachinko parlours where pinball-crazed housewifes enact a
scene identical to that in the casinos of Las Vegas or Atlantic City.
But as the Dundee Hawkhill Harrier tackles her final work-outs, she is right at
home. Japan was where she tackled her first-ever major championship, in 1985,
before almost any Scot had ever heard of her. At the World Student Games in
Kobe she finished fifth in the 3000m, and fourth in the 10,000m - the last time
she was beaten in the Land of the Rising Sun.
Subsequent victories include the Fukuoka cross-country, less than three months
after Eilish's birth, a world record in the Tokyo half-marathon, and another
win in the Tokyo Marathon, plus her world 10,000m triumph on a typhoon-lashed
night in 1991.
Tomorrow she faces a tougher field than any previous marathon: Valentina
Yegor-ova, Russia's Olympic champion bidding for her third succcessive win in
the race; double Commonwealth champion Lisa Ondieki, who has never forgiven
McColgan for making her squirm in New York; and Junko Asari, the 1993 world
champion from Japan, who will have two sub 2-27 compatriots for company, as
this is their Olympic trial.
For McColgan, who has been in daily phone contact with coach Grete Waitz as
well as her daughter, her time - rather than the place - tomorrow will tell
whether she can again scale the Olympic heights after a three-year injury
nightmare.
</TEXT>
