<DOCNO>GH951118-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chasing the record and a new sponsor ATHLETICS</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LESLIE Deans Racing Club will not only be chasing a chapter in Scottish
athletics history tomorrow in the eight-stage, 45!s-mile Edinburgh to Glasgow
road relay, but also to secure their own future, writes Doug Gillon.
If they win the Barr-sponsored event, it will not only gain consolation
silverware for their sponsor, Edinburgh solicitor Leslie Deans whose football
team, Hearts, seem incapable of stocking his trophy cabinet, but Racing would
join Victoria Park as the only club ever to win in five successive years.
Club founder Alan Robson confirmed that talks are in the pipeline for a new
backer - Deans has never stood in the way of their securing support on a
grander scale. ``Clearly, victory would do these talks no harm at all,'' said
Robson.
Racing will field Ken Chapman, Tom Hanlon, Davie Ross, John Robson, Frank
McGowan, Brian Kirkwood, Glen Stewart, and Scott Cohen. All but the last two
were in last year's octet, and the addition of Stewart, outstanding road man of
the current season, and Cohen, in fine form, suggest they will achieve their
goal.
Shettleston also field six survivors from last year's runners-up squad: Dave
Cameron, Billy Coyle, Dermot McGonigle, Graeme Wight, John Mackay, and Andy
Little, plus Brian Sally and Adrian Callan, who can only strengthen that
line-up.
Cambuslang have one or two injury niggles and problems to resolve today, but
the team which took bronze at the national cross-country relay championships -
Alex Robertson, Graeme Croll, Charlie Thompson, and Steven Wylie - are all
available. British internationalist Keith Anderson and hill-running ace Colin
Donnelly are not.
</TEXT>
