<TEXT>
Welsh Water
marks time
WELSH Water, a potential bidder for South Wales Electricity, yesterday pulled
back from elaborating on possible terms when the two companies met. Swalec said
later that it was ``very disappointed'' that Welsh Water had still not
clarified whether it intended to make a bid for the company and voiced concern
at what it called the uncertainty being created.
Welsh Water made clear that it was continuing to examine the possibility of
making an offer for Swalec and if it went ahead would seek the backing of that
company's board. But any offer would not include Swalec's stake in the National
Grid. On this basis, no firm price will be put on the company until a market
value for the National Grid could be established.
The two companies have agreed to meet again after this. The demerger involves
distributing most of the shares of the National Grid to the shareholders of the
regional electricity companies, which are its owners.
A prospectus for the National Grid is due to be published on November 22.
Trading is due to start on December 11.
Zantac sales fall
THE decline in sales of Zantac, the anti-ulcer product, has hit the overall
growth of Glaxo Wellcome. Group chairman Sir Colin Corness told shareholders at
the annual meeting yesterday that sales of Glaxo and Wellcome products for the
10 months to October 31, 1995, when compared to the sales of both companies for
the same period of 1994, grew by 4% in sterling terms, 5% at constant exchange
rates. Excluding Zantac, sales are growing 8% at constant exchange rates, ``a
credible performance given the impact that the bid and integration process have
inevitably had on the sales forces of both Glaxo and Wellcome''.
Boost for Fife firm
HUGHES Microelectronics Europa announced yesterday it had secured a #2m
contract for the production of approximately 200 of the electronic guidance
systems used in Tomahawk missiles. The Glenrothes-based manufacturer will
assemble the control module guidance systems and relay boxes for Tomahawk
missiles built in the US by Hughes Aircraft Company.
Devine resigns
ANNE Devine has resigned as finance director of the Glasgow-based specialist
engineering company Clyde Blowers after two years in the post. The company said
she had resigned for personal reasons to pursue a new career and she was
leaving with the board's best wishes. Company secretary and group financial
controller Alex Stewart will take over her responsibilities while a new
permanent finance director is sought.
</TEXT>
