<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland could be `drawn' clear of England</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323265</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OFFICIALLY, Scotland will be one of 12 countries thrown into an all-in draw,
minus four seeds, for the European Championships in England next summer. UEFA
yesterday named the quartet of privileged sides, who will not meet each other
at the group stage, as hosts England, holders Denmark, Spain, and Germany.
Spain and Germany have been given their seedings based on records from
qualifying results for last year's World Cup and the European Championship
qualifying matches. All the rest are to be distributed at the draw in
Birmingham on December 17, which means that in theory Scotland could be put in
the same section as England, and another fine mess that would get UEFA into.
However, the grapevine has it that, somehow, in this draw yet to be made, the
Scots will be kept apart from their near neighbours, as far apart as Newcastle
and London, but until December 17 we will have to wait and see.
England have been placed in Group A, which will be contested in London and
Birmingham, although the hosts will play their games at Wembley, but the other
three seeds will know their venues next month. Group B matches will be played
at Elland Road, Leeds, and St James' Park, Newcastle, Group C teams play at Old
Trafford, Manchester, and Anfield, Liverpool, and Group D sides are based at
Hillsborough, Sheffield, and the City Ground, Nottingham.
UEFA also announced that the Republic of Ireland's qualifying play-off with
Holland at Anfield on December 13 will incorporate the `golden goal' rule. That
means if the two teams are level after 90 minutes, 30 minutes extra time will
be played, with the tie being settled by the first goal scored. A penalty
shoot-out will be used if the teams fail to score during extra time.
.
</TEXT>
