<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brolin at last signs for Leeds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323266</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEEDS manager Howard Wilkinson finally got his man yesterday when Swedish World
Cup star Tomas Brolin signed from Parma for a reported club record fee of #4.5m.
The capture of 25-year-old Brolin ended 10 days of ``will he or won't he''
speculation and months of searching for a top class partner for Ghanaian
striker Tony Yeboah.
Brolin appeared alongside Wilkinson at an Elland Road news conference yesterday
and could make his debut in today's home match against Chelsea.
Wilkinson, who would not discuss Brolin's fee, revealed that the main hurdle in
the signing had been an agreement that the player could leave at the end of
this season.
``Agreement took place four or five days ago,'' said Wilkinson. ``There was
only one sticking point. Tomas wanted an option where if he couldn't deal with
the country he wanted to be able to get out. It's a contract not a prison
sentence.''
</TEXT>
