<HEADLINE>Aggressive Samoans may prove tough to crack Victory essential to mark dawn of a brave new world</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRETORIA on a balmy Sunday in June, when Scotland lost to New Zealand and
exited the World Cup, seems now like a smudgy snapshot from another era.
Today, against Western Samoa at Murrayfield, the action moves back into sharp
focus and a Scottish side containing just eight individuals who wore the
Scotland shirt on that last outing against the All Blacks is charged with the
responsiblity of flying the flag on home territory for the first time since the
spring and of ending the November blight of the past two seasons when New
Zealanders and South Africans contrived to spoil the party.
The first point is that the Samoans may have been World Cup quarter-finalists,
but if Scotland cannot beat the Pacific islanders at Murrayfield - and the
weather is a chilly ally - then the brave, new world of professionalism, even
though the Scottish contracts are not yet signed, will have a hollow ring.
But it will not necessarily be easy. Scotland are without Gavin Hastings, Craig
Joiner, Scott Hastings, Iain Morrison, Eric Peters, Peter Wright, and Kenny
Milne.
Yesterday, the Scottish High Command in the shape of coaching director Jim
Telfer, coaches Richie Dixon and David Johnston and the new captain Rob
Wainwright, were stressing that, even with a much changed line-up, the aim is
to present a continuation of the style of play which took Scotland successfully
through the Five Nations' tournament and, up to a point with success, through
the World Cup campaign.
Telfer noted that, against the Tongans during the World Cup, Scotland had been
faced with the same kind of South Seas aggressive defence and the ability to
conjure something from nothing which will be on show from the Samoans.
The Samoans, though, are better than Tonga whom Scotland disposed of 41-5 in a
bruising encounter in Pretoria. They play hard, intelligent rugby as befits a
side of which the core is schooled in the New Zealand provincial system. They
beat Scotland in Apia two years ago but were defeated by the Scots at
Murrayfield during the 1991 World Cup quarter-final.
On this trip they have lost to North and Midlands but have defeated Edinburgh,
and more significantly, Scotland A. That performance against the Scottish
shadow side indicated what the Samoans are capable of, but the tactical manner
in which North and Midlands disposed of the Samoan second-string was even more
noteworthy from a Scottish viewpoint in that it points the way for Scotland
today.
Yesterday, Wainwright said his side would learn from the general framework of
the North and Midlands victory, basically ensuring that the work was done
properly in first and, just as importantly, second and subsequent phases with
the opposition well tied in before setting the backs off on sallies for the
line.
With Graham Shiel and the mercurial Gregor Townsend in the centre and finishers
like Kenny Logan and Michael Dods (who will be front-line goal-kicker) out
wide, and cap debutant Rowen Shepherd behind, the capacity is there for
devastating attack. Bryan Redpath and Craig Chalmers will not want to waste the
attacking potential outside them.
But with no Ian Jardine or Scott Hastings to provide the defensive power in
midfield should Scotland struggle for possession, as did Scotland A at
Mansfield, then the centre combination who have never played together at this
level before and the back-row cavalry will have to be at their defensive best.
The devastating angles of attack employed by the Samoans are so much more
profitable than those witnessed on the Scottish club scene each weekend and in
this regard, at least, Scotland can look and learn, but hopefully not today.
Backs' coach Johnston indicated yesterday that the Scots will, indeed, be
offensively inclined when he was asked whether the comparative defensive
frailty in midfield - compared that is to the heavy-hitting Samoan attack and
the proven defensive record of Ian Jardine and the non-available Scott Hastings
- caused him to be overly concerned.
``If we picked the best defenders at our disposal then I don't think that we
would win. What we are looking for is balance,'' he declared.
This is a crucially important tour for the Western Samoans. They have lost half
a dozen of their World Cup squad to rugby league and have been frozen out of
the Southern Hemisphere's International Provincial Competition by their
fair-weather friends in New Zealand, Australia, and South Africa.
Their coach, the former All Black wing Bryan Williams, said when they arrived
that it was essential they did well so that they could maintain their
hard-earned status as one of the world's top eight sides.
With three new caps in Shepherd, Stuart Reid, and Jim Hay, a new captain in Rob
Wainwright and seven fresh faces from Scotland's last outing in South Africa,
today's match represents something akin to the start of a new era. But that old
imperative of a convincing victory remains top of the agenda.
Scotland - R J S Shepherd (Melrose); M Dods, G P J Townsend (Northampton), A G
Shiel (Melrose), K M Logan (Stirling County); C M Chalmers, B W Redpath (both
Melrose); D I W Hilton (Bath), J A Hay (Hawick), A P Burnell (London Scottish),
G W Weir (Melrose), D F Cronin (Bourges), R I Wainwright (West Hartlepool), S J
Reid (Boroughmuir), I R Smith (Gloucester).
Replacements - H R Gilmour (Heriot's FP), I C Jardine (Stirling County), G
Armstrong (Jed-Forest), S J Campbell (Dundee HS FP), J J Manson (Stirling
County), S J Brotherstone (Melrose).
Western Samoa - V Patu; B Lima, T Vaega, G Leaupepe, A Tela; D Kellet, J
Filemu; M Mika, T Leiasamaivo, P Fatialofa, L Falaniko, P Leavasa, S Kaleta, P
Lam, S Vaifale.
Replacements - M Vaea, C Burnes, S Leaega, S Smith, G Latu, B Reidy.
Referee - T Henning (South Africa)
q KICK-off 2.30. Tickets on sale at Murrayfield booths from 10am. There will
also be a limited number of turnstiles for cash entry.
</TEXT>
