<HEADLINE>Consultancy Earthward has a deep-rooted concern for the land Cultivating a caring approach to the earth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRAILBLAZERS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EARTH, the dictionary says, is ``our planet, home''. Ward is linked to
``guardianship, a sense of care, and also a direction''. These definitions
express precisely the philosophical soil in which Earthward is rooted. It is an
ecological consultancy with environmental purpose. And it is a flourishing
example of how this type of land husbandry can prosper in fertile soil - in
this case in the Borders.
Graham Bell, Earthward's director, is blazing a radical new trail in his
approach to agriculture and the environment, a trail which he believes offers
the only long-term method for managing of the earth's resources. This, he says,
is permaculture.
It is, he explains, a way of designing and creating sustainable environments
and systems. These apply everywhere - from farms and gardens to economic
systems, from community development to energy efficient construction.
The Earthward consultancy was established 18 months ago at Tweed Horizons
Centre for Sustainable Technology at Newtown St Boswells in the Borders, and
here, on the 25-acre site, Bell is practising what he preaches.
There are, he says, 3000 edible plants in the UK, yet only a fraction of them
are cultivated for culinary use. Scotland has vast areas of what could be
described as wet upland desert, yet these impoverished acres could easily be
productive.
Earthward is taking fresh stock of how we look at the environment. Any part of
it can be seen either as a liability or as an asset. Animal waste, for example,
can be a pollutant, or it can increase the soil's fertility; the impoverished
hills and bogs of Scotland can be transformed into productive agro-forests
where the trees improve the soil as well as providing a marketable product.
Bell's vision is of a Scotland regenerated by myriad small, self-sustaining
communities whose inhabitants, like those of Denmark's villages, combine
agricultural as well as industrial functions. And at Earthward, his mission is
to prove it is attainable.
When he took over the grounds at Tweed Horizons they were neglected and
unproductive. Already there has been a transformation. This has been achieved
neither by spending large sums on diggers and other machinery, nor by employing
armies of gardeners.
By covering the ground with biodegradable waste material, and then with a thick
layer of manure, Bell has got the earthworm to do the work for him. The worms
have created a new water-retentive fertile soil structure. And in this
regenerated land Earthward grows a vast range of trial crops.
For, having shown how to re-create productive soil, his next mission is to
prove how many plants, until now considered unsuitable, can be viable and of
economic value. In his mulched beds he is trying out all kinds of fruits and
vegetables, from the almost forgotten Elizabethan medlars, to new and unusual
combinations of grafted fruits and berries - Arctic raspberries, jostaberries,
thornless blackberries and so on - perennial herbs, different kinds of walnuts,
apples, pears and dozens of vegetables.
Finally, he is establishing an agro-forest on a five-acre field. This he hopes
will improve soil fertility as well as provide valuable shelter. Not every
trial plot succeeds. But many do, and valuable lessons are learned from every
experiment.
These trial beds and woodlands are practical demonstrations, scientifically
monitored, of the permaculture philosophy, and Earthward is now able to exploit
them commercially. Bell runs demonstration courses and acts as consultant to
all kinds of organisations which are interested in rural, self-sustaining
regeneration as well as to individuals in need of advice.
He runs training courses in specific skills, such as apple tree grafting, and
students come from Robert Gordon University in Aberdeen and the Borders College
to learn the value of the permaculture approach. Earthward is also establishing
links with agricultural colleges in Europe.
In this way, his trailblazing ideas on the benefits of rural regeneration are
already spreading far beyond the Scottish Border. And his solid confidence in
the global significance of permaculture looks like ensuring Earthward will go
from strength to strength.
The award and entry
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon below.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner will be presented with an award certificate and will be
featured in an article. The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company
specialist on an agreed specialist management training course at the renowned
Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
