<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>High-flier is not guilty party</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
High-flier is
not guilty party
THE organisational abilities of ScottishPower's publicity services executive
Rachel Sherrard have impressed many since she joined the company earlier this
year. Not only has she coped with a demanding work schedule but she has also
found time to complete an MBA at Strathclyde University. in addition, our
high-flying publicity executive is just seven hours and a written test away
from gaining her pilot's licence.
As if that were not enough, it seems she also pursues a career as a part-time
model. She is, for example, the ``mystery'' professional who appears in posters
and leaflets advertising ScotRail's new Executive Ticket service.
Business Diary readers may recall a little tale we recounted some weeks ago
about ScottishPower's jumbo public relations executive Gordon Laidlaw, who on a
flight between Belfast and Glasgow was requested to shift his then 18st ballast
to aid take off.
We always keep our sources confidential but it appears some people believe
Sherrard, who was Laidlaw's travelling companion at the time, was the guilty
party, which may explain why I received a note during the week about the travel
arrangements she made for friends from all over the UK to join her at a
ScottishPower ceilidh in Glasgow. They arrived early - by a full week! I am
also told many travelled by ScotRail.
Revenge is sweet. Trouble is, I could have sworn it was a male voice who
recounted the Belfast-to-Glasgow weight problem story to me.
A wife's work
is never done
THE cliche that behind every successful man there is a woman may be true, at
least as far as BDO Stoy Hayward is concerned. When it held its annual UK
partners' conference in Brussels last week around 150 partners and their wives
attended, among them eight from Scotland.
The wives joined the partners on a session about the firm's strategy, acting as
expert advisers to the growing business. In addition, the women had a two-hour
session on their own to discuss how BDO should be marketed.
Ian Valentine, the firm's Ayr-based Scottish managing partner, told Business
Diary: ``It was certainly different but all the indications are that they
enjoyed it. Our wives are a very important part of the business - they can help
create the right impression about the company and help with the marketing
effort.''
Painful case
for the defence
IT certainly was not MacRoberts' night when the law firm took part in a
five-a-side football tournament at The Pitz in Townhead, Glasgow, in aid of the
Beatson Institute. The team lost every game, and goalkeeper Craig Turnbull was
so determined to keep the opposition from going into double figures that he
dislocated his shoulder making what colleague Allan Taylor described as a
``brave save''.
The Old Boys Network team belied their name and won the 10-team tournament
beating John Watson, the printing firm, 6-2 in the final. Motherwell star Chris
McHart presented the prizes, and our readers will be glad to know Turnbull is
back at work. He was last heard muttering something about the defence needing
to be tightened up.
Sixties soiree
to help hospice
A GROUP of French tourists admiring the shops in the Buchanan Street precinct
in Glasgow during the week were rather taken aback when confronted by TV travel
man Bryan Burnett dressed as one of their countrymen.
Kitted out in French-style gear and Hercule Poirot moustache, he was
publicising a sixties soiree being held in aid of the Prince &amp; Princess of
Wales Hospice at the Glasgow Moat House Hotel on December 8. The hospice
recently launched an appeal to raise #1.4m to boost its day and home care
provision.
For more details of the soiree, contact Julie Hanson on 0141 429 5599. Palace
sources have assured me that the Princess of Wales will not be trying to sell
the #25 tickets when she appears on Panorama on Monday evening.
Women get into
the network
TWO hundred women turned up for the launch of Lanarkshire Development Agency's
Women into the Network programme, and 100 signed up for the first series of
women-only seminars at the Scottish Enterprise Technology Park in East Kilbride.
The programme was drawn up after the Scottish Enterprise Foundation at Stirling
University carried out a survey to assess women's views of what they needed to
help them into business and what they saw as missing from existing business
start-up programmes. Among the subjects they asked to be included were
assertiveness and motivation.
If you would like more information on Women into the Network, give Lynn
Wilkinson of the LDA a call on 01698 745454.
Argument over
strong words
PR and former Glasgow Lord Provost Michael Kelly has reappeared on the
political scene although this time with a small p. He has been appointed
secretary of the Scottish Industry Forum, a grouping of business people who
support Labour.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson addressed the meeting in the Glasgow
Trades House at which Kelly took up his new duties, and tackled the question of
Labour's plans for a Scottish parliament.
Some wags at the meeting spotted that Roberston was speaking under the Trades
House crest which carries the motto ``Unity is Strength'', and were heard to
suggest that this was rather ironic. However, as any ``old'' Labour supporter
would have told them, this phrase was also a popular slogan of the Labour
movement. In any event, Robertson would argue that by devolving power to
Scotland, the House of Commons would indeed be strengthening the Union.
Worried on a
different score
THE reason I am told that Malcolm McPherson, managing partner of Henderson Boyd
Jackson, is not looking too happy in this photograph is to do not with the
words Sioux Me painted above his head but with the fact that he had just been
told the latest Hibernian score. I'm not exactly certain for which game but his
expression fits what most Hibee fans must have looked like after being beaten
2-0 by Falkirk.
McPherson was visiting the American Passion exhibition his firm is helping to
sponsor and which is currently showing at the Royal College of Art in London.
</TEXT>
