<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Knocking the stuffing out of Eddie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be wrong to compare the career of our own Prince of Wales with the
brief, blighted reign of Edward VIII. Wrong, petty, insensitive, even cruel -
but fun. After all, a family that has prospered so thoroughly from the
fascistic notion of ``breeding'' surely deserves to have its funny little
genetic affinities (not to mention its flirtations with fascism) held up to the
light.
The pity is that the Secret Lives evisceration of the reputation of the Duke of
Windsor (Channel 4, Thursday) was overshadowed by news of Panorama's
participation in Diana's divorce negotiations (``Another ten mil or I really
spill the beans.''). The story of a self-obsessed, morally frail, sexually
rapacious princeling with many political interests and no political sense was
of more import than anything the Frock might have to say, and certainly more
relevant to the monarchy.
The Traitor King stitched Eddie up a treat, nevertheless. Little of it was as
new as some reports would have had you believe - did anyone really believe
Britain's numerous Nazi sympathisers simply repented in 1939? - but the story
was told in such a cool, merciless style that you had to laugh. All those lies,
all that fantasy, all those deeply silly costumes . . .
In brief, the charge was simply that the duke, a fascist by instinct and by
choice, was prepared to sell out his country to Hitler in exchange for the
throne. Because it suited his own book he bought the preposterous Nazi
proposition that Germany should have the run of Europe while Britain retained
its empire. In the process, he probably gave away state secrets and certainly
failed in his duty, such of it as he was capable of recognising.
So far, so predictable.
The flaw in the piece was its casual use and limited understanding of the word
``establishment''. Never properly identified, this vague entity was said to
have decided from the beginning that Wallis Simpson, far from being a nuisance,
would actually be useful in the unseating of Edward, whose pro-German
sympathies and lack of self-discipline were deemed dangerous to the state.
Thus the editor of the Times, the Archbishop of Canterbury, and the Government
were described as participating in a conspiracy against the King.
Yet the Times, in the thirties, was at least as enthusiastic for fascism as
Edward. The Nazi peace deal he espoused was later put to the war Cabinet and
only rebuffed by Churchill with the support of Attlee's Labour Party -
prominent Tories, some of whom still bewail its rejection, would have accepted
it happily. In other words, ``the establishment'' was never a unity.
Other, smaller details were equally troubling. Pre-Wallis, Edward toured the
colonies bedding squads of district commissioners' wives and, by all accounts,
any other married woman he could lay his hands on. Yet we were also told
(another old story) that Mrs Simpson owed her ability to snare the underendowed
royal to exotic techniques she had picked up in Chinese brothels. At one
moment, in other words, Eddie was a sexual athlete; at the next a sexual
inadequate.
All that said (and we could have done with some comment on the vindictiveness
of the dear old Queen Mum - or are some things still taboo?) this was a damning
essay on Anglo-Saxon attitudes.
It was not Edward who failed but the royal house itself, and by extension a
weird constitutional process that hinges on thick, pompous princes and monarchs
whose only loyalty is to their own survival. Ring any bells? But enough of
sheer nonsense.
Isn't it about time this review put in a word for Due South (BBC1, Tuesday),
the oddly-engaging fable of the Canadian Mountie and the Chicago cop? Certainly
it is, not least in recognition of the fact that the house nine-year-old was
right all along about a show that seemed, at first glance, too wacky for its
own good.
This week's instalment, a ``feature-length'' offering, displayed to advantage a
curious mixture of elements that shouldn't work but somehow does. A comedy
thriller with a solid emotional core, a preposterous hero (Constable Fraser
never tells a lie and always does the Decent Thing) more realistic than the
stock cast of ``realistic cops'', a pet wolf with more brains than Lassie, a
flamboyantly wicked woman, and an Italian-American sidekick who acts as though
he's waiting for the call from Scorsese: how many eggs does a pudding need?
Yet this week Due South attempted a difficult theme - that love is mad, not
blind - while delivering a decent little plot about diamonds and good men
wronged. Well-paced, expertly-shot, and above all strikingly well acted, it put
ITV's The Bill (when will someone summon the nerve to despatch this tired
show?) to shame. It had the courage of its daft convictions, something the
opposition long ago lost.
THE word "lost" also springs to mind when contemplating Rowan Atkinson in The
Thin Blue Line (BBC1, Monday), Ben Elton's lamentable attempt to write a
``classic'' prime-time sit-com. This was Mr Bean Speaks rather than Blackadder
Returns and it was almost partonisingly bad, as though Elton, clever chap that
he is, had decided not to test the audience by offering them anything
resembling a script.
As the commanding officer of a small town police station, Atkinson might have
been expected to play the part with the sort of toughness and sarcasm
appropriate to policemen (and Blackadder). Instead, he preferred to bumble, and
there is nothing, nothing at all, worse in this world than a comic who bumbles.
It becomes like an itch you can't scratch, an irritation that won't pass, an
inducement to scream ``Get on with it!'' at the set.
To be fair, Elton (here sans Richard Curtis, and it showed) gave the star
little to work with. The sight gag and the double entendre have their place,
but comedy does not live by fart jokes alone. Thus Atkinson was reduced to his
funny faces, and if there is one thing the television audience has seen too
much of it is the Atkinson funny face. Still, at least this turkey will give a
hitherto fawning media the chance to realise that Elton isn't as funny as he
thinks we think he is.
Cracking Stories (BBC1, Wednesday) offered a wry, funnyish look behind the
scenes at Edinburgh's Jenners store that became, by extension, a portrait of
the Edinburgh bourgeoisie, their ancient self-regard, their
snobbery-in-mothballs, and their absolute immunity to anything resembling
taste. It was done gently and well, though it overlooked a question: does the
``Harrods of the North'' still subject staff to the humiliation of bag searches
at the end of each working day?
</TEXT>
