<HEADLINE>Minstrel calls the tune</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By TOM McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOB Champion, who rode Aldaniti to success in the 1981 Grand National, made an
emotional return to the winners' enclosure at Aintree yesterday with his first
winner as a trainer at the course.
Pats Minstrel comfortably won the memorial chase from De Jordaan when Clay
County, the odds-on favourite, came to grief at the fourth.
Champion's Pats Minstrel, third three days ago at Wetherby, led from the sixth,
jumped well at Becher's Brook, and left De Jordaan flat footed from the last.
``It has been an ambition - something special to have a winner at Aintree,''
said the trainer.
Kilcolgan, trained in the Borders by Dawn Goodfellow, has his first crack at
the unique Aintree fences today when he lines up in the Becher Chase.
The eight-year-old, successful at Kelso a month ago before finishing fourth to
Emerald Charm two weeks later, is not without a chance in the field of 10.
</TEXT>
