<HEADLINE>Russell finally halted  by storm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRICKET
UMPIRE Cyril Mitchley halted play on day two of the first Test as a spectacular
electrical storm moved ever closer to Centurion Park in Pretoria.
Batsmen Jack Russell and Angus Fraser had been willing to carry on in the murky
light before torrential rain arrived, but Mitchley took the law into his own
hands. As he explained later: ``I've lost two friends to lightning strikes. One
of them was killed on a golf course and the other while playing in a local
league cricket match. I didn't want it to happen again.''
Mitchley had no rule to back him up. But he added: ``I acted under Law 43
(non-existent) - common sense.''
But England were not complaining. ``The umpires were worried, and that's fair
enough,'' commented Russell, whose half-century led the tourists to 381 for
nine.
Ten minutes later, an electrical storm of incredible violence broke over the
ground. Forks of lightning lit up the black sky and the outfield was turned
into a lake almost instantly.
One spectator, armed with an inflatable surf board, skimmed across what had
been grass while others, for reasons best known to themselves, slid for yards
over the plastic covering sheets.
But the upshot was that England had lost two hours' valuable playing time. At
one stage they threatened to waste some of Graeme Hick's superb work, slipping
from 320 for five to 359 for nine, but Russell, in the best batting form of his
life, simply would not let South Africa's bowlers have the last word.
Earlier, Robin Smith's new protective visor, worn following last summer's
facial injury sustained during the Old Trafford Test, was given an early
examination by a wicked Shaun Pollock bouncer. But he had hit one 6 and six 4s
by the time Brian McMillan knocked back his off stump.
Hick's fourth Test century finally ended after lunch on 141 with the
persevering Pollock winning an lbw decision, and Dominic Cork (pulling to
backward square leg), Darren Gough (missing a straight one) and Richard
Illingworth (yorked) followed in quick succession.
McMillan did most of the damage, filling in admirably for Brett Schultz, who
may play no further part in this game because of injury.
Russell, though, would not be shifted - until umpire Mitchley pointed him to
the pavilion for his own safety.
