<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Injuries are a sore subject</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT never rains but it pours for Dunfermline these days, and yesterday another
four players - Brian Rice, Greg Shaw, Norrie McCathie, and Neale Cooper - were
added to the clubs' catalogue of injuries.
Of course, today's opponents, St Johnstone, coming off back-to-back victories,
may be unimpressed by news from East End Park, but Dunfermline manager Bert
Paton was not his usual cheerful self yesterday.
Two Junior players plus a trialist are called into his pool - Stephen Ferguson,
from Rosyth, and John Fraser, from Oakley, as well as 19-year-old Ryan Hegarty,
nephew of Paul. Paton hopes that Finnish internationalist Kari Rissannen will
be available. That may bring a smile to his face.
The big game of the day is the Dundee derby. Jim Duffy's men will wander along
the few hundred yards of Tannadice Street to the opposition's patch.
The only team problem is on the United side, with player-coach Maurice Malpas
facing a fitness test this morning on a groin strain.
Morton manager Allan McGraw is confident that there is life after recent
Rangers signing Derek McInnes, and McGraw could give Craig McPherson the chance
to fill the gap as the Greenock side play hosts to a St Mirren side that is
finally fulfilling the potential claimed by manager Jimmy Bone.
``We are happy the way things are going,'' he said. ``I've always said it would
take time, and now we are beginning to deliver the goods.''
McGraw's big problem is whether or not to alter a defensive midfield set-up
which has lost only one goal - from a penalty - in five games. ``I'll think
about it overnight.''
Bottom club Hamilton must try to gain ground at Firhill against an Airdrie side
who have not been setting the first division heather on fire, while Clydebank
travel to Boghead to try to forget last week's drubbing by Dunfermline.
That defeat may see positional and personnel changes by the Bankies, for whom
striker Ken Eadie should return.
</TEXT>
