<TEXT>
GOLF
FOR a man with money on his mind, the Australian Peter Senior played carefree
golf yesterday in the second round of the Dunlop Phoenix tournament in Japan,
writes Margaret McMaster.
He scorched round in 64, equalling the course record, with six birdies, an
eagle and only one bogey. It gave him a 133 aggregate, nine under par, and left
him two clear of Robert Gamez and three ahead of eight players, including
holder Jumbo Ozaki, Barry Lane, and Tom Watson. ``That's the best I've putted
all year,'' said Senior, who uses a broomhandle job. ``I had only 27 putts and
they were all uphill.''
A bit of a wheeler-dealer in between golf, Senior has a sound business sense.
on Monday a company called Cash Converters, in which the Australian has a
sizeable interest, goes public. Senior was looking forward to being paid a sum
not far short of seven figures in US dollars. Not bad for an initial investment
of around #150,000. Leading scores (Japanese unless stated):
