<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Take this `Man' to strike gold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN COOK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUND Man looks the sound choice for the First National Gold Cup at Ascot this
afternoon.
This race has been won six out of nine times by a horse with a previous run,
which gives him an edge over rivals who nearly all make their seasonal debut.
The Irish raider proved his class with a close second in the Arkle Chase when
Camitrov, Dancing Paddy, and Morceli finished well behind.
The form of that run was confirmed on Thursday, when the winner, Klairon
Davies, scored on his reappearance, and Sound Man can give it another boost
today.
Bas de Laine would have won at Wincanton had that race been over today's trip,
and was unlucky to be caught in the closing strides that day.
He has now turned in two impressive second places since returning from a long
lay-off, and should go one better in the Gardner Merchant Chase.
On past form, Garrison Savannah and Sibton Abbey will need this run, the first
of their seasons, but Run Up The Flag is a danger. He won over course and
distance at this meeting last year and had a creditable prep-run a fortnight
ago.
Young Hustler was well fancied for each of the last two Grand Nationals but
failed to complete on either occasion.
That was hardly his fault, however, as he was brought down last year, while
this year his unfortunate jockey was unseated by a fractional jumping error.
Given better luck, Young Hustler, whose jumping is usually faultless, can
outclass his rivals in Aintree's Becher Chase over the national course.
The ground should be just right for him and he is used to the kind of burden
which he is set to carry here.
Sue Bramall's Veleda can chase him home.
Mister Drum appeals as the value in the Stanley Leisure Hurdle.
After a cosy win in a competitive Cheltenham Handicap last December, the grey
was highly tried without success for the rest of the season.
He should be the better for a promising reappearance behind Silver Groom,
whereas Keep Your Distance runs well when fresh and will not be helped by his
recent run.
</TEXT>
