<DOCID>GH951118-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots who made America dream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Webster</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THAT American aptitude for the felicitous phrase became clear once again the
other evening as a collection of the well-heeled and influential gathered in
the fashionable heart of New York for what that energetic nation calls a Power
Party.
The connotation is one of raising money and spreading the news - and the
beneficiary on this splendid occasion was none other than the image of Scotland
and the part this modest-sized nation played in the early development of a vast
continent.
The story of Scotland and the Americas is such a neglected one that the famous
John Carter Brown Library of Rhode Island decided to do something about it.
It mounted an exhibition, published a book, and arranged a series of gala
receptions and lectures with the intention of giving the Scots, as a distinct
nation, due credit for the quite remarkable role they played in the Atlantic
culture of the period between 1600 and 1800.
In this spirit of goodwill and recognition of a small country, we had come to
the prestigious Forbes Magazine Gallery on Fifth Avenue, itself the home of
treasures which include the priceless Faberge Eggs, and marvelled at the vast
array of books, maps, and prints which have been preserved by the John Carter
Brown Library.
When the exhibition had been sampled through an hour of cocktails, I joined in
a sponsors' dinner (the guests had coughed up no less than $250 per head),
feeling rather moved that the historians of a nation which can sometimes
overlook the rest of the world had bothered to pay this tribute to Scotland.
The fact that the Royal Bank of Scotland now owns a major bank in Rhode Island
would not have discouraged the enterprise - but this was no time for cynicism.
Around me were influential figures of American life whose very presence lent
weight to the occasion. At my elbow, for example, was the fabulously wealthy
Mrs Drue Heinz, who was just one of 57 or more varieties.
On my other side was the charming Anne Cox, whose Scottish family became huge
landowners in America and whose lawyer son is married to Tricia Nixon, daugher
of the former President ``We all spent a wonderful Christmas at the White
House,'' she told me.
John Carter Brown, namesake and great-grandson of the library founder, was also
there and the rest of the company included Scots-born Manhattan lawyer Alan
Bain, president of the American-Scottish Foundation; Mimi Mead, stepdaughter of
the late Lord Malcolm Douglas-Hamilton, once a prominent New York Scot; Peter
Innes, director of British Information Services in New York; and Candy van
Allen, whose late husband, James, was not only a member of the Vanderbilt
family but found a solution to the over-long tennis match by introducing the
tie-break.
The dinner was being hosted by two of the Forbes brothers, Timothy and Bobby.
And all of this, in a strange way, was to symbolise a drift of good fortune
towards the name of Scotland.
The John Carter Brown director and librarian, Norman Fiering, confessed that,
when they started planning the exhibition in 1992, they were unaware of certain
factors which would prove more than helpful to the image of Scotland.
For example, they knew nothing of the forthcoming films, Rob Roy and
Braveheart, which have done so much for Scotland's name in America. And, though
they had planned to stage the exhibition in the Forbes Galleries, they could
not have guessed that the head of that Scottish family enterprise, Stephen
Forbes, would be seeking the Republican nomination for the 1996 Presidential
Election.
For once, it seemed, the fates were conspiring to give Scotland a much-needed
break, in a land where the power of the vast Irish lobby is hard to match.
Fiering and his staff had already arranged a series of gala receptions, at
which American audiences have had a chance to learn about the Scottish
involvement in the colonial period of America. They have been listening, for
example, to distinguished academics on subjects like ``The Cult of the Celt and
the Kilt in Scotland'' and ``The Highland Warrior in American Colonial Wars''.
The Director of the National Galleries of Scotland, Timothy Clifford, is in New
York this week talking about Scottish art. By coincidence, the pipes and drums
of the Black Watch were joining the massed bands of the Household Cavalry in a
musical spectacular at Madison Square Garden, marking the 50th anniversary of
the Second World War coming to an end.
Intertwined in all this, the American-Scottish Foundation was preparing for its
St Andrew's Day reception, at which the guest-of-honour will be Scots author
Roddy Martine.
And, as it happened, it was also staging an inaugural American showing of my
own documentary film about that great Cunarder, the Queen Mary, which gave me
the chance to face an audience full of enthusiasm for the story of Clydeside
and the great ships it once built for the world.
Yet again by coincidence, however, it was another Herald writer, Michael Fry,
who set the ball a-rolling for that celebration of Scotland's role in the
development of America.
As well as writing his column in this newspaper, the Oxford-educated Fry is a
distinguished historian, much admired in the United States. He became involved
in the current project during his time as a visiting scholar at the John Carter
Brown Library, which is based on the campus of Brown University at Rhode Island
and has a long record of collecting primary historical sources about America
before 1825.
It fell to Fry to write the introduction and one of the chapters in the new
book on Scotland and the Americas - and to address that distinguished gathering
at the Forbes Galleries.
So what is this story which stirred a leading academic institution to the point
of a major American exhibition? For a start, as we know well, the Scots had a
reputation as tradesmen and merchants, educators and religious leaders,
political administrators and agricultural immigrants and, most famously in the
mid-eighteenth century, we had a brilliant intellectual elite in Glasgow and
Edinburgh which included those giants of our history, David Hume and Adam Smith.
Every political or religious crisis in Scotland through the seventeenth and
eighteenth centuries sparked off an emigration to America. Scottish settlements
in Nova Scotia and New Jersey are perhaps the best-known communities and the
presence of the Scottish tobacco traders in the region of Chesapeake Bay is
also well documented.
However, the scholars of today are now giving more attention to the
significance of the Scots in places like Georgia and the Carolinas, Florida,
Jamaica, and Barbados. There they could be found as planters, clergymen,
officials, merchants, soldiers, and in many other roles.
At least seven colonial governors were Scottish - Virginia's Spotswood,
Dinwiddie, and Dunmore were most notable - and our race was serving as
foot-soldiers and officers in the French and Indian War as well as on both
sides during the War for Independence.
The Americans are being reminded more and more about the Scottish influence on
their education. On a personality level, Thomas Jefferson was just one of their
famous sons to be educated by a Scottish tutor.
Graduates of our universities were prominent in the early establishment of many
American colleges, including Princeton and the University of Pennsylvania, and
many distinguished American physicians of the time went to Edinburgh for their
training.
With the settlement of Virginia and the need for a college there, it fell to
Aberdeen graduates, headed by James Blair, a clergyman and graduate of
Marischal College, to lead in the formation of what became the highly
prestigious College of William and Mary at Williamsburg.
That debt was widely acknowledged this year when the current principal of
Aberdeen University was accorded an honorary degree, appropriately at a time
when Aberdeen was celebrating the 500th anniversary of its university.
When Michael Fry worked at the John Carter Brown Library in 1993-94, he was
astonished and delighted to find the richness of the library's holdings in that
field of early Scottish-American relations.
He put his audience right on certain matters: ``When Americans think of
Scotland today, they probably think first of colourful traditions, chiefs and
clans, kilts and tartans, dancing and bagpipes, the things they are likely to
see at any Highland Games in the United States.
``These actually form only a small part of our national life, and historically
not a very authentic part: most are the products of Victorian romanticism.
While enjoyable enough, they have unfortunately tended to obscure more serious
aspects of Scottish history and the deeper connection between our small country
and the great continents of the New World.
``To appreciate these, we must step back in time, to the centuries before
anyone thought of inventing synthetic heritages, when America was still being
formed and when Scotland's genuine traditions vigorously flourished.''
Fry recalled that the Scots and Americans spent almost three-quarters of a
century together as members of the British Empire, from the Union of 1707 till
the Revolutionary War.
They had much in common as imperial provinces trying to define their
relationship to the English metropolis. Nevertheless, their experience produced
opposite results.
Though most Scots originally opposed the Union, they became steadily more
attached to it, especially to the economic system in which it placed them. The
Americans, though for long sharing a pride in British expansion, grew away from
the mother country till they decided to sever their connection with it.
``It is in the light of this paradox,'' said Fry, ``that Scottish reaction to
the American Revolution must be judged.''
Most Scots thought the Americans were in the wrong but, in private, our two
leading philosophers, David Hume and Adam Smith, sympathised with their
grievances.
To Hume it was clear that the colonies, since their foundation, had developed
into moral communities, bound to take a course of their own no longer amenable
to control from England. Since it was best to accept this reality, he wrote in
a letter to a friend: ``I am an American in my principles.''
The great Adam Smith was not so forthright but did make his position clear when
the crisis of Anglo-American relations broke just as he was about to bring out
his famous work, The Wealth of Nations, in 1776.
In that, he said the Americans should either be fully integrated into the
British political system with representation in Parliament - in which case the
seat of the Empire might in time be transferred across the Atlantic - or they
should be set free altogether.
No mention of Scottish involvement in the Americas can overlook the Darien
scheme of 1698-1700 when we attempted to establish a colony and trading-base on
the isthmus of Panama.
This was the brainchild of William Paterson from Dumfriesshire, better known as
the intellectual godfather of the Bank of England, who regarded the Darien
scheme as the most important project of his life.
However, it ran into opposition from both England and Spain and illustrated
Scotland's difficulties after the Union of the Crowns in 1603, when she became
increasingly subordinated to her larger neighbour.
The Darien scheme ended in disaster, costing Scots investors the huge sum of
#400,000 and almost bankrupting the country. It also played a large part in
ending Scottish independence, brought about by the Union of Parliaments in 1707.
So the highly significant role of the Scots in the making of America is being
trumpeted across that continent. And one man who is delighted is 59-year-old
Alan Bain, Manhattan corporate lawyer, businessman, and patriotic exile who is
president of the American-Scottish Foundation.
The foundation, created in 1956 by Lord and Lady Malcolm Douglas-Hamilton,
promotes contact between the two countries on a broad base and Bain gives much
of his time to fostering its activities.
``One of my aims,'' he said, ``is to revive the Wallace Award, which fell into
abeyance but used to honour Americans of Scottish descent who had made a
significant contribution to society.
``The Scots are a fair-minded people who integrated well into American society.
I think it is important to raise the Scottish profile in America. After all, it
is not a bad profile to raise, is it?''
</TEXT>
