<HEADLINE>Queen Mother takes her first steps to recovery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen Mother was on her feet yesterday for the first time since undergoing
a hip replacement operation on Thursday.
A Buckingham Palace spokeswoman said: ``We understand that she took a couple of
steps this morning.''
Earlier, the palace said the Queen Mother, 95, would be having a quiet day
following the operation, and not seeing visitors for the time being.
But it was thought she might be able to attempt one or two steps near her bed.
This is normal procedure for hip replacement patients, who need to be mobile as
quickly as possible to avoid complications.
A bulletin released by Buckingham Palace yesterday, said: ``Queen Elizabeth The
Queen Mother had a good night and has been seen by doctors this morning.
``It is hoped that Queen Elizabeth will sit up in bed for a short time and
possibly take a few steps today.
``On doctors' advice the Queen Mother is having another quiet day of rest and
recuperation, and will not be receiving visitors for the time being.''
The hospital has been inundated with flowers and goodwill messages for the
Queen Mother, who is one of the oldest patients ever to have undergone the
operation.
Meanwhile, the BBC yesterday performed a quick about-turn over plans to rush
release Panorama's Princess of Wales interview as a Christmas video.
BBC Worldwide Enterprises managing director, Mr Nicholas Chapman, said no
decision about release had been made - just three hours after a #12.99 video
had been announced by other members of his staff.
Corporation video chiefs had been unable to view the programme - which is under
lock and key amid unprecedented security to prevent leaks. Until they have seen
it, no decision could be taken, Mr Chapman said.
Only eight people, among them director general John Birt, have seen the
interview tape, which is being edited into a one-hour programme by reporter
Martin Bashir. BBC Video staff will see the eagerly awaited interview on Monday
night with everybody else.
Whether or not a video is eventually produced, the BBC stands to make
considerably more than #1m through overseas sales alone. ABC News has paid an
unconfirmed one million dollars, or #642,000, for first screening rights in the
US, and deals have been clinched with more than a dozen other countries.
But the BBC has scotched suggestions that some of the programme proceeds should
go to charity. A BBC Worldwide spokesman said: ``The programme has been
financed by BBC licence payers, and it is only fair they should get the
benefit.''
A Panorama spokeswoman confirmed that no money had been offered to any of the
Princess's charitable causes for the interview. ``We did not pay either the
Princess or charity any money,'' she said.
A spokeswoman for Carlton said all profits after costs of its Prince of Wales
documentary, carried out by Jonathan Dimbleby last year, were given to the
Prince of Wales Charities Trust.
</TEXT>
