<HEADLINE>Stranraer out to kick habit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRAW is a common, and often acceptable, result for a local derby, but the men
in charge of the home sides will not be thinking that way today - least of all
Stranraer manager Alex McAnespie.
He has seen his men draw seven of their 13 league fixtures, a habit which could
scupper their promotion hopes. Stranraer were relegated with Ayr last season
and, of the two, have better prospects of a quick return.
``We did well against Ayr last season,'' said McAnespie, who has stability in
his team. Ayr's Gordon Dalziel, in contrast, is still tearing his hair out as
he tries to build up his playing strength.
Leaders East Fife, surprisingly, have begun to draw their home matches, but for
which they would be even further ahead. Today they are hosts to Stenhousemuir,
and can expect to have to work hard.
Berwick entertain lowly Queen of the South. Home manager Tom Hendrie would have
pencilled this in as a possible three-pointer - until the plague of injuries
which has hit his club, while Clyde's meeting with Stirling Albion at Broadwood
could be the most entertaining match in the second division. Forfar will hope
to keep neighbours, Montrose, still winless after their visit to Links Park.
Ross County have signed Clach's Stuart Golabeck in time for the Highland derby
at Dingwall against Caley Thistle, a fixture that would have been expected to
attract the largest crowd of the 10 games in the third division.
However, that gate may be surpassed by another contest in the basement, that
between leaders, Livingston and Cowdenbeath.
Almondvale Stadium was overflowing last week and another capacity crowd of 4000
is expected for today's official opening against the Fifers.
The 'Shire visit Alloa, Arbroath entertain Brechin in the Angus derby, and
Albion Rovers will be trying not to add to their tally of six red cards so far
when they visit Queen's Park at Hampden.
</TEXT>
