<HEADLINE>Scotrail in scathing attack after signal failure causes massive rush-hour delays Train and track chiefs go to war</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR and IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTRAIL managers are close to breaking point over their inability to run
trains as scheduled because of the Government's drive towards rail
privatisation.
They are furious that Railtrack equipment failures, outwith ScotRail's control,
led to delays of up to three hours for rush-hour passengers on two of
Scotland's main commuter routes - Glasgow-Edinburgh and Edinburgh-Dunblane - on
Thursday.
ScotRail director John Ellis apologised in a letter issued to customers
yesterday for the ``havoc'' caused by power and signalling faults at Polmont,
near Falkirk.
However, senior colleagues in the train operating company expressed outrage
that ScotRail was being pilloried by customers for the delays. They are
questioning whether Railtrack is worth the #175m a year paid for access to
lines.
The ScotRail officials fear its money is not going towards maintaining track
equipment to the levels required to keep the railway system fully operational.
They also suspect Railtrack did not react as quickly as it should to the
breakdowns because ScotRail had paid for services in advance, and expressed
concern over alleged delays in letting controllers know about the faults.
Chains of command have been altered since ScotRail and Railtrack became
separate entities under BR's break-up.
ScotRail is likely to seek compensation for delays to 24 trains during
Thursday's rush hour, on grounds that the service paid for was not supplied.
One source said of its increasingly fraught relationship with Railtrack: ``As
the train operator, we are its customer, in the same way that the passenger on
the platform is ours.
``You would be miffed if driving to work you found the roads were full of
potholes or closed because they had not been gritted.
``But our customers only see `the railways' and are not interested in who is
responsible for delays. Our members took it on the chin from them.''
Ironically, the equipment failures coincided with the Rail Users' Consultative
Committee for Scotland (RUCCS) declaring in its annual report that the split
between ScotRail and Railtrack was diverting money, time, and effort away from
improving services and infrastructure.
Yesterday, the committee called on Railtrack to institute ``the most searching
inquiry'' into what happened on Thursday and claimed passengers were not only
delayed but found it difficult to get information about what was happening.
ScotRail director Mr Ellis said in his letter to passengers that the delays
were caused by a fault in the external power supply to Polmont signalling
centre and the failure of the railway's back-up supply.
One train was held up for 178 minutes, while the Glasgow to Edinburgh train was
175 minutes late, despite Railtrack's ``strenuous endeavours'' to restore the
signalling system.
Mr Ellis said these delays were ``totally unacceptable'' to ScotRail, as they
were to its customers.
Railtrack said a full investigation into the cause of the disruption would
start on Monday, with British Rail being asked to participate as the scope of
the inquiry would include all aspects of how the situation was handled.
Railtrack said it was not known if the signalling power failure at Polmont was
directly related to a ScottishPower supply failure minutes earlier but this
would form an important part of the investigation.
Railtrack Scotland's director, Mr Paul Prescott, who also apologised to
affected travellers, said the power failure occurred at the very worst time of
day adding that, at one point, 10 trains were trapped on the Glasgow-Edinburgh
line.
A Railtrack spokeswoman later rejected suggestions that the infrastructure was
not being properly maintained and said: ``We are doing our very best to keep
Britain's rail network in good shape.''
She added: ``The money that ScotRail pay is pre-agreed and covers what we
agreed it costs to have the railway for that period.
``But it is important to remember that you don't pay for what you don't get -
ie, the variable costs, the actual trains you run. If you don't get the trains,
you don't pay.''
She also dismissed allegations of delays in Railtrack informing ScotRail of the
problems and said such delays were impossible because controllers from
Railtrack and ScotRail sat next to each other in the rail control room in
Glasgow.
Ms Helen Millar, the RUCCS's new chairman, said yesterday that the problems
reinforced the need for a ``compact integrated organisation'' to run Scotland's
railways and the need for investment.
Labour's Shadow Transport Minister Brian Wilson said it was ``absolutely
outrageous'' that delays of this scale were occurring.
He said: ``There appears to have been a complete breakdown of communication,
which is what happens in a fragmented railway.
``The uncertainty of privatisation has created a blight in investment
throughout the railway network and, if Railtrack was sold off, there would
still be no incentive for them to invest.''
</TEXT>
