<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Friend tells court Wardells appeared happy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE last time Mrs Carol Wardell was seen alive by her building society
colleagues was on the doorstep of her house standing with her arms around her
husband, who is now accused of her killing.
Mr Gordon Wardell, 42, of Bonneville Close, Meriden, Warwickshire, denies
murdering the 39-year-old Woolwich mangeress at their home and then faking a
robbery at the branch where she worked in September last year.
Colleague and close friend June O'Connell told Oxford Crown Court she and her
husband last saw Mrs Wardell when they left the couple's home after a small
dinner party on the night before she was allegedly killed.
She said the foursome had spent an enjoyable evening and there was no obvious
friction between the Wardells.
She said: ``We left around 11pm. Carol and Gordon stood together at the front
door with their arms around one another.''
It was not until the Monday morning that Mrs Wardell's body was found in a
lay-by on the A444, two miles from Nuneaton.
Motorists told police they did not stop because they thought the body was a
shop window dummy. Mr Peter Beard told the court he initially thought the same
but after pulling into the lay-by he realised it was a body.
Police and ambulance crews were alerted and leading paramedic Andrew Golds said
rigor mortis had already set in.
A police officer at the scene, Inspector Roger Price, noticed a sling-back
sandal near Mrs Wardell's left foot. When he was later called to the suspected
bank raid, he noticed the matching sandal in the branch and made the connection
between the two scenes.
The prosecution claim Wardell planted the sandal.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
