<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cold comfort for cold callers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I'M always put on my guard the moment the call comes through. They plough their
way through the phone book, these poor cold-callers, and our phone is listed
under my wife's name, not mine. So when they ask me, `is that Mr Ellis?', I
don't try and explain, I just put on my not-very-interested voice, let them
ramble on a bit (it's a miserable job, so I let them feel they've tried) and
then tell them no, I don't want their fitted bathroom, demonstration
kitchenware, or their chance-in-a-lifetime luxury patio extension.
Most are happy to take no for an answer, though you do get the odd plucky one
who, either in novice enthusiasm or old-hand desperation, tries to put up a bit
of a fight. But they know you can always slam down the receiver. Sometimes they
make a feeble attempt at conversation, hoping to lure you into their amazing
world of household improvements and easy-credit terms, such as the one who said
to me after I'd turned her down: ``So you've got all the windows and doors you
need, then?''
And I wished I could have thought of something witty to say. Because my flat
does indeed have just the right number of windows and doors. They fill the
holes in the walls. I'd be lost without them. But sarcasm failed me.
One of these days, I suppose, someone will phone up and offer me something I
actually want. Marketing research will eventually become so sophisticated that
at the very moment a hunger-pang strikes they'll call up and offer me a pizza
fungi. I'll only have to daydream about a new pair of shoes and immediately
that phone will ring. But until that time, the answer must always be no.
Except the other week I was intrigued. Some time previously I'd had someone
call up and ask me a load of questions about holidays. How often did I go, what
countries had I visited, did I go self-catering, was I between the ages of 28
and 45, did I earn more than #13,000, was I still listening?
I answered tersely and thought nothing more of it. But something I'd said in my
half-attentive way must have given them the profile they were looking for,
because 10 days later I got a call telling me I'd won a holiday for two - just
like that!
Now anyone who's grown up watching Esther Rantzen on That's Life! knows that
people don't just call up and give you a holiday for the hell of it. Like
sleight-of-hand magicians, they'll appear to give you a holiday while duping
you into doing something else. You know there'll be a catch. Such as the friend
of mine who was told he'd won a catamaran. Straight up. Strangely they forgot
to mention it was only an inflatable catamaran and he'd have to stump up a #75
postage fee to get it.
So to claim my free holiday all I had to do was turn up with my wife one
afternoon the following week at a rural leisure complex in the Borders and
listen to a two-hour talk.
``We do emphasise that in order to claim your free holiday there is no
obligation to buy any products you might be offered,'' rattled out the voice on
the phone, bringing me glad tidings from her prepared script. ``All we ask is
that you listen to the talk and, if you are impressed, that you tell your
family and friends about it, because we believe that personal recommendation is
the best form of advertising.''
Exactly what these products actually were remained a tad vague, though the
combination of holidays and leisure facilities seemed to suggest timeshares.But
we reckoned as long as we headed down with a steely resolve not to commit
ourselves to anything, we'd come away with our fabulous prize and might even
have a bit of a laugh in the process.
To tempt us further, they said they'd bought 100 lottery tickets and, if one of
them hit the jackpot, all that week's customers would get a share of the
winnings.
So off we went to a little corner of Northumberland called Akeld where there's
a complex of low-built farm cottages in the grounds of an old white manor house.
There was us and five other couples, ordinary-looking folk between those
statistically significant ages of 28 and 45, and each of us was assigned to a
sales rep. I'd rather hoped to get one of the identikit salesmen, all forced
sincerity, desperate jollity and cheap suits, but we were given a perfectly
pleasant, unpushy woman called Louise who had a German accent, a white
bouffant, and a bad back.
This was the deal. Imagine for the next 10 years that you and your family will
spend #400 once a year on a single week's holiday expenses (not including
flights). In a decade you'll have spent #4000. Now imagine instead of doing
that, you sink #4000 straight away into a week of - you guessed it - timeshare
in Akeld.
For the next 80 years you'd have no further holiday accommodation costs bar the
odd maintenance charge. Of course, you'd also be lumbered with having to take
February holidays in the Borders for the rest of your life, so the clever bit -
and here's the incentive - is that timeshare ownership would let you into an
international holiday exchange system, giving you the chance to stay in someone
else's timeshare property almost anywhere in the world for a dirt-cheap rate.
They're not stupid, these people. They know we've all grown wary of hard-sell
techniques. They know we've heard about disastrous deals struck between
unscrupulous operators and dreamy holidaymakers in Spanish beach resorts. They
know we're only here to claim the prize and won't stand for any heavy-handed,
arm-twisting stuff.
And they also know that the deal they're offering isn't all that bad. With a
nice human touch, Louise even revealed she had a timeshare option of her own,
and only this year had been living it up in some exclusive Swiss resort for
hardly more than #50. Their style is to be as reasonable as possible, offer you
an extra discount if you sign up straight away and - in as gentle a way as
possible - make you believe you'd be behaving irrationally (think of the #4000
just thrown away, never to be seen again!) if you didn't whip out your cheque
book immediately.
And the frightening thing about sitting through two hours of this reasonable,
logical, oh-so-sensible sales patter (plus slick video) is that you do find
yourself being persuaded.
Stuck in a room miles from home, surrounded by glossy brochures and people
being pleasant to you, it's easy to forget that when you woke up that morning
the idea of paying for a holiday, timeshare or otherwise, had not crossed your
mind. ``Doesn't it seem stupid to pay for your holiday every year when you
could be saving money with this method?'' asks Louise, and you can only agree
that, come to think of it, yes it does.
And the more you say ``yes'' to this kind of question, the closer you come to
being seduced by the whole package. As far as I can tell, there's nothing
implicitly wrong with the deal - I'm sure there are many who have signed up and
it suits them fine - but in what other circumstance would you commit #4000 on
the strength of a two-hour chat, without even checking out the competition?
What other product would you buy not because you ever thought you wanted it but
because someone phoned you up and all but bribed you to come and see it? Yet
it's dead easy to lose sight of what should be your natural scepticism. Even
the Geordie couple we spoke to on our way out, who quite plainly weren't into
the idea at all, even if they could have afforded the initial outlay, were
still giving the matter their serious attention.
And two things are really significant. The first is that the moment you make
your excuses and wriggle your way back to the outside world, all the smooth
arguments that seemed so persuasive five minutes earlier just vanish. It's
already hard to believe that you almost fell for it.
The second thing, as if to confirm this, is that even after you've promised to
go home and think about it, they give you no paperwork, no fancy brochures, not
even a copy of your original invitation to take away. I expected to be
inundated with pushy phone calls, pleading with me to see sense, but so far -
four months on - there's been nothing. It's as if they know that once you're
out of their clutches you're a lost cause. And you have to wonder why, if it's
such a good offer, you can't buy it without travelling 100 miles and listening
to two hours of guff.
And what of our fabulous free holiday? Well, it could work out, just as long as
we each pay #34 for the privilege of going to a destination of their choice
with as little as a fortnight's notice. Or else we can go for one of five
``exciting leisure options'' to suit our ``lifestyle and personal preference''.
Such excitement includes being given the air tickets but having to pay for the
accommodation, and getting the accommodation but having to pay for the food. I
can hardly contain myself.
And as a salutary note to all those weekly gamblers among us, out of the
#100-worth of Lottery tickets they bought on our behalf, only one produced as
much as a #10 prize.
Mark Fisher has some sympathy for people doing a difficult job, but still
refuses to be taken in
</TEXT>
</DOC>
