<HEADLINE>Dishes for the duke</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LELIA FARRAH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n The Duke of Atholl
BREAKFAST is unvarying and consists of grapefruit juice, eggs and bacon,
coffee, toast, butter and marmalade - with the occasional kipper.
I don't eat between then and lunch which will be something such as liver and
bacon, or rice, spaghetti, or macaroni - I like pasta - followed by biscuits
and French cheeses like Camembert or Bresse Bleu.
I never take tea in the afternoon and my lunch lasts me until dinner which is
at 8.15pm. I will have something like potted shrimp or pate, then grouse or
pheasant, either roast or casseroled, which I might have caught on the estate -
theoretically, I will have done, although not always practically.
Or I'll have fish, or a course with meat from the local butcher, MacDonald and
Campbell. I drink claret or white wine with dinner according to what I am
eating. I never have a pudding as I don't like sweet things, but will sometimes
have a savoury of Scotch Woodcock.
Salads and vegetables I don't much care for - except for parsnips. In London I
eat at White's Club, and in Scotland I eat in the dining room of the private
apartments.
I can't think what my favourite dish might be. That's difficult. I can't
actually do it, although food is a source of pleasure.
The Duke of Atholl was talking to LEILA FARRAH
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000141</DOCNO>
