<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French connection</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRAIGENDARROCH, at the start of its second decade, remains a good reason for
visiting Ballater. Fine autumn weather, setting the Deeside scenery aglow, is
another. On such a day, amid the hills and forests, you could imagine yourself
in the remoter reaches of Alsace - not necessarily more beautiful, but with
food and wine of a consistent excellence difficult to find in Scotland.
It is a link that Craigendarroch's French chef, Eric Faussurier, seems
instinctively to have recognised, and to have underlined in cuisine which is
simultaneously rustic and sophisticated.
Faussurier in fact, hails from St Etienne, which lies south of Alsace, quite
close to Lyon, and his adept Scottish assistant, Paul Moran, is from East
Kilbride.
Between them they have transformed the Oaks Restaurant, as the gourmet portion
of the hotel's multi-sided operation is called, into a place with a resourceful
range of Franco-Scottish ideas.
Earlier this month, in the head chef's temporary absence, the kitchen turned
its hand to Jacobean banquetry, though anyone unexcited by the thought of
partan bree or oatmeal pudding had no need to despair. The absent Faussurier's
modern French menu was also on offer, and for a fixed price of #25 you could
opt for one or the other, or even switch dishes between them.
However, since the Jacobean banquet was conceived as an entity, switching would
have marred its effect. Moreover, since the French menu was riddled with
supplementary charges - #4.50 extra for game terrine, #6.50 extra for medalions
of beef - this was a minefield it seemed sensible to steer clear of. Even by
French standards, mark-ups on 10 dishes out of a total of 18 seemed a record,
and the restaurant has wisely decided to revamp this unendearing policy.
Aside from that, which menu was better? As an autumn offer, and as an
off-season promotion in which Ballater's other hotels and restaurants took
part, the Jacobean package was clearly good value, especially for anyone
addicted to oatmeal. On the other hand, the standard menu's starter portion of
warm avocado and artichoke with pine nuts and breadcrumbs possessed a very
French seductiveness, scoring in terms of colour, texture, and integration of
ingredients.
Not all the differences between the menus, however, were quite so marked. The
baked saddle of Deeside venison, with its parsnips, cherry brandy, cranberries,
and Poire William, was obviously French in its inspiration and elaboration, but
were the simpler collops of venison with their claret sauce recognisably
Jacobean? And in today's kindness-to-calves climate, who would expect the baked
veal and mushroom pie to count as Jacobean rather than French?
In fact, the Auld Alliance in one form or another characterises most of
Craigendarroch's cooking - game terrine appeared on both menus and only the
steamed marmalade pudding seemed indisputably Scottish.
Rejecting this, as I did, in favour of crepes Suzette proved a blunder. Cooked
at the table, these were piled in a chewy heap, reminiscent of pub-lunch
lasagne, with so much garnish (berries, ice-cream) that the dish lost focus.
Garnish, as in many another British restaurants, is a major industry at
Craigendarroch. The bowls of mixed vegetables likewise did little for the
dishes they accompanied.
Most of what the Oaks Restaurant does, however, it does very well, using good
ingredients and treating them with flair, even if some of the combinations
(roast duck, honey, and whisky consomme) look contrived, and some of the names
(``mirages'' of seasonal vegetables, ``sentries'' of scallops and sole)
pretentious. The high-powered, mostly French, wine list contains little of
interest below #20 but some really good things, including a first-class Rully
not much dearer than that.
A second restaurant, the simpler and cheaper Club Room forms one of the added
features - time-share chalets, two swimming-pools, fitness rooms, squash court,
dry-ski slope, children's creche - that have increasingly enveloped the red
stone Victorian mansion that was the hotel's starting point 10 years ago.
In comparison, Glasgow's Town House Hotel, a few steps from Queen Street
Station, seems quite austere, though in calling itself a ``quiet retreat'' it
shares the aims of most country-house hotels.
Lunch one recent Monday was certainly quiet. The building, another redstone
edifice, once housed the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama, but no
longer rings with music and bustle. Now Beethoven's bust at the top of the
stairs frowns into space. The ornate old recital hall, transformed into a
functions area, looks like a haunted ballroom. The so-called Symphonies
Restaurant plays subliminal baroque music from hidden speakers. A soft-footed
waiter discloses a pair of set menus, ranging from #16 to #24 depending on
what, and on how many courses, you order.
The food, cooked by John Shields, is of the same Franco-Scottish sort as
Craigendarroch's. Collops of venison, paupiettes of chicken, parcels of trout
loom large. My stir-fried wood pigeon in its pool of soya sauce, had flavour.
My salmon escalope, reposing on top of three scallops, had not. A small
side-dish held seven different vegetables. The wine list, all this and that,
stays mostly on the right side of #20. The house wine, from Carcassonne,
suffices, the red rather more so than the white.
n Craigendarroch Hotel, Braemar Road, Ballater (call 013397 55858).
Three-course dinner for two at the Oaks Restaurant with a modest bottle of
wine, about #70.
n Town House Hotel, West George Street, Glasgow (call 0141 332 3320).
Three-course lunch or dinner for two at the Symphonies Restaurant with a modest
bottle of wine, about #46.
Conrad Wilson discovers a Gallic renaissance            in Ballater and samples
from a menu served as                 a complement to traditional Scots fare
</TEXT>
</DOC>
