<HEADLINE>Is the garden going to       seed?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.THE next best thing to being in a garden at the height of its spring or
summer perfection may be to see it on screen. A series of videos offers this
possibility.
The list includes Brilliant Gardens (showing eight of Britain's botanic
gardens, Glasgow's and Edinburgh's among them) and Treasure Gardens (eight
great English gardens, ranging from Chatsworth's to Woburn Abbey's). Peeps into
Secret Gardens and More Secret Gardens are also offered, as is the official
souvenir video of the 1995 Chelsea Flower Show. The videos can be acquired at
branches of W.H Smith or via mail order at #12.99 each from Tadpole Lane
Productions, 13 Winnall Valley Road, Winchester, Hampshire, SO23 8LU; tel 01962
841 100.
n.City parks and suburban gardens alike are knee-deep in leaves just now. The
business of brushing them up is a Sisyphean labour, for no sooner are paths
cleared and the detritus bagged, than another lot of leaves fall.
Now this seasonal labour can be made simpler by the use of a self-powered leaf
blower with an optional vacuum collection attachment. As a blower the gadget is
designed to clear out leaves and debris from under bushes and shrubs, street
furniture, and stadium seating as well as clearing grassed and paved areas of
fallen leaves (and litter).
An optional vacuum attachment transforms the blower into a suction unit feeding
a vertically mounted collection bag.
The Allman M88BL leaf blower is priced at #350 plus vat. Local Strathclyde
suppliers are Hamilton Brothers of Bishopton, Renfewshire.
n.Leaves disposed of, it's time to prepare your garden for the winter and to
finish planting the bulbs whose spring flourish will cheer you in a few months.
This year, because of the prolonged hot summer, it's more important than ever
to repair damage to the soil structure, while winter rains bring their own
hazards of ``packing'' soil or washing it away. By adding lots of organic
matter, along with nutrients, you will help to open up the soil structure once
again and boost its fertility.
There is virtually no limit to the amount of humus a soil can take. Steaming
heaps of ordinary manure have their virtues but pleasant handling is not one of
them. An alternative is a 100% natural fertiliser such as Organic Concentrates'
6X. This, claim the manufacturers, is six to eight times richer than ordinary
manure and therefore can be applied in handfuls, rather than barrowloads. The
product has also been heat sterilised, so contains none of the weed seeds that
can cause problems with manure. For details of your nearest stockist or free
home delivery service phone free on 0800 413 065.
n.Once the soil is in tip-top shape what to put in it? Johnsons of Boston (the
Lincolnshire one) are marking their 175th anniversary with their biggest-ever
mail order catalogue. It is packed with more than 900 varieties of flowers and
vegetables, many of which are exclusive or new to Johnsons. The new catalogue
is backed by a daily freephone order line (0800 614323) and a free packaging
and delivery service.
n.Geranium specialists Vernon's have more than 50,000 sq.ft of greenhouse in
which they grow more than 1000 varieties of geranium and almost 200 species of
fuchsia. Among the delectable collection of geraniums, the new PAC Harmony will
bloom almost through the four seasons. Free catalogue from The Vernon Geranium
Nursery, Cuddington Way, Cheam, Sutton SM2 7JB.
Lesley Duncan has suggestions for times when garden chores are too much to bear
</TEXT>
