<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inside the machine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ruling Britannia: The Failure and Future of British Democracy
Andrew Marr
Michael Joseph, #16.99
ANDREW Marr is a native of Dundee, and yet another in the long line of Scots
who have found fame and fortune as a political correspondent in London. And
he's still only 36.
His last book, The Battle for Scotland, was one of many projects born on the
tide of home-rule certainty that preceded the 1992 General Election. This is a
much more substantial work, taking a cool look at our institutions of power and
the nature of British governance.
A sustained note of warning runs through the text. Marr is troubled by the
continuing evisceration of local government. He attributes this partly to the
mass-media - whose obsession with Westminster encourages voters to treat every
local poll as a referendum on the Government, thus inciting our statesmen to
excessive meddling in the town hall - and, too, to a decline of British power
abroad. As Whitehall has lost an empire, so it justifies its existence by
scooping up responsibility from below.
Marr is also troubled by Europe. He sensibly defines ``sovereignty'' as nothing
more than the power of veto, or secession, invested in a member-state's
electorate. However, he thinks this power should be acknowledged by European
institutions.
He wants greater internal democracy in the European Union, and warns of the
dangers of ``mystification'', citing the Maastricht Treaty.
Marr's solution for Europe is what he calls ``minimalist federalism'', with
balance of powers and a two-tier centre - the Council of Ministers, as an open
senate rather than a cosy cuddle between statesmen, and the Strasbourg
Parliament. The right of a member state to leave the Union should be clearly
declared.
He resents quangoes, and certain privatised utilities, and is concerned by the
amount of power now slipping from public scrutiny and elected control. He
dislikes the rising influence of lobbyists in Britain. He says the job of the
Prime Minister, in this day and age, is frankly impossible; and by the time he
has outlined the impossible physical and mental burdens laid upon the Chief
Secretary, and the paucity of the direct staffing and resources at No 10, you
feel new admiration for John Major.
It's a big book, a stimulating book, but not the easiest of reading, despite
Marr's irritating penchant for moments of levity. It is short on colour and big
on involved descriptions of agencies and institutions.
The book is informative in its detail, keen in its analyses, and good reading
for those with an intense interest in constitutional politics. However, Marr
failed to persuade me that structural reform could, at the end of the day, make
any real difference to ordinary lives.
JOHN MACLEOD
</TEXT>
</DOC>
