<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Craig's touch could be vital Samoans will play `rugby league'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HEAR from a spy in the camp that the Western Samoans have hardly practised
scrums or lineouts during their stay in Scotland. Maybe it's just been too damn
wet and cold, but more probably they see themselves as acceptable scrummagers
and lineout workers already. Which is true.
Whatever, it gives a flash of insight into the mentality of one of the world's
most under-rated teams in that they see continuity as the cornerstone of their
game. Western Samoans view glorious passing movements as beautiful in
themselves, but pretty handy, too, when it comes to putting points up on the
board.
So how to go about beating them? What needs to be done? Well, the starting
point for Telfer, Dixon, and Johnston will have been in trying to figure out
what the Samoans do. All this talk about only thinking about our own game is
baloney. You can't design your own style until you know how the opposition is
to play.
And I mean exactly what they do. I phoned Roy Laidlaw up the other day and when
the call was put through to him, he was busy editing bits of video for
examination, and there will have been some in-depth analysis of video-tape to
see just what the Samoans are up to in every different department of play.
For instance, when they arrive at rucks does the first man drive over, or does
he get his hands on the ball and pass it back? How do their mauls work? How far
away are they when they launch their tackles? And how high? What's their
defensive line-up at each phase of play, and what are their attacking ones?
What have they done each time they have received the ball? Honest to goodness,
you'd want to be a chess master nowadays before the SRU gave you a job.
I figure the game will rest on a couple of things today. The first is that, for
one of the few occasions in Scottish rugby history, we will be more at ease
about kicking the ball out of play than they will. There are going to be
occasions when the Scots find themselves under so much pressure that they have
to play for the refuge of the touchlines, and they can probably do so in
relative comfort, but I wonder if Craig Chalmers will be told that gaining
ground with a touch-find is on if he wants to.
So getting the ball in the first place, and stopping theirs at source, is today
- as always, frankly - the main name of the game.
The second is the use the Scots can make of the possession they receive, and
their ability to stop the Samoans in their tracks when the Scots don't have the
ball.
You see, what the Samoans do with the ball in hand that is different, and they
showed it against Scotland A last weekend, is that the man on the ball tries to
beat a man to get over the imaginary gain-line, and then supporting runners
take the ball on, now behind the defenders. It's very rugby league, nosing
through gaps and giving quick passes. It's not so much a test of defensive
alignment, more a question of defensive awareness and tackling ability.
They don't do that much in front of the defence, unlike Five Nations' teams,
and they leave their actions very late. Stopping the Samoans this afternoon
will be fun and games, and I fancy that there is a great, big game of bluff and
double bluff about to be enacted when the Samoans have the ball, because so far
they have run most of the possession that has come their way. Therefore the
Scots will feel entitled to go up flat, and quickly, to stop them making
ground. If you were a Samoan, you would want to question that Scottish
assumption straight away by getting some of your hard-won ball as high over
Rowen Shepherd as possible.
It would certainly make Chalmers and company think twice the next time about
rushing up in defence. Makes you think, doesn't it? And what was that about
Townsend and Shiel having shoulder injuries?
A harem-scarem game later today doesn't do Scotland any good, and they will
need control. A kicking game would, as Jim Aitken used to say, ``bore them to
death.''
The Samoans have won a PR battle so far. The big hits of the Edinburgh game
have been absent ever since. If I were a Samoan, I'd bring the flaming things
right back today to give those little Scots boys a darned good fright.
Which leaves the Scots with the question of what to do when they go into
contact. Run at the individual tacklers - like Big Gav did in 1991? Run away
from the tackle? Run to the shoulder? Run at those rather nice, swinging arms
of the Samoans as they tackle and change direction sharply just before the hit?
Again, bluff and double bluff.
The Samoans expect the Scots to run at them, just like 1991, and like the North
and Midlands on Tuesday. Which affords Chalmers and his merry band the
opportunity of swerving, side-stepping, and chip-kicking to take them by
surprise. Ah, the joys of inventing a game plan.
The easy way to win, of course, is just to score more points. I'm a confused
man.
Good luck to the new caps - it'll be the shortest 80 minutes of your lives,
boys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
