<HEADLINE>A community too tragic for satire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARL MacDOUGALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
T  CORAGHESSAN BOYLE is perhaps best known as author of The Road to Wellville,
a desperate satire on the American obsession with self awareness and
immortality, personified by the inventor of the cornflake.
Here he turns to another America, a society which developed alongside the
cornflake, a community too tragic for satire, whose condition is partly
explained in the epigraph from The Grapes of Wrath by John Steinbeck: ``They
ain't human. A human being wouldn't live like they do. A human being couldn't
stand it to be so dirty and miserable.''
In contemporary California, Boyle finds a society at variance with the state's
popular image of conspicuous wealth. The Great Depression has sunk into a
collective American dreamstate where the misery has been emulsified and
revisionist historians say it wasn't all bad. A generation ago, migrant workers
were championed by writers as diverse as Steinbeck and Woody Guthrie.
Now Boyle shows that the system is intact; migrant workers are still exploited.
His obvious intentions are saved by the fact that he is a great stylist,
capable of wild and imaginative feats of language and diversion, using irony
and humour in a way that suggests nothing is capable of surviving his
coruscating wit.
He implies that California's wealth and collective liberal conscience is
supported by illegal immigration. He underlines this with a more obvious aspect
of Californian life, and even though the symbolism is heavily signalled, it
still manages to convey the friability of West Coast existence. Nothing is
fixed, and for all that one side of Californian life continually sanitises
itself from the other, their common denominator is the fact that the ground can
literally shift beneath them at any minute.
Delaney Mossbacher, a liberal humanist with an unblemished driving record, a
freshly waxed Japanese car and personalised plates, is driving up the canyon
from his home in Arroyo Blanco Estates when he hits an illegal immigrant.
His first thought is for the car, but rather than take Candido Rincon to
hospital, or even report the accident, he responds to the man's request, gives
$20 and leaves him to limp back to his 17-year-old pregnant wife, whose name is
America.
While Mossbacher writes a weekly newspaper column, Wide Open Spaces, on the
joys of rural California from behind the seven foot fence he has built to keep
wildlife and immigrants off his land, Candido and America make do in Topanga
Canyon, struggling each day for casual labour, dreaming of a house in a
friendly neighbourhood and trying to avoid the immigration authorities. Boyle
moves between Mossbacher's antiseptic world, where he buys and sells real
estate and his son fights Space Invaders, and existence on the canyon, where
cheap booze makes Candido's life bearable and his wife comes to detest him for
removing her from her family and friends in pursuit of a dream.
For most of the novel, America's pregnant. Her daughter is born on the earth to
the sound of bombers spilling water over a forest fire and though life is short
the birth is a catalyst, bringing a conclusion that is both natural and
relentless. The land destroys them, leaving Candido with his pride and broken
wife, almost sobbing.
``But men didn't sob, men endured; they worked for three dollars a day.  they
worked till there was no more work left in them.''
CARL MacDOUGALL
</TEXT>
</DOC>
