<HEADLINE>Springboks fired by Catt calls ENGLAND v SOUTH AFRICA</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323305</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND could today discover the full cost of Mike Catt's unfortunate comments
regarding World Cup-winning captain Francois Pienaar.
When fly-half Catt described Pienaar as an average player, he handed South
Africa all the ammunition needed to ensure a thunderous occasion at #60m
new-look Twickenham.
Referring to potential problem areas, coach Kitch Christie commented: ``We have
a new front row which is a slight problem - and in another area we have a very
average player. We are working on him, but we haven't got that right yet!''
Looking at Pienaar, who was sitting beside him, Christie added: ``He's got a
nickname now. They call him `average'!''
South Africa arrive having won 13 games on the spin, although last weekend's
40-21 victory over Italy in Rome was clearly not one of their best.
Regarding today's opposition, Christie said: ``They have strengths and
weaknesses like all sides, but if you asked me to pinpoint one thing that
worries me I'd say the lineouts - they must have the best lineout barricade in
the world. One guy is a skyscraper and we'll need to take out some step-ladders!
``I think they are a good side. They've got rid of their two pit-bulls in Moore
and Richards, so we'll see if the new guys can take their place.''
Andy Robinson has broken the recent pattern of England selection by winning a
recall from a previous rugby age to face South Africa.The Bath flanker wears
the white shirt well over six years after his last appearance.
As important as any of the six Bath players in the line-up is Ben Clarke, who
has been shifted back to his position at No.8 and has won the race to be pack
leader. ``My job is to get the pack in the right frame of mind and then take
the right decisions on the field,'' said Clarke.
q.SALE scrum-half Chris Saverimutto has been handed a key role on his
international debut for Ireland against Fiji at Lansdowne Road today.
The swift-passing, sturdy 24-year-old from Manchester has impressed in training
and his selection suggests Ireland will opt for an expansive game, aiming to
bring in attacking backs like Jonathan Bell, Simon Geoghegan, and Jim Staples.
</TEXT>
