<HEADLINE>Lakes superior</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MACINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WAINWRIGHT: the biography
Hunter Davies
Michael Joseph, #16.99
In common with so many others, I have spent days walking the Lakeland Fells
with one of Wainwright's guides in my backpack, stopping to consult his
hand-drawn maps and reading his directions on vantage points and footpaths.
No one is better equipped than Hunter Davies to write Wainwright's biography.
He lives half the year in the Lake District, and has written several books
about the area and its literary associations, and his narrative style is as
down-to-earth as Wainwright appeared to be, despite having spent so much time
among the clouds.
Born in Blackburn in 1907, Alfred Wainwright joined the borough council at the
age of 13, and by dint of assiduous study in accountancy became borough
treasurer of Kendal. Living there gave him easy access to the Lake District,
and most weekends he set off by bus to walk the fells. The big man only had to
appear in the doorway of the cafe in Keswick for the waitress to shout: ``one
plaice and chips!'' It sounds like a bachelor existence, but Wainwright had
married Ruth Holden, a cotton weaver, in 1931. She had to have his lunch on the
table when he came home from the burgh office at 1pm, and instead of keeping
her company in the winter evenings, he re-created the Lakeland of his summer
walks with bottles of ink, a clutch of pencils and infinite patience.
It is claimed that Wainwright's constant absences on the fells caused the
breakdown of his marriage, but Davies shows that the opposite is true: it was
the failure of Wainwright's marriage in the first place that sent him out on to
the fells. His son Peter, born in 1931, accompanied his father in his young
years, but later would experience the neglect and indifference that his mother
had had to endure.
In 1942 the man who disappeared whenever relatives came to call predicted that
``my life's blood will be Wainwright's Guide to the Fells, and will be my
memorial.'' In 1955 he brought out his first book, The Eastern Fells, on a
self-publishing basis, but the first 2000 copies were soon sold.
His seven pictorial guides to the Lakes were really his illuminated books,
though he liked to work in black and white. Pounding off the presses, the
guides kept the Westmorland Gazette in business. Davies estimates that by 1985
the total revenue was more than #2 million, and that did not include the 40
other books he had written by then.
It was only in guide number seven that Wainwright revealed he was married and
thanked ``All Who Have Helped Me'', including ``my wife, for not standing in my
way.'' They separated in 1966, and there were disputes over money. He gave away
most of his earnings to animal causes, principally Animal Rescue in Cumbria.
In 1957 the borough treasurer of Kendal had written a letter to Betty McNally,
demanding 10 shillings for an extended booking of a hall. After his divorce
from Ruth he married Betty and found the happiness that had been denied him for
so many years.
Wainwright was a unique author and illustrator, his work as much a part of
Lakeland as Wordsworth's. He could be rude, withdrawn, intolerant, condemning
the walkers that his books had brought to the fells and hiding from them behind
cairns. His feast was a pancake in a Little Chef, preferably after coming down
from a day on the fells, but he loved Scotland also, and made television
programmes about it as well as the Lakes. Like his guides, you cannot put down
this biography.
LORN MACINTYRE
</TEXT>
