<HEADLINE>Such grand designs on the tartan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mikhail Pietranek has succeeded in giving the world's most memorable cloth a
contemporary look with his palette of subtle colours. Clare Henry profiles a
businessman who is taking his unique style of textiles around the world
WITH a name like Mikhail Pietranek, why would you be promoting tartan around
the world? Pietranek is quick to explain. ``My father was a Polish Russian
tailor who made kilts in Aberdeen. He married a girl called Jean Macdonald
Munro McLean.''
Now 34 and on his fifth job, Pietranek's tartan textiles are taking the United
States by storm.
``Most of my fabric is exported. Films like Braveheart and Highlander have
sparked off a lot of interest. It's the right place at the right time. The
Americans are going wild for my tartan.''
In fact, he only started in interior design by chance, opening his Aberdeen
shop, Ambiance, in 1991. He started his tartan wool fabric business a mere
three years ago when he found it difficult to get the right weight of tartan he
wanted for upholstering purposes.
Since then, he's moved to designing tartans, subtly altering the colourways,
some paler in hue; others richer in tone and changing the scale of the set to
make it more suitable for chairs, sofas or jackets.
At the beginning of October his fabrics appeared at London's prestigious
Decorex trade Fair at Syon Park on classic Whytock &amp; Reid furniture. Whytock &amp;
Reid were established in 1807 and are Scotland's most distinguished interior
designers, and are decorators and furnishers by appointment to the Queen. They
have almost 200 years history.
It's very early days for Pietranek, but already he has given the world's most
memorable fabric a contemporary look with his subtle colour palette and his
fabrics already adorn one Lear Jet and several notable homes, including the
refurbished Haddo House, opened by the Queen and Prince Edward. Who knows what
will be next?
Pietranek admits to being ambitious. ``I always throw myself into my work. I
began as a draughtsman, then worked at Aberdeen airport. I ended up in a
transport firm, importing bits of Piper Alpha. Then I was promoted and moved to
Birmingham. The firm amalgamated, my wife was unhappy down south and we wanted
to move back to Scotland for the sake of the three kids.
``When we got back I did up the interior our new house myself. It was easy. I
had the right skills and background.
``As a child, because of my father's job, our house was always draped in
tartan. As an engineering draughtsman I knew how to construct things. Friends
liked my work. Gradually, I was asked to do more.
``My new job didn't work out, so I considered setting up professionally as an
interior designer. Friends said to go for it! So I did. But the shop I leased
had dry rot. The day I got the keys I thought, My God! What have I done?''
In fact, he'd found a gap in the market. Four years later Pietranek's fabric
range is being handled worldwide by a leader of the fabric trade: Colefax and
Fowler. Selling Scotland is big business and Pietranek does it well.
Pietranek began with just four fabrics. With Maclean of Duart, (named after his
mother's family), he merely played around with the colours, to soften them.
That was followed by two based on the ancient Macmillan and Macpherson tartans
which he mixed with Colefax and Fowler flowery chintz in pinks and blues -
which works surprisingly well.
From that it was but a short step to Clan Rotal, Royal Lomond (``Our best
seller''), Highlander and Wallace Rose (``God bless the film industry!'') and a
dark blue/red Drummond of Perth (``I always liked rich colours'') plus a
classic Black Watch enlarged to a scale suitable for jackets, which Pietranek,
six foot four in his socks, wears with style.
``I was determined to bring the furnishing side of tartan into the 21st
century.''
To do this he used a computer, so that via computer aided design (or CAD), he
can fine-tune his palette electronically. Traditionalists will, no doubt, be
horrified at his ``messing about'' with ancient plaids and names, but this
entrepreneur is unperturbed.
``It's a totally Scottish company. All the fabrics are 100% wool, and woven in
the Borders. I can now create my own look. After all, I give them all totally
fictitious titles. Glen Louis is named after my eight-year-old son.''
Originally, Pietranek adapted his tartans to pick up the colours in Colefax and
Fowler's fabrics. Now he draws up his own floral, rather William Morris
designs. However, lengths of 120 metres, be it tartan or patterned, made
supplies difficult.
``In 1994 I took the bull by the horns, made appointments and went to London. I
started at the top with Colefax and Fowler and two well-known interior
designers who often work in New York.
``They loved my tartans and now sell my Baronial Home Collection of fabric,
cushions, throws and bedspreads for me in New York, Chicago, and 11 other
outlets across the States. Prices are around #30 to #45 a metre.''
Last year, with rapid expansion, there came the usual problem of finance. ``I
knew I was onto something big, so I approached all the Grampian and Aberdeen
Enterprise people. No luck. In the end, I just got a small bank loan.'' This
enabled him to diversify into Glen Checks, cotton checks, (woven in Dundee),
then Glen Lomond Rose, a lovely heavy jacquard tapestry weave with an almost
imperceptible rose woven into the check, rather like a shadow. This is his most
expensive cloth and retails at #54 a metre.
Trefoils came next which sell well in France and tartan wallpaper follows on
his list.
``It will be available by the middle of next year,'' he says. ``I'm responding
to the market. Already the demands abroad are extensive.'' And will doubtless
increase after London's Decorex trade fair.
Here the combination of his new Glen Lomond tartans with the age-old elegance
of Whytock &amp; Reid's hand made Dalmeny Lug Chair and their Forsyth sofa covered
in the dramatic, predominantly red and blue Wallace Rose tartan will certainly
wow the clients.
I left Pietranek waiting for Red Star to deliver his lastest tartan so that
Alistair Milne, one of Whytock &amp; Reid's upholsterers, could finish his task.
``It's always last minute if you want to move fast with brand new items,'' said
Pietranek cheerfully. ``I guess I'll be making up the pattern books the night
before!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
