<HEADLINE>Busy weekend can decide Britain's fate WOMEN'S HOCKEY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA and Germany go into their weekend games in the Olympic qualifying
tournament in Cape Town as the only sides with maximum points, and they will
start favourites to be in a similar position come tomorrow night.
Meanwhile, Holland, the European champions, yesterday picked up their first
points. They beat their hosts South Africa 3-2, with their goals coming from
their captain Wietske De Ruiter, Marlies Vossen, and Ellen Kuipers.
China, too, scored their first success, overcoming Canada 1-0, with Ying Lin
scoring their first goal of the tournament in the thirty-sixth minute.
Great Britain had a rest day following their 1-1 draw with Canada on Thursday
but they have two games in the course of the weekend, against Germany and
China, which could give an insight as to their prospects.
They will be looking to take at least two points from these games in order to
give their challenge momentum. Results:
South Africa 2, Holland 3; China 1, Canada 0.
Today's games: Argentina v South Africa; Great Britain v Germany; Korea v
Holland. Tomorrow: China v Great Britain; Canada v Germany.
</TEXT>
