<HEADLINE>This time the orders are to win RALLYING</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN McRae and team-mate Carlos Sainz set out from Chester tomorrow morning in
the Network Q RAC Rally and the major prize that victory will bring, the World
Rally Championship title.
The Scot and the Spaniard, driving identical Subaru Imprezas, start the
four-day, 1445-mile rally equal on points and unimpeded by the team orders in
the previous round in Spain, which saw McRae win on stage times but pressured
into incurring a time penalty to allow local hero Sainz to take victory.
``Carlos may be my team-mate, but it's a straight head-to-head fight for the
title,'' said McRae. ``He will be as determined as I am to win, but that
doesn't worry me. This is my event, on home soil, in front of a home crowd. I
won it last year and can do so again.''
On recent form, Andrew Cowan's Mitsubishi Lancer team could well win the RAC
Rally and the manufacturers' world championship.
The rally, which tackles Northumberland's Kielder Forest on Monday, finishes
back in Chester on Wednesday afternoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
