<HEADLINE>Making the best of both worlds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Frances Campbell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sign outside the disused church in Glasgow's Church Street is intriguing:
``World's End,'' it announces in letters around the top of a globe. ``One day
all antique stores will be like this . . .'' Underneath it adds: ``TV and film
props for sale and hire''.
I'm drawn inside the portals, up a carved staircase and through a narrow door
that looks down on a U-shaped balcony.
There's something about a balcony - perhaps it's our descent from tree-dwellers
that gives such a thrill at rediscovering the height and perspective.
This balcony is furnished like no other: 1950s lamps and tables line the
seating tiers, a 10ft papier-mache cactus sprouts from the floor, and a giant
CD-playing Cola can sends music round the vaulted ceiling. Rony Bridges, who
runs World's End, certainly knows how to achieve a theatrical effect.
Yet there was a time when he sold traditional antiques. ``Jeelly pans and
grandfather clocks - I was bored witless,'' he says. ``Anyway, the bottom's
fallen out of the antiques market. You can't get the stuff. People are too
aware.''
And what's made them aware? ``Television programmes like Going for a Song,
Lovejoy, Antiques Roadshow . . . '' Bridges gives a shrug. ``There are more
people at auctions bidding against dealers. And if someone calls you to view a
piece, they expect to make a fortune from it. If you don't offer what they
want, they get scared and say `we'll just hang on to it'.
``I'm sick of hearing people in the trade saying business is awful. But they
won't move because it's safe - what they sell has a recognised value at
auction. This is dangerous: you have to create an environment where people can
see an object's potential. That's why it says on the sign, `One day all antique
shops will be like this'. I can buy something for 50p at auction and sell it
here for #15.''
That may sound like robbery but, in fact, it's marketing. Ultimately, Bridges
aims to find bigger premises and charge an entrance fee. It's easy to see why.
Already browsers call to each other across the tiers:
``Hey, check this!''
``Wow!''
``Do you think it's too much for the living-room?''
``Could be.''
For me, a child of the fifties, it's like a Museum of My Youth. The
pastel-coloured uplighter lamps evoke the very quality of light. The great
glass ornaments - fish and cockerels - are giant versions of the birthday gifts
I gave my mother. Every few feet I pause, caught up in strands of memory. For a
child, that era was visually rich - every surface textured, coloured, or
embossed. But could I bear to live with such over-decoration now?
Bridges tells of one customer, the comedian Bruce Morton, who bought a cocktail
bar with matching stools. ``It was covered in tiger skin. He had to have it. It
was so awful it was great.''
What then are the hallmarks of the fifties, sixties, and seventies gear Bridges
sells? ``The main thing is it was very trendy in a given period . . . maybe
only for a couple of months. The furniture then was the same as the clothes.
Everything was very transitional. But most of the stuff here was expensive
enough in its time. People may remember the style of a table or a lamp, but
probably not in their mum's house. Chances are they saw it in the shops. ``Even
so, this is not the kind of stuff you pass on to your grandchildren. Folk throw
it out. They smash it up and sneak it out so the neighbours won't see. It's as
hard to get as Chippendale.''
I ask if we really had such bad taste then. Bridges answers with a parable:
``See that standing lamp - the orange cylinder? That was in Rab C Nesbitt in
Mary-doll's house. But it was part of the set on NB, the arts programme, too.''
The artefacts have appeared in productions such as Hamish MacBeth and Shallow
Grave. And he constructs props, too. ``My background is in design. I wanted to
go to art school when I was young, but my parents said: `No, you'll look for a
job.' So I started making things - wacky mirrors and the like.
``People saw them in hairdressers and asked me to do stuff for them. I did the
Trading Post restaurants, Ichi-Ni-San, and upstairs in Nico's in Sauchiehall
Street. But it's almost impossible to be a designer in Glasgow. It's like
everything else. You have to go to London to make it.''
During July, Bridges went to Millport instead. ``These guys there were worried
about the number of businesses closing down, and decided they had to attract
people to the island. They came up with the idea of holding a Country and
Western Festival, then went to the BBC for props, and the BBC put them on to
me.''
Bridges spent every spare moment building false shop-fronts for the event which
was held in August. A local pub became the Tombstone Saloon complete with the
sign of a noose. The newsagent's became the Nashville Gazette. ``The enthusiasm
of the people carried me along,'' says Rony. ``But you do get the odd one.
Sometimes I'm was a ladder hammering and I heard this ``Tut-tut'' behind me and
I felt like turning round and saying: ``Look, do you want to be able to buy a
pint of milk on this island?''
But you can't please everyone.
Down in the body of the kirk, the sedate business of selling pine goes on. How
does the pine seller like his neighbour? ``Oh, he thinks I bring life to the
place,'' says Rony. ``Because it's a church people used to whisper - `How much
is a chest of drawers?' Now I have the Stones playing and he picks up custom
from people who come in to see me.''
According to Rony the minister of the church was the original for Rikki
Fulton's Reverend Jolly. ``He still comes in and asks where his pulpit has
gone. He's none too pleased when he hears it's in a restaurant in Italy.''
Frances Campbell climbs a carved staircase
to find herself in a theatrical wonderland of
the strange and absurd
</TEXT>
