<HEADLINE>Expensive pension lesson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by R E Dundas, Christopher Sims ,Angus Gawn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q In 1993 I decided to top up my pension contributions and on the
recommendation of a friend (I am a schoolteacher) saw a representative from
Laurentian Life. He advised me to take out a policy with contributions of #25
per month. Six months ago Laurentian merged with Lincoln. In the meantime I
discovered it would have been possible for me to increase my contributions to
my main policy by taking out AVCs.
This was not explained to me by the Laurentian representative and in a
subsequent questionnaire which Lincoln sent out I stated this. Lincoln says
that this is not an area it is looking at since I did not give up my teachers'
pension scheme.
I stopped making monthly payments three months ago and Lincoln has now sent a
transfer form. The amount seems incredibly low considering my #25 per month
premiums for more than two years. Should I agree to this settlement?
n This is the sort of thing which has given the pensions industry a bad name.
The transfer value is so low because the costs of setting up the policy,
including commission paid to the salesman, were taken at the start of the
contract. So most of your premiums have gone towards this. Only from this year
has the industry had to spell out exactly what the costs are as a matter of
course.
Your only options are to take the transfer amount and put it into an AVC or to
leave the policy paid up. The amount is so small you may as well take the
transfer value. The Scottish teachers' superannuation scheme has an AVC with
Prudential and, with hindsight, this would have been the best option for you.
q I need to be clear on the inheritance tax position on assets passing between
husband and wife before I finalise details of a term assurance policy being
taken on my own life. Can you confirm that on first death there is no
inheritance tax payable on the estate passing to the remaining spouse?
It has been suggested to me that the new policy should be written in trust for
my wife but I cannot see the benefit in this if no tax is payable.
n Transfers between spouses either during lifetime or on death are exempt from
inheritance tax. This applies whether the assets are left direct or in trust.
Life policies written in trust are commonly used in inheritance tax planning
for beneficiaries other than a spouse where the proceeds of a policy can be
omitted from the rest of the estate.
There is no inheritance tax benefit in writing the term policy in trust for
your wife, but there can be a cash flow advantage as it is likely that the
proceeds of the policy will be paid to her quicker. In the case of a policy
written in trust it is not necessary to await confirmation of your estate
before obtaining payment of the proceeds. This will be made on production of
the death certificate.
q I read earlier in the year that moves were afoot to allow the trading of
British investment trust shares on the US stock market. If such a move does
come about what type of investment trust is likely to benefit from it?
I hold a mixture of three UK income trusts and three international income
trusts with a view to boosting my retirement funds in some 15 years time and
would like to hear your opinion before investing further.
n A US listing is only practical for the larger trusts and is likely to appeal
only to those trusts investing internationally. Greater exposure to US
investors may possibly increase demand for the shares concerned, but as far as
you are concerned an American listing has little relevance.
q I am aged 72 and my wife is 62 (both retired) and we are still living in our
family house which is valued at about #150,000. We have no mortgage and no
dependent relatives. My company pension is index-linked and together with our
state pensions amounts to about #20,000 per annum.
We have Norwich Union Asset Management Funds with a current value of #57,000
which have shown an excellent return since we bought them in 1983. We also have
a Provident Mutual Life Managed Fund, worth #46,000, which shows good gains
since we bought the first issue in 1983.
Norwich Union may go public and Provident Mutual is being taken over by General
Accident. We have #4250 in a Halifax 90-day extra account and #2250 in premium
bonds. In view of the pending changes within Norwich Union and Provident
Mutual, should we change our investment portfolio?
n Neither of the two events of itself suggests the need for changes in your
portfolio, but there are other more serious considerations. It seems to us to
be tempting providence to have more than #100,000 tied up in just two products,
however well you make think they have served you.
Given the capital at your disposal you should have a broad spread of
investments, and you would be wise to seek the advice of a good stockbroker to
see how best you could work towards such an objective. You seem well served by
your pensions, and the capital is there to provide the icing on the cake.
q Last year I set up my own business and I understand that in some
circumstances it is not necessary to provide the tax office with a full-scale
set of accounts. If this is the case, can you give me details of the rules for
this concession?
n A simplified system of return of profits for small businesses was first
introduced for the tax year ended April 5, 1990, and it applied where annual
turnover before expenses was less than #10,000. This limit applied up to April
5, 1992, when it was increased to #15,000 for accounts submitted after that
date. The Inland Revenue will accept from such businesses a simple three-line
summary of profits, that is total turnover less total expenses equals net
profit.
This simplified system does not do away with the necessity of maintaining
business records, as the Inspector may require more detailed information in
some cases, and it is important that records of income and expenditure are
available.
There is a helpful leaflet issued by the Revenue, number IR104, which explains
the system and provides information on the type of expenditure allowable and
how to claim allowances for capital items.
q I am 66 and have an annual gross income of approximately #14,500 which
includes state pension of #6268, a small private pension and earnings from
part-time employment. My wife is in full-time pensionable employment and her
income is about #22,000 per annum. She will retire in three-and-a-half years.
I have a pension fund of #45,000 and would now like to benefit from the
tax-free sum of some #11,000. To do this I would require to commit myself to
full pension when this is not actually needed. On the other hand, my part-time
employment could end at any time.
My adviser believes that current interest rates are particularly low and that I
am still a little young to purchase a life-time annuity. He, therefore,
suggests a ``drawdown plan'' which allows for flexibility in drawing pension
from the fund as required.
He has made abundantly clear to me the disadvantages as well as the advantages
of the scheme. He has also advised that the cost will be just under #3000 and
various other charges including 0.03% per month of the fund value will be
incurred.
The dilemma is whether to take the lump sum and full pension now, albeit at low
interest rates, or enter the drawdown plan with its high charges and the risk
of my having to take full pension from it, sooner rather than later.
n Most companies offering personal pension income withdrawal plans specify a
minimum fund size of at least #50,000, indeed many specify #100,000. Your fund
of #34,000 after allowing for the lump sum is really too small for the plan
taking account of charges. Even the full #45,000 is barely viable.
The return from the fund has to be equivalent to the annuity you could buy and
once charges are added it is quite likely the capital would be gradually
eroded. Once the fund falls too far you have to convert to an annuity. How the
fund was performing would be a constant worry. It would be safer in the long
run to buy an annuity from the outset and save the income until you need it.
