<HEADLINE>EU animal welfare proposals condemned as `unworkable'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BOB GEDDES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE has been widespread condemnation throughout South-west Scotland of a
consultation document which is aimed at tightening up regulations on the
transport of animals.
Farmers, auction markets, livestock hauliers and the Road Hauliers' Association
rejected the proposals which were discussed at a well-attended meeting in
Castle Douglas.
The controversial changes are contained in a European Union consultation
document. The deadline for comments is December 15.
It is recommended that the maximum journey time available for animals is eight
hours, followed by a rest period of 24 hours.
This would apply to all livestock transported over a distance greater than 50km
or 31 miles.
The time starts when an animal leaves the farm and includes waiting time at the
market and the journey to its destination.
If this cannot be completed the market would have to provide accommodation,
food and drink for the animals.
Extended times would be available for certain animals and there are options for
markets and hauliers to upgrade to EU standards which could prove costly.
At the meeting at Wallets Marts it was agreed that strong representations
should be made against the implementation of the directive because of its
detrimental effect on farmers and allied industries in rural areas.
Robin Anderson, manager of Wallets Marts at Castle Douglas, said: ``The
directive in its present form is impracticable and unworkable as far as auction
marts are concerned and the institute is sending a delegation to the Ministry
to make this clear.
``Markets would have to provide lairage for the animals for 24 hours if they
could not be transported in time. At our biggest sale we have 18,000 sheep and
you can see just how impracticable it would be. Like many markets our buyers
and sellers come from all over the country and it would just not be possible
for most to get the animals home within the space of the eight hours.''
Robert Hamilton, manager of Harrison &amp; Hetherington at Lockerbie, also said it
would be detrimental to the livestock trade.
``If an animal left the farm at 6am for a sale which started at 10am it could
be several hours before it is sold which would leave little time for it to be
taken to its destination.
``What they are talking about is just not workable and whoever drafted it has
not given any consideration for the commercial implications to what they are
doing'', he said.
John Thomson, a director of Thomson Roddick &amp; Laurie, added: ``There is a
misunderstanding of the welfare side of this and it should be kicked into
touch. It is our livelihood and we are not out to cause ill-heath and cruelty.''
</TEXT>
