<HEADLINE>Primitive release</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Herald's regular team of reviewers listens to
the best of the latest sounds
Loads and Loads More, Happy Mondays (London)
q.Instead of saying ``London'' on its sleeve, this should really be on the
Manchester label, man, shouldn't it? Self-determination and all that. But
that's these smarmy metropolitans for you. Too organised, they are. Us Northern
primitives come up with the art, and all these Cockney barrow-boys fill their
pockets by taking care of the business. Poor old Mondays. They did not sit up
straight at the back and pay attention. That's what gave their hits their
unravelled charm. And that's what sank their Mancunian record label. Remember
them this way, via 16 original singles and seven essential re-mixes. Wrote For
Luck, Step On, Kinky Afro, Loose Fit, Lazyitis: for these we salute you by
spitting vehemently towards London, Mondays.
Made In Heaven, Queen (EMI)
q.Dead Freddie bellows in histrionic fashion from the vale of the undead. His
accomplices apply fresh paint to his gravestone. Queen fans are happy. But then
they always were easily pleased. This posthumous album ends with 22 minutes of
ambient tosh. Elsewhere there are the lines: ``Ba ba ba ba bap bap ba baah/ La
la la la la lah/ You don't fool me/ You don't fool me.'' You have been warned.
Mara, Runrig (Chrysalis)
q.Ochone. Ochone. Tattie scone. A further instalment of yon old-fangled stuff
from the bloke with the sucked-in cheekbones, and the other blokes who've
listened to too many Gentle Giant albums. Place this on your stereogram and you
can engage in much listless and melancholic hand-wringing. Ideal for folk who
don't much like music, but they do like a good listless hand-wring and a
melancholy hokey-cokey. But never mind Mara, gie' us a new album of the laconic
Caledonian funkateering of Michael Marra.
DAVID BELCHER
Prokofiev/Ravel: Piano Concertos, Martha Argerich (Deutsche Grammophon)
q.Collectors' item. It's exactly 30 years since Martha Argerich, then a
24-year-old unknown from Buenos Aires, exploded on to the music scene after
winning the Chopin Competition in Warsaw. Within two years she made her
recording debut on Deutsche Grammophon's famous yellow label with a pair of
concertos that had critics reaching for the word ``definitive''. These -
Prokofiev's Third Piano Concerto and Ravel's G Major - are now re-issued on
DG's splendid ``Originals'' series, where the disc is blacked up to resemble a
mini-vinyl. The recordings, with the Berlin Phil conducted by Claudio Abbado
(who was also making his DG debut) are as stunning today as three decades ago.
Nobody has matched Argerich's sheer fire in the Prokofiev or sparkle in the
Ravel. They were one-offs from a pianist who was to become a rare and elusive
bird. The chance to have them again, in this form, should be snatched.
A Life in Music, Isaac Stern (Sony)
q.Bumper collection of concertos from wee Isaac Stern, whose sound, with its
sweetness (too saccharine for some) and lyrical intensity, is one of the most
genuinely individual and instantly recognisable in the business. Brahms and
Beethoven feature on this double CD set. In the violin concertos by both
composers, Stern is accompanied by the New York Phil with conductors Zubin
Mehta and Daniel Barenboim respectively.
In Brahms's Double Concerto, Stern is joined by his old compadre Leonard Rose
on cello with Eugene Ormandy and the Philadelphia Orchestra, while in
Beethoven's Triple Concerto the full Stern gang - the wee man, cellist Rose and
pianist Eugene Istomin - give a rattlingly extrovert performance that always
made this recording (from 1964) one of the best, and recalls too their old,
classic CBS recordings of Beethoven's Piano Trios. An excellent testament for
Stern fans.
MICHAEL TUMELTY
High Life, Wayne Shorter (Verve)
q.Nine years on from his previous album, Joy Rider, Shorter returns with his
keen ear for melody intact. The characteristically forlorn soprano and more
robust tenor saxophone styles are to the fore in a lushly orchestrated set that
evokes Bolero-ish romanticism, recalls Weather Report's more elegant jazz/rock
passages and, inevitably with producer Marcus Miller's bass aboard, kicks the
occasional ass in a thoroughly agreeable fashion.
Big Girl, Candy Dulfer (BMG)
q.With a little help from her main mentor David Sanborn, in person and
alongside other sampled stars, the Dutch alto saxophonist adds rap, hip-hop,
Latin grooves and soul balladeering to her usual funky rhythm and blues stew.
Capably played and sung, and not without its excitements (take a bow, trumpeter
David Rockefeller), but on balance more the sort of jazz fusion you do aerobics
to than turn cartwheels over.
ROB ADAMS
</TEXT>
