<HEADLINE>Lessons in the garden</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the special schools category, Russell Landscapes Ltd won an award for work
carried out at Blackfriars Primary School for Glasgow Development Agency. The
school itself was involved in the design of the project, which involves themed
landscaping around the school, including a rainforest area, wildlife garden and
adventure playground.
In transforming the site, paths, pond, a grassed area and wildflower meadow
were created and a log pile from felled trees made an ideal place for seating.
The Wildlife Garden project has not only transformed the land at the school,
improving the environment, but it has also provided a valuable educational
facility by creating an outdoor classroom demonstrating the ecology of the land.
The project was run as a Glasgow Works exercise with Glasgow Workers employed
by Russell Landscapes, who selected the candidates at interview and then put a
training programme in place. Gorbals Initiative provided guidance, counselling
support and training for the Glasgow Workers.
The fact that the project has picked up such a prestigious award also
emphasises a key point in Glasgow Works - that long-term unemployed people are
capable of doing a quality job of importance to the city.
Ken Wardrop of the Glasgow Development Agency said: ``Scottish Natural
Heritage, Scottish Enterprise and BALI have all recognised the quality and
importance of the work involved in this project and it reinforces the message,
particularly to employers, that a lengthy period out of work should not
necessarily act as a barrier to an individual getting employment.''
Ian Russell, director of Russell Landscapes, who had 12 Glasgow Workers on two
separate projects, said: ``When these men came on to the project they had been
out of work for more than 12 months and not one of them had experience of the
landscape industry.''
During this period the men worked with the company three days a week and
attended Langside College where they went through a personal development
programme.
The Blackfriars School project was jointly funded by the SRC and GDA, with a
significant amount of private sector sponsorship as well, including #15,000
from the Junior Chamber of Commerce and financial assistance from the European
Social Fund.
The project also picked up a commendation at the Environmental Regeneration
Awards, given annually by Scottish Natural Heritage and Scottish Enterprise.
</TEXT>
