<HEADLINE>Descent into heaven's sinister underworld</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Born Fi' Dead
Laurie Gunst
Payback Press, CanongateBooks Ltd, #9.99
WESLEY picks me up at the airport and guns the car along Hope Road with the sun
slipping behind the Grand Ridge of the Blue Mountains. At Papine the wooden
doors of rumshops are wide open and the boom-boxes send waves of music over the
heads of those trudging up into the foohills. A bus jerks out ahead of us,
bodies hanging from the windows, spilling out the door and we judder to a halt.
Wesley, wary as I've never known him, cusses and touches the snub black gun in
his waistband. He is angry.
``Dawta, why ya come back now, huh? Me no waant to say, but me t'ink dis time
fe Jamaica alone . . . yunno? Jes dis week a white writer get mash-up bad. Dey
bad-bwoys just box'im in him head and kick'im batty. 'Im lucky him not kapoomed
with a bullet, ya know.''
It was a good question and I had no good answer. This was 1980. Jamaica was in
the midst of the undeclared civil war of its bloodiest ever general election,
and here I was coming back. Again.
Journalists from around the world were coralled in the Pegasus Hotel, the
grounds patrolled by armed guards. What was I: foolhardy, stupid? Fear seeped
in with the soft night winds.
There were 891 murders that year in an island of three million souls. Most
stemmed from political warfare. Jamaica's experiment in democratic socialism
under Michael Manley's People's National Party was ending in what Manley called
a hail of bullets and a river of blood. Destabilized by the US, demoralised by
food shortages, the gunmen were in control.
What drew me back again and again to an island of dream-like landscapes and
nightmare visions remains for me still something of a mystery. The fairest
island that eyes have beheld, Columbus said, where the land seems to touch the
sky. The paradox of an island so heart-achingly beautiful and so violently
tormented.
Yet a place where a piratical, rebellious spirit remains alive in a country
with a history which gives it no spiritual right to beauty. It is heaven and
hell.
So I couldn't tell Wesley why I was back. Whatever drew me there worked its
magic too on Laurie Gunst. Except that while she cannot name the mystery she
has penetrated some of its darkest secret corners. An American journalist and
Harvard history scholar, she has written the definitive story of Jamaica's
political gangs, tracing their roots and legacy.
In 1984, after researching the slave trade from West Africa to the Spanish
Caribbean, she went back to the island she had grown to love, this time to
work. She had a post at the University of the West Indies. But her true reason
for being there was to take a journey, brave or foolish, through the Jamaican
posse underworld.
Her story begins in the ghettos of Kingston, a chessboard of war zones with
human pieces. For as long as Jamaicans can remember, politicians have armed and
paid Kingston's gunmen to enforce their rule and power in the slums. Gunst
traces the history of the posses, from the corrupt racketeering of fledgling
politicians in the run-up to independence in 1962 to the drugs-running in the
US that is its legacy. This is the untold story of tribal gunmen who fought for
Manley's PNP and his archrival Edward Seaga's Jamaican Labour Party.
As she sat in rumshops and tenement yards, watching men light glass pipes of
crack instead of the ganja they would have smoked in mellower times, she heard
the first rumours of the outlaw exodus to the US that was the aftermath of that
bloody 1980 election.
The rankings who controlled Kingston, divvied it up for political masters, were
leaving the ghettos for the cities of the US, transforming their island gangs
into mainland drug posses. The money they made from the drug trade snapped the
leash that once bound them to their political patrons who were faced with an
outlaw underworld they could no longer control. So they turned the police loose
to execute their former paladins. The posse men fled to become indispensable to
the Colombians, Cubans and Panamanians who control the cocaine trade and needed
street dealers to sell crack.
Gunst crossed the line of demarcation, the us and them, to become a trusted ear
and voice for the ``sufferers'' - the poorest of Jamaica's dirt poor. The oral
sources come she believes from the same tradition as the griot of West Africa,
the storyteller historians who preserve the legends of a people.
With a meld of scholarly research and sharp journalistic observation she traces
the roots of the gangster culture from slavery, with the street dons and
politicians taking on the mantle of slave overseers and owners, onto the rubbly
streets of Kinsgton now. She follows the posse members to the US, onto the
meanest streets and into the prisons and crack houses where many ended up. She
traces too the roots of the cocaine trade, from its first appearance in the
pockets, up the noses, of JLP gunmen in 1980.
This book is a fine piece of investigative journalism, jettisoning any pretence
at objectivity, distilling dispassion and compassion in equal measure. The
seeds of the bitter harvest sewn by the slave trade, nourished by colonialism,
is reaped now in the blank-eyed crack culture. It holds other lessons too, not
least the terrifying legacy of hopeless deprivation. As the twig is broken, so
the tree is bent.
</TEXT>
