<DOCNO>GH951118-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ready to blow up a storm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ken Gallacher previews what could be one of the hottest nights of the year for
cornet fans
OVER the years I have listened to most of the top trumpet - or cornet players -
in the jazz world and Louis Armstrong apart, and he is always apart, there have
been few who have excited me as much as Warren Vache.
The 44-year-old cornettist from New Jersey will be the Jazz Co-Operative's
second star billing of their season when he appears at the Moir Hall on
November 28 and it's safe to say that those devotees of his playing will not be
disappointed.
Vache seems sometimes to have been born out of his time. He should have been
around for the cutting contests in the thirties because his approach to the
music contains the aggression and competitiveness which were the trademarks of
such swing era players as Roy Eldridge and Charlie Shavers.
Vache may have missed Shavers in person but he knew Eldridge and he learned a
valuable lesson from the man who was dubbed ``Little Jazz''. It happened when
Vache was playing at the later Eddie Condon's Club - the one on 54th Street in
Manhattan, which was next door to the ``second'' Jimmy Ryan's after it had been
forcibly moved from 52nd Street.
A few years back, on one of his visits to Glasgow, we were standing after the
concert while Warren indulged his taste for malt whiskies and Jimmy Reid opined
that the cutting contests of the thirties were something which he had deplored.
Warren disagreed. He had missed the best of these competitions but he still
spoke of how Eldridge had shown him how things used to be.
``I walked out of Condon's one night,'' he recalled, ``and it used to be that
when the band was onstage in Condon's then the band in Ryan's was off.
``We finished earlier in Condon's and so when I came out there was Roy and he
asked me if I could help him out. He said he was kinda juiced and he needed
help from a younger guy and so I got the horn out again, went into Ryan's and
took the stand with him and his group.
``Well, I played first and then, wouldn't you know Roy came in and he played
left-handed and jingled his coins in his pocket with his right hand and he blew
me off that stand. I looked at him and he just kinda laughed.''
``He was old then but he could blow, especially if he thought some young cat
might steal his thunder. I learned from that. It has stayed with me through all
these years...... ''
What that may have done is give Vache that cutting edge to his tone, that love
of taking chances which mark his playing, and that sense of tradition which has
made him one of the greats.
He also had Pee Wee Erwin as a teacher, of course, and that helped him too. He
will enthuse over Armstrong above all others but will add the names of Billy
Butterfield and Bobby Hackett, Jack Sheldon and Don Fagerquist, Clifford Brown
and Blue Mitchell and, also Erwin who taught him so well over a dozen of his
formative years.
He will tell you: ``Pee Wee was one of the most underestimated musicians of all
time. No-one knows how good a trumpeter that man was. He had me playing
classical music too, Charlier Etudes, for instance. One day I was playing one
of these for him and I messed up. He sat there and he played it from memory,
without the music, and he was note perfect. He was special, very special.''
Three weeks after Erwin's death in l981 Vache recorded Buddy Bolden's Blues as
a tribute to his teacher. He resisted all requests for that song after that
time at the North Sea Jazz Festival in Holland because Erwin had meant so much
to him.
Eighteen months ago he recorded it again in a duet with the bass player Michael
Moore. It was as emotional as the first version, played straight from the
heart, and if we're lucky he might do it again on Tuesday week.
The Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Frank Gilroy summed him up neatly when he
wrote recently: ``He soars. He dares. He works without a net.''
That's Warren Vache. Come. Listen. You won't be disappointed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jester steals the show</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975323318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Wise Enough to Play the Fool: A Biography ofDuncan Macrae
Priscilla Barlow
John Donald, Edinburgh, #14.95
YOU might wait years for a theatrical production when absolutely everything
works. When all the sweat, the training, the rehearsals blend together with the
right script at the right time to create a moment of magic.
I experienced it on my first non-panto theatre visit, seeing Duncan Macrae in
Let Wives Tak Tent, the Scots adaptation from Moliere by Robert Kemp.
I had never heard of Macrae or the beautiful young Gudrun Ure who appeared with
him. The lasting image is of Macrae's extravagantly exaggerated bows, the
sweeps of his plumed hat as the curtain calls went on and on.
He had taken London by storm and I went out into the night with a love of the
theatre which has never gone away.
Priscilla Barlow's biography does not go overboard on this kind of euphoria. It
is not smell of the grease paint, roar of the crowd stuff, but a sound academic
record, produced in association with Theatre Studies Publications of Glasgow
University.
Of particular interest is the account of how Macrae happened upon the scene
which he strutted so well, of how he has become part of theatre folklore.
He was born in Maryhill, Glasgow, in 1905, son of a policeman whose father came
from Sutherland crofting stock, christened John Duncan Graham Macrae. He went
to Allan Glen's fee-paying school and then to Glasgow University with the
intention of becoming an engineer, switched to Jordanhill College of Education,
graduating as a teacher in 1927.
He had a passion for the amateur theatre and some would say that, through a
lack of discipline, he never became a true professional.
To his friends he was always John, or Big John. It was not until 1943 when he
was 38 and understudying Alastair Sim's Mr Bolfry in London that he became
known to the public as Duncan Macrae. Sim suggested it had a more theatrical
ring.
There is a nicely balanced account of Macrae, the actor and the man, with
little to separate the two. A larger-than-life personality, he loved the
limelight to the extent he was frequently accused of stealing it from others.
He did not know how to melt into the background, nor did he want to.
A favourite trick was to smell a stage flower as he lurked at the back, knowing
all eyes were on him. Oddly, although he could get plenty of laughter, he was
mystified as to what caused it.
Being on the scene during what Baxter describes as the Camelot years at the
Citizens', between 1948 and 1952, provided a boost to Macrae's career. He rose
to the heights in several great roles, in Jamie the Saxt, Gog and Magog and as
Oliphant in Let Wives Tak Tent. He was wise enough to play the fool, which
always brings in more money, appearing in pantomime, mainly at the Alhambra and
Empire theatres, Glasgow. These were diversions easily kept in perspective.
He died in March, 1967, having suffered a brain tumour while preparing to play
Long John Silver at the Lyceum, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
