<HEADLINE>LANDSCAPE INDUSTRIES HOLD AWARDS CEREMONY Scottish company wins top award</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT the British Association of Landscape Industries (BALI) annual awards
ceremony held last night at the Glasgow Hilton, the winners of the best
landscape work in Britain were announced by Lord Lindsay. More than 300 people
from the landscape industry in the UK and abroad attended the function which
was being held in Glasgow for the second year in succession. The overall Grand
Award was won by Lanrec Contracts Ltd of Motherwell for the Provand's Lordship
Garden on behalf of the Glasgow Development Agency.
Scotland fared particularly well this year, not only winning the Grand Award
but also two Principal Awards and six other awards. There were 12 categories
and 35 awards made, plus a Special Schools Award which was presented to Russell
Landscapes Ltd for its work at the Blackfriars Primary School Wild Life garden.
This was a joint project with the schoolchildren who were given an insight into
how a derelict area could be developed for the benefit of all.
Mr Bill Gillespie, chairman of the adjudicators panel, said: ``The awards are
judged on several criteria including presentation of entry material, standard
of workmanship, quality of material, the variety and complexity of the scheme
and the contractors response to any challenges presented. Principal award
winners in each category all scored very high on all counts.''
However, it was Lanrec who impressed the judges and also the GDA. Alan Sproul
of the Glasgow Development Agency, said: ``It needs to be recognised that
landscape construction is a skilled business and Lanrec's work demonstrates
this admirably. The Provand's Lordship Garden should be viewed within the
context of the Cathedral area and as part of a wider #2m initiative that has
been pursued over the past 10 years as an important element in the economic and
physical revival of the historic heart of Glasgow.
``Blackfriars Primary School Wildlife Garden was the joint work of Russell
Landscapes, Donald Edwards Partnership and the schoolchildren themselves who
have had a major educational opportunity to develop an otherwise derelict area.
In its own way this project is equally important as the Provand's Lordship
Garden although its profile is not as high.
Chairman Bill Gillespie, said: ``The Provand's Lordship Garden is an
outstanding example of landscape construction. Lanrec Contracts has met the
exacting requirements of this scheme and the standards of workmanship are of
the highest order. The School Wildlife Garden was a delightful scheme using
readily available materials and involved all the schoolchildren from start to
finish.''
The BALI National Landscape Awards are made annually by the British Association
of Landscape Industries to encourage and foster a high standard of landscape
contracting by its members. The aim of the awards is to bring greater awareness
of the participation of landscape industries in creating an improved
environment and to draw attention to the best contributions made to this aim.
BALI has more than 700 members who represent just over 13,000 employees and
provide #500m turnover per annum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
