<HEADLINE>Benefits will flow from milk assurance scheme</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW farm assurance scheme targeted at the dairy sector is due to come on
stream next month, it was revealed in London yesterday.
The scheme is designed to guarantee quality, product traceability and farm
animal welfare in response to increasing pressure from retailers and consumers.
``In the future there will be a two-tier system for the dairy industry; one for
those that just produce milk and another for those that aim for the top end of
the market,'' said Richard Smith, chairman of the Yorkshire-based Northern Milk
Partnership, in unveiling the group's Star Initiative.
He said the group's strategy was to capture and retain the top 20% of the
market through the partnership between its 1100 producers and Northern Foods
who supply most of the leading supermarkets as well as the Express and Dale
Farm doorstep delivery companies.
Prior to milk deregulation last November traceability of product back to the
farm was virtually impossible because of milk bulking. The partnership's closed
chain system enables tight record-keeping and allows bar codes on the final
product to be used to pinpoint initial source.
The group has also produced tight quality standards and a new award scheme
designed to encourage members to improve quality well beyond the minimum
standards.
The third strand of its strategy is to apply strict farm welfare codes based on
those of the Ministry of Agriculture but buttressed by new rules drawn up and
agreed by NMP producer-directors and members. It will be policed by Northern
Foods farm liaison officers.
``Farm animal welfare is no longer a fringe issue. Consumers increasingly want
to know that the food they buy has been produced in an acceptable way,'' said
producer-director Peter Grice who co-ordinated development of the initiative.
``They want to know it has been produced in the safest possible way as far as
their own health is concerned and in a way which also maximises the health and
well-being of the food producing animals.
``It is a demand which will undoubtedly grow. To such an extent indeed that it
is not hard to envisage a future in which there is little or no market for
foods that do not offer these sorts of assurances.''
The scheme will start on December 1. Initially it will be targeted at retail
and franchisee customers but a consumer initiative at a later date has not been
ruled out.
In Scotland preparations are under way for the introduction of a farm assurance
scheme for milk. The National Farmers' Union of Scotland's milk committee has
drawn up a code of practice in consultation with leading figures in the milk
industry and consumer organisations.
Caroline Lang, commodity director for milk at the NFUS, said that the timing
for developing the draft proposals into a full-blown scheme had not yet been
agreed.
</TEXT>
