<DOCNO>GH951118-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union firms levy stance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323321</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish NFU yesterday reaffirmed its opposition to plans by meat plants to
seek a #3.50 levy on cattle to help meet the cost of slaughterhouse precautions
against BSE.
John Ross, president of the Scottish NFU, met the Institute of Auctioneers and
Appraisers in Edinburgh yesterday. He said later: ``The meat trade wouldn't
think much of it if farmers started charging them levies for the costs they
have to bear in complying with Government regulations. There would be no end to
levies if we agreed this principle.''
</TEXT>
