<HEADLINE>Mysterious masterstroke</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LIZ TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323420</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TALE with intriguing elements of secrecy and vanity in high places has just
emerged from the saleroom. A paragraph in the report of returns from a sale of
otherwise unremarkable paintings held by Bonhams on September 20 started me off
on its trail because a copy of Graham Sutherland's portrait of Sir Winston
Churchill was recorded as having sold for the astonishing sum of #23,000. This
price took the auction house by surprise because the estimate had been around
#3000.
The name of the artist who painted the copy was given as Peter of Dalkeith and,
thinking that this might be a misprint, I telephoned Bonhams painting
specialist James Olph. He was guarded but confirmed the artist's name, the
price of the picture, and the fact that it had been bought by someone who
insisted on remaining anonymous. Bonhams are not allowed even to reveal the
buyer's name to the artist. Mr Olph also told me that the copy was masterly and
had been copied directly from Sutherland's work, the portrait that Churchill
and his wife so disliked it was destroyed by one or other of them sometime in
the 60s.
Peter of Dalkeith, he said, was still alive but reluctant to talk to the press.
He suggested that I write him a letter requesting an interview which Mr Olph
would forward but he did not hold out a great deal of hope. Within a couple of
days, however, I had a reply giving the artist's address, his telephone number
and agreeing to speak to me. There was one proviso, I was not to question him
about his parents. His mother was Scottish and that was why he had legally
changed his name to the impressive sounding Peter of Dalkeith, where he has
family connections.
The tale he had to tell was fascinating. He is a professional artist, 57years
old now, but as a young art student, he was friendly with Francis Bacon, Henry
Moore, Graham Sutherland, and the famous forger Tom Keating.
In 1954, Sutherland was commissioned by the House of Commons to paint
Churchill's portrait in celebration of his 80th birthday. In 1961, Peter was
copying a Velasquez painting in the National Gallery when he was approached by
Tom Keating who suggested that they co-operate because Keating had difficulty
painting hands. It was Keating who offered Peter ``a very important
commission'' but warned that it had to be kept secret because it was highly
clandestine. The fee was #500, a considerable sum in the early 60s. Keating's
share was to be #100.
Peter was taken, blindfolded, in a taxi to a secret address, a flat or hotel
room in Central London where he was told he had 10 days to make a copy of
Sutherland's masterly portait of Churchill which was standing on an easel in
the centre of the room. The client who wanted the copy, he was told, was a
``merchant banker'' but Keating later let slip this was not true and ``it would
be a real shock if the identity of the client was known''.
When the work was finished, Peter was told his client was very pleased. He was
paid and returned home again by taxi but not blindfolded this time. If he
thought that was the end of the matter, he was mistaken, for some time later
Keating told him he must return the commission fee because the client was
suspicious that some sort of switch had been made and wanted his money back. By
selling a motor bike, Peter raised the money and found himself the possessor of
his copy of the portrait.
It was shown by him to Sutherland in 1965 and the original artist declared that
he was ``stunned'' by its faithfulness to his own work but urged Peter to keep
its existence secret. In 1978, however, in the interests of posterity, he
replied in writing to a questionnaire Peter sent him about the painting and
this list of answers, signed by Sutherland, was included with the portrait in
Bonham's sale.
In it Sutherland says there is no concrete evidence that the original portrait
really was destroyed. He also gives details of his methods of portrait
painting, telling how he made a series of small studies over 10 sittings, with
three extra sittings for details like eyes and ears. He says that Churchill was
not an easy sitter but talked a lot during the sessions, often ``highly
indiscreetly''. Churchill, said Sutherland, did not appear to have physical
vanity but was concerned that the portrait should not denigrate his image
politically. When he heard that the Churchill family had destroyed his work,
Sutherland said he regretted that they did not have the courtesy to offer it
back to him. He was worried about the existence of a copy of his painting,
however, and that was the reason Peter of Dalkeith kept it hidden until all the
people involved in the project with him were dead.
When he recalls painting the copy, he says: ``I gave it my all. The original
was a magnificent work and for anyone to destroy it was an act of iconoclastic
vandalism. When Sutherland saw my portrait, however, he said that unless he was
told it was a copy, even he would not have known it was not his original
canvas. I took trouble to use exactly the same colours and pigments as he had
used - black and yellow ochre mainly. The chief difficulty was that Sutherland
was right-handed and I'm left-handed, so I was painting against his work
really.''
It is a major regret for Peter of Dalkeith that this copy portrait is the only
one of his works that has sold under his legal name. ``I've never sold a
Dalkeith apart from this one,'' he said. He has made his living painting copies
of Old Masters for owners who hang them on their walls and keep the originals
in the bank where thieves cannot get at them, or for clients who commissioned
him through his advertisement in Country Life. He painted copies of famous
pictures for them to hang in their homes and he said one client owns 42 copies
by him. The most popular copies he did were of Impressionist works and the
easiest to do were Old Masters because of the tight technique of the painting.
Sutherland was probably the hardest artist he ever copied because his technique
was much looser and also because of his ``idiosyncrasies''.
Peter of Dalkeith has given up making copies now because his eyesight is
failing but he still paints, doing what he calls his ``music paintings''
interpreting the work of artists like the Rolling Stones and the Beatles. He
hasn't sold any of these canvases but lives in hope.
``One day I know my turn will come. I hope I'm alive when it does. I would love
a major exhibition in Scotland before I die,'' he said.
He doesn't want to go down in art history simply as the man who painted a fine
copy of the most magnificent portrait of an aged statesman defying weakness and
mortality.
MARKET NEWS
ANOTHER item associated with Churchill was sold by Christie's in South
Kensington yesterday - a Sten gun, now deactivated, which he kept at Chartwell
during the war and on which he used to practise in case he had to defend
himself against Nazi invaders. The estimate for the gun was between #6000 and
#10,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Give us a quiche, but  make it one to savour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LADT CLAAIRE MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323421</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM rapidly going off the word quiche. It has been so bastardised by the
purveyors of fast foods, where quiche is synonymous with thick soggy pastry and
a filling consisting of undercooked onion and undercooked poor quality bacon,
both set in a solid rubbery-textured egg filling. A real Quiche Lorraine is,
however, to be found. The best is made by Marks &amp; Spencer, much as it grieves
me to have to admit it! I wish I could say the best Quiche Lorraine was made by
Claire Macdonald, but M &amp; S's quiche just couldn't be bettered.
The trouble is that the very word ``quiche'' has lost its true meaning, and has
become the blanket term for any savoury tart, whatever the filling. I have
always understood a Quiche Lorraine to contain eggs, cream, cheese, and bacon,
but no onion.
On the other hand, there are any number of delicious fillings for a savoury
tart, and such a dish is versatile in that it can be a first course, or a main
course. It can be extremely useful food for a meal when those participating
don't eat meat, and because a savoury tart is fairly filling eating, for most
appetites all that is needed as an accompaniment is a good salad.
The other aspect of a savoury tart is that the pastry must be good, and in many
cases can be flavoured to complement the filling. For instance, in today's
recipe the filling is of onions, well cooked before being put on the cooked
pastry, and the pastry is rich and delicious with quite a high proportion of
grated cheese, and mustard powder, to accentuate the flavour of the cheese.
We make a tart with walnut pastry and a filling of leeks and goat's cheese -
the three flavours of walnuts, goat's cheese, and leeks are a perfect
combination. I also put cheese in the pastry for a smoked haddock and parsley
filling, or flaked almonds and garlic in the pastry for a mushroom filling. You
can experiment to suit your own tastes.
With two exceptions, which I will talk about in a moment, the balance of eggs,
yolks, and either milk or single cream is what makes or mars a savoury tart.
This is where the lower end of the market, ubiquitous quiches fall down so
badly, because they use whole eggs in their fillings, whereas to get the soft
and creamy texture so essential to a really good filling you need yolks and
whole eggs. I use the proportion of two whole eggs and two yolks to half a pint
of milk or single cream.
The filling needs to be cooked in a moderate oven till it barely wobbles when
the dish is shaken gently. This takes about 20 minutes. I find savoury tarts
nicest served warm, not hot and not cold, but somewhere in between. If you
serve them hot, they are almost impossible to slice without the filling
collapsing out at either side.
I mentioned two exceptions to the usual balance of eggs, yolks, and single
cream (or milk). These are tomatoes, or spinach. For a tomato tart I whiz
skinned and deseeded tomatoes (the seeds make the resulting puree too watery)
to a smooth puree, usually with basil leaves, and I use this instead of the
cream or milk. For a spinach tart I whiz the spinach in a processor, adding
cream cheese (such as Philadelphia) or creamy goat's cheese, and adding the
yolks and eggs to the spinach. As the fresh baby spinach cooks it can become
watery, and I find that if extra liquid is added in the form of either cream or
milk it can prove too sloppy for the yolks and eggs to set.
FRENCH ONION TART WITH CHEESE AND MUSTARD PASTRY
Serves 6.
For the pastry:
5oz plain flour
3oz butter, hard from the fridge and cut into bits
3oz cheddar cheese, grated
2 teaspoons mustard powder.
Put all the above ingredients into a food processor and whiz till the mixture
is crumblike in texture. Pat this firmly around the sides and base of a flan
dish approximately eight inches in diameter. Put the dish in the fridge for an
hour, then bake in a moderate oven, 350F, 180c, gas mark four till the pastry
is golden, about 25 minutes. You may need to push the sides of the pastry up
the sides of the dish with the back of a metal spoon during cooking time.
For the filling:
6 onions, skinned and sliced very thinly
3 tablespoons sunflower oil and 2oz butter
1-2 cloves of garlic, skinned and chopped very finely
2 whole eggs beaten well with 2 egg yolks and               !s pint single cream
Salt, freshly ground black pepper.
Heat the oil and melt the butter together in a wide saucepan and cook the
sliced onions over moderate heat for 10-15 minutes - stir from time to time so
that the onions don't stick during cooking. They will collapse in quantity, and
become very soft and turn brown at the edges. Add the chopped garlic towards
the end of the cooking time. Spoon this onion mixture over the cooked pastry,
and then stir the salt and pepper into the cream and egg and yolks mixture and
pour this in with the onions. Bake in a moderate  oven, as for the pastry, till
the custard just sets, about 15-20 minutes. Serve warm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BIRDWATCH</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH OUSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323422</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SAD little story: last spring our garden blackbird seemed incapable of
settling into a regular, fluent song pattern. There were two hen birds around;
maybe he couldn't decide between them. One morning, as I was pruning the
gooseberries, came a desperate cackling and the two hen blackies shot round the
side of the house, followed by a steely blue blur, which picked one off six
feet from me and dived over the neighbour's bushes.
There stood a sparrowhawk on the grass, ``mantling'' its victim, covering it
with its strong round wings, all striped chest and staring yellow eyes. This
was evolution in action. The next day the cock blackbird relaxed into a full
throated song, his mind made up for him.
Sparrowhawks are hated because they kill garden birds, but really they are
garden birds themselves. Once you learn to recognise the broad wings and long
tail, the deep-chested russet females and the sharp little blue-grey males.
In the sixties, this species was one of the hardest hit by organochlorine
pesticides building up in their bodies at the top of the food chain, thinning
the eggshells and driving them on to the protected species list. Now they are
common. I know that an hour in the garden will always have me seeing one.
In summer it is easy: the scolding of swallows always mark their passage over
the field. With no warning one tears under the arch at the corner of the house,
over the roof of the car as you are opening a door, under the ash tree as you
play with the children. Always they trail excitement, a few seconds' jink and
dash burning on to your eye, setting fire to a morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Proving it's good to talk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROL ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Imagining Characters: Six Conversations About Women Writers
A S Byatt and Ignes Sodre
Chatto &amp; Windus, #16.99.
A DREAM is very different from a work of art . . . and yet, at the most basic
level, it must come from the same "place" in the mind. This is just one idea
thrown up by this unusual book by Byatt, the novelist and critic known
especially for her 1990 Booker prizewinner Possession, and Sodre, a Brazilian
psychoanalyst who has practised in Britain for over 20 years.
Byatt and Sodre first met when both were asked to discuss George Eliot's
Middlemarch at the Cheltenham Festival of Literature in October 1992, a key
theme being psychoanalysis and literature. Their lively encounter sparked off
Imagining Characters.
The novels it considers are Jane Austen's Mansfield Park, Charlotte Bronte's
Villette, George Eliot's Daniel Deronda, The Professor's House by Willa Cather,
Iris Murdoch's An Unofficial Rose, and Toni Morrison's Beloved.
Each chapter concentrates on one novel and opens with a plot summary, useful if
you haven't read the novel or just need your memory jogged. There are also
brief notes at the end of the book, including references and some further
reading.
I admit to having been initially somewhat sceptical about this book. Rebecca
Swift's enthusiastic, if rather vague, preface points out that the chosen
novels are ``six major tests from different periods in history'', but one of
the nagging questions in my mind was: Why these six writers, these particular
texts? Why, for instance, Mansfield Park, perhaps Austen's least popular novel
in which, as Byatt herself admits ``nobody can manage to like the heroine''?
Why Daniel Deronda, and not, say, The Mill on the Floss?
Two of the novels are American, one by a black writer. Is this tokenism? No
rationale is given beyond the taste, personal preference, and interest of the
two conversationalists. These are six novels which Byatt says at one point they
picked ``because they are books that we revisit and revisit so that they become
part of our selves''. No apologies.
Despite my cavils, I was converted once I began reading. I had wondered,
puritanically, if there wasn't something rather self-indulgent about the chosen
form. However, as the preface points out, the dialogue ``was a favourite of
Greek philosophers'', a means ``of making complex debate accessible'' and of
including the ``listener''.
I found this book highly readable and often illuminating. Its approach is
old-fashioned in a way, based on the view that ``we read novels primarily for
the pleasure of being told a story'' and characters are imagined and discussed
``as if they were people we knew''.
At the same time, Imagining Characters is enriched by Byatt's erudition,
intellectual energy and obvious engagement and Sodre's lucidly expressed
insights which draw on her psychoanalytic training. The major point of
reference seems to be Freud rather than the fashionable French, and the book is
largely jargon-free.
Threads linking the six novels emerge. The preface briefly mentions shared
elements such as underlying archetypal structures and there is much fascinating
discussion of the way these novels use or echo fairytales.
There is consideration too, of the novelists' concern with the thwarted
energies of women - a theme which, for Byatt, ``recurs most powerfully in all
the novels we are looking at''.
The fictional representation of place and space is another recurring topic,
``the relations between human beings and the houses that contain them''; and
the intertextual relations between these and other works are explored, often
revealingly.
The reading of Villette was, for this reader, particularly stimulating as was
the final chapter on ``Dreams and Fictions'' which pulls the book together.
Overall, the way in which Byatt draws on her own experience as a novelist also
lends her commentary special immediacy.
I wonder who will be the audience for this book, however. It doesn't seem quite
aimed at the "ordinary reader", and neither is it a standard academic work.
With luck, it may fall into the hands of those who simply love literature or
have questioning minds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A BOOK AT BEDTIME</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROL LAULA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>BOOK AT BEDTIME</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975323424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n Singer Carol Laula tells Ann Donald about her late-night reading.
I have been reading a brilliant book by E L Doctorrow called Ragtime which is
set in America of the early 1900s. It's a real patchwork of factual and
fictional characters which focuses on two fictional families and actual
historical characters like Sigmund Freud, Harry Houdini, and Evelyn Nesbit, who
was a Hollywood starlet of the time.
The families have no names but are referred to as ``mother'', ``father'' and
``young boy with a sailor suit'' in the case of the all-American rich family
and, in the case of the Jewish immigrant family, as ``mamie'', ``tatie'' and
``wee girl in a pinafore dress''. The first family are flying the flag for
America and, as far as they're concerned, immigrants will be the downfall of
their country. Unfortunately for the Jewish family, America is their downfall
as they end up living in the squalor of New York and the mother has to sell
herself to her employer to feed the family.
There is one quote from Freud that is the crux of the entire book. He really
gets the best line when he says: ``America is a mistake, a gigantic mistake!''
Doctorrow's description is incredible. Usually I skim books but with this I've
spent the last three days totally devouring it. It's the kind of book you
really want to shout about.
Another book I've been reading is a novella called Rita Hayworth and the
Shawshank Redemption from a book of short stories by Stephen King called
Different Seasons. I saw the film The Shawshank Redemption which I think was
far cleverer than the book. The book tended to focus on the theme of hope being
a dangerous thing if you remember that quote from Morgan Freeman's character
Red, who says: ``I hope for the best but expect the worst.'' I think King is an
under-rated writer to a degree - many people dismiss him as a horror writer but
he writes brilliant thrillers like Misery and Salem's Lot.
</TEXT>
