<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tensions rise as city falls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>49</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CARLISLE, November 18 - Prince Charles Edward Stuart rode in triumph today into
the first English city he has taken, mounted on a white horse and preceded by
his 100 pipers.
But the council of war which followed at his headquarters in Highmoor House was
fraught with tension, as several who were there confirm. Deep divisions emerged
between his inner circle of advisers and the Highland chiefs captaining his
regiments.
Charles insists on the need to keep up the invasion's momentum. The Scots want
to return home and consolidate there, while daring the Government in London to
send forces north and attack. They are convinced that such a move would fail,
that effective French aid would meanwhile arrive and that Scotland would again
become independent under the restored Stuarts.
Tempers rose in the room as the Jacobite commander, Lord George Murray, set out
his case. He cited also the logistical problems of going on. Ever since the
5000 Jacobites left Edinburgh three weeks ago, it has been hard to keep them
together. They march as a modern army, but the clansmen are basically
irregulars.
About 500 deserted as they crossed the Borders. There was no welcome from the
locals, who stole what equipment they could lay their hands on, including all
the tents - in future the army can only be quartered in towns. The weakness of
its artillery, with just 13 guns, is embarrassing.
Charles angrily rejected these arguments, according to the reports from inside
the council. He said delay would only benefit his enemies. The Hanoverian
regime had been woefully unprepared for his challenge, but was now working
feverishly to counter it.
A force under General George Wade was already at Newcastle, and a second one
under General Sir John Ligonier had been sent through the Midlands to intercept
the Jacobites. Their best chance lay in forestalling a junction of these
armies, which could only be done by advancing to fight them one at a time.
The prince was supported by his secretary, John Murray of Broughton, who said a
shortage of money meant that staying put was not an option; only #60 had been
raised in a levy on Carlisle. The matter was clinched when Charles asked the
French envoy accompanying him, the Marquis d'Eguilles, to reveal his
instructions from King Louis XV. They stated France would not commit herself
fully until she could gauge how much English support the Jacobites would win.
The prince said that meant going on into Lancashire, where the large Roman
Catholic population is supposed to be sympathetic. The chiefs were forced to
agree and the council took a decision to continue the invasion. The army will
resume its southward march as soon as possible.
The meeting of the council cast a pall over the Jacobites' easy capture of
Carlisle. But discord had already become evident during the short siege. Lord
George Murray declined to direct it himself, on the grounds that he knew
nothing about this aspect of warfare. The joint commander of the Jacobites, the
Duke of Perth, took charge instead. He flung himself into the task and, amid a
heavy fall of snow, dug trenches in his shirt sleeves along with his men.
The effort proved hardly necessary because, except for two casualties inflicted
by snipers, Carlisle put up next to no resistance. The local militia was called
out and assembled in the city, but most of these untrained farmers ran away as
soon as they saw what they were up against. The crumbling defences were then
manned only by 80 old soldiers who live in retirement in the castle. There was
panic among the townsfolk, who followed the militiamen in climbing over the
walls or forcing their way through the gates to escape.
A white flag was hung out over the ramparts four nights ago, less than a week
after the Jacobites arrived. A message had got through from General Wade saying
he must abandon an attempt to come to Carlisle's relief. Beaten back by snow he
was, after two days' march, no nearer than Hexham. He retired to Newcastle.
The mayor of Carlisle, Alderman Thomas Pattinson, and members of the
corporation then met Perth with an offer to surrender the town but not the
castle. He refused, and they had no choice but to give way.
The next day, November 15, they went out to Brampton, five miles to the east,
where the prince was waiting with most of his army to block Wade's expected
assault across the Pennine Hills. The mayor and magistrates appeared before him
on their knees to deliver up the keys of Carlisle. He returned them in ``a very
obliging manner'', assuring the citizens of his future protection and favour.
Lord George Murray, uninformed about all this, exploded when he learned of it.
He told the prince that Perth should never have been allowed to take the
surrender of the first English town, because his Roman Catholic religion made a
gift to Whig propaganda. Murray resigned his commission and announced he would
from now on serve as just a volunteer. Charles accepted the resignation,
unaware that the clan chieftains were siding with Murray.
Go-betweens then had to persuade the duke, now left as the Jacobites' field
commander, to cede rank to Murray for the good of the cause. Charles was thus
forced to reinstate Lord George, and indeed give him for the first time sole
overall command. But he did so with ill will.
Meanwhile, on November 16, the Corporation of Carlisle attended in state at the
market cross where King James III of England was proclaimed. He assembled again
today to greet the prince on his entry. Most townsfolk stayed at home, however,
apparently for fear of the clansmen.
The small crowd which did turn out was silent and sullen. This does not augur
well for any rising of the English Jacobites, from whose leaders Prince Charles
has yet to hear.
</TEXT>
