<DOCNO>GH951118-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The hills of home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PETER EVANS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975323426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOUNTAINS have long held a fascination for man. Walking and climbing among them
engenders powerful emotions, and for those whose souls are captured by the lure
of their wildness there is no escape.
The adrenalin rush the climber gets from grappling with a difficult move; a
solo walker's first sight of a remote, lonely corrie - these are addictive
drugs, but without the harm.
For many there is the added attraction of learning more about the natural
environment: the plants and birds they see forming an inextricable link with
their surroundings; dramatic glaciated glens and rock strata laid down over
millions of years.
There is a permanence about it all which puts man in his place, gives us a
sense that the mountains will still be there long after we have departed the
planet. In a human world where rapid change is a dominant feature of everyday
life, the mountain world is an anchor.
Yet there is change here, too. Perhaps not immediately perceptible, it
manifests itself over time, and the consequences for mountain flora and fauna
can be startling. Man, of course, plays a significant part, through
agricultural practices, estate management and recreation. Whether we choose to
recognise it or not, these are all forms of environmental exploitation.
A new book involving a collaboration between one of Scotland's best known
landscape photographers, Colin Baxter, and Dr Des Thompson, head of uplands and
peatlands studies for Scottish Natural Heritage, is a celebration of mountains
in words and pictures, but also brings into focus how the upland natural
heritage can be influenced by human activity.
Baxter needs little introduction as a photographer whose work has been widely
published and acclaimed, and the mountain mood is captured to striking effect
in this large, coffee table format book. Not all the images will make you gasp
in awe, but those who know mountains will recognise the subtle choice of
subject matter, the delicate interplay between light and landscape.
Thompson's writing is better known in academic circles, but here again is a man
who empathises with mountains and can write eloquently and authoritatively
about them. ``I am moved by the beauty and nature of these places, and by the
powerful union of light, land and life. I thrill at the prospect of a new top.
The return to a familiar place is eagerly awaited; the birds and plants, the
views and impressions, that peculiarly intoxicating excitement of reaching the
summit - all contribute to milestone experiences and to the continuation of
life at its best.''
The attraction of Scotland, Land of Mountains is that it is not just another
book of pretty pictures. It sets out to say something about the Scottish
landscape and the changes that have been and are being wrought upon it.
As Magnus Magnusson says in the foreword: ``. . . so many of our wild areas are
inhabited and managed. `Wilderness' is a misnomer. But we do have wild
landscapes, with the natural elements of rock, water, peat and vegetation so
predominant. It is the inhabitation and management (or lack of it) of some of
these areas which has meant that wherever one looks there seem to be conflict
and difficulty. This is a land which gives to all what it can, but receives
sorely little in return.''
Thompson's working life is spent studying and researching the upland
environment, and in a chapter entitled Man and Land Use he describes the major
factors influencing change.
Intensive grazing by sheep and the trampling and browsing effects of large
numbers of deer have stunted the natural regeneration of mountain vegetation.
Huge expanses of heather have disappeared, as has the woolly fringe moss,
characteristic of exposed summit plateaux. Erosion has resulted on steep
slopes, stripped bare of vegetation, where acid rain deposition further
contributes to the loss of globally rare mosses.
Two bird species in particular - the ptarmigan and the dotterel - have had
their breeding habitat squeezed into areas where it will be relatively
unaffected, in the Highlands. Heather, a food source for ptarmigan, has been
decimated in the southern uplands, and attempts to reintroduce the bird have
failed. As a ground nesting bird, the dotterel suffers from nest trampling by
sheep and deer.
Recreation can wreak havoc on the mountain environment. The footpath network
spreads as more people venture into the hills, and erosion can be severe in
steep or boggy areas. Five downhill ski centres in Scotland attract more people
to the tops, and ski paraphernalia such as lifts and fencing itself has a
negative impact.
Says Thompson: ``The battle for our mountains, to protect their biodiversity
and wildness, was started long ago - before the emergence of younger, better
informed generations. But it is they who must rise to the calling of the
mountains.
``It is between sheep and deer, people and their clutter, fire and rifles, and
the ghostly passage of clouds and pollutants that we have to secure a better
balance.
``Many regions of the world have sacred and mystical elements of nature
associated with their mountains. There, one finds degrees of reverence and
protection not found in Scotland. Our mountains have an aura of spirituality,
but not a corresponding degree of sanctity. The mountains deserve our best.''
Scotland, Land of Mountains, by Colin Baxter and Des Thompson, is published by
Colin Baxter Photography, Grantown-on-Spey, and costs #20.
</TEXT>
