<DOCID>GH951118-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Last stand for independence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM HEWITSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN, after a month of tiresome preliminaries, the last Scottish Parliament got
round to debating the First Article of Union (November 1706) it turned out to
be pure theatre, culminating in a noble lord throwing himself on his knees and
pleading with tear-filled eyes for the preservation of Scottish self-government.
Before the members was the proposal that: ``The two kingdoms should, after 1st
May (1707), be forever after united into one kingdom by the name of Great
Britain, and their heraldic cognizances be conjoined'' (which, to the layman at
least, sounds pretty final). Although it was said that this First Article was
only part of a package and that if the others could not be agreed the first
would fall, no-one doubted that with the First Article approved it would really
only be a matter of fine tuning thereafter. With a majority in Parliament the
Government could already taste victory.
The opening speeches summarise the entire debate - Seton of Pitmedden and Lord
Belhaven (Jock Hamilton to his buddies) put the opposing viewpoints, Pitmedden
stressing the economic disaster which awaited Scotland without the Union and
Lord Belhaven emotionally describing ``a free and independent nation delivering
up what they had fought for since the days of Nimrod''.
Although in recent years suggestions that the motivation among the Scottish
establishment in seeking union was to get in on England's vast trading network
have been largely discredited, and it seems that more selfish motives, bribery,
even military threats, were at work, William Seton of Pitmedden certainly
stressed Scotland's precarious economic position in urging the acceptance of an
incorporating union.
The main thrust of his argument was that Scotland was lagging behind other
European nations in foreign trade and, being poor, could not reap great
advantages until able to share in the trade and enjoy the protection of a
powerful neighbour .
Gazing into his crystal ball Pitmedden predicted that if Scotland continued
under the same sovereign as England but with a separate parliament, the numbers
of the nobility would increase, the commons would be oppressed, the Scots
Parliament would increasingly fall under the influence of England, competing
factions would disrupt the peace, the rich would get richer and the poor
poorer, and emigration would increase.
He continued: ``But above all, my Lord, I think I see our ancient mother
Caledonia, like Caesar, sitting in the midst of our senate, ruefully looking
about her, covering herself with her royal garment, attending the fatal blow
and breathing out her last with a `et tu quoque, mi fili?'.'' Betrayal was his
message.
The First Article was approved. The die was cast. Scotland sent 45 members to
Westminster the following spring, roughly the same number as Cornwall. There
were more English bishops alone in the House of Lords than Scots peers. Has the
Union been merely a 300-year hiccup, or is this a united kingdom for keeps? The
next decade should surely provide the answer.
</TEXT>
