<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000181</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000181</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>He who did true valour see</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOREEN TAYLOR=WILKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The letter had reached me from Cafe du Commerce in Lauzerte in the Garonne.
``Having a day off here in a little fortified, hilltop town. Well timed too!
Yesterday it was flooding down with rain and today is dodgy as well, so I have
had a chance to get dried out and to avoid a second soaking. Tomorrow Moissac .
. . ''
The date, April 25 1995, indicated that David Irving was almost four months
into his mammoth walk, which started at his home near Stranraer, and would end
on June 20 in the Great Cathedral Square at Santiago de Compostela. By then,
walking the famous, centuries-old Pilgrim Way through France and Spain, he
would have covered some 2700 miles.
On January 4, he set out from his front door and made for the Southern Upland
Way, just north of Portpatrick. By chance, he had chosen one of the fiercest
winters for many years. The journey divided into three sections: through
Britain to Portsmouth, from Caen in northern France, through Angouleme, to the
Chemin St Jacques, the start of the Pilgrim Way. After that came a heavy mist
over the Pyrenees, when he only knew he was across the border by a sign in
Spanish, then 500 miles to Santiago de Compostela. But this time, he was no
longer an oddity, an eccentric. As he went south, the route began to fill with
fellow walkers.
Irving is well qualified for the rigorous journey. A hill walker since he was a
boy, he had been principal teacher of Biology at Stranraer Academy when he
decided to take early retirement, age 51. ``It's hard to say which came first,
the retirement or the pilgrimage,'' he said. ``But I remember a science meeting
last year. It was going well when it suddenly hit me: `This time next year I'll
not be addressing them, I'll be on the road about the middle of France' - and
it did come true.''
The hardest part of the journey was, without doubt, south through Britain, as
far as possible off the roads. He walked the Southern Upland Way, and the
Pennines, through the Peak District, and later to the Tissington Trail to
Ashbourne, Stratford-upon-Avon, the Cotswolds and the towpath of the Avon
Canal. After the River Test Way to Southampton, it was a day to Portsmouth and
his first main break, a week's rest.
That summary may not sound too difficult. The reality was, with blinding snow
on the northern hills, snowbound minor roads, and once a snowplough operator
who told him the way ahead was closed. But, used to the Galloway Hills, Irving
took out his compass and struggled over the tops. For every pilgrim, as he
found later, the day's most urgent target was to make sure he had somewhere to
stay. He admits to almost a sense of panic when, with dark closing in, he
reached a village and could not find a B&amp;B or a pub. Later, in France and
Spain, with the better weather, like most pilgrims he found it easier to start
very early - 5 or 6am - and stop at a likely village around mid-afternoon.
In France, it was often a campsite: ``Most days, `warm' is changing to `hot'
and shorts are the gear. But, when camping, one must remember on a clear, hot
day, at this time of year, the temperature plummets at night, with the dreaded
early morning frost. I guard against this by wearing every garment I have and
stuff myself with lots of Paris Match or Sud Ouest!'' There were also Gites
d'Etapes (hostels) costing a fiver or so and, by this time, he could use the
special Refuges - Refugios in Spain.
Their standard varied enormously. ``In Spain, the refugios were a bit like the
Old Windmill Theatre. They never closed!'' He remembers one in a Spanish
village dominated by a huge monastery. ``Eighty bunks in tiers, but 120 people!
With the bunks full, there was a huge pile of blankets!'' Usually there was a
kitchen, sometimes without cooking pots. In contrast, the best, at Rabanal near
Santiago, was run by the British Confederation of St James. Staffed by
volunteers, it even provided an ample breakfast.
To qualify for free use of the refugios, walkers need a pilgrim's certificate
handed out on the French side after close questioning by a formidable lady,
Madame Debril. In France, too, they were limited to people arriving on foot,
horseback, or bicycle - the last unpopular with walkers, as they could reach
the refugios so much easier and take the best beds.
Once Irving had reached the Pilgrim Route in France, he had begun to meet
people . . . ``It became a celebration,'' and by Spain he was already a
celebrity . . . ``Walked from Scotland?'' was the astonished greeting. People
met and parted and met again, but many, ticking along around the same speed,
tended to form bands and walk together. He saw a lot of a Dutch couple but lost
touch with them going over the Pyrenees. He neither saw nor heard of anyone
from Scotland until he found a letter of greeting at a pilgrims' drinking
fountain off the Chemin de St Jacques. In French, it was from a Scots couple,
signed Arthur and Margaret. He met a Welsh pilgrim in Le Pui, an Anglican
priest in Spain. But most came from France and Spain. ``There's a great
camaraderie on the road,'' he said, ``Some of us will keep in touch.''
Irving also found fame in Spain as ``the man with the lightest rucksack''. His
worst moment came just before the Spanish border, when the waistband of his
rucksack broke, hurting his back. Watching him hobble, one traveller asked if
he were making the pilgrimage as a penitence! ``That was funny later. But I
feared then I would have to give up.'' Irving said instead, the back improved,
and he was ruthless with his rucksack, pruning it to two pairs of shorts and
underpants, one pair of jeans, two pairs of socks, two pairs of walking socks,
and always, his journal. ``I wrote it every night, usually in a cafe, and
missed only a very few times . . . when my back was bad, or I was terribly
tired . . . or I had had too good a night!'' He sent back each volume as he
finished it, now eight in all.
Prudent with his money, he allowed himself only #20 a day. Meanwhile, at home,
his wife Isy (Isobel) was organising the sponsorship plan that has now raised
more than #6000 for the Multiple Sclerosis Society - an appropriate charity for
Wigtownshire where MS is prevalent. ``Four of my friends have it,'' he said. He
phoned home most nights, and Isy was able to organise cash replenishment and
other practical details, made difficult by fluctuating currency.
The last night, with dozens of others, he spent at a fine building, Monte Gozo,
built for the Pope's visit in 1989. This refugio had cafes and a bar. The next
morning, scrubbed and groomed, after discarding his ragged shorts for the
well-cherished jeans, he teamed up again with Jason from America, another
well-known pilgrim, with an injury that had left him walking in one shoe and
one boot. The pair set off early for the Great Square at the heart of Santiago
for the journey's finest moment. ``It was amazing. We were almost open-mouthed
gazing at the great Cathedral.''
In the Pilgrims' Office, where they filled in forms and declared themselves
either ``spiritual'' or ``cultural'' pilgrims, the face of the priest in charge
fell when he heard Irving select the ``cultural'' role. It was the first time
he had seen a Scottish pilgrim and had hoped for a spiritual journey. The
special pilgrim's mass followed in the Cathedral, underneath the largest censer
in the world. It swung to and fro dispensing incense as the service ended and,
church or not, spontaneous applause broke out.
As a passionate traveller, the sense of achievement at the end of this great
pilgrimage was tremendous for David Irving. But did he gain anything spiritual
from it? ``I think the journey did not so much change people as etch in their
previously held beliefs,'' he said, ``but it did strengthen my views of the
goodness of human nature. So many people have turned themselves upside down to
help me that I'd now say 90% of the world are kind people.
IF you wish to contribute to David Irving's fund the Multiple Sclerosis
Society, contact Harriet Collins, Seaward, Bowling Green Road, Stranraer,
Wigtownshire. Cheques should be made payable to the Multiple Sclerosis Society.
</TEXT>
