<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951118-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951118-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surviving in a hostile environment, thriving on next to nothing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>50</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CACTI, fish, cooking, and oil paint do not automatically go together, but
Donald Urquhart, winner of the Scottish Arts Council 1995-6 Amsterdam bursary,
is no ordinary artist. ``I once worked out that housing my 150 cacti - which I
have never painted - takes up a quarter of my studio, and so costs me #500 a
year. Crazy!''
Then there's his fish. The day I was due to go for coffee his new aquarium
burst and 40 gallons of water gushed out. ``There were fish flapping and
gasping all over the floor. What a trauma. I'm sure they'll need counselling!
``Paul Nesbitt, exhibitions director of Inverleith House, was there too. He's
very good at telling you their Latin names - but that was not perhaps the right
moment!''
Luckily Urquhart has a sense of humour as well as a good eye. ``Cacti remind me
of artists. They too need strong defence mechanisms and have to survive in
hostile environments, thriving on next to nothing!'' His interest in cacti
started with one seed he collected off a plant in the Arizona desert on a visit
there in 1988. ``It germinated and started to grow. So I bought it a friend -
then another. I knew nothing about them so I got a couple of books. Pals gave
me their cacti and I found a mail-order firm in Norfolk. The next thing I knew
I had 125 species.
Urquhart says despite living in Glasgow he's a rural boy. He was born in
Perthshire and his current work and last five exhibitions address the theme of
its landscape, its trees, and pollution. Drumbuich Wood is a favourite,
inspirational place in his native Perthshire which he first explored as a child
in the company of his forester grandfather. The woodland is hidden away between
the River Almond as it flows to the Tay and the main A85 to Crieff, not far
from the village of Bankfoot where Urquhart was born in 1959.
A lovely linear etching of a dock plant dated 1925 hangs on his wall. ``It was
in the room in my grandmother's house where I was born - so it's officially the
first piece of visual art I ever saw!''
His last two solo shows, Sylva at Edinburgh's Botanic Gardens and Ptarmigan at
the Dick Institute, Kilmarnock, both take their starting point from Drumbuich
Wood and his interest in natural history. Scots Pine, birch and spruce feature
upside down in photographs which are manipulated in the developer with a brush
and overpainted with pale, ghostly gouache afterwards. Why upside down?
``I was walking through the woods one calm, bright winter's day after heavy
rain and was astonished to see a wonderful sunlit reflection in a forest pool.
It took me more than a year to capture 40 upside-down trees in pools in black
and white. The veils of paint isolate each tree and add an emotive quality. I
call the series The Lost Trees of Drumbuich, a title which refers not just to
the transience of the watery reflection but also to acid rain and a loss of
innocence,'' he explains.
``As a child, nature is magical. There is a wonder about everything. As an
adult I feel a pessimism in the realisation that the landscape is polluted;
trees are bathed in acid rain and radioactivity is on the increase.''
His most recent work, for Kilmarnock, emphasises the dangers to the environment
via the ptarmigan, Britain's most northerly bird which for Urquhart represents
all that is ``wild, beautiful, fragile - and threatened''. Ptarmigans carry
residual traces of radioactivity from Chernobyl, and are retreating higher up
the Scottish mountains as global warming alters our climate. ``The birds now
live above the 1500ft line. It's concrete evidence of pollution; so I use the
ptarmigan as a metaphor for environmental destruction.''
Perthshire flora and fauna also appeared in more straightforward paintings
(seen at Glasgow's Intermedia Galley in 1994) where one of his fine linear
drawings of flowering plants was bought by George Wylie for his wife Daphne.
BBC presenter Alex Bell also owns Urquhart's work including 10 of a series of
20 panels. Bell's sister bought the other half!
Since graduating from Edinburgh College of Art in 1982, itchy feet have also
taken him to America, Paris, Brussels, Madrid, and Barcelona in 1982 courtesy
of the Royal Academy's Richard Ford Award (he was the first Scot to win it); to
Amiens in France as part of Glasgow's 1990 cultural exchange programme; to
Slovenia and Croatia in 1992; now to the Netherlands for a year, after which he
goes to Slovenia to exhibit.
In May 1996 he shows in Boston and Harvard simultaneously. The exhibitions then
tour to New York and Los Angeles in 1996-97 - not forgetting a new show at
Edinburgh's Collective Gallery and Stornoway's An Lanntair in 1997-98.
Funding all this for eight years has been his work as a chef. ``My mother and
grandmother are both amazing cooks. I've always been interested.''
His current cool style, characterised by a ``dreich minimalism'' (his words)
plus monochromatic cream, ochre and grey/brown palette, is actually fairly new.
In the 1980s he was fiercely expressionistic, painting huge heroic canvases of
rearing stallions, battles and crucifixions in gory, shadowing red and black
chiaroscuro.
So why the change? ``I went to India in 1989 and found it impossible to take on
the vivid colours of the Jaipur spice markets or India's complex mythology in
three months. On my return I had my first solo show at Main Fine Art and it
seemed inappropriate to use bright colours in a dreich Scottish climate so I
painted Indian carvings of the Nandi gods in sombre tones. I had time to ask
myself, `What do I really want to paint? Why am I dissatisfied with figurative
work?' I decided I needed to put more intellectual thought into my pictures
rather than rely on spectacle. I filled five notebooks with ideas and writing.
That's when the new work began.''
I left Urquhart amid his spiky green cereus and mammilaria, his grey sedum and
woolly cerhalocereus senilis (from the high Andes) listening to his favourite
jazz. Urquhart has a nice line in irony, demonstrated by his parting shot to me
as I rushed onwards. ``You need something to calm you down,'' he said. ``You
should get a fish tank.''
</TEXT>
