<HEADLINE>Soaring with the dove abd phoenix</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JILL CRAWSHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM the depth of a stretched Mercedes, the Lebanese woman emerged, clad from
head to the toes of her very high-heeled shoes in the latest designer Chanel,
and like some haughty, brightly-plumed bird, stalked fastidiously round the
potholes and heaps of rubble before disappearing into a jeweller's shop.
No problem, no despair, no veils either - because we are in Beirut, the city
that's trying to beat all building records to rise, literally, from the dust
and ashes, and so reclaim its former status as the playground of the Eastern
Mediterranean.
And I'm here to evaluate Lebanon's current tourist potential. There are now
three airlines flying regularly from the UK, and Jim Smith, the Glaswegian
owner of Jasmin Tours, has already put the Lebanese capital back in his
brochure to complete his Middle East portfolio.
At first glance, Beirut is hardly the stuff that holiday dreams are made of as
you notch up the shell holes and identify the Holiday Inn, the once famous
Phoenecia Hotel, the hole that was the American Embassy - just some of the
gutted remnants of a vicious civil war that raged for nearly 20 years, killing
150,000 of its citizens. And what the bombs couldn't destroy, the cranes seem
to be finishing off now.
But a closer scrutiny reveals the more human and hopeful face of Beirut; even
in the most blighted areas surrounded by an acreage of rubble, an old man
busily sweeps his shop front, another, seemingly the only occupier of a
derelict building has planted geraniums in old oil-drums, put out dusty chairs
and reopened his cafe.
At the Yacht Club in the shadow of the shelled out hotels, Lebanese girls are
sunbathing in brief bikinis, and in the reopening restaurants along the once
famous Corniche, tables are groaning with 30 and 40 dish Mezzes, all served
with wine, beer, or champagne - there are no Muslim restrictions about alcohol
here!
Even in the dreadfully damaged and aptly named central Martyr's Square, with
the martyr herself pitted with bullet holes, vendors are hustling postcards of
``then'' and ``now'' and ``ancient coins'' from excavations that have revealed
layers of civilisation dating back to the Phoenician era.
Pride of place in the square belongs to a huge tableau and model of the plans
already under way to restore those buildings that can be restored, reconstruct
new parks, promenades, plazas and souks - at #333m, the largest building
project of the 1990s, undertaken by a government-backed, privately financed
development company.
One corner of the square has already sprouted a new Maronite Church, while the
National Museum, situated on the Green Line that divided the city for so many
years, is reopening early next year.
Little wonder that flights from the UK, from Germany, even more from France -
though not yet from the US (which still forbids entry to its citizens) - are
disgorging businessmen, bankers, and constructors eager to sniff out their
share of this once dynamic, and now re-emerging little state.
We arrived in a comfortable four-and-a-half hours with the new British
Mediterranean airline with five flights a week from Heathrow, slightly nervous
at the huge portraits of Syrian President Assad adorning the airport (his
posters outnumber the Ayatollah's by about 20-1 in most of the Lebanon), and
the number of machine gun-toting young soldiers - though the formalities were
somewhat faster than at Heathrow, and, as we are to discover later, at the
checkpoints manned by police, Syrian or Lebanese militia at every crossroad, we
are always waved through.
A great deal more terrifying is the white-knuckle style driving, with every
Beiruti still seemingly determined to dice with death as he emerges from some
of the worst traffic jams I've ever experienced.
In a country as small as Wales, with 17 religious factions, politics and
religion are not issues to be taken lightly, nor is it easy for tourists to
understand the hatreds, the sheer collective insanity of a population which can
cause such mass destruction. Yet a few years later they can welcome visitors in
such a relaxed and urbane fashion.
``Until I was 18,'' says Jocelyn, our young and pretty guide, ``I knew nothing
but war. Yes, we knew that some of us would get killed, lose friends, family,
homes, and livelihood. That was normality. Yet five minutes after the bombs
went off nearby, we'd be off down to the beach.
``Of course there are still tensions, many of them psychological,'' admits
Barid, another of our young escorts, who has returned after five years living
in Canada (two-thirds of all Lebanese live abroad), to work in his country's
fledgling tourist industry.
In Beirut itself, this industry is busy getting its act together. All the big
hotel groups are going back, and about a dozen hotels are operating more or
less normally - ours, the Beau Rivage, hs unfinished wall fittings, an
unpainted dining-room, and the fountain in the lobby is still in its plastic
cover. But at breakfast on the day we leave, even at 4.30am, they can produce a
miraculous spread of eggs, dips, vegetables, tea and coffee.
Realistically, Beirut is as yet worth a day's sightseeing at most, to stroll
along the Corniche where old men are playing backgammon, and the young flaunt
their Armani - most designers' stores never left this lucrative,
fashion-conscious outlet.
Much of the rest of the action is centred round the dusty Hamra district, with
its cramped shops and cinemas, the Mayflower Hotel already building its legend
as the place where the kidnapped hostages enjoyed their last drinks.
Most of the nightlife is based in one long beachfront sprawl in the
neighbouring resort of Jounieh, from discos to belly dancers, where a night out
can cost $100, geared for wealthy Gulf Arabs, for whom Beirut was always the
Paris of the East.
But when the Casino reopens, the locals say that ``we'll really know that
Beirut is really back in business''.
For now though, the highlights of the Lebanon are well outside the city; we hug
the rapidly developing coast, glimpsing golden beaches and picnicking families
in between the skyscrapers and frenetic traffic, and arrive in the oasis which
is Byblos, to browse among even more ancient rubble.
Byblos is the oldest continuously inhabited settlement in the world, and from
its chunky Crusader ramparts the strata of about 7000 years of civilisation can
be clearly identified; the simple dwellings of neolithic man, obelisks from
Egypt, the tombs of early Phoenician royals, a tiny exquisite Roman theatre, a
Romanesque church, each building recycling centuries-old archeological
detritus, so that Roman columns are embedded in Arab walls, Hellenistic remains
packed with prehistoric stones. Byblos claims the first Roman example of the
alphabet on the thirteenth-century BC tomb of King Ahiran (now in the National
Museum).
The town also gave its name to the Bible (the word means ``book''), trading
cedar wood for the Pharaohs' tombs for papyrus from Egypt for its book-making
industry.
The once bustling harbour now dozes virtually undisturbed, bougainvillea and
jasmin ramble over white walls, fishing-nets dry in the sun, a few tourist
boats putter off down the coast. From the souks behind drift those Middle
Eastern smells of spices, bitter coffee, and cardamon. Meanwhile, on the roof
terrace of the Abi Chemou restaurant we linger over tabouleh (wheat salad),
hummus, shawarma (meat balls), baba ghanouj (mashed aubergine), and fresh fish,
and we gaze out across a filigree of Roman porticoes, minarets, and walls.
Byblos is enchanting. On Sundays, most of Lebanon is en fete, and we join much
of Beirut streaming out of the capital to picnic in the mountains. We're
heading for Baalbek in the Bekaa Valley, a Hizbollah stronghold, where until
recently tourists have been advised not to travel independently. As a reminder,
our driver points out the mountain village of Nabi Shit, where Terry Waite was
believed to have been held, but told us we'd need a special permit to visit it.
The valley rolls away peacefully enough, a succession of orchards and wheat
fields, though there are none of the famous cedars of Lebanon - they're further
north of here, and only about 400 of them left.
Nothing prepares you for the shock of Baalbek; the bus rounds the bend of a
typical dusty Arab village, and suddenly out of the bare, bleached hills, six
great golden columns thrust into the sky, and another great temple alongside
appears so complete, so perfect that it could be a film set, the whole site as
daunting and majestic to the twentieth-century traveller as this City of the
Sun, or Heliopolis as it was called, must have been to the subjects of its
dominions 2000 years ago.
Using an already ancient site, the Romans built the great complex to worship
three of their Gods, Jupiter, the Roman name for Baal, Bacchus, and Venus, but
though it took nearly 250 years to build, both its religious and political
message failed.
By 220.AD the Roman Empire was in decline, and Christianity had usurped the old
cults. Baalbek is one of history's most sublime examples of folie de grandeur.
For much of its next 2000 years Baalbek was half buried in the sand, as
graffiti, some as late as 1882, halfway up the columns reveal.
Inevitably statistics dominate. The six columns that remain out of the original
54 from the Temple of Jupiter are 67 feet in height, seven feet in diameter.
The smaller temple to Bacchus alongside is actually larger than the Parthenon.
Although the Romans were not usually subtle builders, there's an almost Semitic
sensuousness in the poppies, grapes and eggs, floral motifs often hanging
lopsidedly from walls and columns, which soften the stern Roman culture.
Virgins, wives, daughters, and prostitutes were offered to strangers in these
temples in this last bastion of the pagan faith, but the Christian Theodosius
smashed their idols and practices, Muslims later hacking out any faces of the
gods that remained, with earthquakes adding their toll.
But the great bulk of Baalbek is still there, almost too awe-inspiring to
tackle, but we're behind 38 coachloads of Sri Lankan housemaids (they earn
about $100 a month) and their boyfriends on a day out run by their priest, and
they have no such inhibitions.
They laugh, chatter, approach the altar and drape themselves round the pillars
like exotic butterflies, bringing the temple to life more than the most erudite
guidebooks.
At the gates of the site where the vendors cluster, the tour buses are parked
under Hizbollah signs in English and Arabic that read ``Islam is the solution
to all problems'', and ``Hizbollah, party of justice, truth and
egalitarianism'', and more sinisterly, in Arabic alone, another showing a large
machine-gun, though whatever the message, there is no hostility towards
visitors; everyone seems determined to enjoy their Sunday.
In the dusty square we consume delicious Baalbek lamb and onion pies, the Sri
Lankans have photos taken on three camels, while a group of Lebanese youths
pose in Arab headdress, and then preen themselves gazing long at their
reflections in the car windows. A young bootblack wanders disconsolately among
trainer-clad feet, a joyful Lebanese wedding party streams across the square as
the old fortune-teller in black at last finds a customer. Nothing could be more
peaceful.
We can't visit the old palace of Beiteddine as planned on our way back from
Baalbek because the Prime Minister is there, apparently having a
kiss-and-make-up session with the Druse leader and the site, and roads are
closed. So we divert to Aanjar instead, an ancient walled city built in the
eighth century by an Ummayad caliph Khalid el Walid, whose powerful influence
once spread from Spain to India.
By comparison with the massive grandeur of Baalbek, the ruined palaces, walls
and slender arches where an eastern court wined and danced, are refined,
delicate, and haunting.
A Lebanese family on an outing are just packing up after their Sunday picnic
under the cypress trees at the entrance, and as usual, the children rush to
greet us and practise their English. With one small boy I gravely discuss Garee
Linayka, his brother clutching a large expensive electronic keyboard; we
finally persuade him to give us a tune, expecting the latest chart-topper.
Instead, we get the strident Arab cadences of an old folk-tune, and as if by
magic, we form a circle, clapping spellbound as our Jocelyn and then the boy's
raven-haired sister, both in their tight western jeans, step into the circle,
and perform their own spontaneous belly dances, eyes flashing, hands
fluttering.
You feel the great Caliph would certainly have approved.
