<HEADLINE>Realms of a peaceful mind</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE most intimate world of Rosamunde Piclher is that of her imagination, from
which she has conjured such best-sellers as The Shell Seekers and now her
latest book, Coming Home. But her world also includes the temporal places where
she was brought up, has lived, and has worked. These permeate her books as the
atmospheric backgrounds to her tales of human emotion.
Reflecting the enormous international interest in her and everything connected
with her, an illustrated volume called The World of Rosamunde Pilcher has just
been published by Hodder and Stoughton. It had its genesis in Germany, where
Pilcher's most British of books enjoy a great vogue. Its sumptuous photography
could be appreciated even without reference to the text, which consists of
biographical snippets and apposite quotes from her work.
In the opening chapter, My Second Home, Pilcher demonstrates the quality of her
writing as she describes her first inauspicious contact with the little
Sutherland town of Dornoch and how later it came to entrance her enough to buy
a flat (above a bank) there.
One spring morning she felt she had returned to the past and sets the scene:
``It was cold, but the first daffodils were beginning to push up through the
rough grass; there was the smell of flowering currant and newly turned earth,
and somebody somewhere had lighted a bonfire.'' The prose is evocative,
familiar.
Sepia photographs illustrate Pilcher's early days: her childhood in Cornwall
(her father was a Royal Navy officer stationed in the Far East); her brief and
boring war-work with the Foreign Office in Woburn Abbey before she joined the
Wrens; her post-war marriage to Graham Pilcher.
The colour pictures of Cornwall are delectable. There is a thatched cottage
with window frames and arched door of cerulean blue (``It was a secret house
and, as well, a house that seemed to slumber in the past,'' goes the matching
text from The Shell Seekers). Pink florabunda roses spill across the foreground
of another picture which shows an old, high-eaved, country house with strapped
walls and tall brick chimneys and a lily pond. And away from the glowing
colours and intimacy of old gardens, the author laughs under a red umbrella on
Cornish rocks, patently at home with the sea.
A painting, it will be recalled, was central to the plot of The Shell Seekers.
A selection of canvases of the period includes one by Laura Knight of a
pigtailed girl staring at rocks and a swirling purple-blue sea. A modern,
abstract study of St Ives is accompanied by another excerpt from the same book,
enthusing about young men with bright visions who will come ``not to paint the
bay and the sea and the boats and the moors, but the warmth of the sun and the
colour of the wind''.
And still on painting, and still from The Shell Seekers, the central character
of the book muses on the thousand different blues of the sea: ``Over sand,
shallow and translucent, it was jade-green, streaked with aquamarine. Over
rocks and seaweed, it darkened to indigo. Far out where a small fishing boat
bucketed its way across the waves, it became a deep Prussian blue......'' The
words are mirrored by a photograph of foaming breakers with Godrevy Lighthouse
on its island beyond.
The bustle of lived-in, homely Cornwall is caught in a double study that shows
swans sailing in the orange and white water-shadows of fishing boats in Looe
Harbour.
London is another favoured setting for Pilcher's books and it yields some
atmospheric pictures - most notably a beautiful garden in the heart of Chelsea,
with a brick wall overhung with pink roses and the remains of afternoon tea on
a blue-checked table-cloth. Pilcher's writing celebrates domestic and civilised
enjoyments - and this intimate view seems to encapsulate the pleasures of house
and garden.
And thence to Scotland. The family scrap-album yields pictures of Graham and
Rosmary Pilcher with their four, now grown-up children; the welcoming house
they built in 1955 and still live in near Dundee; the revelation that the
best-selling author still works with a manual typewriter; and the reflection
from the couple of almost 50 years that ``marriage is like a job. A long
difficult job and both partners have to work harder than ever before''.
The Highland pictures are gorgeously atmospheric with brooding lochs and hills
and sparkling waters. But they are perhaps too familiar in nature to delight as
much as the southern ones. Less predictable is the view of the mini-village of
Crovie on the Moray Firth, its little houses all at characteristic right angles
to the sea. It matches a quote from The Blue Bedroom.
A bird's-eye view of the Royal Caledonian Ball is linked to this conversational
exchange from September about the Reel of the 51st Highland Division:
``Never heard of it.''
``It was devised in a German prison camp during the war.''
``It loooks extremely complicated.''
``Well, why not? They had five-and-a-half years to make the bloody thing up.''
Pilcher's humour - not too common a trait among her best-selling confrres -
had not really been hinted at until this point but it lurks again in the
picture of a black and white spaniel, paws on nose under heraldic emblems. The
caption says: ``Gun dog conserving its energy outside the shooting season in
Scotland.''
It would be nice to think that Pilcher had written that one herself.
n.The World of Rosamunde Pilcher, edited by Siv Bublitz with picture research
by Lieva Reunes, is published by Hodder and Stoughton at #20.
