<HEADLINE>Dangerous liaisons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anvar Khan and photographer Phil Rider spend a night on the road with the
Scottish Ambulance Service and discover that medical traumas are not the only
obstacles the crews have to overcome in an unjust and selfish society
IT'S Friday night, and all is quiet in Temazapam city. Glasgow, after two major
football matches, isn't fully celebrating the weekend. No-one has the energy or
the finance to drink enough to get into a fight. But private trouble is
everywhere. The night before, Peter Robinson, 34, a paramedic with the Scottish
Ambulance Service, had been called to a hanging.
He said his last shift had been a bad one because he had received ``genuine
calls''. Thanks to BT and its call-chasing facility, the number of hoax calls
to the emergency 999 number have dwindled. During the course of an eight-hour
shift, however, the ambulance service are asked to help various people in
varying degrees of danger.
``You wouldn't believe what people call an ambulance for,'' is a staff mantra.
Take the man who's had backache all week, for instance, and then decides on a
Saturday, at 2am, that he needs to go to hospital. And then there's the
consistent demand for service from Govan, where life is cheaper than a
phone-call. But more on that later.
The staff mess room at SAS HQ in Maitland Street has a TV, record player and
kitchen facilities. There's a cupboard full of cans and Mars bars - ``the
shop''. Framed photos of labrador puppies, potential dogs for the blind, sit
cutely on the wall. Here, paramedics and ambulance technicians await calls from
control.
Tonight, the control office is manned by three women. They receive up to 300
calls every 24 hours. It is their responsibility to gain the correct
information to pass on to the paramedic team. This is a challenge. People in a
panic tend to lose what they're sure they know, like their address. ``You can
hear assualts actually taking place,'' says Control Superintendent Denise
MacDonald, 43. ``It's very distressing.''
The public want ambulances because they're safe, but working one isn't. It
turns out that a crew was assaulted on the early shift, by a woman feigning
illness. Both men spent some time holding a somewhat personal item, between
their legs, in pain.
An ambulance is manned by two staff, a technician and a paramedic. Technicians
are on #16,000, paramedics on #17,000. I don't know what else ambulance service
men and women take home, but it can't always be job satisfaction. There is no
such thing as a mere ambulance driver. There's no room for anyone who isn't
trained to act in an emergency.
The paramedic can administer drugs because he must manipulate the status quo.
If a victim has a life-threatening injury, he must stablise them so they arrive
at hospital with a chance of survival.
Richard Kerr, 27, is a trainee technician. Two members of his family are
already in the ambulance service. He enjoys his job. Robinson and Kerr admit to
developing a morbid sense of humour, which even I get a taste of while hanging
around in front of the TV. You compare local knowledge with the time on your
watch and think, ``Someone must have been stabbed by now''.
The SAS is one of the few jobs, like soldiering, where violence ensures the
demand for your service.
A crew is called out to Govan, this happens a lot. Control reports that a
40-something woman in a ``slightly intoxicated'' state has fallen down tenement
stairs and possibly slashed a finger. A neighbour, in another act of melodrama,
has decided to forgo the search for a Band-aid or a cup of sobering tea, and
called for the paramedics. But no-one gets slightly intoxicated in Govan. ``It
doesn't matter how many times you ask them how much they've drunk,'' says
Robinson, as collegues respond to the call by slapping on gloves and a hard hat
(well, she could be a big wummin), ``It's always the standard response - two
pints''. The ambulance team can only hope to give her a plaster and a shunty up
to bed.
Robinson has long hours and a family, and hints at marginalisation when he
says, ``I just fit in with them''. Kerr has a dog called Gizmo, which he
insists on dragging out for walki
Robinson has to give overdose victims a drug called Narcan, which brings them
round ``to lucidity''. They awake sober and get abusive and upset. Why?
Robinson shrugs. ``It's #20 wasted, their trip is ruined.''
Euthanasia is illegal, but it is quite within someone's rights to smoke as much
as they want, or drink as much as they want until they get ill and die. A
victim of any emergency has the choice as to whether he's saved. A paramedic
will stabilise him, then get his signature on a form which entitles the
ambulance to leave, but the victim is allowed to change his mind. Do they ever
feel like just stomping off, when they're in the firing line? The boys nod.
``Frequently.''
What's the worst experience you've ever had? Robinson goes quiet as he offers:
``Cot-deaths are hard. You become a jack-of-all-trades, from trying to
resucitate someone to bereavement counselling.''
In Glasgow, there are 20-30 paramedics and only one is female. All must be
dedicated and professional, all must be responsible. For those who make it to
the grade of qualified ambulance technician, and want to go on to become a
paramedic, they are assessed each quarter. They either pass or fail exams,
there is no percentage mark. Training is interspersed with weeks in hospitals,
in cardiac, accident and emergency wards, and operating theatres. You only get
to be a paramedic when you're good and ready.
At 5.40pm, the crew check their ambulance and its supplies. All vans are kitted
out the same. Apart from drugs, equipment and trolley beds, each has a bottle
of Lucozade for boosting sugar levels. Never mind thieving junkies, with that,
passing athletes might be tempted too.
At 6.20pm we're called out on a non-emergency, our job, to take an old man in a
wheelchair to the Southern General. I follow the two men into a cluster of
sheltered housing in, you guessed it, sweet Govan.
I would call the old man's home a shed with a roof on. From the outside it
looks like a nice, wee council flat. Inside, he's growing orchids, it's
tropically hot. There's a trapeze above his bed, no carpets, no comforts, no
paint or wallpaper on the cardboard walls. He's wearing old black shoes of an
unrecognisable style. He has a sofa you might find on the pavement at a rip-off
merchant's on the South Side, and a record player circa 1970 at thigh-level.
There are gadgets to accommodate his disability, but they are covered in thick
dust. Endless wires are plugged into the sockets. The old man lives in mute
poverty. It's like walking into a brightly-lit collapsable sauna, turned into a
hideout from where he can devise some way of speaking.
As it happens, at the moment, the bent and buckled pensioner with a urinary
tract infection can only communicate through a heartbreakingly basic toy, a
battery-operated Speak and Spell which he clutches like a lifeline. With more
than an average appreciation of the value of communication, he tries to make
conversation in the back of the ambulance.
He tells Kerr he's always lived in Govan. A robotic voice annunciates each
letter the way the BT directory annunciates each number.
Blood and gore is the Hollywood film director's interpretation of horror, but
there are many versions of hell, as individual as the humans who comport each
idea. You don't need riots to be appalled in this job, you just need to see the
conditions in which some people are living. But the paramedics aren't in the
business of improving life, they prolong it. And in this society, that's the
measure of caring.
Talking about caring, the second stop is in the West End of Glasgow. It's
7.30pm, and a nursing home wants the ambulance to take an 80-year old woman
with a fractured femur to the Western. The nursing home don't want the press
inside. I hear the old lady going on about how someone trampled on her leg. A
member of staff tells her to ``stop her haverin' '', and joins us in the back
to accompany her to hospital.
The carer, carrying a can of Diet Coke and chewing gum, doesn't know much about
the old lady and can't answer Kerr's questions about her age or needs. ``My
lips are sticking together,'' the old dame cries, while strapped to the
stretcher. ``Lick yer lips,'' instructs the nurse. ``Put your tongue out and
rub it on your lips.''
The old woman does an impression of an iguana in the desert. ``I can't.''
Later, we pile in the back and wait, stationed at the tradesman's entrance, for
another call. We chat about nursing homes, and their reputations. ``We've been
in some crackers,'' Robinson sighs. In a statement, which to me infers
residential neglect on a wide-scale, he adds: ``You'd be amazed how many old
people we pick up who've fallen.''
At 8.55pm we get a call saying someone's been knocked over by a car in West
Princes Street. Probably a drunk. Amid flashing blue lights and sirens, we fire
through traffic, and at 9pm, another call comes over the radio. The onlooker
has cancelled the request. The street is checked anyway for stray bodies. At
9.03pm, we receive another call, an angina-attack in Knightswood. Such an
attack can be the precursor of a heart attack. The sirens go on again.
I think going to save a life is pretty straightforward, but you'd be amazed as
to how many otherwise sanguine members of the public feel obliged to prolong
the journey. If it was their relative they would be chewing the carpet, for
without conscientious drivers, the disciplined and speedy response of the
ambulance team is worth nothing.
A flash git in black BMW thinks that it's beneath him to pull over and pulls
out instead, thus impeding the ambulance's progress. A couple of dozy women
about to cross a dual carriageway, stop to look at the ambulance blaring
towards them. One stays on the pavement, the other runs out. She makes it but
Robinson has to slam on the brakes. I swear at her.
The 70-year-old lady at home in Knightswood had felt pain for an hour and a
half but didn't want to bother anyone. Her husband, already in hospital,
doesn't have long. Robinson tries to coagulate her, Kerr to calm her, but when
old people get frightened their main arteries contract, and the needle won't
take.
She's not in immediate danger, but the more tense she becomes the more pain she
receives. Her relatives escort the ambulance to the Royal.
Robinson takes the siren off so he doesn't alarm her any further. ``Now you'll
see how many people look in their rear-view mirror,'' he promises. Only the
blue lights are flashing, but I guess some road-abusers think that means the
driver's in a party mood.
We spend a good five minutes behind a line of traffic who do not move over
because they haven't noticed us. They look up, guiltily, when we finally
overtake, but guilt isn't enough. Again and again, cars dawdle. Kerr tells
Robinson to step on it because she's getting worse. I'm inwardly cursing every
apology on four wheels. Let's face it, the dying always have right of way.
</TEXT>
