<HEADLINE>Listen to some words of wisdom,  argues Allan Laing and . . . Let it be</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HELP! In a showbiz industry which thrives upon hyperbole, it is the greatest
hype of all. It might also turn out to be the saddest. Someone has fooled the
media - who in turn have fooled the public - into believing that The Beatles
are. The truth is that The Beatles were.
And that is why we love them so. They were the greatest pop group ever. No-one
did, no-one does, and no-one ever will surpass them. Forget Elvis. They alone
forged the template for a kind of music which affected a generation . . . and a
generation after that. For a handful of years they made our youthful lives
worthwhile and altered our image for evermore.
It is difficult to contemplate what life would be like today if The Beatles had
never existed. It would be a colourless world, one bereft of what we now call
pop culture. Without their contribution, the swinging sixties - their music,
their art, and their fabulous chaos - would never have happened.
But you must always talk about The Beatles in the past tense. When Mark Chapman
murdered John Lennon outside the Dakota Building in 1980, he took the very
breath away from the group, consigning it to history with a shot from a gun.
The Beatles couldn't be any more. The possibility of re-forming had gone
forever. So let it be.
Other groups were different. They could continue to continue even when death,
an all too common currency in rock music, intervened. The Stones survived when
Brian Jones died. The Who carried on without Keith Moon. The nature of these
bands made it possible simply to replace an individual member. But not so with
The Beatles. They were too intimately connected, each of them too crucial to
the creativity (or, rather, re-creativity) of the whole. And maybe, in a warped
kind of way, it was just as well.
Imagine a world where the once fab four were all still around and sometime,
let's say for the sake of argument the late eighties, they patched up their
differences and decided to re-form. What resulted might have been good; it
might have been very good. Then again, it might have been bad or, worse still,
it might have been simply average. The only certainty is that, whatever form it
took, it would never have held a candle to the work which The Beatles released
between 1963 and 1969. You cannot, after all, improve upon the perfect.
``Liverpool Lads Enlist Rap Star To Help Flagging Career!'' Mercifully not. So
the fact that the greatest pop group in history cannot now come together is a
blessing, surely. Fate has ensured that they can't ruin it for all of us. What
we have is what they left behind. A legacy of beautiful music. Wondrous
memories.
And then some well-intentioned someone comes along
Not until the end of the eighties, when Apple finally settled their business
differences with EMI, did it finally emerge as a serious proposition. For the
past three years, Apple's television production offshoot has painstakingly
searched the world's archives for the rarest and most precious footage of the
group in concert, in the studio, and in conversation. McCartney, Harrison, and
Starr also provided a wealth of personal material - in addition to some frank
and lengthy interviews.
Of the three musicians, it seems it was Harrison who was most anxious to ensure
that the project went ahead. His reasons may have been primarily altruistic but
there was certainly a strong financial element involved. To put it bluntly, he
was the one who most needed the money. The demise of his movie business,
Handmade Films, seriously affected his once-sizable fortune. He should have
little to worry about in the future. The documentary, for which the American TV
rights alone cost the giant ABC network a reputed $20m, should earn Paul,
George, Ringo, and Yoko Ono (the latter on behalf of Lennon's estate) as much
as #70m, particularly when you take into account the massive spin-off in
records and video sales.
What we are promised is a warts-and-all portrait. The real story. Something we
should cherish, for it is unlikely that the three survivors will ever again
involve themselves in such a project.
Now comes the hype. ITV, having paid an estimated #5m to Apple Productions for
the series, naturally wish to make the most of it. So they embark upon this
massive public-awareness campaign. Suddenly there is a media blitz on The
Beatles. It starts with major articles in all the smart glossy magazines. Then
it moves to tabloid overkill. Finally, the quality press take the intellectual
high ground and start trying to analyse The Beatles' popularity. We are in the
middle of a nostalgia frenzy (this article, by its very nature, is part of it).
And there is more. To coincide with the launch of the programme, EMI (which,
like all record companies, is never slow in coming forward when there's a
marketing opportunity available) dusts down its old discarded Beatles tracks
from the vaults and prepares to release them in a blaze of reflected glory. It
already had a dry run last year with The Beatles Live at the BBC, a double-CD
of interesting but essentially inferior tracks from the group's early days,
which nevertheless sold more than five million copies.
The new recordings, also entitled The Beatles Anthology, will be much better.
Of that there can be little doubt. Produced in association with Apple, who
finally came to an agreement with EMI over access to the group's huge back
catalogue of material, it will consist of three double CDs (only the first will
be released this year) combining studio music, live recordings, radio and TV
sessions, and private tapes. Most of it has never been heard before. The
recordings have been carefully remixed by George Martin, appropriately in the
legendary Studio 2 at Abbey Road - using 1960s equipment for the sake of
authenticity - and Paul, George, and Ringo were also heavily involved in the
track selection process.
Among the 40-odd rare tracks on the first album are previously unreleased
versions of such Lennon/McCartney songs as Love Me Do, Please Please Me, and A
Hard Day's Night along with never-heard-before tracks such as In Spite Of All
Danger, an embryonic McCartney composition which was recorded by Lennon's
Quarrymen in 1958, a version of Ray Charles's Hallelujah I Love Her So from
1960, and Leiber and Stoller's Searchin'.
And then there's the big one. Or, to be more precise, the big two. Shortly
before his untimely death, Lennon made some rough recordings in New York of two
new songs, Real Love and Free As A Bird. As part of their involvement in the
anthology project, the three survivors took Lennon's demos and (together with
Martin) reworked them to include their backing vocals and instrumentation. So,
effectively, what we have are two brand new Beatles recordings. Which is rather
wonderful, whichever way you look at it.
Take away these two tracks, however, and what you have is an album of inferior
recordings. Like all bandwagon ``rarity'' recordings, they've been languishing
in the vaults for one good reason. And that is the fact that they probably
weren't very good in the first place. If The Beatles and George Martin had
considered them worthy, then they would have been released at the time. If you
like Love Me Do then you'll already have it; the best of it. Why should you
need it again?
Is this a tad churlish? Well, perhaps. As a true Beatles fan (they really did
influence my life; there was a time when a day never passed without me playing
their records), I look forward to the documentary series. I am genuinely
excited by the prospect. The series, after all, has been made with great love
and care by people of my fortysomething vintage. It affords us the opportunity
to re-create a portion of our youth. Perhaps it will even allow us to finally
persuade our techno-brat children that, without The Beatles, their music would
never have been. The Beatles, it appears, have never been more hip. Oasis are
not the only group to fall under their musical influence; they are merely the
latest. Blur even aped the fab four by playing up on the rooftops, Get Back
style. Clearly, The Beatles have cast a spell over a significant number of
today's guitar-based groups.
So are The Beatles - as were - really worth the hype - as is? Well, try
comparing them to anyone else. The Stones? Queen? Springsteen? Massive, yes.
Maybe even legendary in their own sweet way. But they could never hope to touch
The Beatles.
Part of the reason, of course, is the fact that The Beatles came first - which
gave them a head start. But in their short history, The Beatles quite simply
created the best pop music ever. If there were defining mom-ents during that
golden age of creative expression, the sixties, then it was John, Paul, George,
and Ringo who defined them. With every album, they moved the whole thing
forward. It was then left to everyone else to catch up.
They wrote and performed some of the most enduring music of the twentieth
century. A catalogue of more than 200 Northern Songs. They were witty, they
were dangerous, they were romantic, they were weird . . . they were damned near
everything under the sun. But, above all else, they were the best.
Choose a Beatles song? You can't. Choose half-a-dozen? You still can't. Choose
an album? Well, we've all got our favourite. With me it's Sgt Pepper because it
fondly reminds me of a time and an age. You can argue, but that recording (and
this is obviously a personal view and not a statement of fact) was not only The
Beatles' finest moment but also pop music's greatest achievement. It's a cliche
but it truly was the album by which all future albums would be judged. After
that it was downhill, albeit ever so slowly, for The Beatles. A long and
winding road to the inevitable break-up.
The double White Album was undoubtedly a tour de force but there were tiny,
almost imperceptible, signs of a worrying drop in quality, perhaps even
commitment. It was too long for a start and a few of the tracks (Revolution No.
9, in particular) smacked of self-indulgence. But, like everything else about
The Beatles, it was all relative. It was and still remains a masterpiece.
The White Album, we know now, was where the cracks began to appear. It was too
ambitious a project which took far too long to record. The pressure to create
served to adversely affect relationships. But, despite the hassles, they
soldiered on.
When they recorded the tracks for what would eventually be ``posthumously''
released as the Let It Be album the acrimony, hidden from view until then, was
achingly apparent and (thanks to a film crew's ubiquitous presence) recorded
for posterity. Lennon and McCartney were at each other's throats. Finally, in
the summer of 1969 they recorded Abbey Road and it was over. The Beatles were.
BEATLE-ZANIA
French Interviewer: The French have not made up their minds about the Beatles.
What do you think of them?
John: Oh, we like the Beatles. They're gear.
F.I: Do you like topless bathing suits?
Ringo: We've been wearing them for years.
John in an interview with Maureen Cleave:
Christianity will go. It will vanish and shrink. We`re more popular than Jesus
now; I don't know which will go first, rock'n'roll or Christianity. Jesus was
all right, but his disciples were thick and ordinary.
American Interviewer: Sorry to interrupt you while you are eating, but what do
you think you'll be doing in five years, when all this is over?
John: Still eating.
American Interviewer: What do you call your haircut?
George: Arthur.
American Interviewer: Do you wear wigs?
John: If we do, they must be the only ones with real dandruff.
British Interviewer (after the Beatles had received their MBEs): What about the
Queen?
Paul: She's lovely, great. She was just like a mum to us.
American Interviewer: One of your hits is Roll Over, Beethoven. What do you
think of Beethoven?
Ringo: He's great. Especially his poems.
