<HEADLINE>How coffee  could become  a has-bean</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE little insect above looks harmless enough, but it could sour your morning
coffee, and it could drive the price of cappuccino out of sight. It's the
coffee berry borer beetle. It's incestuous, resistant to pesticides, and it is
a problem.
A new strain of the insect, entomologists say, could represent a serious threat
to the international coffee industry because it is resistant to the most
commonly used insecticides.
And because the beetle has a rare and unusual means of reproduction, the gene
that gives it protection from the pesticide may spread through the world
population faster than might be expected with other insects.
Scientists at Purdue University, and the Institut Francais de Recherche
Scientifique in New Caledonia say the bug's unusual sexuality is a threat to
the world's #10bn coffee trade. Females outnumber males by a 10-to-1 ratio. The
few males in the brood are unable to fly and never leave the coffee bean so
they mate with their flighty sisters before they fly off the bean.
This incestuous relationship increases the likelihood that offspring will
receive two doses of the resistance gene. Because of this, the resistance is
likely to spread throughout the population much faster.
Besides being of interest to Java junkies and those interested in the sexual
behaviour of insects, the coffee berry borer is intriguing to scientists
because recent discoveries indicate that the beetle may be an intermediate step
in the evolution of one of nature's genetic mysteries.
Most creatures, including humans, other mammals, birds and insects, have two
sets of chromosomes or genes, each inherited from either parent. However, in
one large class of insects that includes ants, wasps and bees, the males have
only one set of chromosomes, which they inherit from the mother. The coffee
berry borer appears to be an unusual intermediate between the two types. In the
coffee berry borer, the males receive both sets of chromosomes, but they shut
off the set they receive from the father.
