<TEXT>
SCOTTISH contractors made their mark once again last night following last
year's successful judging when nine entries were nominated for awards. Out of a
total of more than 78 entries, with three from overseas, the panel of judges
commented that winners ``scored high on all accounts''.
In the Domestic Garden Scheme Construction Category, costing more than #10,000,
Lorne Landscapes were principal award winners. Their instruction required the
planning and landscaping of grounds around an old farmhouse that overlooked
Loch Creran.
Trees had to be cleared and farm machinery removed from around the house which
is built on a ridge of gravel. A boggy area behind the house was drained and a
lochan constructed to produce a natural finish. An area of 12 acres was planted
in oaks and 15 varieties of trees and shrubs and a sweeping dry stane dike
measuring 300 yards built.
The design also won an award from Argyll and Bute based on buildings and
landscaping section.
Another principal award winner was Wilkinson Landscapes Ltd of Co Durham. In
the Domestic Garden Scheme Construction category costing less than #10,000 the
award centred on landscaping including the building of patio, steps, rock
retainers and pond at a house in an estate in the village of Newton Aycliffe.
The new de-sign gave a much bigger sitting area in Yorkshire style paving with
gravel and planting areas. A timber pergola helped soften the side utility area
and sandstone was used to build retaining walls for the top garden. A pond with
rock steps was positioned to be visible from the bungalow, and provide access
to the top lawn.
Premier One Tree Services Ltd of Linlithgow has won an award in the Grounds
Maintenance category for its maintenance and general upkeep work carried out at
General Accident's data processing unit in Dundee. Last year the company won an
award in the Soft Landscape Construction category for the same facility.
Designers were Ian White Associates of Stirling. Chairman of the adjudicators,
Bill Gillespie commented: ``An excellent example of good honest workmanship and
planned, directed effort. The result shows exactly why clients should use BALI
contractors for satisfaction and value for money.''
Landscaping takes many forms and is often carried out in a variety of
conditions and locations. Rentokil Tropical Plants of Bath was given the task
of internal planting on the Oriana cruise liner, a design installation that had
to consider the various environments found on board a ship such as the swings
of temperature between pool areas and open decks.
On the face of it the project was not too dissimilar to the design installation
for an office, however, the company had a logistics headache when the liner
instead of docking at Southampton stayed in Germany. And plants, pots and
personnel were packed up for an unexpected journey.
But for their efforts the company won an award in the design and build
category. Its Aberdeen office was also successful in the interior landscape
category with its work carried out at Amereda Hess, an oil company in the
granite city. Particular reference was made to the quality of maintenance and
work in the reception area.
In the Interiors Landscape Installation category at cost over #10,000, Waterers
Landscape Ltd, Windlesham, Surrey appeared winners for work completed in a
Government building in Cheltenham. The company acquired, climatised and
installed the plants in an exotic interior scheme for an atrium created by
adapting a courtyard wrapped round by the existing buildings and relying on the
adjoining office heating.
The scheme has achieved its objective by greatly improving the staffs' working
environment and where they may relax in colourful exotic surroundings amid
Kentia Palms from the Pacific, Zagloul Palms from Egypt, Adonia Palms from
Florida and Peace Lillies from Columbia.
Bromeliads were used for underplanting and although normally tree climbers,
they have been used for their bright and exotic colours over a long flowering
season. Some replicas (silk flowers) have been used in those areas where the
supplementary lighting is insufficient.
The Soft Landscape Construction Scheme, under one hectare, was won by Evergreen
Landscapes of Bristol. The concept of the display garden was to provide a
showcase for its potential clients. The garden is also used by charities for
open fundraising days and as a domestic garden site.
David Stevens was required to design a garden suitable for personal use and
also as a client display garden. It had to reflect quality of work, use
different materials and show a variety of styles yet retain the effect of a
complete garden. The completed garden has a multitude of materials and plants
to create areas with swings of style and mood. Some of the features include
timber and metal arches, shrub borders, rockery, waterfall, lawns and seating
areas.
A Scottish company, New Lands (Contracts) Ltd of East Kilbride won an award in
the Grounds Maintenance (with limited public access) category for its work at
Gap Housing Association, Glasgow.
In this contract the work comprised the reinstatement of overgrown gardens and
open spaces plus regular maintenance. Additional sites are being added to the
contract as new build properties come out of their defects liability period,
and as existing older properties are acquired by the housing association.
The range of properties are quite diverse, ranging from traditional red
sandstone tenement blocks to new purpose-built sheltered housing complexes. The
regional contract currently covers Greater Glasgow, Monklands, Renfrewshire,
Ayrshire and Dunbartonshire.
Last year New Lands (Contracts) won a Principal Award for Grounds Maintenance
for the Northern Development Area, East Kilbride.
Bill Peebles, chairman, welcomes delegates
Following last year's massive success, the British Association of Landscape
Industries has once again brought its national landscape awards ceremony to the
city of Glasgow. But not only that, its annual conference, entitled
Benchmarking - Managing the Process has also been incorporated.
As last year, there are a wide selection of winners, encompassing Scotland's
Bali Contractors, who have won a significant number of awards themselves. This
year, awards have been made to a domestic garden in North-east England, a major
hard landscape site in Glasgow; P&amp;O's flagship cruise liner, Oriana; and an oil
rig in the North Sea. This clearly identifies the work that BALI contractors
undertake and the quality of that work
