IT'S been foretold by the techno-wizards who say the television in the corner
will be used just like a computer . . . and vice versa. Well, sooner than
later, this is it, the PCTV, the conjunction of systems.
Made by Fujitsu ICL, it's an all-in-one box that is computer, television, and
CD player, and the makers claim that while it's small, it's big on
entertainment, education, and convenience. Possibly it's ideal for users who
fancy a break and get bored by those interminable screen savers. They can
simply switch to television and enjoy Cell Block H.
The whole thing comes as one unit plus a keyboard, and with only one mains
lead. The first PC to have a built-in fully functioning TV, the picture quality
is said to be very high, even when viewed close up, and it has Nicam
digi-stereo playing through two flush speakers developed from Philips'
ground-breaking Acoustic Horn system.
ICL say their baby explodes the myth that computers are complicated. It's aimed
at the new-user market, people who might find technology a turn-off, but will
find this easy to turn on. It even has a remote control for that very purpose.
PCTV comes with an on-screen tutorial, illustrated by picture images for
instructions in keyboard use, and it has a built-in trackball. The system can
be programmed through Teletext for personal TV listings and will even send a
busy user a screen message to say when a programme is about to start.
Probably ideal for people with little spare space, and an idea that hi-tech
should be low profile. Comes in at #1500 less #1.
GLASGOW has become a dear green place once again, thanks to the big city
clean-up campaign. And this is not good news. The green is caused by algae,
which is causing a sheen on stone buildings. According to Dr Norman Tennent of
the University of Strathclyde's Department of Pure and Applied Chemistry, some
chemicals used to clean buildings has made them vulnerable to algae attacks.
Even the City Chambers in George Square has gone down with a dose of the
greens. Dr Tennent organised a recent meeting of scientists working in the
field of art and architectural conservation to address these and other
problems. The major museums and galleries including the V &amp; A, British Museum
and the National Museums of Scotland were represented.
In a city such as Glasgow, the algae problem could have further cultural
effects in the city of culture. If scientists don't find a cure for the greens,
they will probably have to look to the biochemists to develop a blue algae,
just to keep the cultural, if not the ecological, balance.
THE ancients used snow stored in straw-packed boxes. Later, scientists used
the principle of evaporation cooling to invent the refrigerator. Now a group of
Israeli scientists have taken cool a further leap forward. They've invented
``liquid'' ice.
Ontec Ltd in Beersheva has developed a liquid ice generation system which
produces a gel-like slush, based on fresh or sea water and a number of secret
ingredients. The system, they say, not only cools the slush and freezes it more
efficiently than standard ice machines, but it produces a coolant as cold as,
or even colder than, ice. But while it's frigid, it ain't rigid, so this super
coolant will pump to where it's needed.
The firm say they've succeeded in binding the superior heat transfer capacity
of ice to the superior fluid attributes of water. The new development rests
solidly on the laws of physics. The process produces crystals surrounded by a
fluid jacket which prevents the crystals from sticking together the way water
crystals do, which gives them enough fluidity to circulate in cooling systems
which make them work better.
The fluid ice can also be made during the night when power is cheaper and when
the temperature is cooler, making the manufacture cheaper too.
MICROSOFT say they will add support for the digital ISDN telephone service to
their Windows 95 operating system to enable rapid access to information. The
company say ISDN solves the need for higher data transmission speeds, with a
ten-fold increase over traditional analogue modems. The support enables rapid
access to the Internet.
