<HEADLINE>Uncorking the gene genie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Donnelly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As we continue to coat the planet in plastic,
Joe Donnelly asks if we're laying the foundations
of years of scientific research for our descendants
ABOUT 67 million years ago, the dinosaurs were wiped out. Scientists believe
their extinction may have been triggered by a global catastrophe caused by an
asteroid impact on the earth. This theory is based on the discovery of a layer
of iridium, only a few centimetres deep, which has been found around the world
and has been dated to around the time the big lizards died.
What has this to do with today's technology, you may ask. Here's the answer. In
as many millions of years into the future, scientists, human or otherwise, will
find a thin layer of rare and complex molecules under the earth's surface.
Their tests will date it to the late twentieth century. If they have
sophisticated equipment, they will be able to show the layer was laid down in a
mere 70 years or so, and then suddenly stopped.
This layer will be plastic: complex chains of tough organic polymers, dumped
all over the world by messy humans. The fact that the deposit will suddenly
stop, could be down to the work of one Scotsman.
He is Dr Oliver Peebles, from Slamannan, near Grangemouth, a PhD graduate of
Aberdeen University, now working in Cambridge, Massachusetts. His claim to
fame, and it's a fair claim too, is that he's done some very interesting
recombinant DNA work with bacteria, which makes them do something quite
astounding. They make plastic.
What's more, it's a plastic which breaks down after it's been used, and it's
likely to have a stunning effect on our planet's ecology.
A century ago, plastic was virtually unknown, except as a laboratory curiosity.
Now it's the most ubiquitous substance used by man. Where once plastic bags
were a novelty, now they're stuck in every tree and barbed wire fence. Bottles,
containers, and all sorts of objects made from the stuff litter our beaches and
hedgerows. Future scientists will have no trouble finding it, because it will
still be there, intact, in millions of years. Plastic lasts forever. In
comparison, a diamond is for about ten minutes.
NOW Peebles, who has a BSc in biochemistry and a doctorate in molecular
biology, has married his two fields of expertise to get bugs to make what man
has been looking for - a plastic which is tough enough to last as long as
needed, then breaks down into something environmentally nice. What's more, he's
able to transfer the bacteria genes to get plants to do the same thing on a
huge scale.
``We use recombinant DNA systems to make polymers,'' says Peebles, who has
co-founded the Metabolics Company, next to Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, to develop the system. He came to MIT in 1984 and got involved in
applying molecular biology to industrial problems, a fairly open field as most
of his peers were working on new drugs.
``The first stage was to get bacteria to manufacture types of polymer as a food
store. The next is to use the genetic material from the bacteria to get plants
to do the same thing, and we can then form it into film and plastic bags and
containers.
``The great thing is that when it's used, it can be thrown into a compost heap
and it will simply be eaten by bacteria so that it will be broken down again.
``The system was pioneered in the seventies by ICI, who produced a commercial
product, but it was prohibitively expensive. Now there is a demand for a cheap
plastic which is biodegradable. If you think of all those disposable nappies,
fast-food containers, bottles, and the like, they will be around forever. On
the Continent, some Governments, like Germany's, are really pushing this kind
of development because there is real concern about the ecology. Sooner or
later, we will have to realise the plastic problem will not go away, unless we
develop a plastic that will go away.
``We have developed cutting-edge gene technology for making the stuff, and we
can make it at a cost the market will accept. When you think that the
biodegradable market is about #500m, it's really worthwhile.
``Our gene technique allows us to make the plastic for about $4 a kilo, which
is still high compared to polystyrene. But that price will come down because we
have patented a method of splicing the genes into plants like rapeseed which
can be used as agri-manufacturers to make the plastic for us.
``Already, the world is developing industrial agriculture to manufacture some
goods. Now we have the technology which will allow farms to make vast
quantities of industrial plastic that is truly degradable.
``Our plastic, derived from crops, will break down in the soil, or in the sea.
If you look at the shores around Scotland, littered with plastic, that can only
be a good thing. Plastic itself is a great material and people like it. They
don't want to go back to glass bottles for every liquid, but people don't like
to think we are polluting the world by dumping uncountable millions of tons of
the stuff that will never erode.
``Very soon, there will be a great pressure on industry to use materials which
are much more environmentally friendly. As long as it is cheap enough to
produce, then industry, and therefore the consumer, will welcome it.
``I'll be pleased to have played a part in that. The day is coming when we will
be able to buy as many plastic-wrapped goods as we want, then simply bury the
stuff in our gardens to help plants to grow.
``That's a great deal better than leaving it lying around for millions of
years.''
