VINCENT is a reputedly revolutionary new digital video engine from Data
Translation. Data says the single-card engine for Apple's Powermac systems is a
benchmark for digital video power, quality, and simplicity. It augments and
improves on the two-card design to give users higher performance.
HEWLETT-Packard has announced the HP CopyJet printer-copier, the first to
integrate colour printing and digital copying in one unit. Selling at #2139,
the system copies at around 5p a page.
LOGITECH, a frontrunner in pointing devices, has launched the TrackMan Marble,
a thumb-operated trackball with marble sensing technology for tracking ball
movement. The system offers virtually maintenance-free and consistently smooth
operation.
WITH computer theft on the increase and a huge surge evident in black-market
chips, ICL, one of the major suppliers of personal computers in Europe, has
been taking steps to combat the hardware thieves.
ICL computers now come with anti-theft devices which protect them in the same
way as car radios. If the machine is disconnected from mains power, it can only
be used again, once reconnected, after the user has given a pre-specified
password. There's also a password protection, a dual level key word that can be
set to prevent unauthorised start-up after the machine has been switched on.
Without the password, the system software will fail to load.
Data files are also encrypted with a user specific key which prevents them
being read. The protection is built into the normal windows interface and
protects files on fixed and exchangeable media and across networks.
Physically, the internal hardware can be protected, to a degree, with a
mechanical key lock which seals the PC cabinet to prevent unauthorised access
to the works, helping to prevent theft of data and valuable hardware like disc
drives and feature cards.
ICL says all its products carry bar and serial numbers enabling them to be
tracked to commercial users and purchasers. It is examining the most effective
way of registering and tracking all PCs sold to individual purchasers, and is
toying with the idea of including an ultra-violet marking kit with every
computer as a simple, proven, and cost-effective deterrent.
IT'S a brave, interactive and integrated new world, according to Granada, the
TV rental firm, which predicts that by the year 2000 more than half the
households in Britain will have at least one personal computer and will have
gone interactive.
Granada's look at the future paints a rosy virtual picture of computer-control,
with almost everything from voice recognition systems for door entry security
to switching on appliances. PCs will be so sophisticated that home automation
will be the norm, doing almost everything but the vacuum-cleaning. The gadgets
for the new century, according to Granada, include the Plasmotron, the ultimate
Flat Screen television which is only three inches thick and simply hangs on the
wall. Starting prices are expected to be about #7000, but should be affordable
by 2001.
Digital television will have a simple decoder on top of the television with a
tiny antenna to pick up CD quality sound and digital pictures with access to
some 200 channels, making the roof aerial extinct. Interactive television and
video will let viewers choose not only what they watch but also how to end the
film. Granada also predicts that people will soon be able to participate live
in TV games shows. Did we say the future looked rosy?
And there's more. The shape of things to come will also have a face . . . an
unpaid and willing slave who appears as a computer model on touch-screen, at
one's beck and call to do all those little tasks like setting alarms, doing the
shopping and even, so Granada bravely suggests, phoning one's mother.
</TEXT>
