<HEADLINE>Liars who saw the light</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPAGANDISTS in the Second World War may have been inadvertently telling the
truth when they were telling whoppers.
Trying to disguise the early use of radar, the War Office said that British
pilots were eating carrots, which gave them much-improved night vision.
In fact, Vitamin A, found in high concentrations in carrots, seems to be
successful in combating a rare genetic disorder which causes blindness. The
vitamin is converted by the eye into retinal, a molecule which is used to
detect light. In tests, one patient found his night-blindness had returned
after concentrated doses of Vitamin A. So Bugs Bunny was far-sighted
after all
Los Alamos resear-chers, working with Texas Instruments of Dallas, have
developed a prototype electronic module that allows a huge increase in the
amount of miniaturised circuitry packed into a single package and vastly boosts
its performance. The ``High-Density Interconnect'' multichip module achieves
twice the density of circuit interconnections found in other comparable
technology. The HDI module demonstrates better performance, lower power
consumption, and higher reliability than existing systems, making it ideal for
applications in space systems and just about everything else.
Flatulence from farm animals is thought to be one source of greenhouse gases.
They increase when food animals are fed cereals, and it's a serious and
evil-smelling pollutant in major producing centres. Chemicals firm Rhone
Poulenc has applied for a British patent on a system which curbs all this hot
air by adding glucanaze to the feed. A check on the ammonia levels in a chicken
battery was significantly lower after the diet, tests showed.
</TEXT>
