<HEADLINE>A scarlet letter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323439</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The hype makes Anvar Khan pout but she finally has to admit it's the colour
that will be on everyone's lips
MAKE-UP designers are making a big meal of colour co-ordination this Christmas.
They say you should wear red lipstick at fancy dress and office parties. Red,
they enthuse, makes a woman seem vampish and seductive, dangerous and
delicious, brooding and beautiful.
Designers are big on adjectives. I always find it completely outrageous that
anyone should expect a lifetime's mess of emotion to suddenly simplify and
produce a clear-minded and choreographed vixen for the party season, merely by
choosing a more bloody shade of lipstick. I see red often, as it happens, as I
am becoming much more intolerant than I used to be.
I resent time laid aside for dealing with the stupid and the cloying. But
thankfully I see red more often on some silly, insipid wee girl who wants to
appear grown-up and in control.
Celebrities with their own range of make-up, such as Paloma Picasso, have
customised the colour red and parade it as the insignia of a sultry, Latin
temperament, and it works. When the time comes to entertain some kind of
abandon, the wannabee hedonists pull out the Mon Rouge.
n Yves Saint Laurent Teint sur Mesure #32; YSL Poudre Semi Libre #26; YSL Rouge
Definition #17.50; Mascara Moire #14; Dessin Kohl Eyeliner #8; Paloma Picasso
Mon Rouge available from large department stores.
THE Cheap and Cheerful Department at Beauty Box Headquarters suggests
handpainting washed out T-shirts with Dylon's range of dyes and fabric paints
in order to give them a new lease of life.
Indeed, Dylon are somewhat fanatical about getting the public to start
painting. This is a mission perhaps, to help us find the creative urge within
the adult, supressed from childhood onwards. The best way, they infer, to deal
with constipation of an artistic nature, is to paint  surreal designs on your
clothes, then you can go around showing them off.
In fact, get enough people to do it and you could sit on the subway and play
spot-the-neurosis. Dylon, the therapists of the future, have even provided a
consumer hotline which will dispense advice, a sort of psychiatrists's chair.
Maybe it backchats with questions such as ``Why do you feel the need to paint
yellow circles and red spots on your Conran shirt? Do you see them often?'' If
only it was so, but I guess it's just a service for helping you find that
particular shade of magenta.
Dylon Consumer Advice Line 0181 663 4296.
Not quite role models
KNOWING we'll be interested, Options magazine has sent Beauty Box a synopsis of
the contents of the latest issue. Something called The Facts Behind the Figures
- Supermodel Vice Survey. The feature tries to deal the dirt on the true lives
of the models and we have been kindly supplied with a chart for our persual,
which we duly distorted.
What do supermodels drink? 92% drink beer; 8% responded: ``What is drink?''
What do they eat? 85% eat red meat; 15% queried: ``What is eating?''
What vices do they have? 78% smoke and own a push-up bra; 22% are push-ups.
What about their weight? 65% have never dieted; 35% prefer bulimia.
What about stress? 57% bite their nails; 43% marry rock stars.
What about chat? 42% own a cellular phone; 58% confess to not learning how to
converse.
Who do they date? 35% date actors or rock stars; 65% don't understand the
concept.
And ambitions? 14% take acting classes; 86% can't think.
n BRITISH Home Stores ``Lingerie Fortnight'' is an exclusive promotion which
aims to encourage women to pamper themselves. For every #30 spent in the
lingerie, sleepwear, and hosiery departments, Christmas shoppers will receive a
gift voucher worth #5 to use in the same departments plus womenswear.
Intriguingly, BHS tell Beauty Box all about their tempting ``warm, brushed
cotton-pyjamas in a striking tartan'', a wonderful buy at #25, but what about
satin suspenders and stockings and lacy French knickers? I mean, in what way is
buying a romper suit, settling down for the night in purdah, pampering oneself?
No wonder men buy women sexy undies. It's not because they want to humiliate
you, or want a baby doll, they just thought you'd fancy a change.
The BHS `Lingerie Fortnight' voucher offer runs nationwide and ends on
November 26.
Confession of a
sugar plum fairy
UNDER a pelt of tomatoes and accusations of Scrooge, I have to say I hate this
season. It's fun choosing Christmas presents, but I hate the endless round of
parties. It wouldn't matter if I got invited to any interesting ones but I
don't. And after coming out as a crabby prude, I certainly won't be now.
I am not, therefore, at all worried about how I'll look in that bare-backed,
mini-dress with the shoelace straps, as Weightwatchers has kindly pointed out I
might be wearing. The ``Fat Police'' as I call them are doing their rounds,
asking us to grab an inch or a foot or two of food, thoughtfully stored up
during the summer for any cold, starving nights this winter.
Their press release shouts joyfully, like a born-again Christian asking you to
repent, ``Be Fab not Flabby this Christmas''. Oh whoopee! Wouldn't you rather
be fabby than flabby? I love that word-play. Weightwatchers then go on about
how to deal with the shock that you can't do your zips right up to the waist, a
part of your anatomy, of course, which is disappearing altogether under folds
of flesh piled up on top of each other, like blankets in the spare room.
In order to lose weight, they advise, take a look at some of the recipes in
their Merry Christmas Cookbook. There's Golden Stuffed Turkey and Chocolate
Pots with Tia Maria or Chestnut and Vegetable Stir-fry. And if they can't bore
you off food, they have ``real-life experts'' who've drawn up ``a multitude of
cunning ploys to deal with social problem areas''. What? Society has other
social problems apart from fat people?
WW's suggest saying to people who pester you to have a drink, that your glass
of orange juice really contains vodka. That's a good idea - it means you can
cheat while taking part in drinking-each-other-under-the-table competitions. If
you can tear yourself away from a set of scales, that is.
Weightwatchers' Christmas Cookbook is available at meetings throughout the
country. For details of your nearest meetings call 01628 777077.
</TEXT>
