<HEADLINE>Rustle hearty, you philistine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It was an ordinary night at the theatre when Marcella Evaristi looked back in
anger to confront the phantom sweetie-eater
I WAS at the theatre the other night, in a Dress Circle seat (an expensive
treat from a kind friend), leaning forward on the velvety balcony, riveted by
Stoppard's cat's-cradle of dialogue pulling in and out of itself, when the
first little crackle happened. Directly behind me. My head did a tiny sideways
twitch and I thought ``Bloody hell, a theatre sweetie merchant'', and grudged
the distraction. I hope it's the flavour you loathe, that coffee-and-rum one, I
thought, and you haven't noticed in the dark - our dark - my dark. May it lodge
itself on to your plate like black Blu-Tak so your tongue has to battle with
your dentures till the interval. I thought, please unwrap it quickly will you
so I can forget this tick of distraction ever happened. For after the
unwrapping surely you will pop your stupid sweetie in your stupid mouth (I'm
not at all nice when I'm concentrating).
But this was a seriously selfish crackle. This was no apologetic ``I'm sorry,
I'll unwrap very quickly, I promise I will, I won't try and do it subtly and
slowly - that only prolongs the agony - I will do it rippingly, like an
Elastoplast, to get it over with. I'm sorry, but believe me, it's better this
way. Honestly, I'd be coughing like Steptoe otherwise. And I swear it's not a
crunchy one, it's a silent sookie one. Soon you'll forget it ever happened.''
Oh no.
Behind-Me's crackling was taking too long for that. The noise scrunched
relentlessly towards my head; it stalked nearer and nearer while the whole
stage began drifting further away and down. The generous ticket money was spent
waste now, for suddenly I was sitting in the very back row of the gods. Through
a sickness of vertigo I could barely focus on Sharon Maughan, much less hear
what she was saying. One minute she was explaining how that early
nineteenth-century landscape commonly held to be organically archetypally
English, was in fact a contrived vista whose source was human painters, not
``nature'' at all. Next minute, all I could make out was that she was tilting
her head wryly and lifting a cup. She might as well have been back in her Gold
Blend advert.
I realised no mere sweetie was involved here. It must be a Crunchie. No, it was
even taking too long for that. I missed something major on stage involving
Newton and Byron as I considered the alternatives. Yes, I whisper. Yes. My
friend glances towards me, thinking I have softly endorsed Stoppard's
demolition of dubious academicism. But the ``Yes'' was actually the beginning
of me thinking ``Yes, I've got it. The only confection this can possibly be, to
necessitate this eternity of unwrap, is the giant Toblerone. God, giant
Toblerones, I haven't seen one of those since . . . ''
People were laughing at some rejoinder, laughing not up but down-roariously, so
as not to miss out on the next line. And there was I, squandering my friend's
money, decoding confectioner's crackle, all because of this cretin. He probably
wasn't listening anyway. Probably only there because his wife's doing an
extra-mural class in contemporary drama, which he's delighted about, I bet,
because while she's Pintering away, he's pausing late with his secretary.
The bastard. I am losing out on my first outing in weeks because of a
philandering nerd, a two-faced philistine who probably wankled his ticket on
expenses. (Ed: Don't you mean ``wangled''? Me: I know what I mean.) And I'm
just sitting here, tense in my posh seat, with a surreal sense of sitting in
the worst seat at the King's, Arcadia's plot forever lost to me, wondering what
I will say about the play in the interval. ``I wonder how they got that pretend
tortoise to move in that lifelike way? Wasn't it clever of the author to call
him `Lightning'?''
No. I take a breath, I turn round from the waist, and I stare. Pointedly, is
not the word. The stare is pure acupuncture. And I don't look at his face, I
stare at the crackle source, and then slowly return my back to him. My thoughts
black out, then slowly the lights go up on the realisation that he has nothing
in his hand but a sweetie paper. Sitting there in his suit, looking straight
ahead, rubbing away at a little piece of dark corrugated paper (my eyes have
adjusted by this time).
Not even a toffee of an excuse. The crackling continues. I might as well be
watching The Singing Kettle. In fact The Singing Kettle will be my next big
outing over the next few months. There's a big red star on my impressively
professional year wall planner to prove it. But pusillanimous - a word I learnt
appositely enough from Look Back in Anger when I was 15 - wretch that I am, I
wait till Act Two before I turn round and say, quietly, but with projection,
``Would you stop doing that, please?''
The noise stops, the stage moves towards me, two couples separated by centuries
are waltzing around the same space, and a little later the stage cloth
descends. I will never know how, earlier in this torture, the tortoise got
downstage and where the lettuce came from. Never mind, says the Pollyanna part
of my soul, maybe Behind-Me's wife has met some nice young man at her evening
class, who makes her laugh. Perhaps they go to matinees on Saturday afternoons,
and hold hands instead of wrappers. And maybe this year, she will have a good
secret reason not to mind that predictable marital Christmas present, the huge
shop-wrapped box of chocolates, flat as a pizza carton, wide as a lawnmower,
and personal as a personal ad. For you see, when you're in the wrong seat, you
sometimes have to make up an alternative new play for yourself.
After I had voiced my pathetically postponed objection, I overheard a woman say
to her friend, in a small, relieved voice: ``She's just asked him to stop!'' A
little circle seated around Behind-Me had obviously been suffering silently
too. Everyone had been similarly aggravated and everyone had been waiting for a
braver soul to speak up. This ``you go first'' attitude is deeply ingrained in
our fearful psyches, the fear being that our allies will melt away behind us
should we go forwards.
I remember at a post-performance party at the Edinburgh Festival years ago, a
small group of us were discussing a rather dull Dryden play, and we all agreed
that the actress in the leading role had vastly contributed to the tedium by
hamming it up to a quite baroque extent. When joined by an actor from the show,
we all neutrally discussed the author and honestly complimented his performance
- one poor soul then proceeded to repeat the judgment on the leading lady,
giving a neat synopsis of our shared low opinion of her skill. We weren't
implicated though, she spoke only for herself.
The actor pulled back his shoulders and went all raised-jaw and haughty. ``I
must disagree,'' he said, ``I believe my wife's quite magnificent performance
to be the absolute highlight of the production.'' And off he marched. The poor
woman blushed and stammered and looked like she wanted a trap-door to swallow
her up. But she also looked betrayed, as if we should all have got into
trouble; as if we should have done the decent thing and owned up to the
consensus. And I guiltily couldn't help but sympathise with her. She ``went
first'' while we had studiously inspected our canapes.
Going out on a limb can easily become going out in limbo if you've got dodgy
backers. God is love, said Mae West, but get it in writing. Same thing goes for
being a spokesperson because the conduit for the collective can easily become
perceived as the troublemaker. And, next stage, the scapegoat. So most remain
unconscientious objectors, silently drinking the corked wine, chewing on the
gristle they should have sent back to the kitchen, quietly accepting
aggravation as the price for a quiet life - with ulcers.
One of the satisfactions of writing fiction is that the ``wish I'd said that''
is actually granted. You can go first, say the right thing, delete the
inadequate, and take three hours to come up with an instant rejoinder. It's the
perfect profession for the loud-mouthed coward; sitting in front of the screen
in an empty house you can bravely tap the offender's selfish shoulder, then
confidently insist that he immediately desist. Then you can make yourself a cup
of coffee and rewrite the articulate diatribe. And it's unanswerable, because
that's how you've fixed it.
But I honestly did tell Behind-Me to stop crackling - and he didn't answer. I'm
going to write it on my year wall planner, ``Stoppard's Arcadia - very
daring'', because that's the most courageous thing I've done since I told the
children that their goldfish had died, instead of replacing it while they were
at school. Well, they were only five and I had wanted to postpone the mortality
discussion. The fact that the pet shop didn't have one the same colour had
nothing to do with it.
</TEXT>
