<DATE>951118</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let's keep faith with Yesterday</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975323441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
My favourite Beatles song is Let It Be, because I haven't. My second favourite
is Lucy In The Sky With Diamonds, but that cannot be taken as an admission of
anything.
Alex Salmond, SNP
Tomorrow Never Knows from Revolver. This track stands out and it's a sign of
things to come later on Sgt Pepper. The recording techniques are, I'm told,
very advanced for the time and certainly the sound has influenced many current
bands. like Oasis and PM Dawn.
David Campbell,
chief executive, Virgin Radio
FIVE BEATLES SINGLES THAT DIDN'T MAKE No.1
Penny Lane/Strawberry Fields Forever (1967, kept off top slot by Engelbert
Humperdinck's Release Me).
Something/Come Together (1969, No 4).
Let it Be (1970, kept off top slot by Lee Marvin's Wandrin' Star).
Yesterday (No 8 in 1976).
The Long and Winding Road (not released as a single in Britain, although it
made No 1 in America).
It's all beautiful stuff. All those early songs like Love Me Do, I Wanna Hold
Your Hand and She Loves You. They're all very simple love songs, but they are
done with such fresh spontaneity. None of us knew what was happening at the
time, none of us ever realised what a global influence they would have.
Alan Freeman, broadcaster
I saw them when I was 21 in Liverpool in a special show with David Jacobs and I
thought they were the greatest. I've the entire record collection. There is
only Bach, Mozart and The Beatles.
Jeffrey Archer, novelist
As a spry 45 year old I'd hoped to sneak through life without ever being asked
to name my favour-ite Beatles song. I feel like a Chelsea Pensioner being asked
to relive his war experiences.
The only one that still excites me is A Day In The Life because it caught the
feeling that life is a continual fugue of boredom and madness, again a bit like
war.
Maybe when all the old codgers die off they'll be replaced by geriatric Beatles
fans shuffling past the cenotaph to the strains of Sgt Pepper. If so, I hope I
die before I get old(er).
Ian Pattison
The Beatles were always a little too clean-cut for my liking, but I loved I Am
A Walrus and Polythene Pam. They were a lot dirtier than the usual. I remember
listening to them and loving them as a schoolgirl far too long ago.
Pam Hogg, Designer
Eight Days A Week. It was the song that made me fall in love with John Lennon.
I was five when my auntie used to play it to me from the Beatles For Sale
album. It was the first song that made me feel something. People say that they
were too clean but compared to Saint Cliff they were blessed relief.
Elaine C Smith
The song that brings back the biggest wave of nostalgia is Ticket To Ride. For
years I thought it was ``I've got a ticket to Rye'', where maybe there was a
big pop concert going on. I loved the movies too, at that time it would take
films a year to reach Belfast, but Help! and A Hard Day's Night came in just a
week.
Bernard McLaverty, author
</TEXT>
